<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-BRADLEY-DINNER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE CALLS BRADLEY TO MORE DEBATES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Includes parts of IOWA-GORE)  (rk) 
 By   RICHARD L. BERKE AND KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ Standing before 3,000 Iowa Democrats and the
man who is blocking his path to the Democratic presidential
nomination, Vice President Al Gore Saturday night challenged former
Sen. Bill Bradley to an immediate series of debates.
</P>
<P>
   In a dramatic appeal before an important partisan crowd in this
battleground state, Gore offered himself as a feisty underdog and
gestured toward his rival in the audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I listened carefully, Bill, to what you had to say about
making this campaign a different kind of experience and lifting up
our democracy,'' Gore said. ``I really agree with that. I think we
have a chance to do exactly that. But you know the best way to do
that is to have regular debates on the issues. Let's have one every
week. What about it? Let's have a debate on agriculture in Iowa
right now. What about it, Bill? If the answer is yes, stand up and
wave your hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley did not wave his hand. The candidate's aides have said
he would definitely debate Gore this year. But they have not agreed
to the challenge of frequent debates.
</P>
<P>
   In his address, Bradley, riding a wave of positive publicity and
poll numbers, portrayed himself as the candidate of the high road
and called on Gore to run a positive campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes discipline to be positive,'' Bradley said. ``I
believe that _ to the deepest core of my being the American people
want that.''
</P>
<P>
   Appearing together in the same ballroom for the first time in
the 2000 campaign, Gore and Bradley drew ebullient responses from
Democrats from across Iowa, which will hold the first presidential
caucuses in late January.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates' appearances were carefully choreographed so they
were sure to get equal billing. Behind the left side of the stage,
a banner declared, ``Iowa Loves Bill Bradley.'' Behind the right
side, a banner of similar size proclaimed, ``Al &AMP; Tipper Gore.
Change That Works For Working Families.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley and Gore made back-to-back appearances before the
Democratic National Committee in Washington two weeks ago, but
neither was present for the other's speech.
</P>
<P>
   As they mingled with participants during the dinner, the two men
_ former colleagues in the Senate _ shook hands for the first time
in the 2000 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   They smiled broadly as Bradley tapped Gore gently on the
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to Iowa,'' Gore said. ``Best to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Gore drew his sharpest contrasts yet with
Bradley, casting his rival as one who went along with the Reagan
budget cuts and fled Washington after Newt Gingrich and the
Republicans took over the Congress.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Bradley cast Gore as a captive of the
establishment and the entrenched powers of the party and the Vice
Presidency.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   During a campaign walk through neighborhood streets, Gore
portrayed Bradley as a disloyal Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   The 1981 budget vote, Gore said, was ``the single most defining
vote for the Democrats in the last 20 years,'' and the
determination to counter Gingrich was second.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each of us was called upon to fight against it with everything
we had or not, and he did not,'' Gore said of Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   The two candidates so far plan a joint appearance at a town-hall
meeting in New Hampshire on Oct. 27, and a debate on Jan. 8 in Des
Moines.
</P>
<P>
   The event here was particularly important because Iowa _ which
is scheduled to have the first presidential caucuses on Jan. 31 but
may move the date up by a week _ is shaping up as a crucial
battleground.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has cultivated Democrats in Iowa for years, and has the
aggressive support of the party establishment, including Sen. Tom
Harkin and Christie Vilsack, the wife of Gov. Tom Vilsack, who is
neutral. Gore is leading in the polls, but the surveys also show
that Bradley has been gaining ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important for both candidates to leave a good
impression,'' said Rob Tully, the chairman of the Iowa Democratic
Party, ``because this particular campaign, I think, is still fluid
enough that either candidate can leave themselves open to criticism
after the dinner's over in terms of how they may have addressed
each other in terms of issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Tully said that this was the best attended Jefferson-Jackson Day
dinner in Iowa history _ and that both campaigns had asked that
their candidates not sit at the head table but mingle in the
audience.
</P>
<P>
   Offstage, the Bradley campaign responded to Gore's barbs.
``There is a quote from Robert E. Lee,'' said Anita Dunn, Bradley's
communications director. ``When you're too weak to defend, you must
attack.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said the vice president was a product of the Washington
establishment and still enmeshed in vice presidential trappings _
trappings that Gore is trying to escape.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question that we are up against an entrenched
power.'' Bradley said. ``When a candidate has the president of the
United States standing by his side, loyally, as he has stood by his
side, and he has the Democratic National Committee, most of the
large Democratic fund-raisers, arrives in Air Force II, and is
ahead by 15 points nationally, well, that's entrenched power. All I
have is the people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
