</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-BBA-YANKS-ONEILL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O'NEILL'S RIBS NOT FEELING ANY BETTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Paul O'Neill, the Yankees' right fielder, was
out of the starting lineup for Game 3 Saturday night because of
bruised ribs, and he feels he will be out indefinitely unless he
improves quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it doesn't get any better, I might be out for awhile,''
O'Neill said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill tried a deep knee bend Saturday as his teammates
stretched for batting practice, his torso upright, and his pain was
betrayed by a grimace. ``I really felt it today,'' O'Neill said
later. ``I came out to try to stretch, and I'm really feeling it.
We'll have to see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Yankees manager Joe Torre indicated that if his team had been
playing a decisive game Saturday night, then O'Neill probably would
have been in the lineup. But that clearly wasn't the case.
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Ledee stood in right field during batting practice,
chatting with O'Neill while the veteran stuck his left hand below
his shirt and felt his chest. Ledee may have been asking O'Neill
for pointers in playing the position: Ledee played only seven
innings in right field this season, over three games, and had just
17 innings in right in 1998. ``It's not a big difference from left
to right,'' Ledee said.
</P>
<P>
   When O'Neill sat out games this year, Shane Spencer usually
played right field, but the Yankees chose to keep the utility man
Clay Bellinger on their 25-man roster for the playoffs, rather than
Spencer, and with O'Neill sidelined, the team is short on
outfielders. Darryl Strawberry has played the outfield most of his
career but has not played there since rejoining the Yankees in
September. Designated hitter Chili Davis hasn't played in the field
in the latter half of this decade, and Bellinger has been an
infielder most of his career.
</P>
<P>
   With O'Neill ailing, there is a strong chance the Yankees will
reconsider the option of adding Spencer to their roster before the
next round of playoffs begins Wednesday, with the Yankees playing
either Cleveland or Boston.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill was injured while playing the Devil Rays on Oct. 2. With
David Cone's 12th victory on the line, O'Neill ran hard after a
foul ball, bounced against the wall, spun and slammed the right
side of his torso against the top of the fence. O'Neill left the
game immediately, holding his right side, and after taking some
batting practice last Monday, he played in Game 1 and Game 2 of the
division series in New York, going 2 for 8.
</P>
<P>
   But he had to come out of the first game for a defensive
replacement in the ninth inning, and he thinks he aggravated the
bruise while running in the outfield in Game 2. His pain is located
in his two lowest ribs, and Torre said it is probably the type of
injury that won't improve until O'Neill is fully rested in the
off-season.
</P>
<P>
   The bruise bothers O'Neill when he runs, and hurts most when he
throws.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill usually bats third, but Saturday night Bernie Williams
batted third, Tino Martinez fourth, Strawberry fifth and Ledee
sixth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-10-99 0012EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991010.0014 </DOCNO>
