<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-10 00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2287 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-USC-LADN     10-10 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC STOPPED COLD BY ARIZONA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. _ There was finger-pointing. Expressions of
befuddlement. Answers bordering on alarmist.
</P>
<P>
   And these were the least disconcerting things that happened to
USC on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In the oppressive 95-degree temperature at Arizona Stadium, USC
suffered a complete meltdown that ominously looked like something
capable of lasting a lot longer than one game.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 22-ranked Trojans lost to Arizona 31-24 before 51,418.
But the final score was the only statistic that failed to reflect
the game's lopsided nature.
</P>
<P>
   USC (3-2, 1-2) rushed for minus-20 yards, the second-lowest
total in school history. This is particularly troubling when you
consider Arizona's defense was ranked 10th against the run in the
Pacific-10 Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona (4-2, 2-1) amassed 550 yards offense, and its previously
porous defense limited USC to 271 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans' defense, which gave up 334 yards rushing in its
first four games, allowed the Wildcats 307.
</P>
<P>
   But this wasn't really about the defense. It had a partial
excuse for its shortcomings, since it was forced to stay on the
field for more than 35 minutes, while USC's nonexistent offense
played less than 25.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our offense was horrendous,'' USC coach Paul Hackett said.
``(Arizona) completely shut down the run. We didn't block anything.
The offense has to take some responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Remember the finger-pointing? It came from an unlikely source.
</P>
<P>
   USC trailed 24-17, with barely two minutes left. The Trojans had
a fourth-and-3 at their own 35-yard line. But before a play could
be run, quarterback Mike Van Raaphorst fumbled the snap, Arizona
cornerback Kelvin Hunter recovered and went 24 yards for a
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fumble is inexcusable,'' Hackett said. ``That was the
turning point of the game. I had no doubt we would convert there.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett wasn't done assigning blame. USC got the ball back and
scored a touchdown with only 28 seconds left when Van Raaphorst
found Marcell Allmond in the end zone to cut the lead to 31-24.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans tried an on-sides kick, but David Bell's effort
bounced out of bounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was inexcusable,'' Hackett said. ``That's shoddy special
teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Others were more reluctant to say it but couldn't completely
mask the Trojans' biggest problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed in the way we played defense, but you have to
throw some blame to the offense,'' free safety David Gibson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's things you want to go and say,'' linebacker Zeke
Moreno said. ``It's to the point where you don't want to sit there.
Tell me what to do. I'll go block somebody.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to do something. Maybe even call plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Hmmm, there's an interesting suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   The expressions of befuddlement? Asked what the offense could do
to avoid future embarrassment, Van Raaphorst said, ``I don't
know.''
</P>
<P>
   Tailback Chad Morton added: ``I really have no idea. I never
thought my senior year would be like this.''
</P>
<P>
   They sounded almost exactly like wide receiver R. Jay Soward,
who tried to figure out the offensive woes, despite suffering a
likely concussion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were confused,'' Soward said. ``I really can't call it.''
</P>
<P>
   Alarmist answers? Here's one of many.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at a major crossroads right now,'' Gibson said. ``It
will be easy for guys to go into the tank.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost amazingly, the Trojans held a 17-10 advantage early in
the third quarter even with so many deficiencies. Wide receiver
Windrell Hayes (nine catches, 115 yards) caught an 18-yard pass
from Van Raaphorst, and the Trojans went ahead for about 10
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought when we went ahead 17-10, it would be a momentum
changer,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona struck back on a 17-yard pass from Keith Smith to Dennis
Northcutt and took the lead in the fourth quarter when Trung
Canidate (194 yards) scored on an 11-yard run to give the Wildcats
a 24-17 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans never recovered. Van Raaphorst was intercepted on
the next series, USC went three-and-out and then the all-important
fumbled snap decided the game, according to Hackett.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a motivational game. It's a big setback,'' Gibson
said. ``Some guys might say, `We can't go to the Rose Bowl, who
cares?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Someone who does care is athletic director Mike Garrett. Outside
the stadium, before heading back to Los Angeles, he had a succinct
response to the day's events.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't play very well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-10-99 0020EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
