r s BC-FBC-USC-SIDE-LBPT     10-10 0474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-SIDE-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMITH STANDS OUT FOR ARIZONA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE IRVINE  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. _ Keith Smith, who is half of Arizona's
quarterback combo, insisted Saturday afternoon that he still shares
the position with Ortege Jenkins.
</P>
<P>
   Forget, Smith says, that he was the one who took 70 snaps and
Jenkins only six in Arizona's 31-24 victory over visiting USC. And,
never mind, Smith pleads, that he completed 15 of 23 passes for 243
yards and a touchdown and rushed for another 87 yards, including a
57-yard scoring run in the first quarter, while Jenkins' totals
were one incomplete pass and minus-7 yards rushing.
</P>
<P>
   It is, according to Smith, still both quarterbacks' job to
share.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no guy,'' said Smith. ``I think (offensive
coordinator Dino Babers) just went with the flow.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona coach Dick Tomey wouldn't bite when asked if the flow
would last past Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a credit to all of our guys,'' Tomey said. ``Keith
played well and O.J. was doing everything he could to help us
win.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Smith didn't need any help _ at least not from
Jenkins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was this my best game?,'' Smith said. ``Cal my freshman year
(when he set an NCAA freshman record with 502 yards of total
offense) was pretty hard to beat. But we didn't get the win that
day. So, yeah, it may have been.''
</P>
<P>
   He completed 7 of 12 passes for 102 yards in the first half, but
it was his running that made the difference, going 57 yards
untouched with 10:20 left in the first half to give the Wildcats a
7-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew when we called that play I was going to take it to the
house,'' Smith said. ``The field was so wide open I couldn't
believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Wildcats fell behind 17-10 in the third quarter, Smith
went to work on an eight-play, 65-yard drive that was extended
twice on third down by completions of 21 yards to Dennis Northcutt
and 9 yards to Bobby Wade. Smith also showed excellent touch on a
sideline completion to tight end Brandon Manumaleuna and the
17-yard touchdown pass on a fade pattern run by Northcutt.
</P>
<P>
   The go-ahead touchdown came on a 11-yard run by Trung Canidate,
but it was completions of 44 yards to Palmdale High graduate Malosi
Leonard and 16 yards to Northcutt that set up the score.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keith was just on (Saturday),'' Northcutt said.
</P>
<P>
   There was a reason for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just the fact that there are a lot of guys on this team from
California who didn't get recruited by (USC) makes it more
special,'' said Smith. ``I wasn't even offered a trip there when I
was in high school. It makes you want to play extra tough. You
could just feel it when we got off the bus and went into the locker
room. Whenever we play USC, it seems like the legs get stronger and
you get faster.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-10-99 0030EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991010.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-10 00:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2293 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     10-10 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' OFFENSIVE FUTILITY DEFIES A SIMPLE EXPLANATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAYX 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ A hundred years from now, future baseball
historians will stumble across this statistical Titanic,
immediately register doubt, and then order extensive research.
</P>
<P>
   No way, they will say. The record books are out of whack, they
will think. It couldn't have been that bad. Not for a club good
enough to be in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Computerized double-checks will be ordered. Old box scores from
late in the 20th century will be revisited. Grainy video from NBC
and Fox will be watched,inning by inning. Consider for a second,
the boredom involved in that assignment.
</P>
<P>
   But once all the facts and figures have been gathered, the
historians will then rest easy. The truth will be known. There was
no mistake.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' batting order of 1999 will live forever in baseball
infamy, outdone in futility, just barely, by the Rangers' batting
order of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 0-for-October Gang'' became a discredit to their
profession, but for what it is worth, which is exactly nothing, a
permanent fixture in baseball record books.
</P>
<P>
   No postseason team has ever come close to displaying this kind
of rotten wood, and just think, the Rangers did it back to back.
It's difficult to believe, even in another 100 years, that it could
happen again. Unless, of course, the Rangers have a first-round
matchup in October 2000 against the same ol' Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   In the broom-kill last night at The Ballpark in Arlington, New
York pitchers did what New York pitchers have done for six
consecutive playoff meetings over two years. They breezed. In fact,
shutting down the Rangers in the postseason has become so easy for
Yankees hurlers, their efforts are unfairly diminished.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the name-calling mounts for those in the Rangers'
batting order. Heartless, gutless, chokers _ probably all of it
applies. But whatever, Roger Clemens worked seven shutout innings,
Mariano Rivera applied the finish, and the Yankees won, 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   Those three runs came on a first-inning home run by Darryl
Strawberry, coming off another drug suspension. Manager Joe Torre
last night mentioned Strawberry's ``hiccup,'' meaning an arrest
last spring on charges of cocaine possession and asking a hooker
for favors. Joe, this is Cowboys' country. Down here, you can call
it what it is. We understand.
</P>
<P>
   Esteban Loaiza regrouped after the Strawberry bomb, and his
seven innings were a winning effort. But over two years, there's a
long line of Rangers' pitchers who can say the same.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers scored one run in the three games, the same as 1998.
The Rangers had 13 hits last year in 27 innings. This time it was
14 hits. In other words, this ``record'' is now twice as bad, and
again, no postseason club has come close to this sort of misery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two runs in two years _ there is no explanation for that,''
said catcher Pudge Rodriguez. ``I will, however, give credit to the
Yankee pitchers. It wasn't just us not hitting. It has also been
them pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have been searching for explanations for two
Octobers. Again last night, mouths did open, words came out, but
really, how do you explain this statistical impossibility? Two runs
over six games in two years goes beyond words even for the Yankees,
who also stumble around verbally when trying to give answers.
</P>
<P>
   As a side note, however, Rodriguez achieved more last night with
a simple act of courtesy than anything that was said in the
post-game gloom. He popped out of the dugout a few minutes after
the final out, and begin waving to what was left of the ballpark
crowd. Pudge was saying his thank yous, and the fans responded
loudly.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a great crowd _ really into the game,'' said general
manager Doug Melvin. ``The shame is we don't give them much to
cheer about, either this time or last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the 50,269 in attendance was ready for action before
the first pitch, and stayed revved up despite nine scoreless
innings from the home team. For noise and awareness, it was the
best crowd in Arlington history. And this was totally due to
self-motivation. Certainly the Rangers provided nothing in the way
of excitement.
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, Melvin pondered the question of where the team
goes from here. ``Let me think about that one for a while,'' he
finally answered.
</P>
<P>
   A hundred years from now, baseball historians will be saying the
same thing. Two runs in two years will have them thinking about
double-checking the accuracy of the record books.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
