<SLUG> BC-BELMONT-TESTS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO CLEANUP PLAN YET FOR BELMONT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY SHERRY JOE CROSBY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ State toxics officials told an independent
commission Saturday they weren't prepared to recommend a cleanup
plan for the toxin-laden Belmont Learning Center site because
significant tests had yet to be conducted on the site of the
nation's most expensive high school.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the state Department of Toxic Substances Control
instead gave the Belmont Commission an overview of the site
mitigation process for the 35-acre property that was once an oil
and gas field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not recommending a particular alternative (remediation
plan),'' said Bob Borzelleri, DTSC's chief deputy director. ``We
don't have all the information I'd like to see to make that
categorical statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Borzelleri said it may be possible for an engineering solution
to be found to prevent potentially explosive methane gases and
dangerous toxics like hydrogen sulfide from reaching the surface.
But, the state officials said, the extent and cost of that solution
would not be known until all tests were complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``The information we've gathered so far doesn't mean any deal
breakers'' aside from any unforeseen test results as the
environmental investigation continues, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Commission member and former state Sen. Charles Calderon, who
was looking for possible cleanup remedies and associated costs,
said he was surprised and disappointed by the testimony of state
toxics officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was expecting a mediation plan based on a worst-case
scenario that would tell us whether to proceed or not go forward,''
Calderon said. ``I don't see this information in that report. I
don't know where we're going from here.''
</P>
<P>
   Other commission members said they were no closer to a decision
on abandoning or proceeding with construction on Belmont after
Saturday's meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are we to do with all this data,'' lamented Maribel
Marin, co-chairperson of the eight-member commission. ``All this
data does is point to the fact there is a risk.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission is charged with making a recommendation to the
school board by Oct. 20 on the advisability of completing the
school.
</P>
<P>
   State toxics officials said they won't be able to recommend a
cleanup plan until a seismic study is done and other soil testing
is complete.
</P>
<P>
   The seismic test is needed to determine potential pathways for
hydrogen sulfide and other toxins to reach the surface. The study
is expected to take three months, including a month-long pilot to
determine if the assessment method is appropriate and will yield
the desired data.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's missing is the seismic study,'' said Hamid Saebfar,
DTSC's chief of Southern California's cleanup operations branch.
``Once we have that and a feasibility study, we can answer those
questions.''
</P>
<P>
   A feasibility study -- which will detail alternative remediation
plans, their related levels of health protection and costs -- is
not expected in February or March.
</P>
<P>
   ``The district contractor is due back to address likely
solutions that could receive DTSC approval and the cost of those
solutions,'' said Angelo Bellomo, chairman of the district's safety
team. ``The district contractor will look at how extensive the
possible remedial actions will be and their associated costs.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the commission is expected to learn about a range of
possible cleanup remedies and their costs from Environmental
Strategies Corp., the firm conducting environmental testing at the
Belmont site.
</P>
<P>
   ``ESC is due back to address likely solutions that could receive
DTSC approval and the cost of those solutions,'' Bellomo said.
``ESC will look at how bad can the remedy be and how much will it
cost.''
</P>
<P>
   During Saturday's meeting, state toxics officials described one
possible remedy to clean up the school site.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would feature a gas extraction system and a series of
methane barriers that would cover the entire 35-acre property to
prevent the escape of gases such as hydrogen sulfide.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just incredible to me the type of mitigation that is
feasible for this site,'' Marin said.
</P>
<P>
   Saebfar said the best remedy won't be known until the
environmental investigation is complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's look at all the alternatives and design a system that is
more efficient and cost-effective,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
