<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS SETTLE FOR 2-2 TIE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Kings flew back to Los Angeles after Saturday
night's 2-2 tie with the Washington Capitals, knowing they left
something sour on the ice of the MCI Center.
</P>
<P>
   Surely they had reason to smile after going 3-1-1 during the
first leg of a seven-game road trip that resumes Friday in Calgary.
But by raising the bar since last season, blowing a two-goal lead
in the third period was the part they will remember.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I happy?'' said Luc Robitaille, who added a seventh goal to
his league-leading total. ``I guess. But we have to learn to bury
teams in situations like this.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings got their first taste of the league's new overtime
rule, which includes playing four on four to cut down on ties.
Actually, the Kings played almost two minutes shorthanded after
Robitaille was called for a penalty in the final seconds of
regulation.
</P>
<P>
   The team held on, with goalie Stephane Fiset stopping a blast by
Adam Oates after a 2-on-1 break with 13 seconds to go.
</P>
<P>
   But rookie coach Andy Murray, who said he would have been
ecstatic with seven points before the trip start, smiled through
clenched teeth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was better than a good trip, but not quite a great trip,''
Murray said. ``After they tied it, we retook control of the game,
but we let this one get away.''
</P>
<P>
   With the team off today, Murray is catching a 5 a.m. flight to
his home in Minnesota, where he will spend most of the day with his
wife Ruth watching his two sons play hockey. He'll get back on a
plane at 10:30 tonight and return for practice Monday at the
Iceoplex.
</P>
<P>
   Murray certainly will have his tray table down to help figure
out what happened Saturday after his team controlled the Capitals
for the first two periods.
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille had given the Kings the lead early in the second
period with Caps defenseman Ken Klee off for holding. Jozef Stumpel
had missed on a rebound of Rob Blake's blast from the point.
Robitaille didn't waste a third chance, poking it past goalie Olaf
Kolzig.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings made it 2-0 just over two minutes later. Third line
right-winger Marko Tuomainen beat Kolzig in front after Ian
Laperriere dug the puck out of the corner.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first career goal for Tuomainen, who played four
games for Edmonton in 1994-95 but spent the past two seasons
playing in his native Finland.
</P>
<P>
   It also was the first goal by a forward not on the first line.
Donald Audette and Bryan Smolinski from the scoreless second line
had six shots, but Glen Murray was shut out and was on the ice when
the tying goal was scored.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings outshot Washington 24-13 in the first two periods but
never scored again.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Bondra, one of the fastest skaters in the league, cut the
Kings' lead to 2-1 with a power-play goal with 15:57 left in
regulation, but the game still seemed well in hand.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings' only loss on the trip, however, was last Wednesday
against Florida when they allowed three goals in the last two
minutes. They rebounded against Tampa Bay the next night, but
Saturday the Caps kept on the pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Simon, Washington's popular long-haired left winger, tied
the game with 8:13 left when he tipped in Joe Sacco's blast from
the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was happy, getting a point after trailing by two goals in
the third period,'' said former Ducks coach Ron Wilson, in his
second year with Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a 4-on-3 advantage early in overtime, the Caps could not
sustain the momentum. The Kings outshot them 4-3 and stopped a
2-on-1 break when Fiset gloved a blast by Oates with two minutes
left.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recovered nicely after they tied the game, but it's still a
game you want,'' Fiset said.
</P>
</TEXT>
