r s BC-BBN-DBACKS-BICKLEY-AZ     10-10 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMACK WASN'T ONLY ONE TO DROP THE BALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK - For an eternity, Tony Womack sat at his locker. Head
down, feet bouncing, tears trickling down his cheek.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, his eyes were fixed on the back of his cubicle. A
man staring into nothing but despair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just dropped it,'' he said. ``I just dropped it. Oh, gosh.''
</P>
<P>
   A quick reminder for anyone who wants to lay the goat horns on
Womack for dropping a fly ball that changed the course of a game
and a season:
</P>
<P>
   An infielder by trade, he never wanted to play right field in
the first place. He did so reluctantly, at the team's request. He
made progress. He kept his mouth shut. And in the 166th game of the
season, the experiment blew up.
</P>
<P>
   ``No excuses,'' Womack said. ``I've been doing it all year. I
was making adjustments. I was making progress. I'm not going to
make excuses. I just dropped the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   There is bitter irony here. In Pittsburgh, Womack learned to
play second base because Jay Bell was the incumbent shortstop. In
Arizona, Womack was displaced again after Bell was moved to second
base.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, long before his right-field miscue, Womack made a
tremendous play at shortstop to save a run. Remember that. He was
moved to the outfield for defensive purposes _ because the original
right fielder, Bernard Gilkey, misplayed a line drive that cost the
Diamondbacks a run. Remember that, too.
</P>
<P>
   History will not go easy on Womack. Our obsession with success
carries a rough edge, and these kind of moments rarely fade out of
memory. Instead, they become ghosts with a lifetime pass. Just ask
Mitch Williams. Brant Brown. Jean Van de Velde. Scott Norwood. A
cruel list that goes on and on.
</P>
<P>
   To this day, people assume Bill Buckner's legendary error handed
the Mets a World Series title in 1986. It did not. It only gave
them Game 6. A similar distinction applies here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony's played great baseball all season, and today he made a
mistake,'' Bell said. ``But it didn't cost us a game. It only tied
it up. I hope this doesn't turn into Tony Womack bashing, because
that's not what this should be about. We all fail.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, and if you want to cast blame, start with everybody. With
only a few exceptions, the Diamondbacks underachieved in the
postseason. They did not play well. Their manager, Buck Showalter,
made some questionable decisions in two of the three losses. In
their finest moment, they fell apart.
</P>
<P>
   Together, they will have to live with balancing 100
regular-season victories against hollow playoff failure. In the
discomfort of knowing the defeat was largely of their own making.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not play up to our potential,'' Brian Anderson said.
``Maybe if we do that, the series comes out different.''
</P>
<P>
   In this era of the tape-measure home run, we are reminded that
baseball is, indeed, a game of inches. On Saturday, Bell's clutch
double clipped the top of the wall. Another inch, and he's rounding
the bases. Instead, he's thrown out at home moments later. By an
inch.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Colbrunn's home run barely cleared the fence. Darryl
Hamilton's at-bat in the eighth inning could've blown the game wide
open. Except his looping fly down the left-field line dropped foul.
By an inch.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, a series-winning home run that bounced off Steve
Finley's glove.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should've had it,'' Finley said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Womack stared forward, wondering whether his error ended a
magical season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough question,'' he said. ``A tough, tough question.''
</P>
<P>
   As the sun set in New York, a huge gathering of birds circled
just above an empty stadium, flying over an imaginary carcass. A
dream season died Saturday. In time, the good memories will
resurface and the bad memories will turn to motivation. But whether
they'll ever get this chance again is impossible to predict, and in
the end, the biggest loss was an opportunity wasted.
</P>
<P>
   Together, they dropped the ball. Long before the right fielder
did. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at (602) 444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com via e-mail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-10-99 0052EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
