<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NLDS-GAME-4-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D-BACKS EXPRESS HITS WALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ How do you begin to describe the end?
</P>
<P>
   Dejection. Pain. Tears. Fatigue. Anger. The contemplation of
what could have been. If only . . .
</P>
<P>
   After 100 regular-season victories and a division title won by
the Diamondbacks in just their second season, the magic disappeared
in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Pratt, filling in behind the plate for the second straight
game after Mike Piazza suffered a thumb injury, hit a solo home run
off Arizona closer Matt Mantei with one out in the 10th inning
Saturday to lift the wild-card New York Mets to a 4-3 victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets will face the Braves in the National League
Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you come this far, you hope for something better,''
Diamondbacks Managing General Partner Jerry Colangelo said. ``Could
have, would have, should have . . . it doesn't matter now. It is a
moment of euphoria for them and the end for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks had hoped to force a Game 5 today back home at
Bank One Ballpark with left-hander Randy Johnson on the mound. No
go.
</P>
<P>
   Pratt's blast, which was nearly caught by Arizona center fielder
Steve Finley as he reached over the fence and had the ball hit the
tip of his glove, brought to an end a game that should be
considered one of the classics of this or any season.
</P>
<P>
   None of the 56,177 fans at Shea Stadium _ not even Pratt _ knew
for sure whether Finley returned from no-man's land with the ball.
Pratt made the turn at first base and was headed toward second when
he realized that Finley had come up empty. Fireworks exploded, the
crowd erupted and Pratt's teammates poured onto the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw Steve starting to plant for his jump and we have all
seen it a million times on the highlight films _ Steve bringing
back balls,'' said Pratt, who hit .293 with three homers and 21
RBIs in 71 games for the Mets this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went up and I lost the ball, kind of paused. I thought he
had the ball, actually. Then he put his head down. I didn't see the
umpire, but he (Finley) put his head down. I knew we won the game
right then.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley wished his arm were a fraction of an inch longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I should have caught it. It hit the end of my
glove. I've caught a lot of those before,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Buck Showalter met briefly with the team after the game
before addressing the media. Colangelo consoled many of the
players, especially right fielder Tony Womack, who was quite
shaken. Outfield coach Dwayne Murphy also gave Womack support.
</P>
<P>
   Starter Brian Anderson, who gave up seven hits and two runs in
seven innings, said Showalter told the team ``that he was very
proud of us. It was emotional.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Showalter: ``My thoughts are on the players. I think as
many ebbs and flows of the season there are, that the finality of a
situation like this is real tough for them . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``I just told them that the pain would pass, but the burning
desire to get back here and get it right won't, because that is the
type of people they are. Tucson (spring training) will be here
before they know it.''
</P>
<P>
   Game 4 also featured:
</P>
<P>
   Solo home runs by Mets second baseman Edgardo Alfonzo (fourth
inning) and Arizona first baseman Greg Colbrunn (fifth).
</P>
<P>
   Solid seven-plus-inning efforts by the starting pitchers,
Arizona left-hander Anderson and Mets left-hander Al Leiter.
</P>
<P>
   A two-run double by Jay Bell in the eighth inning that brought
Arizona from behind for a 3-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Bell being thrown out on a close play at the plate to end the
inning after a single by Matt Williams. Colbrunn was the next
scheduled hitter. The play came back to haunt the Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   The ejection of Mets third-base coach Cookie Rojas by left-field
umpire Charlie Williams after Rojas protested Williams' ruling of a
foul-ball call against New York in the eighth inning. Rojas is
certain to face a fine and possible severe disciplinary action
after shoving Williams.
</P>
<P>
   The stunning removal of third baseman and MVP candidate Matt
Williams from the game in the eighth on a double-switch that put
Lenny Harris at third and brought Mantei into the game.
</P>
<P>
   A dropped fly ball in deep right field by Womack that helped the
Mets tie the game at 3 in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Mantei escaping further damage in the eighth by catching John
Olerud in a rundown between third base and the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Mantei pitched two innings, matching his season high. He had
pitched two innings twice with Florida early in the year. He had
not been used in the first three games of this series, but said the
inactivity didn't affect him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been up (in the bullpen) a lot,'' he said. ``I felt good.
He (Pratt) just hit the ball hard. That happens sometimes. We had a
good run, but all good things must come to an end.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
