<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-10 00:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2300 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s BC-BBN-DBACKS-GOMEZ-AZR &LR;      10-10 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMOVING WILLIAMS TORE OUT TEAM'S HEART 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK - Many will point to Todd Pratt's home run in the
bottom of the 10th inning as the crushing blow to a terrific
Diamondbacks season, the final dagger that left the Arizona boys
laid out on the canvas for the final time in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   But what occurred two innings earlier may have played just as
big a role in the demise of the Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   For the very first time in his career, Matt Williams said, he
was removed from the middle of a game as part of a double-switch in
the bottom of the eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   There's one school of thought _ one that starts right here _
that says the Diamondbacks had absolutely no shot of winning once
Williams was removed. No chance.
</P>
<P>
   To understand what the no-nonsense Williams represents, consider
he is the absolute and unquestioned leader of this club, which, in
so many ways, plays the game exactly the way it was intended.
</P>
<P>
   He is the heart, soul and spiritual leader that pushes the
Diamondbacks in the right direction. He is the club's father, son
and holy ghost.
</P>
<P>
   When the rest of the Diamondbacks looked toward third base in
the final two innings Saturday, they did not see Williams. If they
looked toward the bench, there sat Williams, unable to do a damned
thing to help prolong the Diamondbacks' wonderful season.
</P>
<P>
   To this bunch, Williams is the equivalent of Gen. Patton, ``Old
Blood and Guts.'' He inspires his teammates simply by manning his
spot at third base. He is the anchor of the club, and, while there
are others who definitely motivate, they simply do not come close
to representing what Williams does.
</P>
<P>
   On paper, Manager Buck Showalter's call made sense. After all,
Williams had made the last out of the eighth inning, and inserting
Matt Mantei into Williams' slot and putting Lenny Harris into the
pitcher's spot in the lineup appeared logical.
</P>
<P>
   There was one flaw in that thinking: This game has never been
played on paper. It's played by human beings who have an emotional
attachment to the game and what it represents. Take away the
leader, and you are left with a shell.
</P>
<P>
   Certain players should never ever come out of a crucial game
unless they are injured. Williams is the rock of Gibralter for this
team. The one steadying constant that everyone else can always
count on.
</P>
<P>
   Take him out of the game, and you've removed the Diamondbacks'
heart. It's that simple. You don't take Barry Larkin, Jeff Bagwell
or Chipper Jones out of any game. Matt Williams is at the top of
that list.
</P>
<P>
   Following the 4-3 loss to New York that eliminated the
Diamondbacks in the best-of-five series, Williams defended
Showalter's move to the end. Then again, what else would anyone
expect?
</P>
<P>
   Forget that nothing happened at third base or that Williams'
spot in the lineup never came up before Pratt's game-winning home
run off Mantei. Taking away the best defensive player on the field
was reason enough not to make the move.
</P>
<P>
   Showalter could have chosen several other moves, including
removing Luis Gonzalez, who hits right in front of Williams, for
Andy Fox. Even taking out Jay Bell and moving Hanley Frias over to
second base and inserting Fox at shortstop could have been done.
</P>
<P>
   Anybody but Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something he's got to do,'' Williams said of Showalter's
double-switch. ``I understand it and fully agree with it and have
no problems with it at all.''
</P>
<P>
   A few seconds later, Williams was again questioned by a reporter
from the Midwest about the emotions surrounding his removal. This
time, the response wasn't so kind. Williams ended the initial
question-and-answer session and walked into the trainer's room.
</P>
<P>
   The loud, profanity-filled diatribe that followed was strong
enough to make sailors blush. What was actually said was
unimportant, though many were stunned to hear such an outburst. A
few minutes later, after having cooled off, Williams returned and
politely answered most questions, once again punctuating what kind
of man he is.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, his verbal eruption was not surprising because of
the passion with which he embraces the game of baseball. This is
not simply a job to Williams. It never will be, and that's what
makes him so special.
</P>
<P>
   It was almost impossible to envision the Diamondbacks winning
this game once Williams was removed. How could Arizona possibly win
any game without Williams? It's impossible to fathom. &QL; 
Pedro Gomez can be reached at (602) 444-2364 or at
pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-10-99 0056EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
