</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANDERSON MAKES CASE FOR 2000 ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _  &UR; Brian Anderson punctuated Saturday the case he made
in the season's last two months: that he should be part of the
Diamondbacks' starting rotation in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Lost amid one the most nerve-racking, wild playoff games in
memory was Anderson's seven innings of brilliance. The left-hander,
who loves postseason pressure, gave up seven hits and two runs,
walked none and struck out four.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's performance in the 4-3 loss to the New York Mets
didn't escape Manager  &UR; Buck Showalter, who had spent the past
couple of days fielding questions from the media about why he
wasn't coming back with his ace,  &UR; Randy Johnson, for Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson showed why Showalter had so much faith in him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see how (Johnson) could have pitched any better than
Brian Anderson did. . .'' Showalter said. ``We felt like this was
our best option, and we are real comfortable with it, to be able to
hold this team to this type of runs. B.A. was outstanding. That
didn't surprise me.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson escaped a potential catastrophe in the sixth inning
when the Mets scored just one run. They had runners on second and
third with one out, and Anderson got out of it. &QL; 
Are you old school? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This was as wild and as intense a game Anderson has ever pitched
in. It didn't get any less intense after he left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could feel myself actually aging watching it,'' Anderson
said. ``Randy made the quip in the ninth inning: `Man, this might
be one of those instant sports classics.' He got in my face and
said, `Are you old school?'
</P>
<P>
   ``It was certainly one of the better baseball games you'll see
in a long time.'' &QL; 
An imperfect world &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nobody felt worse for right fielder &UR; Tony Womack than  &UR; Bernard
 &UR; Gilkey, the man Womack replaced in right before dropping a fly ball
that ended up tying the game at 3 for the Mets in the eighth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Womack started the game at shortstop, but he moved to the
outfield in the late innings when  &UR; Hanley Frias came in at short
for defensive purposes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's human,'' Gilkey said. ``Everybody makes mistakes.
They've found glitches in computers. It's not a perfect world.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way it is. I'm still with Tony. I want him on my
side any day.'' &QL; 
Playoff leaders &QL; 
Left-handed reliever  &UR; Greg Swindell led the bullpen. In the three
games he appeared in, Swindell did not give up a run in 3 innings
and yielded just one hit.
</P>
<P>
   Center fielder &UR; Steve Finley, who was 2 for 22 in last year's
division series for San Diego, led the Diamondbacks with a .385
batting average (5 for 13) and five RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman &UR; Matt Williams was second in batting average at
.375 (6 for 16), but he did not have an RBI after leading the
Diamondbacks with 142 during the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Losing sucks, but we work hard,'' Williams said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
