<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PRATT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALK ABOUT DELIVERY  
 PIZZA GUY PRATT'S FAIRY-TALE HOMER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL CORO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It began with his mom tossing underhand to him, and
somewhere along the way, it diverted to tossing pizzas.
</P>
<P>
   But in a borough that loves its pizza, fairy-tale New York Mets
hero Todd Pratt delivered a baseball legend Saturday afternoon in
Queens.
</P>
<P>
   Pratt smashed an improbable 10th-inning home run to the
center-field graveyard where deep flies die at Shea Stadium,
sending the new-look Miracle, Amazin', destiny-charmed Mets to the
National League Championship Series against enemy Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Improbable, not so much because of the extra-inning tension, his
lack of a hit in the series or his 10-day cold. Not even because of
the fact that Pratt never would have hit in the series if not for
All-Star catcher Mike Piazza's quirky sprained thumb having an
inflammatory reaction to a cortisone shot Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Improbable, because Pratt was managing a Domino's Pizza
franchise three years ago. The closest he came to baseball in 1996
was teaching kids at Bucky Dent's baseball school in Boca Raton,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, with one wicked lick of ash on hide, Pratt is the king
of Queens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to cry at that moment,'' Pratt said, chugging a
magnum bottle of Budweiser with Andre champagne soaked to his
scalp. ``It was just awesome rounding third to see my whole team
waiting for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a little bit of power. If I got consistent at-bats,
I'd hit a lot of home runs.''
</P>
<P>
   He laughs, but he's not really joking.
</P>
<P>
   Pratt hated baseball so much for not giving a career .300
Triple-A hitter a fair shot at staying in the show that he left
baseball and learned pizza management in Florida, only to return a
year later for more frustration with the Mets organization.
</P>
<P>
   He nearly quit baseball twice last year, but Rick Dempsey talked
him out of it the first time, only to be reduced to tears the next
time he was sent down. An injury gave him an opportunity to stay in
New York that time.
</P>
<P>
   And then after nearly being the goat for bouncing back to
Arizona reliever Matt Mantei with runners on first and third in the
eighth, Pratt donned a cape in the 10th that was a reminiscent fit
to another New York backup catcher, Jim Leyritz, in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was one hell of a script,'' Piazza said. ``We hope there
is some sort of underlying destiny for this ballclub. We're not
asking questions. We don't want it explained. We just hope it
continues.''
</P>
<P>
   Pratt, who last homered in April, took a first-pitch curve. He
said he had been looking to get ahead of a Mantei fastball on the
pitch he homered.
</P>
<P>
   He stalled rounding first, thinking center fielder Steve Finley
hauled it back. But Finley's head sunk and Pratt's arms soared.
</P>
<P>
   When the severity of Piazza's injury came out Friday morning,
Game 5 starter Al Leiter was the first to make reference to the
unlikely heroes who surface in postseason play.
</P>
<P>
   The first clue that this was Pratt's day came in the eighth,
when he applied the tag that nailed Jay Bell at the plate in the
eighth inning. Then came the 10th and the best moment of his
career.
</P>
<P>
   A stadium employee later approached Pratt to sign the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Expletive), I'm taking it,'' Pratt said as he snatched the
ball, noting he has intentions to give the man a gift.
</P>
<P>
   Mets fans would say he already has. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
