<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEITER STAYS CALM ON MOUND BUT DRINKS PEPTO AFTERWARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL CORO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The pressure was too much. Mets starter  &UR; Al Leiter
had to sneak into the hallway &UR; Saturday behind the New York dugout
to take a swig of Pepto-Bismol.
</P>
<P>
   This was the 10th inning, three stanzas after he had left the
game only to watch reliever &UR; Armando Benitez blow his lead. The
mound was no problem for Leiter, whose cool big-game personality
rose to the occasion again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have much more of a hard time watching than playing,''
Leiter said.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter got the Mets to this National League Division Series with
a two-hit shutout of Cincinnati on Monday, when he threw 135
pitches. He came back Saturday to toss 108 more in a quality start
that began with four no-hit innings.
</P>
<P>
   He held up a 2-1 lead entering the eighth, when he was pulled
after a walk and an infield single with two outs. Just as he did
for Florida in Game 7 of the 1997 World Series, Leiter gave New
York the chance to win in extra innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what we play for,'' Leiter said. ``I treat every game
now like it's my last start. That means every pitch could make the
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Leiter was the difference against a team that led the league in
hitting against left-handers. He gave up three hits and faced the
minimum in five of his first seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Leiter has been huge, and today he was excellent,''
Manager &UR; 
 &UR; Bobby Valentine said. &QL; 
Cookie monster &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mets third-base coach &UR; Cookie Rojas may not join his team when
the National League Championship Series starts Tuesday in Atlanta.
He got into a heated argument with left-field umpire  &UR; Charlie
Williams over a correct call on an eighth-inning foul ball.
</P>
<P>
   Rojas shoved Williams during the obscenity-laced exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the ball hit on the line,'' Rojas said. ``We argued
back and forth until he called me a (expletive). I'm not going to
take that from anyone or any umpire.''
</P>
<P>
   Replays showed that Williams, who was rated the worst umpire in
the NL by players last year, made the correct call on  &UR; Darryl
Hamilton's looping drive with two runners on and the game tied at
3. Williams had left the umpires' locker room by the time a
reporter approached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Rojas ran from the coach's box to shallow left field to confront
Williams and was ejected. As the argument grew heated, Manager
Bobby Valentine sprinted out of the dugout to try to restrain
Rojas.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine and others restrained Rojas, who left the field to
chants of, ``Cookie, Cookie.'' &QL; 
Fitting for Franco &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mets reliever  &UR; John Franco got the win. How just is that?
</P>
<P>
   Franco is a boyhood Mets fan and New York native. Franco had not
been to the playoffs in 15 seasons, the longest drought for any
active player. Franco had not even won a game since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the greatest moment of my career,'' he said. ``All
hell broke loose, and I couldn't believe I was the pitcher of
record.'' &QL; 
Doing right on lefties &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Mets picked up all three victories when Arizona started
left-handers, the purported strength of Arizona that would hurt New
York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a lefty myself, I like the fact we got the lefties,''
Mets first baseman  &UR; John Olerud said. &QL; 
Includes information from the Associated Press. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-10-99 0059EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991010.0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-10 01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2305 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s BC-BKN-SUNS-RULE-CHANGES     10-10 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-RULE-CHANGES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RULES CHANGES MAY HELP SLASH, DASH SUNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLAGSTAFF _ Last season, by accident more than design, the
Portland Trail Blazers were a team constructed to perfection for
the concentrated, 50-game sprint caused by the labor lockout.
That's because the Blazers had a stockpile of youth and depth.
</P>
<P>
   Could the Suns be a team that, coincidentally, is built to order
this season for rules changes implemented by the NBA? The league
made several changes, some in the rules and some in the way they're
to be enforced, to create more movement and flow.
</P>
<P>
   And that figures to benefit a team such as the Suns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think so. It's not going to be so much of a power game
anymore,'' Suns guard Penny Hardaway said. ``It's going to be more
of a finesse game now. I think the league wants it to go back the
way it was, teams scoring 110, 115 points a game with guys knocking
down shots.''
</P>
<P>
   And with players such as Hardaway, Jason Kidd, Rex Chapman and
rookie Shawn Marion _ players who all can slash to the basket _ the
Suns could be difficult to defend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's going to help me a lot,'' said Hardaway, who was
eager to get into a more wide-open style of game in the Western
Conference and now may find even more room to work. ``Nobody is
going to put their hands on me as much.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing we had for me in Orlando was a cross-screen,
and guys used to able to really hit me when I came across that
cross-screen. Now, they're not going to be able to do that, so it's
going to make it a lot easier for me to get to the lane.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's going to hurt sometimes because you don't want to put
your hands on somebody and end up over on the sideline with two
fouls early in the first quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   The new rules will prohibit a defender from making contact with
his hands or forearms except below the free-throw line, extended
from sideline to sideline.
</P>
<P>
   The changes also mandate that players must either shoot, pass or
pick up their dribble within five seconds if the player has his
back to the basket. This is called the ``Charles Barkley Rule''
because it's aimed at players such as Barkley, who take large
chunks off the 24-second shot clock while backing down with the
ball and waiting for a second defender to come to them.
</P>
<P>
   Also, defenders may now double-team a player on the side of the
lane where the ball is, even if that player doesn't have possession
of the ball.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, the 24-second shot clock will be reset to 14
seconds if there is a violation with the clock below 14 seconds.
The clock won't be adjusted if there are 14 seconds or more on the
shot clock.
</P>
<P>
   There also is supposed to be an emphasis on cleaning up contact
in the key, particularly grabbing players coming off screens or
penetrating the lane. At the same time, offensive players won't be
able to get away with pushing off to create space.
</P>
<P>
   Suns guard Rex Chapman, a master at setting up defenders and
working off screens to get shots, believes the rules will help him
at the offensive end and are going to be murder on everybody at the
defensive end.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're going to really call it like they say they're going
to call it, you're going to really have to fight on defense,'' he
said. ``To be honest, if they're not going to let you touch anybody
on defense, there are going to be times when you just have to hope
guys miss shots.''
</P>
<P>
   There are only about a dozen players in the league who have
truly mastered the art of using screens, players such as Chapman,
Indiana's Reggie Miller, Washington's Mitch Richmond, New York's
Allan Houston and Golden State's John Starks.
</P>
<P>
   But Chapman said they all may have to adjust because the new
rules could work against them in other ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of us get down there (in the paint), and do a lot of
acting to get a call,'' he said. ``I have a feeling there are going
to be a lot of offensive fouls called if we try that stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of the Suns best defenders, Kidd and forward Clifford
Robinson, don't expect the rules to eliminate their ability to lock
up opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defense is a matter of moving your feet,'' Kidd said. ``There
are some people who say I have bad habits because I don't touch
anybody on defense. But I don't touch them because I don't like the
offensive player to know where I'm at. I think the rules will help
the offense and the defense equally. Everybody has to adjust.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still going to come down to being determined. You hear
people say some guys can't play defense, but they can. Defense
always comes down to determination.''
</P>
<P>
   With big guards such as Kidd, who is 6 feet 4, and Hardaway, at
6-8, the Suns may find they have an advantage in double-teaming on
the strong side. Players may now drop down and double-team a player
on the post even if that player doesn't have the ball. Tall guards
like Kidd and Hardaway will make it tough to get the ball over
them, yet they've got the length to recover to a shooter on the
perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said he's still learning all the changes and how
they're going to affect his game and the Suns. But he believes that
it's impossible to eliminate the contact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so used to bumping guys when they come through the lane,
that's going to be tough for me,'' he said. ``The defensive
position they're going to allow on the strong side may make it
easier to keep the ball out of some players' hands, like Shaq
(O'Neal).
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still learning it, but we'll adjust to it. I think
you'll still see a lot of bumping because it's just part of the
game. But there's definitely going to be a smoother flow to the
game. And it's going to make everybody work a lot harder, too.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
