<HEADLINE>
HIGH STICK MEANS ROENICK MUST SIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As expected, Coyotes center Jeremy Roenick was
suspended by the NHL for his high stick Friday night to the face of
good friend Tony Amonte of the Chicago Blackhawks.
</P>
<P>
   Just how long Roenick will be suspended remains to be seen. The
league ordered him to sit out today's game against the New York
Rangers pending further review.
</P>
<P>
   Roenick could be eligible to return to the lineup for Monday's
game in Buffalo, or he could face further discipline and miss
additional games depending on his hearing with Colin Campbell, the
NHL's director of hockey operations.
</P>
<P>
   A hearing could be held in Campbell's office today or Monday. It
also isn't unusual for hearings to be handled over the phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 12 years, I've never been suspended. Hopefully, that will
work to my favor,'' Roenick said. ``I haven't seen the replay, but
when Campbell reviews it, I hope he agrees it was a split-second
reaction on my part and that I had no intent to injure Tony at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just one of those things that happen in a game. I tried
to give him a whack on the hands. . . . He had his head down low,
and I guess the tip of my stick rode up and caught him on the
chin.''
</P>
<P>
   But Roenick, who received a five-minute match penalty and
automatic ejection, also hurled a stream of expletives at Amonte,
his former linemate in prep school. He said that, too, was just
part of the game, but acknowledged it was just a bad night overall.
</P>
<P>
   In Roenick's absence, the Coyotes planned to recall center
Daniel Briere from Springfield of the American Hockey League.
Rookie defenseman Radoslav Suchy, meanwhile, a healthy scratch in
the Coyotes' first three games, was assigned to Springfield. &QL; 
In 12 years, I've never been suspended. Hopefully, that will work
to my favor. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
