<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-YANKEES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS GIVE ZERO RESISTANCE AS YANKEES REPEAT '98 SWEEP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The end came swiftly and without mercy for
the Rangers at The Ballpark in Arlington last night.
</P>
<P>
   There was no lingering at the scene or any hint of drama to stir
the 50,269 fans who showed up in a surprisingly enthusiastic mood,
ready to cheer loudly at any signs of life in their team.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Strawberry sounded the death knell with a three-run homer
in the first and Roger Clemens finished the dirge with a
three-hitter over seven innings, leading the New York Yankees to
3-0 victory and, for the second consecutive year, a three-game
sweep of the Rangers in their American League Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one is definitely hard to swallow,'' shortstop Royce
Clayton said in the somber clubhouse afterward. ``We felt much
different than last year. Last year we just wanted to get in the
playoffs. This year getting to the playoffs was not our goal.
Getting to the World Series was our goal. It's very disappointing,
but we have to deal with that. We're going to have to deal with it
again next year and that's hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Mark McLemore, sitting at his locker and staring
glumly off into space, said, ``I can't describe the feeling right
now. It's very hard to take, very hard to take. We came into this
year with a better ballclub and the same thing happened again. It's
tough to deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, a franchise once known for having never been in the
playoffs, are now saddled with the stigma of a nine-game postseason
losing streak, the fifth longest in major-league history.
</P>
<P>
   For the second consecutive year, the Rangers are left wondering
how their offense can be so good during the regular season and
still score only one run in three games against the Yankees. They
batted .152 in this series, only 11 points better than their 1998
funk when they also scored one run.
</P>
<P>
   About the only thing different from the 1998 series is that Game
3 wasn't delayed by rain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a good hitting team,'' designated hitter Rafael Palmeiro
said. ``We ought to be able to hit any pitcher. I can't explain
what happened. I can't explain how we could score just one run in
three games. I'll think about it all winter.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangers starter Esteban Loaiza pitched a decent game, except for
the three-run homer by Strawberry in the first. Derek Jeter's
triple and a walk to Bernie Williams set up the blast and the
Rangers never recovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could have that first inning back,'' Loaiza said.
``That was the whole ballgame. One pitch and it could have been a
different game. We could still be playing.''
</P>
<P>
   A 3-0 deficit in the first inning never gave the Rangers cause
for alarm during the regular season. Loaiza even beat the Yankees,
7-3, on Aug. 25 despite being down 3-0 in the third inning.
</P>
<P>
   But this is the playoffs. Don Larsen is about the only pitcher
who could have saved the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a better ballclub but that's part of what makes them
so good,'' center fielder Tom Goodwin said. ``They make other teams
look not as good as they really are. It's definitely stunning.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, in getting his first playoff victory since 1986, left
after seven innings, allowing three hits and two walks while
striking out two. After Jeff Nelson allowed a single to Goodwin to
start the eighth, Mariano Rivera pitched the final two innings for
the save.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers never got a runner past second base and only once
did they get the tying run to the plate. That was with two on and
two outs in the fourth, but Clemens got Lee Stevens to ground out
to end the threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we played tight the first two games in New York,''
third baseman Todd Zeile said. ``We didn't let it all out. I didn't
see that tonight so there really isn't an explanation. The bottom
line is you have to look yourself in the mirror and say you didn't
get the job done.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
