<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-MITCHELL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MITCHELL'S DAY LEAVES SOONERS FEELING SICK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By NATHAN SANDERS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ A sinus infection had Texas running back Hodges
Mitchell playing at only about 75 percent yesterday, but it didn't
seem to slow him down when the game was on the line.
</P>
<P>
   Neither did the Oklahoma defense.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the illness, Mitchell overwhelmed the Sooners for a
career-high 216 yards on 30 carries in the Longhorns' 38-28 victory
over Oklahoma at the Cotton Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   At 5-foot-9 and 190 pounds, Mitchell is the first to admit that
he's no Ricky Williams. But on this day, he broke through with
Ricky Williams-type numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to make every game my breakout game,'' said Mitchell, a
junior from Dallas Skyline who became only the seventh UT running
back to crack the 200-yard mark. ``I was just seeing the holes a
lot better today.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell's biggest run came when Texas needed it most. Trailing
by only three points early in the fourth quarter, Oklahoma downed a
punt at the Texas 1 in front of an end zone section full of vocal
Sooners fans. After straining to hear quarterback Major Applewhite
audible, Mitchell was surprised when Applewhite turned and handed
him the ball three yards deep in the end zone on a draw play up the
middle.
</P>
<P>
   That surprise turned to excitement.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Major handed me the ball, I looked up and I said to
myself, `I'm fixin' to go 99 yards,' '' Mitchell said.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell didn't quite make it that far _ he was dragged down
from behind after a 35-yard gain _ but he got the Longhorns started
on a 99-yard touchdown drive that proved to be the clincher.
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns then put the ball in Mitchell's hands in the final
minutes to seal the game. He responded. More than half (116) of his
216 yards came in the fourth quarter, including a 27-yard run on
third-and-17.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an exciting player,'' Applewhite said of Mitchell. ``He
made some big runs today that were definitely a factor in the ball
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell said this was the most drained he had felt after a
game. But to do this well in front of his hometown crowd, it was
worth it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I treated it just like a high school game playing in front of
my fans,'' Mitchell said. ``I hope I did Dallas proud.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
