<HEADER>
A2322 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-ASTROS-BRAVES-TEX     10-10 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ASTROS-BRAVES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASTROS USHERED OUT OF DOME, PLAYOFFS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ As the Astros can attest, those who fail to learn from
baseball history are Domed to repeat it.
</P>
<P>
   As they did six times during their 35-year run in the Astrodome,
the Dis-Astros yesterday lost a playoff series in which they simply
failed to hit the baseball in the clutch. A too-little, too-late
7-5 loss to the Atlanta Braves before 48,553 eliminated the Astros
from their National League Division Series and capped a dreary Dome
era in which they never hit above .233 in the postseason and never
won a playoff series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not being able to score was the biggest frustration of the
series,'' Astros manager Larry Dierker said. ``If we get in the
playoffs next year I'm sure our stigma will grow even greater. The
only pleasure from this is knowing we don't have to come back here
because the Dome's day has gone by.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves, who rode more pressure pitching from John Rocker and
two more hits from Brian Jordan, advance to next week's NL
Championship Series against the New York Mets. Before moving
downtown into the natural-grass, retractable-roof Enron Field in
April, the Astros get to spend their off-season trying to
comprehend their latest ``Livin' La Vida Choka''.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating beyond belief,'' said Astros second baseman
Craig Biggio, 2-for-19 in the series with five strikeouts. ``We
didn't really start playing relaxed until it was too late.''
</P>
<P>
   Visibly demoralized by Friday's 12-inning loss in which they
failed to score with the bases loaded and no outs in the 10th, the
Astros continued their offensive futility early yesterday by
stranding five runners in the first two innings and digging a 7-0
hole against John Smoltz.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, Houston at least made it interesting.
</P>
<P>
   A solo homer by Tony Eusebio got the Astros on the board in the
seventh and a three-run shot by Ken Caminiti got them back in the
game in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   After a run-scoring double by Tim Bogar pulled Houston within
7-5 in the eighth, the Astros actually sent the tying run to the
plate five times. Pinch hitter Daryle Ward grounded to first and
Biggio struck out swinging against Rocker. After Stan Javier walked
to lead off the ninth and bring what was left of the crowd to its
feet, Jeff Bagwell struck out on a check-swing, Carl Everett struck
out swinging and Caminiti flied out to deep right-center to send
the Braves to their eighth consecutive NLCS.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to contain that team as long as we did,'' Braves
manager Bobby Cox said. ``We knew they had to explode at some
point, and the game sort of got on the line there at the end. But
again, Rocker was amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Brian enforced his version of Jordan Rules by
consistently making the Astros pay for pitching around Chipper
Jones with eight hits and seven RBI. The most glaring Astro-Nots,
however, continued to be stars Biggio and Bagwell. After
yesterday's 1-for-9, the two combined to go only 4-for-32 with nine
strikeouts and no extra-base hits or RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Each struck out in his last at-bat as the tying run, a microcosm
of their 10-for-81 (.123) performance during the Astros' 2-9
playoff run the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the NBA playoffs you don't allow layups and in baseball you
don't let those guys get good pitches,'' Smoltz said. ``Those are
the two guys we were determined not to let beat us, and we pitched
them well.''
</P>
<P>
   After Jones' sacrifice fly gave Atlanta a 1-0 lead in the top of
the first, the Astros again failed to score with the bases loaded
when Bill Spiers bounced out weakly to second base. In the second,
Javier grounded to third with runners on first and third.
</P>
<P>
   Including a game in which they had only one hit, the Astros
stranded 31 runners in the series.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves took a 2-0 lead in the third when Smoltz doubled and
scored on Brett Boone's single, then blew the game open with a
five-run sixth that forced thousands of fans to the exits and the
ones that stuck around to begin booing. Singles by Jordan and Ryan
Klesko chased Houston starter Shane Reynolds before reliever Chris
Holt deflated the Dome for good by allowing run-scoring singles to
Jones and Eddie Perez for a 5-0 deficit that eventually ballooned
to 7-0 before the Astros rallied.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
