<HEADLINE>
PAIN LIMITS OATES BUT CAN'T KEEP HIM OUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Rangers manager Johnny Oates came to the
ballpark yesterday feeling terrible, and it had nothing to do with
his team being down two games to the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Oates is suffering from an infection of the prostate gland, a
condition that has occasionally flared up on him over the past 28
years. It started when he was hit by a foul ball in a sensitive
area in 1971, and yesterday he was feeling particularly bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had better days,'' Oates said in his office before the
game. ``They gave me something to relieve the pain. But the
prostate is extremely enlarged.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates said this is the third time in 12 months that he's had the
problem, and he's becoming more concerned about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen a specialist, and surgery doesn't cure it,'' Oates
said. ``It's just something that flares up.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates had a 103 degree temperature Friday night but said it was
lower yesterday. He was not on the field with his team during
batting practice but was on the bench during the game.
</P>
<P>
   Only one time in his managing career has Oates been forced off
the bench because of a prostate infection. That was in 1983 when he
was managing the Yankees' Triple-A team in Columbus, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Third base coach Jerry Narron said the only reason Oates would
have missed the game was ``if he's unconscious. If he's conscious,
he'll be here.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
