u s BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-UNITED     10-10 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-UNITED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION FAIL TO GAIN PLAYOFF BERTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Revolution discovered an effective style of
play on their final day of the season. But it was too late, as they
tied D.C. United, 1-1, Saturday night, then won the shootout, but
were eliminated from playoff contention.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution finished with 26 points, 8 in the second half of
the season. They won twice in regulation time this year. The Miami
Fusion, who took a 2-0 win over Colorado, became the final team to
qualify for the playoffs with 29 points. United, who finished with
57 points, open the playoffs against the Fusion Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Nicol, who replaced player-coach Walter Zenga 10 days ago,
restructured the Revolution midfield, placing Paulo Dos Santos in
front of Leonel Alvarez. The duo helped keep the Revolution compact
and dangerous. Their combination of experience, skill, and stamina
helped set the tone for the Revolution, who wisely retained
possession for long periods in the second half, going to a slow
buildup rather than their usual hurried attack. Not only did this
quiet a boisterous crowd of 20,695, it also limited United's
possessions and relieved the pressure on the Revolution defense.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution surrendered an own goal in the second minute, but
they regained their composure and tied the score on Joe-Max Moore's
15th goal of the season five minutes into the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was common sense to do it,'' Nicol said of the
midfield combination. ``When you come to D.C., you've got to keep
the ball. I played with Paulo with the Bulldogs, and I know what he
can do. He can keep the ball, and he can pass. When the basics are
done well, it can look easy, but you have to have a certain ability
to make it look easy, and Paulo and Leonel have that.''
</P>
<P>
   The new-look midfield meant Jeff Baicher and John Harkes moved
to the outside, as they had occasionally done during other games.
But this was the first time they stayed wide for the entire game,
and Harkes provided the cross for Moore's goal.
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez chested down a hurried clearance by Carlos Llamosa, who
later departed with a knee sprain. Alvarez then calmly held
possession near the penalty area before releasing Harkes on the
right. Moore called Giovanni Savarese off of Harkes's sharp cross
and volleyed the ball in on the first bounce, giving goalkeeper Tom
Presthus no chance.
</P>
<P>
   The tie in regulation time was deserved by the Revolution,
though they were fortunate that Jeff Causey was allowed to handle
his own miskick in the second half and that Jaime Moreno missed the
game because of suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Moreno's replacement, A.J. Wood, seldom troubled Dan Calichman,
though he did provide a decent target for Marco Etcheverry, and Roy
Lassiter squandered an exceptional cross from Etcheverry at the far
post in the final minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Burns helped set the defensive tone with a hard foul on Ben
Olsen in the second minute of the game, and midway through the
second half he cleared a Carey Talley header off the line. Olsen
seldom ventured into a dangerous position after that, but
Etcheverry's free kick went off Ted Chronopoulos for an own goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could afford it, I would take out a full-page ad and
apologize to the fans,'' Calichman said. ``We deserved to be in the
playoffs, and they deserve to have a playoff team. This was the way
we should have played all year, but we put ourselves in a
predicament. If we had played like this all year, we would have
been in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked the lineup we had out there. The effort was
outstanding. You saw us beating them to the ball, and that is
effort and concentration and being sharp. That lineup can match up
against anybody in the league for talent.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nicol was hired as interim coach Oct. 30. His status for next
season is undetermined. ``Anybody wants to go as high as they can
in their profession,'' Nicol said . . . Dos Santos earned a place
on the team as a defensive midfielder during preseason training
camp in Italy, but his only previous full game was as a defender in
a 2-0 loss at Columbus May 15 before he seemed to fall out of favor
with Zenga. ``I was nervous before the game, but once it started I
had fun,'' Dos Santos said. ``That is the position I've played my
whole life, and it comes naturally to me. It's a high-profile
position, and it's a position that some of the top foreigners in
the league play. You have more freedom there, and I was just glad
to have the opportunity.'' . . . The Revolution will meet Tuesday
before disbanding . . . Savarese will return to Venezuela to play
for Caracas FC Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
