<HEADLINE>
THE LOST IS FOUND IN WILDCATS' WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. _ Arizona discovered something Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Itself.
</P>
<P>
   The picture remains incomplete, but a 31-24 victory over
Southern California at Arizona Stadium is a big piece in what is
still a puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   The win also has to be judged through the prism that is the
Pac-10. The league's look is dim and dimmer.
</P>
<P>
   But theories of relativity are for pollsters and talk-show
geeks. For the Wildcats, there is the daily task of trying to
correct a season.
</P>
<P>
   Their battle has been fought from within. They began the year
wearing T-shirts with this motto: Beat The Little Man. The
proverbial idea was to overcome that tiny voice of self-doubt.
</P>
<P>
   After five difficult weeks, the little man had grown into a
monster that was threatening to consume a season. The Wildcats were
a mystery, mostly to themselves.
</P>
<P>
   But against the Trojans, they began to recognize some of the
things they were supposed to be all along.
</P>
<P>
   ``The jury is still out, but my measuring stick is that we
played hard, spilled our guts,'' Arizona Coach Dick Tomey said
after his team (4-2 overall, 2-1 Pac-10) stayed alive in the league
race with a victory over No. 22 USC.
</P>
<P>
   For Tomey, the game was like a reunion. For the first time this
year, he saw the hard-hitting defense that has been the hallmark of
his tenure in Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's reputation for feared defense had begun to sound like
so much fiction after one missed tackle after another.
</P>
<P>
   But there were no misses on this hot afternoon. Playing in
temperatures of about 100 degrees, the Trojans offense evaporated
like the mist from the cooling machines located behind their bench.
</P>
<P>
   The heat and the Arizona defense were one and the same.
</P>
<P>
   Oppressive.
</P>
<P>
   After it was all over, the Wildcats had held USC (3-2, 1-2) to
minus-20 yards rushing. The Wildcats had seven sacks as DaShon Polk
and Idris Haroon led the way with two apiece. The Arizona defense
even did some of the scoring.
</P>
<P>
   Within the final two minutes, cornerback Kelvin Hunter picked up
a bobbled snap by USC quarterback Mike Van Raaphorst and raced 24
yards for a score that assured victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what Arizona defense should look like,'' said senior
linebacker Marcus Bell, who accounted for Arizona's second
interception of the season.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, Arizona's offense marched up and down the field
with a balance that relied on quarterback Keith Smith, running back
Trung Canidate and receiver Dennis Northcutt, who did double duty
at cornerback.
</P>
<P>
   Canidate continued to emerge from his slow start with an
unerring, workmanlike performance that resulted in 194 rushing
yards, his fourth straight game with a 100 or more.
</P>
<P>
   In what might be a promising sign, there were moments when he
looked like the Canidate who was so explosive through the second
half of last season. On an 11-yard touchdown run early in the
fourth quarter, he high-stepped into the end zone. He is beginning
to dance as the tendinitis in his knees begins to ease.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really great to see him high-kicking through the
middle, looking like a horse,'' said Smith, who contributed 87
rushing yards, including a 57-yard scoring scramble in the first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Smith augmented the ground game with poised passing. He
completed 15 of 23 attempts for 243 yards and one touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   The TD was a thing of beauty. The all-purpose Northcutt caught
the ball with with one hand as he cut across an edge of the end
zone. He grabbed the aerial with his right hand and then wedged it
against the side of his helmet.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's effectiveness might signal a change in Arizona's
philosophy. Tomey has relied on a two-quarterback system since last
season.
</P>
<P>
   But against USC, Smith was at quarterback throughout most of the
game. His only mistake was a fumble that USC cornerback Antuan
Simmons turned into a 44-yard TD early in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's counterpart, Ortege Jenkins, was at QB for only one
series late in the first half, which ended in a 10-10 tie despite
Arizona's statistical dominance. The rest of the time, Jenkins
filled in as a receiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same, the same exactly,'' Smith said when asked if
offensive coordinator Dino Babers has decided to make him the
starter and Jenkins the backup. ``Coach Babers just went with the
flow.
</P>
<P>
   ``OJ was in there as a receiver. We needed our best athletes on
the field in some way. And OJ is maybe our best. He's a playmaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no one guy.''
</P>
<P>
   On this one day, there were just a lot of reborn possibilities. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
