<SLUG> BC-FBC-ASU-NOTREDAME-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRISH CRUSH SUN DEVILS  
 TURNOVERS COSTLY FOR ASU 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH BEND, Ind. _ Presented with the opportunity to redeem
itself on national television, Arizona State really dropped the
ball.
</P>
<P>
   Again.
</P>
<P>
   And again.
</P>
<P>
   And again.
</P>
<P>
   And again.
</P>
<P>
   Five fumbles and three interceptions summarize what went wrong
in the Sun Devils' bumbling 48-17 loss to Notre Dame on Saturday.
Everything you've heard about the Pac-10 Conference? It's true.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this wasn't about a difference in talent level,'' tailback
J.R. Redmond said. ``We had the upper hand early and shot ourselves
in the foot.''
</P>
<P>
   The bad news: ASU is 1-6 in its past seven road games and visits
a Washington team that is starting to show some muscle.
</P>
<P>
   The good news: Ummm, hmmm, uh . . . Nope, nothing comes to mind.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils dominated the Fighting Irish early in front of a
sellout Notre Dame Stadium crowd of 80,012. But the Irish scored 27
second-quarter points, 20 off turnovers, and were in command the
rest of the way. They increased their lead to 41-0 in the third
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys started falling apart. You could see it,'' ASU defensive
end Erik Flowers said. ``All year, we've been killing ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils left South Bend with some big-time concerns:
</P>
<P>
   Although a healthy Ryan Kealy looked sharp much of the game, his
alter ego also surfaced and he was intercepted three times. He was
clearly frustrated with himself afterward and wouldn't talk to the
media.
</P>
<P>
   Redmond left in the third quarter after re-injuring his
shoulder. Both the tailback and Coach Bruce Snyder said it was in
worse shape than a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils also helped Notre Dame quarterback Jarious
Jackson have a career day. He tied a school record with four
touchdown passes and also ran one in. He was 10 of 17 for 223 yards
and no interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``He makes plays,'' Fighting Irish Coach Bob Davie said. ``He is
playing the best football of his career.''
</P>
<P>
   ASU seems to bring that out in people.
</P>
<P>
   The tide turned in the second quarter after Jackson hit split
end Bobby Brown with a 42-yard scoring pass.
</P>
<P>
   On the next play, Kealy underthrew Delvon Flowers and the pass
landed in the hands of safety A'Jani Sanders, who returned the ball
28 yards for a touchdown. Suddenly, it was 14-0.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, it was 21-0. ASU's next possession ended when tight
end Todd Heap, who made an impressive catch at the Notre Dame
25-yard line and tried to get extra yards, fumbled. He got knocked
by defensive end Grant Irons, and safety Deke Cooper recovered.
Five plays later, Jackson found tight end Dan O'Leary for a 6-yard
touchdown pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to get a couple of extra yards and got hit from behind
and didn't expect it,'' Heap said.
</P>
<P>
   It was a rare mistake for a player who was otherwise brilliant,
with eight receptions for 100 yards, both career highs.
</P>
<P>
   The Irish took advantage of a another Kealy interception and
scored on the next play. Jackson connected with Joey Getherall for
25 yards to give Notre Dame a 27-0 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The halftime score didn't matter,'' Flowers said. ``We felt
like we could come back from that.''
</P>
<P>
   But that wasn't the case. Notre Dame rolled up 211 more yards of
offense in the second half and outscored ASU, 21-17. The highlight
(lowlight?) was a 48-yard Jackson run early in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ASU didn't score until late in the third on a Gerald Green
1-yard run. A 5-yard pass from Griffin Goodman to Brian Jennings
with 48 seconds in the game resulted in another touchdown, and the
Sun Devils got three points earlier on a Stephen Baker 45-yard
field goal. Previously, he missed one from 24-yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are taking responsibility for the way we played,'' Snyder
said. ``This team was really excited about being here and they
wanted to play a great game. It's extremely disappointing for all
of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Said linebacker Adam Archuleta, ``We will bounce back from this.
Something this team has to learn is that bad things are going to
happen but you just have to be oblivious to them. We're going to
recover. We've got to trust our coaches and trust our team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fighting Irish, meanwhile, improve to 3-3 and play host to
Southern California on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today was a great example of what happens when you don't turn
over the football,'' Davie said.
</P>
<P>
   And what happens when you do.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
