<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-OFFENSE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDS' POINTS DWINDLE, BUT HOPE FOR OFFENSE RISES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Their offense looks like something that needs to
be lanced.
</P>
<P>
   Each week, the Cardinals seemingly find ways to bottom
themselves, or at least that is the perception as their point
totals dwindle, from 25 to 16 to 10 to 7.
</P>
<P>
   The reality is that they are not that far away from breaking
out.
</P>
<P>
   They have more first downs than their opponents (68 to 61), have
a better third-down conversion percentage (32.8 to 32.1), have lost
fewer fumbles (four to five), have the same number of punts (24),
and have been outgained by only 38 yards a game. Over the final
three quarters of games, the Cardinals have outscored foes, 58-50.
</P>
<P>
   ``We probably have played even better than we did early last
year, yet we're nowhere near where we want to be right now,''
offensive coordinator Marc Trestman said.
</P>
<P>
   Where they have buried themselves is with pass interceptions in
the first quarter _ five of their 13 _ leading directly to being
outscored, 52-0, in the first 15 minutes and to the 1-3 start that
has wary eyes cast on the offense with the New York Giants coming
in for a 1 p.m. game today at Sun Devil Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals are ready for a breakout mentally. Physically,
they might not be ready, and by the time the Cardinals get well on
the offensive side of the ball it might be too late. They can
afford no more than six losses and expect to get back to the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we talked about after the Dallas game was that we've been
on a spiral downhill that we've got to stop,'' Trestman said.
``It's been ugly. We haven't been at the standard we want to
perform at. We had to come back out here on the practice field and
work on getting better with an understanding that we will if we
stay focused and stay together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we will do that.''
</P>
<P>
   One would think so, given the Cardinals' personnel. Jake Plummer
was hyped from coast to coast as one of the game's most exciting
and promising young quarterbacks. In Rob Moore, Frank Sanders and
rookie David Boston, Plummer would be throwing to as strong a
threesome as any in the NFL. New tight end Terry Hardy has been a
pleasant surprise who has added a dimension.
</P>
<P>
   With the passing game clicking, three-time 1,000-yard rusher
Adrian Murrell should have no trouble providing the threat of the
run to keep a defense honest. Up front are a lot of sturdy young
players, one of the league's largest lines, who have been brought
along in the Cardinals' development program.
</P>
<P>
   It was expected that the Cardinals would have a powerful,
high-scoring attack capable of carrying a defense weakened by the
loss of both starting tackles.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it has been the defense that has kept the team in games
while the Cardinals deal with widespread injuries on offense,
starting with the groin and throwing hand thumb of Plummer.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer appeared in three preseason series, 15 snaps. Although
he has played in every regular-season game, he practiced little
through the first two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've been getting better and better as the weeks go
by,'' Plummer said. ``But sometimes when you practice better during
the week, it doesn't automatically transfer onto the field, and
that's what's been happening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope we show we're coming around as an offense. That would
be great against a defense as good as the Giants'. As soon as
everyone is out here healthy, I know we'll start to jell and start
looking like a unit that can move the ball up and down field.''
</P>
<P>
   Plummer doesn't have to be told that his two touchdown passes
against 12 interceptions doesn't cut it. His 31.8 quarterback
rating not only is last in the NFC and next to last in the league
among starters, it ranks only third on the team. Backup Dave Brown
is at 38.9. Running back Michael Pittman is at 118.8 on the basis
of completing his only attempt on an option.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jake's had three weeks of practice,'' Trestman said. ``You can
see the development and improvement each day. I think a lot of what
has happened is about turnovers and not really having the big play
being part of our offense right now, not having the big run or the
short throw with a big long run. There hasn't been anything that
gives us a jump-start.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had some opportunities in the red zone we haven't been
able to convert. We've fumbled twice on the 1-yard line, which
hasn't helped us. It hasn't gone anywhere near the direction we
want it to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Spotting the other team two or three touchdowns is no formula
for success.
</P>
<P>
   It also renders useless the exercise of preparing a game plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``What has really inhibited the growth of our offense is we've
gotten down so quickly in games, we've really never had a chance to
run a game plan,'' Trestman said. ``We're down 21 at Philadelphia,
down 17 against San Francisco, down 21 against Dallas. So we've
never had to function in a normal environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's kind of a state of the union.''
</P>
<P>
   Sputtering along at a 246-yards-a-game pace isn't what was
envisioned for the group. Only San Diego and Philadelphia have
total offenses rated lower. Even with the big play non-existent,
the Cardinals easily could be 3-1 absent the turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a similar pattern each week _ we fall behind, we
have to play catch-up from then on, and we haven't played catch-up
well,'' Coach Vince Tobin said. ``Usually what happens when you
turn it over and you're not moving is you lose. Until that changes,
the result is not going to change.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether it changes today against the Giants (2-2), who have won
four straight from the Cardinals by dominating with physical
players, is questionable.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer has not known from week to week which receivers will be
available. Moore is out today because of a hamstring injury.
</P>
<P>
   Boston is expected to play, but he has a sore shoulder. He
hasn't had a chance to concentrate on learning the third receiving
spot. He had to learn Moore's spot during Moore's holdout, and he
had to learn Sanders' spot when Sanders had a sprained ankle.
Boston, 21, came out of Ohio State a year early and is the youngest
player in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   With Moore out, and backups Andy McCullough (hamstring) and Mac
Cody (hamstring) slowed, it could be difficult for Plummer to
throw.
</P>
<P>
   Up front, starting tackles Matt Joyce (knee) and James Dexter
(groin, triceps) have been slowed. Dexter is out today. Starting
guards Chris Dishman (elbow surgery) and Lester Holmes (facial cuts
suffered in an auto rollover) missed most of the preseason and are
just now returning to game condition.
</P>
<P>
   Murrell, at the quarter-season mark, has 198 rushing yards. He
hasn't reached the 60-yard mark in a game yet, and his 2.7-yard
average doesn't scare defenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to say it because everybody wants results now, but the
running game takes timing, and that comes with practice together,
which we haven't had a lot of,'' Murrell said.
</P>
<P>
   It's no mystery, then, why the offense has not been on top of
its game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adrian hasn't had a chance to perform under conditions where
there has been some continuity in the game,'' Trestman said.
</P>
<P>
   Reducing turnovers, getting an early lead, getting Murrell
going, getting players healthy, getting Plummer back to his
confident playmaking self would help, Tobin agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we'd still like to be able to run our offense,'' Tobin
said. ``We're not interested in going into a shell and all at once
becoming like turtles afraid to do anything, because I think that's
the worst thing that we can do.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-10-99 0211EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
