</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-SCHOENFELD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WILD CARDS' MAY EASE REALIGNMENT FOR BIDWILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Regardless of which realignment proposal NFL owners choose, the
Cardinals are done playing the Cowboys home-and-home as of 2002.
</P>
<P>
   It will take a miracle for the Cardinals not to be shifted out
of the NFC East. Every realignment plan has them in the NFC West
with San Francisco, St. Louis and an AFC team.
</P>
<P>
   But  &UR; Dan Rooney, the Steelers owner who is the godfather of
realignment, thinks he has found a way to soften the blow for
Cardinals owner  &UR; Bill Bidwill, whom he has known since the two were
infants.
</P>
<P>
   The eight-division, four-team format would allow a team to play
two wild-card games each year, along with six division games, four
games against other teams in its conference and four games against
teams in the other conference.
</P>
<P>
   Rooney thinks the Cardinals often could play the Cowboys as one
of their two wild-card games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to Billy about it, and he has told me that Dallas
is the only team that has sold out (Sun Devil Stadium) every
year,'' Rooney said. ``I totally understand in his situation, the
Cardinals against the Cowboys could be a game that's played most
years. As it is, they'll play each other every three years,
anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Rooney thinks the two wild-card games will soften the blow for
the six teams that are going to be displaced from their current
divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the wild-card games would be rivalry games _
Jets-Giants, 49ers-Raiders, Dallas-Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Another annual wild-card game would be the match-up of the two
Super Bowl teams from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can have games in which some teams play strong vs. strong
and weak plays weak,'' Rooney said. ``You can take care of some
long-standing rivalries and account for even some rivalries that
aren't geographical, such as Carolina vs. Jacksonville, two former
expansion teams that came in the same year.''
</P>
<P>
   A Cowboys official said the two wild-card games that would
interest them the most would be Houston and Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys like that their west Texas and New Mexico fans can
see them play each year at Sun Devil Stadium. El Paso is closer to
Tempe than it is to Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Cowboys game at Sun Devil Stadium is one of
their biggest paydays each year, and money will talk in
realignment. Teams don't want to lose the big revenues they get
from certain visiting gates. The Cardinals, for instance, receive
their biggest visitors' check when they play at Washington's new
stadium because of the Redskins' high ticket prices and many club
seats.
</P>
<P>
   The league also can make it financially worthwhile for teams to
move out of their divisions. The last time the NFL realigned in
1970, three NFL teams _ the Browns, the Steelers and the Colts _
were paid $3 million each to move to the AFC.
</P>
<P>
   The realignment plan likely won't be voted on for almost two
years. It will take only 21 votes to pass because the Rams, Ravens
and Titans don't have votes as conditions of their franchise
shifts.
</P>
<P>
   Expect realignment to cause one other scheduling change.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Cardinals play the 49ers, Falcons, Packers and
Lions as their four non-division NFC games. But beginning in 2002,
the NFC East would play the NFC Central one year, the NFC West
another and the proposed NFC South the third year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really feel that to have true winners, the more common
opponents you have, the better,'' Rooney said. &QL; 
McGinnis in running? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Former Redskins General Manager  &UR; Charley Casserley is expected
to land an executive position with the new Houston team.
</P>
<P>
   Two coaching candidates have surfaced _ Broncos offensive
coordinator
 &UR; Gary Kubiak, a former Texas A&AMP;M quarterback who was raised in
Houston, and Cardinals defensive coordinator  &UR; Dave McGinnis, a
Texas Christian University product who is from Snyder, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because it's my hometown and stuff, that's why it's a topic,''
Kubiak said. ``But I've got enough problems right here to worry
about.''
</P>
<P>
   McGinnis, who turned down the Bears' head coaching job last
January, said he is flattered that his name has been mentioned but
that his ``only concern is beating the Giants'' today. &QL; 
Lopsided rivalry &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Rams have much history to overcome in today's game against
the 49ers in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   They've lost 17 consecutive times to the 49ers, the longest
current streak in the NFL and the third most lopsided streak in
league history.
</P>
<P>
   Only Buffalo, which lost 20 games in a row to Miami from 1970
through 1979, and Detroit, which has lost 18 in a row to the
Redskins, have longer losing streaks.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the games between the 49ers and the Rams during the
streak haven't even been close. Fourteen of the 49ers' 17 victories
have been by 15 points or more.
</P>
<P>
   Often during the streak, the Rams gave the 49ers bulletin-board
material.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, former Rams safety  &UR; Toby Wright, a Mesa Dobson High
School product, said the 49ers were ``sweating bullets'' over
playing the Rams.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, Rams wide receiver  &UR; Isaac Bruce said he
couldn't wait to step on the 49ers' throats. Another time,
cornerback  &UR; Todd Lyght said the Rams had better personnel than the
49ers.
</P>
<P>
   So what's the Rams' theme today:
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep your mouth shut,'' Bruce said. Play football.'' &QL; 
Honeymoon over &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Things have gotten so bad in Denver, where the Super Bowl
champions are winless, a Broncos fan hit cornerback  &UR; Dale Carter
with a battery in last week's loss to the Jets at Mile High
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was real surprised,'' Broncos quarterback  &UR; Bubby Brister
said. ``I've said since the day I got here that Denver has the best
fans in the country. They understood football, they were a little
smarter than the places I've been. But they turned hostile on us
last week.''
</P>
<P>
   Raiders wide receiver  &UR; Tim Brown, who will play against the
Broncos today in Oakland, called the actions of the Denver fans
``sad.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Two championships in a row, they have a down year with all the
major adjustments they have to make . . . they're bandwagon
jumpers,'' Brown said, ``and I guess they're jumping off the
bandwagon in Denver, which is unbelievable after a team wins
back-to-back Super Bowls.''
</P>
<P>
   Broncos Coach  &UR; Mike Shanahan isn't worried about the fans. He's
furious about a story in this week's ``Sports Illustrated ''that
quotes an unidentified player as saying the team could go 0-8 and
finish 3-13.
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan discussed the story at a team meeting Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Hey, I don't know if someone said that, but if
someone feels we're going to be 0-8 or we're going to wind up 3-13,
please let me know _ I'll send you out of here so quick. I don't
care if you want a bus ticket or a plane ticket. Just let me know.'
'' &QL; 
Quick kicks &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Colts second-year quarterback  &UR; Peyton Manning is the latest NFL
player to get his own breakfast cereal _ Peyton's O's, a honey-nut
toasted cereal produced by the same company, Famous Fixins, that
made Jake's Flakes, Cardinals quarterback  &UR; Jake Plummer's cereal.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys quarterback  &UR; Troy Aikman on this year's upside-down
season: ``I don't know that anybody right now knows how good they
are.'' &QL; 
THE RANKINGS &QL; 
 &UR; THE TOP FIVE &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1. Dallas &QL; Before Cowboys fans book &QL; 
their Super Bowl trip, they &QL; 
should check Dallas' &QL; 
November schedule. &QL; 
 &QL; 
2. New England &QL; Has any unbeaten team
gotten less respect? &QL; 
 &QL; 
3. Green Bay &QL; Even retired, former Packer  &UR; Reggie White continues to
be a distraction. &QL; 
 &QL; 
4. Jacksonville &QL; The latest NFL feud is quarterback  &UR; Mark Brunell
vs.
Coach  &UR; Tom Coughlin. The quarterback will win. &QL; 
 &QL; 
5. Buffalo &QL; There's nothing sweeter to western New Yorkers than
annual fish fry of Dolphins. &QL; 
 &UR; THE BOTTOM FIVE &QL; 
 &UR; 31. Cleveland &QL; It's Bengals week, the Browns'
best chance to win this season. &QL; 
 &QL; 
30. Philadelphia &QL; How bad does QB  &UR; Doug Pederson have to get before
he
gets dumped? &QL; 
 &QL; 
29. Cincinnati &QL; Team President  &UR; Mike Brown wouldn't mind going 2-14
if
the victories were against the Browns. &QL; 
 &QL; 
28. Atlanta &QL; Attention: Coach  &UR; Dan Reeves. &UR; QB  &UR; Tony Graziani can't
play. &QL; 
 &QL; 
27. Denver &QL; Coach  &UR; Mike Shannahan's &UR; team will be a permanent fixture
in the cruddy quintet until it wins. &QL; 
ON THE RISE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Buffalo Bills: With home games the next two weeks against
Pittsburgh and Oakland, the surprising Bills could be 5-1. Their
offense is mediocre, but the defense, led by veteran  &UR; Bruce
 &UR; Smith, is one of the league's best. It has allowed only one
touchdown in the past three games. ``We know we have a lot of
talent,'' free safety  &UR; Kurt Schulz said. ``I don't know if the rest
of the NFL knows that, but I think we're proving that.'' &QL; 
GOING SOUTH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Tampa Bay Buccaneers: The Buccaneers could have the best
defense in the league since the 1985 Bears. But their offense is
27th overall, 28th in passing. Running backs  &UR; Warrick Dunn and
 &UR; Mike
 &UR; Alstott could play for anybody. Their young receivers are getting
better. The problem is quarterback  &UR; Trent Dilfer. He's not good
enough to take them to the next level. It's that simple.  &QL; 
OVERHEARD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Bills Coach Wade Phillips, on how he celebrated Monday
 &UR; night's victory over Coach Jimmy Johnson's Dolphins: ``I didn't go
in and stomp on a can of hair spray or anything.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
ODD-SHAPED BALL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There's a logical reason why the Chiefs lost to the Chargers a
week ago. There weren't enough facts on the Internet for Chiefs
Coach  &UR; Gunther Cunningham to learn all he needed to know about the
Chargers.
</P>
<P>
   ``San Diego stinks,'' Cunningham said, referring to the amount
of information on the Internet about the Chargers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't get any good information out of San Diego. When you
have a media outlet like San Diego, you might as well go to
Tijuana.''
</P>
<P>
   It saddens Cunningham that San Diego is a one-newspaper town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care what people are saying about us,'' Cunningham
said. ``I want to know the little things about other teams. Or
maybe a player will slip and say something that will give me an
inkling of some change.'' &QL; 
SHORT SHOTS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Five of the league's top 15 rushers from a year ago aren't even
dressing for games, including the top four _ the Broncos'  &UR; Terrell
Davis (knee injury), the Falcons'  &UR; Jamal
 &UR; Anderson (knee), the 49ers'  &UR; Garrison Hearst (ankle) and the Lions'
 &UR; Barry Sanders (retirement).
</P>
<P>
   Colts Coach  &UR; Jim Mora doesn't agree with the assesment of the
Dolphins' Johnson that Miami quarterback  &UR; Dan Marino is slipping:
``How can you not say nice things about Dan Marino? My God. He's as
good as any quarterback to play the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Chiefs owner  &UR; Lamar Hunt was told ``thanks a million'' by a
reporter after Hunt returned his call. ``No, thanks to $700
million,'' said Hunt, referring to the price tag of Houston's
expansion team.
</P>
<P>
   Former Cardinals punter  &UR; Jeff Feagles of the Seahawks helped
save last week's victory against the Raiders with a punt that
stayed airborne for 5.2 seconds, the longest hang time of his
12-year career.
</P>
<P>
   Includes information from other media sources. Steve Schoenfeld
can be reached at 444-8334 or by e-mail at
steve.schoenfeld(at)PNI.com &QL;
</P>
