<HEADLINE>
CARDS NEED DEFENSE VS. SCAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Federal court documents unsealed Thursday in
Austin claim that three current and three former Cardinals were
among the NFL players duped into investing $5.5 million in an
illegal scheme run by an Austin resident.
</P>
<P>
   The three current players _ defensive tackle Eric Swann, tight
end Johnny McWilliams and receiver Chad Carpenter _ all said Friday
that they did not invest a cent.
</P>
<P>
   Whether they did or didn't really is their business. It will
come out in the process. Their names are in the court documents.
They more than likely will give depositions or be called as
witnesses against 29-year-old Brian Russell Stearns of Austin, who
was arrested at his home by FBI agents last month.
</P>
<P>
   The greater concern is how any shady figure gets to these guys.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy. Too easy. Scary easy.
</P>
<P>
   All three acknowledged being approached to invest in the scheme.
According to Swann, the contact was made in the parking lot at the
Cardinals' Tempe facility following a practice last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm approached by I bet four people a year out there with
stuff that you know is shady,'' Swann said. ``It's not right. They
shouldn't even be able to get that close to us.''
</P>
<P>
   He is absolutely correct.
</P>
<P>
   Though the building and practice fields are secured with locks,
guards and surveillance equipment, the players' parking lot is not.
There are hangers-on out there every day, most of them innocent
autograph-seekers.
</P>
<P>
   The players claimed Friday they were bright enough to see
through this scam. Swann said he had mentioned it to Carpenter, who
had been an intern with an investment brokerage firm and is
knowledgeable about such things. Carpenter notified NFL security,
he said. McWilliams, who according to documents invested $100,000,
said he, too, notified the league's security department.
</P>
<P>
   The unsealed court documents indicate that former players Lomas
Brown, now with the Cleveland Browns; Larry Centers, now with the
Washington Redskins; and Duval Love, now retired, invested.
</P>
<P>
   FBI agents suspect the players invested in DFJ Italia, which was
operated by Stearns. He is accused of receiving $5.5 million from
players in a wire transfer from Los Angeles sports agent Robert
Caron, according to a report in the ``Austin American-Statesman.''
Contacted by the newspaper, Caron said, ``It's a complete surprise
to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Court documents charge that Stearns worked with Florida
businessman Jerry Vosselman in telling investors they would have
access to secret overseas markets that would generate huge returns
over short terms _ guaranteed 40 percent every 35 days on some.
Only Stearns has been charged.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said they believe Stearns bilked $31 million from
investors from March 1998 until this July. Last week, Stearns also
was indicted by a federal grand jury in New York in connection with
$26 million allegedly defrauded from foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
   Stearns is accused of using the money to support an extravagant
lifestyle that includes a $2.2 million home near Austin, two jet
aircraft, a helicopter and more than $1 million worth of vehicles.
The ``American-Statesman'' reported that Stearns began to float in
high political circles, including fund-raisers for President
Clinton and Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Stearns' attorney, Laird Palmer, denied that Stearns was
involved in any criminal wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   The incident is a wake-up call for the players.
</P>
<P>
   It also should be one for upper management: Secure the players'
parking lot. &QL; 
Lee Shappell can be reached at (602) 444-8254 or by e-mail at
lee.shappell(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
