A2336 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s BC-FBC-ARIZONA-NORTHCUTT     10-10 0525
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARIZONA-NORTHCUTT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UA'S NORTHCUTT A 1-MAN TEAM  
 COLLAPSES AFTER WIN VS. USC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ Dennis Northcutt set an Arizona record for receiving
yardage, returned punts, scored a touchdown, played cornerback and
conducted interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Then he collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   An exhausted Northcutt fell flat on his face in a room beneath
Arizona Stadium on Saturday after meeting the media following the
Wildcats' 31-24 victory against Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   He was suffering from cramps, which were brought on by
dehydration after a long afternoon under a hot sun.
</P>
<P>
   He fell to the floor from a chair as Arizona Coach Dick Tomey
answered initial questions from the media. Tomey interrupted the
interview session and rushed to help his star receiver.
</P>
<P>
   As Tomey resumed the post-game news conference, Northcutt moaned
in evident pain. He was iced down by Arizona's medical staff, which
eventually lifted him from the concrete floor and out of the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just a guy giving it up, giving all of it up,'' Tomey
said.
</P>
<P>
   The stark, yet dramatic moment summed up perhaps the best game
in what already has been a brilliant season for Northcutt.
</P>
<P>
   With his 121 yards on eight receptions, Northcutt became
Arizona's all-time leader in receiving yardage with 2,580. He also
is one game short of tying a Pac-10 record of 37 straight games
with at one catch.
</P>
<P>
   Those are impressive numbers on any scale. But a different scale
has begun to apply to Northcutt, a leading candidate for the
Biletnikoff Award, the prize given to the nation's best receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Tomey is using his talent as often as possible. Late in the
second quarter, the senior lined up at cornerback, his position
when he arrived at Arizona as a freshman.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't wind up with any interceptions. But his sudden
appearance on defense seemed to surprise the Trojans just enough to
knock them off-track.
</P>
<P>
   Northcutt said he had seen a look of bewilderment in the eyes of
USC receiver R. Jay Soward.
</P>
<P>
   ``He lined up once, glanced my way and sort of stopped for a
second,'' Northcutt said before he collapsed. ``Then, on the next
play, I looked over at him and said: `Yes, this is me.' He just
looked back at me like he was stunned.''
</P>
<P>
   In part, Northcutt was pressed into defensive duty because of
the overall weakness in the Arizona secondary. Northcutt said he
was asked if he could handle the additional work in preseason camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd been working at it some for a few weeks,'' he said. ``But
this was the time. USC was the game to spring it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to do whatever helps us win. God gave me the athletic
ability to play both ways. Ever since my freshman year, I've never
stopped doing defensive-back work.''
</P>
<P>
   For Northcutt, the win against USC was especially gratifying. He
grew up on the mean streets that surround the Trojans home field,
Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know a lot about USC,'' he said. ``I kind of grew up with
USC football. For me, I guess there is some motivation in that. We
had to win.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter what. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
