<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ASU-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ST. MARY'S GRAD LOSES KICKING JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH BEND, Ind. _  &UR; Jim Sanson knew this chance was his last.
</P>
<P>
   The Notre Dame senior kicker from Scottsdale missed a chip field
goal Saturday when the game against Arizona State was still
scoreless. In 12 tries going back to last season, Sanson has missed
nine. Not to mention 15 career missed extra points, particularly
the infamous 1996 misfire against Southern California that
conspired to keep the Irish out of the Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Sanson persevered and continued to outduel all comers in
practice until two short misses last week against Oklahoma, when a
loss would have left the Irish at 1-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim Sanson knew the situation going into the game,'' said
Notre Dame Coach  &UR; Bob Davie, who turned to sophomore  &UR; David  &UR; Miller
after the 33-yard miss against ASU. ``He knew he had to be
productive.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller was just that, going 6 for 7 on extra points for his
first Irish points, with the exception being blocked. He did not
attempt a field goal but will from here out, Davie said.
</P>
<P>
   Sanson, a high-school teammate of ASU quarterback  &UR; Ryan Kealy,
who was his holder at St. Mary's, will continue to kick off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was proud of the way (Sanson) stayed in the game on kickoffs
and even got a touchback,'' Davie said.
</P>
<P>
   Sanson, close to tears afterward, said the weight of his spotty
career is heavy: ``I knew I only had one chance,'' he said. ``I
knew that going out. That was on my back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got booed going out there and booed coming in. That's usual
here at Notre Dame. I've gotten used to it. But in the back of my
mind all I was thinking about was being booed by the fans.'' &QL; 
Briefly &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ASU received $600,000 for the privilege of having its 48-17
embarrassment nationally televised by NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Despite being outscored, 77-25, in its first two tries against
Notre Dame, the Sun Devils hope to renew the series on the earliest
possible occasion. That won't be before 2008.
</P>
<P>
   As long as the Irish remain an independent in football, they
will have openings, and have told ASU officials that their Pac-10
preferences are Southern California, Washington, Stanford and the
Devils.
</P>
<P>
   Some 4,000 Chicago-area ASU alumni attended the game, as did a
group of close to 200 Fiesta Bowl sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame (3-3) is perhaps No. 1 on the wish list of the Fiesta
Bowl-owned Insight.com Bowl in Tucson, although the Irish hope to
place themselves higher on the postseason pecking order. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
