<SLUG> BC-FBC-IRISH-JACKSON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRISH QB BURIES PERSIST ENT GHOSTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH BEND, Ind. _ Three consecutive passes for three
touchdowns. His longest career run in the first half, bettered in
the second for another score. A fourth passing touchdown, tying the
school record.
</P>
<P>
   Jarious Jackson not only buried Arizona State on Saturday but a
few more of the ghosts that persistently haunt Notre Dame
quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   The Heisman winners: Angelo Bertelli, John Lujack, Paul Hornung,
John Huarte. Theismann and Montana, your not-so-average Joes,
following Terry Hanratty and leading to Steve Beuerlein.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Powlus never dodged the ghosts, regularly being booed even
while he wrapped up his career two years ago as the school career
passing yardage and touchdown leader. Jackson, the people's choice
over Powlus, came next.
</P>
<P>
   He was what Powlus wasn't, mobile, in taking the Fighting Irish
to a 9-1 record and the brink of a berth in the Bowl Championship
Series. But as he tried to run out the final three seconds of a win
over Louisiana State, Jackson was blindsided low and taken out of
the regular-season finale with a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame lost for a third straight year to Southern California
then, with Jackson back but hurting, to Georgia Tech in the Gator
Bowl. The losing stretched to five out of six with this year's 1-3
start as Jackson battled a turf toe in agonizing defeats by a
combined 19 points to Michigan, Purdue and Michigan State.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Jackson became the fall guy. Except that the
fifth-year senior is too good to be stepped on for long.
</P>
<P>
   His string of five consecutive passing games of 220 yards or
more seems repeatable against any of the Fighting Irish's six
remaining opponents except perhaps Tennessee. And with his toe
better and the offense jelling under new coordinator Kevin Rogers,
who's to say Jackson won't keep up his 100-yard rushing average of
the past two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is playing the best football of his career,'' third-year
Notre Dame Coach Bob Davie said. ``That is a special statement
considering all he has done for us at Notre Dame.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Snyder said it was a much improved Jackson who took out
his Sun Devils with five touchdowns and 316 yards of total offense.
Consider that Jackson passed for 69 yards with one touchdown and
rushed for 7 when the Irish won, 29-8, in Tempe last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Rogers has helped a lot with his diverse offense,''
Jackson said. ``That's the type of offense that can show my
talents. I'm concentrating more on being a better quarterback,
being more accurate on my throws, being more decisive on the option
pitches and trying not to turn the ball over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mentally, I'm not taking any downs off right now.''
</P>
<P>
   With Notre Dame up, 27-0, thanks to his 3-for-3 touchdown
string, Jackson could have taken the second half off. Instead, he
took Davie's halftime critique of the Fighting Irish being ahead
but not in control to heart, ripping off a career-high 48-yard run
on a perfectly executed option.
</P>
<P>
   That was 4 yards longer than his first-half breakaway that only
a diving tackle by Courtney Jackson prevented from going for 50
yards and another rushing touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Davie labeled some of Jackson's early-season option decisions as
silly. But in bringing his team back from 30-14 to beat Oklahoma,
34-30, and against ASU, Jackson worked the defense like Silly
Putty.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have 3-4 defenders around you, you have nowhere else
to run, that's when you just fall down and go to the next play,''
Jackson said. ``When I have the offensive linemen and backs
standing up and I can see the blocking from a certain angle, then
I'll keep going for it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-10-99 0218EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
