<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ASU-KEALY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEALY STILL NO. 1, DESPITE MISCUES  
 BAD DECISIONS LEAD TO 3 INTERCEPTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH BEND, Ind. _ When all was said and undone, Arizona State
quarterbacks coach John Pettas said, ``I still have confidence in
Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   But for how long?
</P>
<P>
   The two sides of ASU quarterback Ryan Kealy surfaced Saturday
against Notre Dame. He was on-target much of the time, taking
advantage of an offensive line that held its own against the
Fighting Irish.
</P>
<P>
   But he also made a handful of bad decisions that resulted in
three interceptions. One was returned for a touchdown, and the
other set one up.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just got to regroup,'' Pettas said. ``I really thought he
was fine other than the critical mistakes. Take away the mistakes
and we'd be thinking differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Kealy wasn't talking afterward, more out of frustration with
himself than with the media. No one on the team takes losses harder
than the junior quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``He shoulders a lot of the blame himself,'' Pettas said. ``But
he's the quarterback and that's the way it should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Kealy completed 18 of 30 passes for 196 yards and no touchdowns.
One interception was intended for Tariq McDonald but ``just got
away from him,'' Coach Bruce Snyder said.
</P>
<P>
   Another, that was intended for Delvon Flowers, was poorly thrown
and landed in the hands of safety A'Jani Sanders, who returned it
for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   The last was a long pass downfield to Richard Williams that was
overthrown and intercepted by Deke Cooper. The Fighting Irish
scored one play later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Ryan was emotionally ready for this game,'' Snyder
said. ``I felt he threw the ball pretty well, excluding the
interceptions.''
</P>
<P>
   Quarterbacks John Leonard and Griffin Goodman both saw playing
time in the second half. Leonard came into the game in the third
quarter and completed 2 of 4 passes for 21 yards. He led the drive
that resulted in Stephen Baker's 45-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman was 4 of 5 for 46 yards and a touchdown. He also
engineered the game-winning scoring drive against UCLA last week.
</P>
<P>
   Kealy had left last week's game because of injuries, but that
wasn't the case this time. Snyder and Pettas said afterward that
Kealy was cleared for the game to play and didn't express concern
about his health.
</P>
<P>
   Bruised ribs and an injured right knee have sidelined him much
of this season.
</P>
<P>
   Even though some disgruntled ASU fans may cry for a quarterback
change, don't look for it to happen.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the three interceptions, Kealy didn't play himself out
of a job. And even though the backups show promise, neither one
made a strong enough argument to take over.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if Kealy was upset afterward, Snyder said, ``Of
course. He cares a great deal about this football team.''
</P>
<P>
   Snyder hopes that care translates into a victory. Soon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
