</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-OBERJUERGE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA DEFENSE DELIVERS AT FINISH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL OBERJUERGE  
 San Bernardino County Sun  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA _ After being missing nearly as long as Amelia
Earhardt, the UCLA defense was discovered Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   In the Rose Bowl, of all places. Making a difference in a
football game, if you can imagine.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps you heard about UCLA's defenders. Never around when you
needed them. As elusive as the Loch Ness Monster. Rumored, but
never actually seen. Much like Big Foot.
</P>
<P>
   A football team's defense is supposed to be its anchor. UCLA's
was its millstone, particularly last season when the Bruins scored
points in bunches _ and gave them up nearly as fast.
</P>
<P>
   Had the 1998 Bruins shown the slightest ability to cover and
tackle, they might have won the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA won its first 10 games thanks to Cade McNown &AMP; Co.; it lost
its last two behind the most inept defenders since France 1940.
</P>
<P>
   The most appalling demonstration was the nationally televised,
49-45 loss to Miami that knocked the Bruins out of the Fiesta Bowl
and made a first-round draft choice of a Hurricanes running back
named Edgerrin James. UCLA's defense that day gave up 689 yards and
what little remained of its self-respect.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA had the Pac-10's best offense in 1998 but its second-worst
defense, allowing a staggering 432 yards and 27.5 points per game.
</P>
<P>
   A new season brought more of the same.
</P>
<P>
   After five games (including three defeats), UCLA was giving up
453 yards and 28 points per game. It was torched by Stanford, then
allowed Arizona State to go the length of the field for a
game-winning, last-gasp drive.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's game vs. Oregon at the Rose Bowl didn't augur any
improvement. In the first 65 seconds, the Ducks threw three passes
that went for a net 86 yards and a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon 7-0, just like that.
</P>
<P>
   Then a strange and wonderful thing happened: UCLA's defense
began making plays. A sack here. A deflected pass there. An
open-field tackle over there. Two fumble recoveries and an
interception that set up 14 UCLA points.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon's offense disappeared. Its running game was stuffed. Its
passing offense was negated in a swarm of rushing Bruins linemen
and tight-covering DBs.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon quarterback A.J. Feeley completed only eight of his next
28 passes, and UCLA bolted to a 34-10 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins' defense was the best unit in the game. It mattered.
</P>
<P>
   Then the offense, in a role-reversal, let Oregon back in the
game, giving up an 81-yard interception return for touchdown. And
the Ducks got hot.
</P>
<P>
   A 44-yard TD pass after a short UCLA punt. A 10-yard TD run
after a UCLA fumbled kickoff return. Suddenly, it was 34-29.
</P>
<P>
   But UCLA's defense stepped up again. And again and again. It had
to, because the offense couldn't muster even one first down to help
kill the clock.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon had three possessions in the final 5:02, but the Bruins
stopped all three. One by interception. Another on downs. The last
by about 36 inches.
</P>
<P>
   OK, it was close, but that doesn't count.
</P>
<P>
   On the final drive, Oregon went 79 yards. It needed 80. On the
last play, the Ducks needed 21 yards. They got 20. Marshaun Tucker
was dragged down at the 1 by Joey Strycula and Joe Hunter, and the
final second ticked off.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA defense had won a game, even if the score was 34-29. For
the first time in a while, they made the plays they needed to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys played their butts off,'' UCLA coach Bob Toledo
said of his defensive players.
</P>
<P>
   They played so hard, they won a game. That's news on the order
of man bites dog. At UCLA, it's also a relief.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-10-99 0254EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
