<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA'S FARMER BACK IN A GROOVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA _ It's no coincidence UCLA snapped a losing streak at
two games the night All-American receiver Danny Farmer emerged as
the Bruins' primary playmaker.
</P>
<P>
   Farmer connected with quarterback Cory Paus the way he teamed
with Cade McNown last year _ catching seven passes for 196 yards
and two touchdowns in UCLA's 34-29 victory over Oregon on Saturday
in the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   His yardage total was the second-best in UCLA history, behind
J.J. Stokes' 263-yard performance against USC in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Farmer, who missed most of training camp and all of two games
because of a sprained left ankle, is gradually finding his groove.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cory's settling down a lot, and the offensive line gave him a
lot of protection, a lot of time,'' Farmer said. ``I think I'm to
the point where I'm on the same page as the quarterback and the
offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Home sweet home: Shaken and road weary, its season on the brink,
UCLA began the home-heavy portion of its schedule Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins play five of their last six games in Southern
California. Four are at the Rose Bowl, and the fifth, at USC, is a
few miles away at the Coliseum. The lone remaining road trip is
Oregon State, on Oct. 23.
</P>
<P>
   Bruins coach Bob Toledo believes the home-field advantage lies
not in the field or the familiar surroundings or a good night's
sleep _ the Bruins spend home Fridays in a Pasadena hotel, anyhow _
but in the crowd and the sideline support.
</P>
<P>
   Pac-10 rules limit travel squads to 60 players. Because the
offense and defense often huddle on the sideline when they aren't
playing, Toledo said, there aren't many bodies standing in support
of the unit on the field.
</P>
<P>
   But a team can dress as many players as it wants for home games
and rivalry games, so the Bruins will have constant support for
five of their last six.
</P>
<P>
   The home crowd helps, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a home-field advantage,'' Toledo said. ``It was a good
crowd, very vocal. It helped to motivate our kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Precious hours: No one seemed to benefit from the 7:25 p.m.
kickoff more than Bruins tailback DeShaun Foster, who's recovering
from a sprained ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Had the game started at 12:30, Foster might not have played.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are important hours,'' Toledo said. ``He can get a
couple more treatments in.''
</P>
<P>
   As it was, Foster played one snap, ran for 11 yards and tweaked
the ankle trying to cut. He spent the rest of the game on the
bench, his status for Saturday's game against Cal in question.
</P>
<P>
   Strange call: When UCLA's Ryan Nece blocked an Oregon punt in
the third quarter, it appeared the Bruins would have sparkling
field position to add to their 27-10 lead. Instead, Oregon retained
possession.
</P>
<P>
   The reason: After Nece's block, the ball hit UCLA's Gabe
Crecion, which signaled a change of possession. When Oregon
recovered the loose ball, it was awarded first down as if it had
been a normal UCLA fumble.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great call, although I didn't tell them that at the
time,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   Uniforms that don't conform: Oregon's new uniforms _ which
include an ``O'' on the helmet where the Duck used to be _ have
drawn mixed reaction. The black and green home jerseys are not as
popular as the white and green road uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``The helmets are awesome and I think most people agree,'' Ducks
coach Mike Bellotti said. ``You always run the risk of change. We
talked about establishing a new tradition. It's an attempt to
change our image to a more aggressive nature.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-10-99 0308EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
