<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-10 03:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2356 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN     10-10 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA HOLDS OFF OREGON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADEN _ Five-point lead, four seconds left, UCLA's defense on
the field. No, not a soul had left the Rose Bowl, especially those
who saw the last-minute collapse last week at Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coaches told us to stand on the goal line and not let
anything behind us,'' Bruins safety Joey Strycula said. ``Once they
threw it in front of me, I knew we were OK.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, the Bruins held. They held by 1 yard _ 1 measly yard
_ as Oregon's final pass ended three feet short of the game-winning
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   But close didn't matter in the aftermath of the Bruins' 34-29
victory Saturday before 55,674 at the Rose Bowl _ not to a UCLA
team that snapped its two-game losing streak and kept its
postseason hopes alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of eerie, the same situation _ one minute left,
and they had to drive 80 yards,'' Strycula said, alluding to the
ASU game. ``I'm kind of relieved. We stopped them this time. It
feels great. We were so sick of hearing that crap about how the
defense (stinks).''
</P>
<P>
   It was a typically wild UCLA-Oregon game, with nine turnovers,
massive momentum shifts, 63 points and 897 yards offense.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins took a 20-10 halftime lead after forcing back-to-back
turnovers and converting them into two second-quarter touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   When UCLA opened the second half with two more touchdown drives
_ both ignited by long passes from quarterback Cory Paus to
receiver Danny Farmer _ its 34-10 lead seemed insurmountable.
</P>
<P>
   But a Paus interception and Lovell Houston's fumbled kickoff
return quickly became Oregon touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   With 11 minutes left, UCLA's lead had dwindled to five.
</P>
<P>
   With four seconds left, the Ducks were 21 yards from victory.
But quarterback A.J. Feeley's pass to Marshaun Tucker, with
Strycula and Eric Whitfield defending, was one yard short of the
goal line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We created a lot of our own agony, but we pulled it out,''
Bruins coach Bob Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   Farmer and Paus were the standout performers. Farmer caught
seven passes for 196 yards, while Paus looked more comfortable than
he did against Arizona State and completed 21 of 34 passes for 332
yards and two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's defense, with former coordinator Nick Aliotti on the
Ducks' sideline, played its best game of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon scored 16 points off UCLA turnovers and did not generate
a lengthy scoring drive after the first quarter. The Bruins (3-3,
1-2) contained Oregon's running game and pressured Feeley into bad
throws and three turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing we're better at is stopping big plays,''
linebacker Ryan Nece said. ``That's what has hurt us. But we're
developing an attitude, and we showcased that tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks scored first, covering 84 yards on three plays on
their opening series for a 7-0 lead. The big play was a receiver
pass from Keenan Howry to Enyi Nwamuo for 38 yards to UCLA's 20.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon tailback Reuben Droughns fumbled on the next series,
giving UCLA possession at the Ducks' 20. But the Bruins, so
devastating in the red zone last year, did nothing with the
opportunity _ gaining one yard in three plays before Chris
Griffith's line drive field goal was blocked.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon had a chance to take command when UCLA's Ryan Roques
fumbled a punt at the 21. But the Bruins held for three downs at
their 1, forcing the Ducks to kick an 18-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA offered a quick riposte, moving 45 yards in seven plays.
The biggest was a 31-yard pass from Paus to Farmer. Four plays
later, Griffith boomed a 48-yarder, and Oregon's lead was 10-6.
</P>
<P>
   The goal-line stand seemed to energize UCLA's defense. First,
defensive end Santi Hall sacked Feeley and forced a fumble that was
recovered by linebacker Billy Pieper at Oregon's 18. Three plays
later, Keith Brown rumbled around left end for the Bruins' first
touchdown and a 13-10 lead.
</P>
<P>
   On the first play of Oregon's next possession, Feeley threw an
errant crossing pass to Tucker. Bruins linebacker Marcus Reese
stepped in front for the interception, giving UCLA possession at
the Ducks' 33. On third-and-one from the 11, Paus hit Farmer on a
curl route in the end zone, and UCLA had a 20-10 lead as the half
ended.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's big lead began to unravel when Paus' short pass to the
left side was intercepted by linebacker Matt Smith, who raced 81
yards for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks scored on their next possession, then again a few
minutes later, when Houston's fumbled kickoff return gave Oregon
first down on UCLA's 21.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
