<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-10 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2384 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH-CONSERVATIVE11-C     10-10 1338
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CONSERVATIVE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush's idea of conservativism criticized
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Seven months into his presidential campaign,
George W. Bush is discovering the bumps in the middle of the
political road.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush is getting traction with his effort to show that his
self-styled ``compassionate conservative'' label is not oxymoronic,
the strategy also invites attacks from the party's right lane.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wobbly moderate,'' is how GOP foe Gary Bauer tags Bush's brand
of politics. And Steve Forbes, in an upcoming high-dollar TV ad
campaign, will target what Forbes campaign manager Bill Dal Col
calls ``Bush's moderate mush.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the criticism, and thanks to fund raising and poll
numbers indicating it would take a political earthquake to shake
his hold on the party nomination, Bush has not allowed the sniping
from the right to divert him from his more moderate message.
</P>
<P>
   It's a path not without peril. ``I think he's a
middle-of-the-roader,'' said Bob Mann, a New Jersey home-school
parent who recently heard Bush speak and doesn't think the Texas
governor is conservative enough. ``With the `compassionate
conservative,' he's trying to play both camps.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite that kind of criticism, several recent developments
indicate Bush shows no signs of swerving from the path that's made
him the front-runner. In fact, some of the events offer evidence of
an effort to move more toward the middle as Vice President Al Gore
faces the possibility of having to veer left to fend off a suddenly
serious challenge from Democratic rival Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Three recent events show Bush as a candidate who believes he
cannot be defeated from the right, a development allowing him to
chart the kind of centrist path to the White House made famous by
Bill Clinton:
</P>
<P>
   When congressional Republicans devised a bill to finance their
spending plans by delaying payment of tax credits for working-class
families, Bush cautioned against balancing the budget on the backs
of the poor. Within days, the plan was dead. The move could help
protect him against ongoing efforts by the Democratic National
Committee to show Bush is in lock-step with a GOP Congress not
widely viewed as the model of lawmaking efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   When the Christian Coalition gathered this month in Washington,
Bush offered up his standard stump speech and made no mention of
school prayer, gay rights and other issues of burning concern to
social conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   Bush got the warmest reception of the candidates at the meeting
and drew this seal of approval, on national TV, from Christian
Coalition President Pat Robertson: ``I think he's committed to the
agenda, but at the same time he's running for president. He's aware
of that. He's aware that he needs to be portrayed as a centrist
candidate.'' Robertson, though still a Bush fan, later cautioned
that Bush's more recent criticism of the GOP could ``alienate the
core conservatives of the Republican Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, in announcing education policy, Bush went out of his
way to scold his own party for too often being `d on the
national economy, to the exclusion of all else _ speaking a sterile
language of rates and numbers, of CBO this and GNP that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too often,'' Bush said, ``on social issues, my party has
painted an image of America slouching toward Gomorrah.''
</P>
<P>
   A day later, Bush softened up a bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was making the case that the conservative philosophy is a
compassionate philosophy,'' he said. ``I'm talking from my heart,
and I hope the Republican Party appreciates it.''
</P>
<P>
   BACKLASH FROM GOP HARD-LINERS
</P>
<P>
   But some within the party did not. From the right, vitriol
flowed from Bauer, an aggressive campaigner who believes every
half-step of his campaign is worthy of a news release. (Last week's
highlight: ``Prominent African-American Pastors from Alaska Endorse
Gary Bauer.'')
</P>
<P>
   On the same day Bush spoke of the GOP's focus on ``rates and
numbers,'' Bauer torched him.
</P>
<P>
   ``George W. Bush this week sent Republican conservatives an
unmistakable message: I don't need you,'' he said. ``Mr. Bush is
distancing himself from the conservatives in the Republican Party
and running as a wobbly moderate under the banner of compassion.
This is seen most clearly in his embrace of big-government,
Washington-knows-best nostrums on education.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's education plan, fleshed out in a speech last week in
Manhattan, calls for federally mandated annual testing by the
individual states of all third- through eighth-graders.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer also said Bush is ``AWOL in the culture war, which is
hardly surprising in view of the hundreds of thousands of dollars
the Hollywood elite have contributed to his campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Bauer told Bush to take a hike.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not need to weaken or water down our conservative
message in order to counter the false and distorted caricature of
conservatives as uncaring and lacking compassion as offered up in
the elite liberal media,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush believes his conservative credentials are confirmed by the
kind of people _ including experts from Stanford University's
Hoover Institution _ who are helping him devise policy.
</P>
<P>
   But Bauer, not content with Bush's day-after attempt to soften
his criticism of the GOP, said, ``the front-runner weasels and
waffles and tries to explain away his comments by saying he did not
mean what plainly he did.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, coming from the right and standing ready with an ad
campaign that will brand Bush as a tax-and-spender, said Bush
``clearly comes across as being embarrassed by the basic principles
of his party _ more freedom and less government.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also fielded some flak from the conservative whose voice
reaches more Americans every day than any other.
</P>
<P>
   ``My humble opinion,'' said radio commentator Rush Limbaugh,
``and for what it's worth to the W. campaign: You people shouldn't
be running to the left of congressional Republicans. You should be
even further to the right than they are. More tax cuts, stronger
defense. Break the back of the liberal monopoly.''
</P>
<P>
   BACKING FROM BOTH CAMPS
</P>
<P>
   But Bush backer Mary Matalin, a former political adviser to the
elder George Bush, said on CNN that Bush's efforts have been
misread by conservatives who are criticizing him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not compromising his principles, he's not running against
Congress,'' Matalin said. ``He's trying to undo the damage done by
Democratic demagogues who defined, wrongly, the conservative
movement. He's recasting it for the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also got an attaboy that could provide fuel for foes who
fear Bush is dangerously moderate. U.S. House Minority Leader
Richard Gephardt of Missouri praised Bush in a letter to the
governor Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears that your influential relationship with House
Republicans may have helped convince some of them that (proposing
to stretch out payment of the earned income tax credit) was a bad
idea that should be rejected,'' Gephardt told Bush. ``I hope this
is just the first step you will take to provide guidance to try and
steer House Republicans towards the mainstream on a number of other
critical issues. You often say that conservatism can indeed be
compassionate. Unfortunately, your allies in the Republican
leadership just don't get it _ compassion isn't at the top of their
agenda. I hope that you will use your position as the Republican
front-runner to help set the House Republican leadership back
towards the center.''
</P>
<P>
   And, in a peculiar twist that could help Bush on the GOP side,
the National Abortion Rights Action League _ not meaning to help _
said Friday that Bush has earned his conservative credentials.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a meeting with leaders of the Christian right, Bush
reassured conservatives that he was not soft on the abortion
issue,'' the group noted, referring to a press account of a Bush
meeting last month with conservative leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
