<TEXT>
<P>
   Add N.Y. Times News Service budget for papers of Monday, Oct.
11:
</P>
<P>
   CULTURE
</P>
<P>
   (Coded e)
</P>
<P>
   BRIDGE-OPERA-OPENING (Chicago) _ In the aftermath of the world
premiere of ``A View From the Bridge,'' four years after it was
commissioned from the composer William Bolcom and the librettist
Arnold Weinstein, the creators and performers were ebullient,
thrilled by the enthusiasm of an overall audience reaction that
seemed to confirm their highest hopes. Part of The Creation of an
Opera series. By Bruce Weber.
</P>
<P>
   BRIDGE-OPERA-REVIEW (Chicago) _ Although it does not break new
ground in the genre, or even attempt to, ``A View From the
Bridge,'' the new opera based on Arthur Miller's 1955 play, is an
admirable and often affecting work that convincingly solves the
problem of translating this play into an opera. By Anthony
Tommasini.
</P>
<P>
   MUSEUM-MAYOR-NOCOMMENT (New York) _ Within a week after Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani first threatened to evict the Brooklyn Museum of
Art over the ``Sensation'' exhibit, so many of the city's
high-profile art institutions signed a letter objecting to his
actions that it was the holdouts who were conspicuous by their
absence. Few of the abstaining organizations would comment on the
issue, which has been a widespread and often impassioned topic of
conversation around the city. By Barbara Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   WRITERS-ON-WRITING (Undated) _ For many decades now I have been
a fiction writer, and from the first I was aware that mine was a
questionable occupation. The Writers on Writing series, this week
by Saul Bellow.
</P>
<P>
   SOULS-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ At the heart of Martin Booth's
novel, ``The Industry of Souls,'' is a story of darkness and light:
a light that shines not only in the fields, woods and vegetable
gardens of the Russian town of Myshkino _ from the incipient
thawing of the 1970s to the post-communism of today _ but more
singularly, in this Tolstoyan tale, in the black tunnels of
Sosnogorsklag. By Richard Eder.
</P>
<P>
   LIMON-DANCE-REVIEW (New York) _ The Limon Dance Company has come
up with a winner in its company premiere and revival of Sophie
Maslow's 1948 ``Champion,'' a terse tale about an antihero, a man
of the people who exploits the people. By Anna Kisselgoff.
</P>
<P>
   TV-DATELINE-REVIEW (Undated) _ When it comes to eyewitness
testimony, you can't always believe your eyes. Such is the lesson
of Monday's ``Dateline'' report on a Greenwich Village murder in
November 1990. By Walter Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded f)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-PRIVACY (Undated) _ So far, on issues of consumer
privacy, Internet companies have prevailed upon government
regulators to allow the industry to police itself. Thanks to the
online industry's campaign, led by Christine Varney, a former FTC
commissioner, the self-policing approach seems to be prevailing on
both sides of Atlantic _ but at what cost to consumers? By Steve
Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   UNIVERSAL-FILMS (Hollywood) _ After a disastrous 1998, with
box-office flops like ``Babe: Pig in the City,'' and ``Meet Joe
Black,'' Universal Films is having its most profitable year ever,
on the strength of movies that include ``Notting Hill'' and
``American Pie.'' Is this the result of Universal's management
makeover or simply a string of good luck? By Rick Lyman. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   APPLE-SOFTWARE-RESURGENCE (Cupertino, Calif.) _ Much has been
said and written about the turnaround at Apple Computer in recent
years. But the seeds of Apple Computer's remarkable renaissance
were sown in a contentious meeting that took place here in January
1997 and that involved the unsung part of Apple's business:
software. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   SOFTWARE-DEVELOPMENT (Undated) _ When the Clinton administration
recently announced plans to relax restrictions on exports of
data-scrambling software, a key fact that escaped notice was that
the new policies affect only shrink-wrapped software, not the
original source code _ the lines of instructions that programmers
actually write. The exclusion threatens to constrain software
developed under the ``open source'' model, most notably the Linux
operating system. By Peter Wayner.
</P>
<P>
   HDTV-STANDARDS (Washington) _ Facing angry opposition, nearly
300 of the nation's 1,600 television stations filed a petition with
the Federal Communications Commission on Friday, formally
requesting a revision in the nation's digital-television standard
that was approved almost three years ago. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   E-COMMERCE-COLUMN (Undated) _ Companies hoping to do business on
the Web are being bombarded with more ``solutions'' than ever _ all
promising to provide services that address the problem of how to
set up shop online. By Bob Tedeschi.
</P>
<P>
   DIGICOM-COLUMN (Undated) _ The technology sector's blazing
financial success in the last three years has been largely a North
American phenomenon. But some forward-thinking investors have been
moving offshore toward untapped markets and investments, often
pushing communication technologies into underdeveloped countries in
Latin America and Asia. By Denise Caruso.
</P>
<P>
   CONFERENCE-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ The theme of the 1999 annual
conference of the Association of National Advertisers is ``Brand
Building for the 21st Century.'' But it might as well be called
``Payback Time III.'' That's because for the third consecutive
year, the advertiser association is selling sponsorships of daily
general sessions of the conference to media companies seeking to
promote themselves to an audience of potential clients. By Stuart
Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-ONLINE-MEDIA (London) _ As Britain's broadsheet
newspapers eye the Web, their traditional, no-holds-barred
competition has taken a new turn and the fabled wars of what used
to be known as Fleet Street have spilled into cyberspace. By Alan
Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   DEFINING-NEWS-MEDIA (Undated) _ How do you decide what is news?
These days, there are so many outlets and news organizations or
quasi-news organizations pumping out information that many things
seem to matter, at least for a moment. A better question may be,
How do you decide what news lasts? Media column by Felicity
Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   REPORTER-SOURCES-MEDIA (Los Angeles) _ A reporter for a magazine
published by a civil rights group has been subpoenaed to provide
tape recordings and notes of an interview with a defendant in an
allegedly race-motivated murder case, after she told a federal
investigator that the man acknowledged committing a murder. By
Christian Berthelsen.
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA-TALK (Undated) _ Notes from the media world.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Notes on computing and online life.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-CALENDAR (Undated) _ Key government figures this week.
</P>
<P>
   BOND-CALENDAR (Undated) _ The week's planned offerings.
</P>
<P>
   EQUITIES (Undated) _ Equity issues coming to market this week.
</P>
<P>
   DIVIDEND-MEETINGS (Undated) _ Major meetings this week.
</P>
<P>
   BIZGLANCE (Undated) _ Major financial stories at a glance.
</P>
<P>
   PATENTS (Undated) _ The weekly patents column. By Teresa
Riordan.
</P>
