<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-10 15:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2444 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v AM-NYT-BUDGET &LR;      10-10 1198
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(th) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR MONDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Monday, Oct. 11:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   PALESTINIANS-GUNS (Nablus, West Bank) _ A shootout at a wedding
has propelled Palestinian officials into a crackdown on thousands,
if not tens of thousands, of illegal weapons, as required by every
peace accord since 1995. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-YUGO-AID (Washington) _ The Clinton administration is
strongly opposing plans by the European Union to provide heating
oil and other humanitarian aid to selected cities in Yugoslavia to
help ease lingering hardships caused by NATO's air war in the
Balkans, American and European officials said. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Grozny, Russia) _ A visit to the front shows
that both Russian and Chechen forces are taking heavy losses and
that Russian troops do not control the territory they have claimed.
By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-DEFENSE (Brussels, Belgium) _ A plan to create a defense
arm for the 15-nation European Union is stirring fears among
American civilian and military officials in NATO about unnecessary
replication the allies can ill afford. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   TIMOR-U.N. (Dili, East Timor) _ The U.N.-backed mission said
Sunday that it will triple the number of peacekeeping troops along
the border with the Indonesian-controlled half of the island in an
effort to thwart violence by anti-independence militias. By Philip
Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   ERITREA-ECON (Massawa, Eritrea) _ War with neighboring Ethiopia
has already begun undermining the Eritrean economy, once a bright
spot on the continent, and the longer it drags out, the harder it
will be for the nation to recover. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   KYRGYZSTAN-GERMANS (Rotfront, Kyrgyzstan) _ The 300 ethnic
Germans who live in this well-kept town are part of one of the
world's most rapidly disappearing ethnic minorities: Germans in the
former Soviet Union. By Stephen Kinzer. (With a map.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
