<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-10 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2454 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-APPLE-SOFTWARE-RESURG     10-10 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLE-SOFTWARE-RESURGENCE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUCCESS IN REVAMPING SOFTWARE IS CLUE TO TURNAROUND AT APPLE 
</HEADLINE>
 - ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT  (ART ADV: Photo NYT1 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CUPERTINO, Calif. _ Much has been said and written about the
turnaround at Apple Computer Inc. in recent years, as measured by
its return to profitability, the resurgence of its share price and
the explosive sales of its fruit-colored iMac machines. But in
fact, the seeds of Apple Computer's remarkable renaissance were
sown in a contentious meeting that took place here in January 1997
and that involved the unsung part of Apple's business: software.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting was held only days after Apple's chairman at the
time, Gilbert Amelio, purchased Steven Jobs' Next Computer. Next's
chief software designer, Avidis Tevanian, was huddling for the
first time with Apple's top engineers. The session, according to
several people who participated, escalated into a shouting match
between Tevanian and the head of Copland _Apple's troubled effort
to create a next-generation operating system.
</P>
<P>
   As Tevanian recalls the meeting, he simply stated that he was in
charge and that, because he had a deep technical grounding in
computer science, it would be impossible for programmers to pull
the wool over his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   But to several of Apple's beleaguered managers, it sounded as if
Tevanian was arrogantly telling them that Next had just acquired
Apple and that he was taking over.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever actually transpired, Tevanian recalls leaving the
meeting with the belief that Apple's technical culture was severely
flawed. ``There were people who were saying, `We're going to work
on what's cool and we're not going to be held accountable,''' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Today that is an impression of Apple Computer that no longer
applies.
</P>
<P>
   Tevanian won the confrontation, the Copland effort was
subsequently scrapped and most of Apple's software managers were
forced from the company.
</P>
<P>
   The revamping of Apple's software effort is the untold story
behind Apple's turnaround, which has led to two consecutive
profitable years; a rebound from the single digits to more than 10
percent in the company's PC industry market share, and Apple's
buoyant stock price, which closed on Friday at $65.5625, more than
double its price 52 weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, while almost all of the reporting on Apple's reversal in
the wake of Amelio's ouster and Jobs' return to Apple as ``acting''
chief executive in July 1997 has focused on the company's
reinvigorated industrial design, new products and glitzy marketing,
it is the story of the steady improvement of Apple's existing
Macintosh software operating system that has done the most to
solidify the company's loyal customers, while giving the computer
maker a means for attracting new ones.
</P>
<P>
   And while Jobs, 44, has carefully presented himself as the
single public face of the revitalized computer maker (which he
co-founded in 1976), it is Tevanian, 38, working largely outside of
the public eye, who has re-energized Apple's programming force and
sharpened its efforts.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 23, Apple plans to begin shipping Mac OS 9, the fifth
upgrade of its operating system software since Tevanian came to
Apple.
</P>
<P>
   Such a prolific series of updates bespeaks a discipline and
efficiency that is not only new for Apple, but rare in the software
industry. And the new operating system will have a range of new
features that are expected to be highly attractive to current and
potential Macintosh users. Significantly, too, a number of the new
wrinkles, including an improved version of its Sherlock search
tool, seamless Internet file sharing and a simple password
``keyring'' that keeps all of a user's security information in one
place, are innovations not found in Microsoft's industry-dominant
Windows operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the new version comes as Microsoft is visibly struggling
with its own software development system, and the computer industry
is watching carefully to see how quickly and completely Microsoft
will be able to ship a more solid and bug-free version of its
Windows NT operating system, recently renamed Windows 2000.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft executives acknowledge that they are well aware of
Apple's new software virtuosity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've noticed,'' said Yusuf Mehdi, a Microsoft executive who
ran the company's marketing effort for Windows 98. ``They've gotten
their software act together.''
</P>
<P>
   But the best testimony comes from Apple's software developers _
the outside programmers who create software that runs on the Mac OS
and who are benefiting from Apple's rising computer sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apple developers like to complain and it was easy to complain
in the early 1990s,'' said David Shayer, a developer at Sentient
Software, a small Macintosh software firm in San Carlos, Calif.
``But although I may not like Steve Jobs, I'm selling software.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The change at Apple is largely the result of a rare chemistry
between Jobs and Tevanian. Jobs is legendary for both his aesthetic
sense, which is not often found in the computer industry, and his
willingness to take risks and gamble on new and unproven
technology. Tevanian has a reputation for staying focused and being
pragmatic.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs lectured his original team of Apple Macintosh programmers
that ``real artists ship.''
</P>
<P>
   Tevanian has adopted a variation of that theme. ``Shipping
software is a good thing,'' he said during a recent interview in
his office, where he sits surrounded by computer monitors.
</P>
<P>
   Over 13 years of working together, initially in the face of
adversity at Next, which was never financially successful, Jobs'
well-chronicled mercurial qualities have been matched by the
ability of Tevanian, who is known as Avie, to be the consummate
engineering manager _ tough but even-keeled. Significantly, it was
Tevanian and not Jobs who took the witness stand earlier this year
during the Microsoft antitrust trial to recount the story of
Apple's bitter behind-the-scenes dealings with Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   The two men met in the mid-1980s, after Jobs lost his battle for
control of Apple Computer with its president, John Sculley, when
Macintosh sales were slow to take off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was traveling to different campuses trying to get a better
understanding of the education marketplace and Avie was a starving
graduate student, so I took him to dinner,'' Jobs recalled. At the
time, Tevanian was already well known in elite computer science
circles for his role in developing a modernized version of the Unix
operating system, known as Mach, while he was at Carnegie Mellon
University.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs wooed Tevanian by telling him that he was willing to bet
his new computer company Next on the Mach software. In return,
Tevanian agreed to join the small start-up, turning down a
competing job offer from Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-10-99 1621EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991010.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-10 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2455 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-APPLE-SOFTWARE-RESURG     10-10 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLE-SOFTWARE-RESURGENCE-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 CUPERTINO, Calif.: from Microsoft. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Bud Tribble, now a Sun Microsystems executive, was a manager at
Next when Tevanian came aboard in 1988, fresh from Carnegie Mellon
with a Ph.D. in computer science. He recalls Tevanian as being
``self-confident and bright'' and quickly rising to run Next's
software operating system group.
</P>
<P>
   ``A key quality, shared by many who successfully work for Steve
Jobs, is that he could definitely hold his own with Steve,''
Tribble said. ``I think Steve admires that, as long as it is clear
that the person really knows what they are talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Tevanian's friends say that for many years, during which Next's
software received high technical marks but failed to catch hold in
the PC marketplace, Tevanian would often speak wistfully about the
large number of Microsoft stock options he had forgone by signing
on with Next. But Tevanian's patience has been vindicated. In 1997,
when he left Next to come to Apple, he received almost 400,000
Apple stock options, potentially worth $27 million at the stock's
current price.
</P>
<P>
   But then it is Tevanian's role in bringing new rigor to Apple's
software operation that has had much to do with the company's
improved financial standing. Apple's operating system strategy,
which is based on shipping a major release each year and a minor
upgrade six months later, is already contributing significantly to
the company's profitability. Although the numbers are not reported
separately in Apple's annual report, Jobs said last week that Mac
OS was now contributing $50 million a year in profit to the
computer maker, which had $300 million in total profit in 1998.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Turning Apple's decade-and-a-half-old operating system into a
cash cow has been one of Jobs' cleverest accomplishments since
returning to Apple. When he sold Next to Apple in late 1996, many
people in the computer industry expected that Apple would simply
replace its aging Mac OS with Nextstep, the elegant but
commercially unsuccessful operating system developed by Tevanian.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Jobs has chosen an approach of gradually trickling the
Next technology into the Mac OS, while continually pushing back the
introduction of a completely new operating system, now known within
the company as Mac OS X.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs said in a recent interview that customer test versions of
Mac OS X would appear early next year, but that a final version
would not reach the market until later in 2000 _ a significant
delay, compared with the original timetable, which called for the
new system to appear by the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Several former and present Macintosh software engineers, who
would speak only if they were not identified, said the company
still had an imposingly large amount of work left to finish on the
project. That would suggest that Jobs and Tevanian, for all their
success in updating the current Mac OS, may have simply succeeded
in delaying the same crucial transition that the company failed to
make nearly three years ago, when it canceled its ambitious but
troubled Copland project.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than merely delaying a potentially wrenching
transition, Jobs contends that he realized there was still plenty
of potential growth in the existing Mac OS.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realized that we were the owners and caretakers of one of
only two high-volume operating systems in the world, and that this
was a wonderful place to be,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
