<DOCNO> NYT19991010.0059 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-10 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2456 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DEFINING-NEWS-MEDIA-N     10-10 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEFINING-NEWS-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAISING QUESTIONS ABOUT WHAT NEWS LASTS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Minn., N.Y., Mass.)   (jw) 
 By   FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Any journalist who gives a talk to a lay audience is almost
certain to be asked, ``How do you decide what's news?''
</P>
<P>
   These days, the question may need to be rephrased. There are so
many outlets and news organizations or quasi-news organizations
pumping out information that many things seem to matter, at least
for a moment. A better question may be, ``How do you decide what
news lasts?''
</P>
<P>
   The news of the past couple of weeks offered two very different
answers.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 29, The Associated Press presented media audiences with
two disturbing reports. First, it offered its own voluminously
documented account indicating that American troops massacred
hundreds of civilians in the first days of the Korean war. Second,
it revealed that in a Playboy interview, Jesse Ventura, the
Minnesota governor and the Reform Party's most visible leader,
dissed the devout. ``Organized religion is a sham and a crutch for
weak-minded people who need strength in numbers,'' Ventura was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
   The Korea story, pieced together over more than a year by three
Associated Press reporters on two continents, went up like a
rocket. It drew on the accounts of the survivors of the massacre at
No Gun Ri and the soldiers who participated, all of whom were
quoted by name. Newspapers in major markets, including The New York
Times, played it prominently, as did the networks' evening news
programs, along with CNN, Fox News and National Public Radio. Time
and Newsweek each did a report. Defense Secretary William Cohen
ordered an investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Not half bad. For about four days, news organizations followed
the Pentagon's reaction and published reports about the AP account.
But after the first accounts and editorials, there was little to
add. The editorial murmurs of regret faded away, with the exception
of Wednesday's searing responses from James Webb, a combat Marine
in Vietnam and a former Navy secretary, who offered a sympathetic
view of the soldiers in an essay in The Wall Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   Compare the arc of the No Gun Ri coverage with that of the
Playboy interview. Brief news accounts about the
wrestler-turned-governor's brash remarks appeared on Thursday,
Sept. 30, but generally played inside newspapers. The interview was
mentioned that night on the evening news programs of NBC, Fox and
ABC. But it was a pipsqueak of an item, compared with No Gun Ri.
</P>
<P>
   At first.
</P>
<P>
   But over the next week, while less and less was said about No
Gun Ri, more and more was said about Jesse Ventura. The Reform
Party's national chairman had denounced Ventura shortly after the
first news accounts of the Playboy interview. Ventura defended
himself and did not apologize. On Sunday morning, the governor's
remarks were revisited on NBC's ``Meet the Press.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Ventura coverage escalated. His statements were
again dissected in a Newsweek cover article focusing on him and the
maybe presidential candidates Warren Beatty and Donald Trump.
   The brouhaha was back on ABC's evening news on Monday and was
featured on CNN's ``Larry King Live.'' Ventura declined to appear,
but his former colleague Hulk Hogan was there.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Oct. 6, Ventura was at the Kennedy School of
Government at Harvard University taping a segment of CNBC's
``Hardball With Chris Matthews.'' That evening, the Harvard
appearance was featured on NBC's evening news.
</P>
<P>
   The No Gun Ri and Playboy-Ventura reports broke the same day.
Both were fueled by new developments a day or two later. The only
other developments and commentary were generated by news outlets
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   News has always been fed by a sense of ongoing struggle, which
puts the No Gun Ri revelations at a disadvantage. Those events
happened long ago and are difficult to reconstruct. The Associated
Press spent 14 months reporting and writing its account and the
memory of CNN's Tailwind debacle last year prompted caution inside
AP, according to two AP editors, and may have done the same in
other newsrooms.
</P>
<P>
   In the coming days, attention may well shift back to No Gun Ri;
correspondents and producers for ``Dateline NBC'' and CBS' ``60
Minutes'' are continuing to explore the topic, as are some print
journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Their work, prompted by the painstaking AP account, could make
Americans rethink a small piece of their history. Which is one way
to define news.
</P>
<P>
   By that definition, the Playboy interview was news, too. It
might make people rethink their views of the Reform Party, which
could, in turn, affect that party's viability in the presidential
race.
</P>
<P>
   But why, in the second week, was Jesse Ventura covered more
closely than No Gun Ri? Because mixing controversy and celebrity
gets attention. And news that raises Nielsen ratings is news that
lasts.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
