<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-10 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2474 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CONFERENCE-AD-COLUMN-     10-10 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONFERENCE-AD-COLUMN-760&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AD COLUMN: MEDIA COMPANIES PAY HANDSOMELY FOR THE RIGHT TO PROMOTE
THEMSELVES
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The theme of the 1999 annual conference of the Association of
National Advertisers is ``Brand Building for the 21st Century.''
But it might as well be called ``Payback Time 3.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because for the third consecutive year, the advertiser
association _ the trade organization representing America's largest
marketers _ is selling sponsorships of daily general sessions of
the conference to media companies seeking to promote themselves to
an audience of potential clients.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, media outlets that are always charging marketers
for commercial time and ad space are now paying the marketers for
platform time and program space.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1997, when the advertiser association became the only
advertising industry trade organization to sell conference
participation, the media companies spending an estimated $100,000
to sponsor general sessions have included the ABC, CBS and Fox
television networks; Gannett Co., for USA Today; and the Time Inc.
unit of Time Warner Inc. Their presentations have ranged from
huckster, including hard sells that were indistinguishable from
infomercials, to low-key, thoughtful discussions of issues that
were indistinguishable from conventional, unsponsored sessions.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the sponsors are five national radio networks and
Conde Nast Publications, the owner of 17 magazines from Allure to
Wired. They are to make presentations at general sessions of the
1999 conference, which is the 90th annual gathering of the
advertiser association. The conference began on Saturday afternoon
at the Ritz-Carlton hotel in Amelia Island, Fla., with a
registration of more than 500 people and is scheduled to end
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd prefer if they thought we were interesting enough that we
didn't have to pay,'' said Catherine Viscardi Johnston, the
executive vice president responsible for marketing and sales at
Conde Nast, a unit of Advance Publications in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would I rather have it without charge?'' she said. ``Yes. But
it wasn't a big issue because we thought we could make good use of
the time.''
</P>
<P>
   During the first general session Sunday morning, Conde Nast
presented a panel of editors of six of its magazines. The editors
included Graydon Carter of Vanity Fair, Elizabeth Crow of
Mademoiselle and David Remnick of The New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our main marketing goal is to have people who advertise with
us _ and those who don't _ see Conde Nast as more than just vendors
of ad space,'' Ms. Johnston said. ``By hosting this panel, we want
advertisers to see us as a resource to help establish connections
with consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of whether Conde Nast paid to be included in the
conference, Ms. Johnson said, ``or they paid us, these editors are
interesting people.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we handed each person in the audience $50,000,'' she added,
``they wouldn't sit and listen to something boring.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Johnston paused, then said with a chuckle, ``Well, maybe
some of them would listen.''
</P>
<P>
   Several media executives whose careers revolve around listening
habits _ top managers at national radio networks _ are also paying
their way into the conference, sponsoring the second general
session Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We view this not as a paid commercial but as an opportunity to
present the facts and figures about network radio and let the
audience members make their own decisions,'' said Lyn Andrews,
president at the ABC Radio Networks in New York, which like ABC-TV
is owned by the Walt Disney Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always love for radio in general and network radio in
particular to be included as part of the regular agenda,'' she
added. ``Given the opportunity was there, albeit on a paid basis,
this is the best alternative.''
</P>
<P>
   Her counterpart at Westwood One Inc., Joel Hollander, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like anything else, you have to pick and choose where you are
seen and heard,'' Hollander, president and chief executive in New
York, said. ``Here, we're in the right arena, with the decision
makers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There had never been a real initiative to carry the flag for
network radio,'' he added. ``So it was a good idea to come up with
the dollars to put together a presentation to solicit advertisers
at a higher level.''
</P>
<P>
   Westwood One is managed by the Infinity Broadcasting Corp., a
division of the CBS Corp. The other network radio sponsors are AMFM
Radio Networks, part of AMFM Inc., which agreed last week to be
acquired by Clear Channel Communications; American Urban Radio
Networks, a division of New Mark Communications, and Premiere Radio
Networks, a unit of Clear Channel.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Though the sponsored sessions break with tradition, some
traditions at the advertiser association conference never change.
Among them are the annual election of officers and the bestowing of
awards.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph V. Tripodi, chief marketing officer at the Seagram
Spirits and Wine Group unit of the Seagram Co., was elected
chairman for 1999-2000. He succeeded John H. Costello, former
president at Autonation Inc., the 1998-99 chairman.
</P>
<P>
   John D. Hayes, executive vice president for global advertising
and brand management at American Express, was elected vice chairman
for 1999-2000. He succeeded Tripodi, the 1998-99 vice chairman. And
Michael Soriano Jr., vice president for marketing services at
Warner-Lambert, was elected treasurer again.
</P>
<P>
   On the awards front, Carolyn J. Levy was presented the Robert V.
Goldstein Award for her work as volunteer director for a public
service campaign against academic cheating produced by the
Advertising Council. Ms. Levy is senior vice president for youth
smoking prevention at the Philip Morris U.S.A. unit of the Philip
Morris Cos.
</P>
<P>
   And Pamela Kaufman, vice president for promotions marketing at
Nickelodeon, the cable television network owned by Viacom Inc., was
presented the Grand Marketer of the Year Award by the trade
publication Brandweek at the opening dinner of the conference on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kaufman, honored for promoting ``The Rugrats Movie'' and
``Blue's Clues,'' was selected from 14 winners of Marketer of the
Year Awards in categories like entertainment new media and
retailing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-10-99 1703EDT &QL; 
