<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WLEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 Chronicle Publishing Company  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DIRECTORS SHOOTING THE BREEZE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Martin Scorsese  &LR; tells  &UR; Spike Lee &LR;  that it may have been good
for his career that he's never won an Oscar.
</P>
<P>
   But doesn't it make you angry, asks Lee in the latest issue of
Premiere magazine, that ``Ordinary People'' won a best picture
Oscar in 1980 over ``Raging Bull''. Nah, says Scorsese.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a little twinge myself since 1989,'' says Lee, when
``Do the Right Thing'' was released and the Oscar went to ``Driving
Miss Daisy.'' ``After that, I said, `I give up.' What can you do?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't do anything about it,'' says Scorsese, and the two
go on to say nice things about &UR; Robert Redford &LR; , who directed
``Ordinary People.'' ``But you know,'' says Scorsese, ``this is
America. It's the children of light and the children of darkness,
you know what I'm saying? The children of light get passed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The movie industry now is dominated by 12-year-olds,'' says
Lee. ``I mean, I'm not trying to sound snobbish, but `American
Pie'? Sticking your d_ in a pie, that's a movie? Come on!''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AUTHOR ON THE ROAD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Feminist  &UR; Susan Faludi &LR; , whose new book about men in the '90s is
``Stiffed'' (Morrow; $27.50), writes in the latest issue of
Harper's about the media tour for her last book, ``Backlash'':
</P>
<P>
   One interviewer asked, ``Do you shave your underarms?'' As she
was waiting to go on in another show's green room, the producers
``burst in with a suggestion: `How about we have you appear on the
set in a bathrobe and rollers?'''
</P>
<P>
   After the tour, advertisers contacted her about celebrity
spokesmanship. A shoe manufacturer asked if she wanted to be in an
ad for high heels. And a cosmetic surgery center asked if she'd
endorse silicone breast implants. When she said she didn't have
them, the center's representative said ``That's OK. We just want to
use your name because you're a feminist.''
</P>
<P>
   HBO has bought movie rights to ``Stiffed,'' paying what the New
York Times called a ``mid-six-figure sum'' to turn it into a TV
drama.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAUSES AND EFFECTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Winona Ryder &LR; , 27, told Vogue magazine that she has an
unnatural fear of becoming separated from her family, ``which she
believes comes from having lost relatives in the death camps'' of
World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile  &UR; Kristin Scott Thomas &LR;  told the Calgary Sun why she
chose her profession: ``I wanted to be an actress since I was four.
I think that comes of being raised Catholic. There's so much
theatricality to the religion.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - Browsing through the Web site for the online brokerage ETrade,
 &UR; Dario Oakley &LR;  came upon this example of positive spin, in a
company profile: ``For the 9 months ended 6 /99, revenues rose from
76.6M to 66.8M.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Prince Edward &LR; 's Ardent Productions has signed a deal with E!
Entertainment Television to make a 13-part documentary on aspects
of royal life.
</P>
<P>
   - Bright idea of the month: Marie Claire magazine has  &UR; Courtney &LR; 
 &UR; Love &LR; , whose husband,  &UR; Kurt Cobain &LR; , committed suicide, answering
``your questions about sex, love and relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   - Police received a report of construction at a house in San
Carlos on Sunday, says a Carmel Pine Cone report forwarded by
 &UR; Daryl Glen &LR; . ``Perhaps was replacing a doorknob. No permit needed,
no violation.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``With the rapid approach of the third millennium, many people
can't help wondering what role the Devil will be playing in it. But
a cursory examination of the mainstream press of America reveals
almost no mention of him, and even using the Internet services that
promise to keep track of everything, it's much easier to find
information on Monica Lewinsky than on the Devil.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Robert Wernick &LR;  in Smithsonian magazine.
</P>
