<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-10 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2486 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BRITAIN-ONLINE-MEDIA-     10-10 1204
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-ONLINE-MEDIA-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADITIONAL BARRIERS FALL AS BRITISH PAPERS PUT NEWS ONLINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Peter Martin, a senior editor, strides briskly through
the newsroom of The Financial Times, gesturing to a bank of
computer terminals where journalists craft the news for FT.com, the
paper's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   In a matter of months, Martin tells a visitor, that relatively
small unit will be gone, replaced by something much more innovative
that, far more extensively than at any other British paper, will
erase what he calls the ideological barrier between online news and
the printed word. In its place, he says, will be a redesigned,
integrated newsroom where journalists will work to feed both the
Web site and the distinctively salmon-colored British newspaper.
And that is not all, says Martin, whose title is deputy editor and
editorial director for the FT Internet Businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site will be reinvented as a full-fledged Internet
portal, featuring a search engine for business readers, diary and
e-mail capabilities and expanded use of columnists and analysts to
provide an early peek into their thinking. ``We envisage it
becoming a global business portal,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways the development at The Financial Times, which
expects to hire as many as 100 new staff members and spend up to
$70 million on its online expansion this year alone, reflects both
a broader push by its owner, Pearson PLC, to wring global value
from its flagship, blue-chip brand name, and a response to growing
competition from a range of business-oriented Web sites like
TheStreet.com., in which The New York Times is an investor.
</P>
<P>
   But The Financial Times' ambitious expansion is also being
played out against a familiar backdrop. As Britain's broadsheet
papers look to the Web, their traditional, no-holds-barred
competition has taken a new turn and the fabled wars of what used
to be known as Fleet Street have spilled into cyberspace. These
days, visitors to the former Fleet Street's Web sites can expect to
be enticed not simply by a rehash of the day's headlines but by a
broader palette, including what George Brock, managing editor of
The Times of London, calls ``rolling journalism,'' driven by the
same urge for speed as are news agencies like Reuters, Bloomberg
News or The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Britain's online broadsheet newspapers are promoting a
range of interconnected offerings _ all advertising-driven _
designed to lure just about everyone from job seekers to movie
buffs to highflying executives. And they are not just competing
with each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Online, the British are competing head to head in a firmly
competitive market where we are also competing with the broadcast
media,'' said Danny Meadows-Klue, publisher of the electronic
version of The Daily Telegraph (www.telegraph.co.uk). ``Our
competitive landscape is no longer just newspapers. It's TV, radio,
specialist sectors like football, where we are competing with
football clubs' own home pages.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the former Fleet Street is not alone. Internet
service providers from Compuserve to Yahoo already offer real-time
news feeds from big news agencies. Newspapers in the United States,
including The Washington Post and The New York Times, are seeking
not just to provide up-to-the-minute news agency feeds but also to
deploy editorial staffs of their own working alongside print
journalists.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Never was that changing relationship between the Web page and
the printed page more obvious than after last week's London train
crash _ the worst in over four decades _ which confronted editors
with what, for some journalists, has become the central puzzle, or
even threat, presented by their online editions: how to serve
readers with breaking news and early analysis without undermining
the value of the following day's printed pages.
</P>
<P>
   Within three hours of the crash, said Simon Waldman, editor of
Guardian Unlimited, the Guardian newspaper's network of Web sites,
``we had everything up'' on the Web site _ including photos and
eyewitness accounts that would ordinarily have been kept for the
next day's printed editions.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Mike Butcher of New Media Age, an induwsletter, said:
``One thing that newspapers have swallowed now is that the Web does
not significantly eat into circulation. People use it in a
different way. People don't really read articles in any depth
online. It's a different medium.''
</P>
<P>
   Distinctions between what is happening in the British press and
among American newspapers are manifold. For one thing, U.S.
newspapers are rooted in a stronger regional tradition, compared
with the scramble for national dominance that distinguishes British
newspapers. And they were generally quicker to go online than their
British counterparts. U.S. newspapers benefited not just from the
much cheaper U.S. telephone rates, which encourage Internet use,
but also from a much bigger potential market. ``Web revenue is not
the same and that explains the different speeds at which things
have tended to develop,'' Brock said.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, ad revenue from British papers' online operations was a
measly $31.3 million last year. But, according to many online
managers, that represented an increase of some 140 percent over
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Some sites, like The Daily Telegraph, with six interconnected
sites, are building networks for students and travelers to win over
a new generation to replace an aging readership.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the desire to avoid being left out that The Independent
(www.independent.co.uk) recently lured Web experts away from rivals
like Rupert Murdoch's News Corp., which owns The Times of London,
to redesign its Web site in an effort to increase the number of
visits to individual Web pages _known here as page impressions _
from a lowly 3.6 million a month. The Times of London
(www.the-times.co.uk), too, is promising new features. It draws
some 12 million visits a month _ roughly the same as The Financial
Times, which reckons that some 40 percent of its online usage comes
from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   And, with five interlinked Web sites catering to news junkies,
job seekers, movie fans and others, The Guardian's Guardian
Unlimited (guardianunlimited.co.uk), begun in January, is pressing
to expand beyond its roughly 10 million visitors a month.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Financial Times' aggressive strategy has raised some doubts
among industry experts, particularly since it says it will be
looking to advertising, not subscriptions, to provide revenue. Noah
Yasskin, an analyst at Jupiter Communications, said the recruitment
of 100 people ``sounds like a lot of bodies for the British
advertising market to pay for.'' And Jamie Wood, European media
analyst at J.P. Morgan, said he was ``not sure that Pearson has
worked out'' where the expansion fits in the overall strategy of a
company whose activities include book publishing, television,
business information and educational publishing.
</P>
<P>
   But Martin has an answer. ``The risk from doing nothing is much
higher,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-10-99 1707EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
