<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPORTER-SOURCES-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORTER GETS A SUBPOENA ON INTERVIEW IN '95 KILLING
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala.. Calif.)   (nk) 
 By CHRISTIAN BERTHELSEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A reporter for a magazine published by a civil
rights group has been subpoenaed to provide tape recordings and
notes of an interview with a defendant in a murder that may have
been racially motivated.
</P>
<P>
   The reporter is said to have told a federal investigator that
the defendant acknowledged committing a murder. She is a writer for
the quarterly magazine, Intelligence Report, which covers
right-wing extremists and is published by the Southern Poverty Law
Center, a civil rights group that regularly holds seminars for law
enforcement agents about trends and beliefs among hate groups. The
magazine is circulated to about 150,000 contributors to the
organization, which is based in Birmingham, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   Trish O'Kane, the writer, interviewed the defendant, Randall Lee
Rojas, in August. Rojas and two others are accused of beating a
black man, Milton Walker Jr., to death in 1995 in California. In a
hearing on Oct. 1 in state Superior Court, FBI agent John Schafer
testified that Ms. O'Kane called him a month after the interview to
ask him some questions, and in the course of the conversation told
him that Rojas said ``the worst crime I ever committed was
murder,'' in 1995, and that he felt remorseful, although he did not
specifically say the murder involved Walker.
</P>
<P>
   Schafer testified he told Ms. O'Kane to preserve her notes and
recordings, and ``she was quite taken aback by my request'' because
she did not realize until then that it they could be evidence in a
criminal case.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors considered issuing a subpoena for the evidence and
notified defense lawyers of its existence but decided against it.
Now, lawyers for Rojas' co-defendants are seeking Ms. O'Kane's tape
recordings and notes in the belief that they may exonerate their
clients. Richard Cohen, a lawyer with the center, said the magazine
would seek to quash the subpoena in Alabama. If it does not
prevail, it will assert the California shield law before Judge
Lance Ito, who is handling the case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-10-99 1707EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991010.0078 </DOCNO>
