u a BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT &LR;      10-10 0412
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, Oct. 11, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A vigorous jet-stream flow over the northern tier of states will
direct a series of fronts from the northern Rockies to the
northeastern states. As a result, marked day-to-day temperature
changes will occur across these regions through midweek. The fronts
will be accompanied by some clouds and a few showers, but the rapid
motion of weather systems will prevent substantial precipitation.
Meanwhile, unseasonable warmth will spread from the Southwest
toward the Plains.
</P>
<P>
   The Northeast will become partly to mostly sunny as a cold front
moves offshore. Breezes from the northwest will gradually deliver
cooler air to interior sections, but coastal areas will stay
several degrees warmer than the seasonal average on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds and showers will linger near a slow-moving front from the
southern Appalachians to the middle Atlantic coast. The coastal
Carolinas and Georgia will have some sunshine, but afternoon and
evening thundershowers will arrive from the west. Farther south,
Florida will be warm and humid with ample sunshine, although a few
showers will occur in the western panhandle.
</P>
<P>
   After a chilly dawn, breezes from the south will deliver warmer
air to the central and northern Plains. Clouds will thicken and
patches of rain will develop near the Canadian border from Montana
to the Dakotas as the milder air rises over cool air in place
across this region.
</P>
<P>
   Sunny and very warm weather will cover the Southwest, but cooler
air will spread into the Northwest late Monday and Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Rip Currents
</P>
<P>
   Rip currents threatened swimmers in southern Florida over the
weekend after several days of steady onshore winds. Because a
wind-generated wave rarely is of uniform height along its entire
length, water piles up near shore where incoming waves are tallest.
Water sliding down both sides of the piles creates flows that move
parallel to the shore. Where these flows converge, water is
diverted seaward, creating a dangerous rip current that can push
swimmers into deep water. People who are caught in a rip current
should swim parallel to the beach until they are out of the current
and then swim back to shore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-10-99 1710EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991010.0079 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-10 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2490 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MEDIA-TALK-ART-NYT &LR;      10-10 1288
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAUTION WITH UNABOMBER BOOK; REAGAN BIOGRAPHY RIVAL; CNN REJECTS
SALON AD
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Colo., Mont., Calif.)   (ART ADV: Photo NYT4 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(jw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are certain publishing rituals that necessarily must be
abandoned when an author lives in a federal prison cell under
23-hour lockdown with just a 13--inch black and white television
for company.
</P>
<P>
   With the approaching publication of Theodore Kaczynski's memoir,
``Truth Versus Lies'' the book's small independent publisher,
Context Books, is trying to figure out just how to promote a title
about brotherly resentment and dysfunctional family life without
much help from the writer. Kaczynski is serving a life sentence in
a Colorado prison for a series of bombings that left three people
dead and at least 22 injured.
</P>
<P>
   Kaczynski has written a book that does not dwell in any way on
the crimes he pleaded guilty to as the Unabomber, who eluded the
federal authorities for more than 17 years. That is because he is
seeking a review of his case by a federal appeals court, said
Context's publisher and founder, Beau Friedlander. So instead, he
said, Kaczynski's memoir is an attempt to offer a more complex view
of himself than portrayals that characterized him as insane.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the 368-page book is devoted to the literary dissection
of David Kaczynski, the brother who made the wrenching decision to
alert federal authorities about his suspicions that his only
sibling might be the Unabomber.
</P>
<P>
   Along with a chapter on ``My Adolescence; Family Dysfunction;
Verbal Abuse,'' Theodore Kaczynski has devoted at least eight
chapters to his brother, from ``My Brother's Ambivalent Feelings
Toward Me'' to ``My Brother's Relations with Linda Patrik; I Break
Off With Him'' to finally ``How My Brother's Attitudes Changed
Under Linda Patrik's Influence; Why He Denounced Me to the FBI.''
(Ms. Patrik is David Kaczynski's wife.)
</P>
<P>
   This book is about the ways Theodore Kaczynski ``was
misrepresented by the media after his arrest,'' Friedlander said.
Friedlander said he proposed the project to Kaczynski. He added
that any share of Kaczynski's book proceeds would be placed in a
special escrow account for bombing victims or their survivors.
</P>
<P>
   The book is scheduled to be published sometime this year. About
promoting it, Friedlander conceded: ``You have a hard time. You
don't do an author tour and Kaczynski is not chummy with the
media.''
</P>
<P>
   _ DOREEN CARVAJAL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rival Reagan Biography Will be Reissued
</P>
<P>
   While critics debate Edmund Morris' controversial memoir of
Ronald Reagan and its blend of fact and fantasy, an upstart
publisher is preparing to reissue a rival biography, contending
that Morris failed to deliver a definitive account of the former
president's life.
</P>
<P>
   In the spring, Public Affairs will publish an updated trade
paperback version of Lou Cannon's 1991 biography, ``President
Reagan: The Role of a Lifetime,'' said Peter Osnos, the publisher
of Public Affairs, a two-year-old company.
</P>
<P>
   Although the two Reagan biographers share the same subject, they
are openly scornful of each other and have started trading literary
uppercuts. As the controversy deepened this month about his newly
published biography, ``Dutch: A Memoir of Ronald Reagan,'' Morris
said that Cannon's book demonstrated why it was necessary to take
the unconventional approach of inserting himself in the memoir as a
semifictional contemporary of Ronald Reagan's with an eyewitness
view of his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lou Cannon, who spent almost all of his professional
journalistic career following Ronald Reagan around, produced a
massive, orthodox political biography of him,'' said Morris, who
received a Pulitzer Prize in 1980 for his biography of Theodore
Roosevelt. ``To my mind, he utterly failed to convey Reagan's
theatrical nature because Lou was a reporter and never a witness.
It's a different view altogether. It's the reportorial view _ too
neutral, too subjective.''
</P>
<P>
   In turn, Cannon _ a former Washington Post reporter who wrote
three books about Reagan _ reviewed Morris' memoir for The Los
Angeles Times. In his critique, Cannon faulted Morris for factual
errors, calling ``Dutch'' a strange book in which ``realistic
political analysis wages a losing battle with novelistic
technique.''
</P>
<P>
   Cannon said he contracted with The Los Angeles Times about a
year and a half ago to review the book with no intentions of doing
anything with his own biography, which is still available in
hardcover from California Journal Press. But after Public Affairs
asked him to bring out an updated version, Cannon said that he was
glad to have his book resurface, no matter Morris' caustic
critique.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think Morris' criticism of me is just another alibi,''
Cannon said. ``Edmund blames everyone but himself. He blames Ronald
Reagan for being a mystery. He's trashing everybody. I can't judge
my own book. I'm not puffed up about it, but I think I did capture
Reagan in my news stories and in my writing. Magic or no magic,
I've got the story of the Reagan administration, and he had such an
opportunity to build on it.'' ``Dutch'' has been selling briskly,
climbing to No. 2 on the New York Times best-seller list and the
two largest bookstore chains, Borders and Barnes &AMP; Noble, said it
was selling well. &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  _ DOREEN CARVAJAL &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CNN Rejects Advertisement From Salon
</P>
<P>
   Does mighty CNN view teeny Salon magazine, the online journal of
culture, news and opinion, as a competitor?
</P>
<P>
   In the last week of September, Salon.com introduced its first
television advertising campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The ad, now running on MSNBC, CNBC, VH1, Comedy Central, A&AMP;E,
Bravo and Fox, features the heads of famous and infamous people on
caricatured bodies: Chris Rock dances with Linda Tripp; Al Gore
watches agog as Tipper Gore chats amiably with the shock-rocker
Marilyn Manson; Howard Stern and Martha Stewart canoodle on a sofa,
and Courtney Love raises her cocktail glass to a beneficent Pope
John Paul II.
</P>
<P>
   The spot was scheduled to appear on CNN on Sept. 27. A few days
earlier, Salon's vice president for marketing, Patrick Hurley, said
he received a phone call from Steven Mizer, manager for commercial
clearance at Turner Networks, a unit of Time Warner Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said that they rejected the ad and would not be able to run
it because they view us as a competitive news source,'' Hurley
said. ``He said it had nothing to do with the spot itself. He said,
`Look, we don't let everybody who wants to advertise on CNN
advertise on CNN.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Hurley said if taste was the issue, he was curious to know
whether CNN had run advertisements from Outpost.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those could be construed as much more tasteless,'' Hurley
said. ``I mean, they're shooting gerbils out of a cannon in those
ads.''
</P>
<P>
   (Hurley was referring to a series of ads from the online
retailer that show, among other things, a muscular man affixing Web
address stickers to infants' heads and, indeed, gerbils being shot
from cannons.)
</P>
<P>
   Mizer referred inquiries to a CNN spokeswoman, Sue Binford. Ms.
Binford could not confirm whether CNN had ever run ads from
Outpost.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything that comes in we look at on a case-by-case basis,''
she said. ``And we will, from time to time, not accept an
advertisement. One of the things we are certainly ng to do
is get into all the ins and outs on why we make these decisions
every time we make one. I think it is sufficient to say that these
decisions are up to us, and we made a decision to pass on this
one.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ALEX KUCZYNSKI &QL;
</P>
