<HEADLINE>
PATENTS: PIANO HONORING GERSHWIN; DURABLE CD BOX; HALLOWEEN-CANDY
TRACER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Del.)  (lb) 
 By TERESA RIORDAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since it went into business in 1853, Steinway &AMP; Sons has
introduced many design and mechanical innovations in its legendary
pianos. Last week Steinway received its 122nd patent _ a design
patent that protects the look of a new, extravagantly detailed
piano called the Rhapsody.
</P>
<P>
   The Rhapsody piano was designed last year to honor the 100th
birthday of composer George Gershwin. And, of course, it is very
blue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's made of curly maple that is dyed blue and clear-coated in
lacquer,'' said Andrew Horbachevsky, director of engineering
development at Steinway.
</P>
<P>
   The piano is studded with hundreds of mother-of-pearl stars, and
its lid features a mother-of-pearl starburst.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very art-deco New York in the '20s and '30s,''
Horbachevsky said.
</P>
<P>
   Designed by Frank Pollaro of East Orange, N.J., the piano has a
music desk hand-carved with the silhouette of the New York City
skyline. The piano plate _ the plate that all the piano strings are
attached to _ is silver and hand-painted in blue with the first 24
notes of Gershwin's ``Rhapsody in Blue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The relevance of the 24 is that it took George Gershwin 24
days to compose `Rhapsody in Blue,''' Horbachevsky said.
</P>
<P>
   The piano is part of a limited-edition series of designs, which
includes a J.B. Tiffany piano, in honor of an art director who
worked for Steinway and was a distant cousin of the famous glass
designer.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Steinway will be introducing the Tri-Centennial, a
limited-edition piano designed in honor of the 300th anniversary of
the invention of the piano by Bartolomeo Cristofori, the Italian
musician and instrument maker.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the limited-edition Rhapsody piano? About $145,000
for the 7-foot version.
</P>
<P>
   ``A doctor from Pittsburgh should be getting the first one any
week now,'' Horbachevsky said.
</P>
<P>
   Steinway &AMP; Sons was assigned patent D414,797.
</P>
<P>
   Father and Daughter Win Separate Patents
</P>
<P>
   Marshall Weingarden and his daughter, Alison, are patenting very
different inventions within a couple of months of each other.
</P>
<P>
   Weingarden, a package designer in Haworth, N.J., recently
patented a new type of CD case that he says is superior to those
clear-plastic jewel boxes that infuriate music lovers by easily
breaking or cracking.
</P>
<P>
   His box is made of polypropylene, which _ unlike the polystyrene
of the hard plastic cases _ is a soft and somewhat pliable plastic
that won't crack.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are other polypropylene boxes,'' Weingarden said. But
unlike those, he said, his box is close enough in size and
configuration to the crystal polystyrene boxes that his version can
be loaded with the CD and booklet on the same packaging equipment
that is already used by the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Alison Weingarden's patent, which is expected to
be issued Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``She came up with the idea when she was volunteering at a
hospital,'' her father said. It's a hand-held remote-control device
that allows a hospital worker to hold an elevator door open while
maneuvering a wheelchair or gurney on or off the elevator.
</P>
<P>
   Does this invention portend an engineering career for Ms.
Weingarden, a senior at Northern Valley Regional High School in
Demarest, N.J.?
</P>
<P>
   Possibly, ag to her father, ``But she's also a promising
oboist.''
</P>
<P>
   Marshall Weingarden received patent 5,931,294. Alison Weingarden
is to receive patent 5,964,319. They are both hoping to license
their patents.
</P>
<P>
   Tracing the Candy on Halloween Night
</P>
<P>
   Gwendolyn Anderson, an inventor in Newark, Del., has patented a
``food donator identification container'' that she says will help
protect trick-or-treaters from tainted Halloween goodies.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Anderson's invention is essentially a big bag containing
many smaller bags, each of which has a label for writing down the
address from which the candy inside it came.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the parent and child go back to their house, they can
examine each small bag of candy,'' Ms. Anderson said. ``This way
there is a way to identify the person who handed out the candy if
there is a problem with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Anderson received patent 5,735,548, which she hopes to
license.
</P>
<P>
   Patents may be viewed on the Web at www.uspto.gov or may be
ordered through the mail, by patent number, for $3 from the Patent
and Trademark Office, Washington, DC 20231.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-10-99 1734EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
