<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOULS-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE INDUSTRY OF SOULS': REDEMPTION AFTER A NATION'S NIGHTMARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By RICHARD EDER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bayliss, an old Englishman, rouses himself in the modest cottage
in a Russian village where he has lived for a quarter of a century
with Frosya and her husband, Trofim. He moves cautiously, testing
his 80-year-old's aches and pains, and wary of getting the sagging
skin on his thighs pinched between mattress and bed frame.
</P>
<P>
   Frosya had called out to him to open his shutters, as she does
each morning: afraid, as she is each morning, of getting no reply.
Now she bustles in with a hot cloth to massage the aching veins in
his legs, and with a breakfast of cheese, pared apple, tea and a
slice of bread: ``dark, dense, slightly moist and grainy.''
</P>
<P>
   It is an errand of reverence and love, repeated daily in the
decades since Bayliss, a ragged scarecrow, stumbled up to the door
with a last blessing from Kirill, Frosya's father, killed in the
mines of the Siberian gulag where the two men had worked side by
side for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Industry of Souls'' goes back and forth between Bayliss'
life a mile and a half underground in Sosnogorsklag (he was seized
and charged as a spy while visiting East Germany on business at the
start of the Cold War), and his years in Myshkino ever since.
Instead of returning to England, he had stayed there, working as an
unofficial village schoolteacher and living as an honored guest.
</P>
<P>
   Why he did not return, and why the villagers honor him almost as
they do the icons they smuggled into their rebuilt church, is the
heart of Martin Booth's novel. It is a story of darkness and light:
a light that shines not only in the fields, woods and vegetable
gardens of Myshkino _ from the incipient thawing of the 1970s to
the post-Communism of today _ but more singularly, in this
Tolstoyan tale, in the black tunnels of Sosnogorsklag.
</P>
<P>
   Bayliss' breakfast is the start of a day of quiet climax. It is
his birthday, and he will spend much of it walking around the
village and receiving the congratulations of his neighbors. Trofim
has started a private garage, is preparing to run a taxi service
and dreams of opening a chain of foreign-car dealerships. The
baker, who had worked for a state enterprise, now has his own
business, making bread by a savory traditional formula and baking
pastries to be sold at the railroad station. Another family has
emigrated to America.
</P>
<P>
   These vignettes tend to be thin and emblematic; a set of
Polaroids to portray the new Russia. Booth takes some shortcuts.
There are a number of conversations that seem to stem from the
point to be made more than the person making them. The author does
not resist an old chestnut about the former Soviet system: that the
workers pretended to work, and the state pretended to pay them.
</P>
<P>
   They are flaws, yet ``The Industry of Souls'' can be remarkably
moving: a morality tale, essentially, and one that reaches well
beyond the obvious. Take one of the village conversations. Toasting
Bayliss with homemade apple kvass, a neighbor offers an apology.
His father was a gulag guard; the apology is on behalf of all
Russia. Grandiose, but Booth knows, and conveys, that in the
Russian tradition grand and heartfelt do not exclude each other.
</P>
<P>
   As he makes his birthday rounds, Bayliss recalls the years in
the mines and the men in his work unit, each from a different
background (a fighter pilot, a sailor, a shopkeeper, an Albanian
student, a mathematician) and each denounced and arrested on
trivial suspicions or for petty revenge. He describes graphically
the hellish conditions they lived in. He evokes, as well, the
extraordinary solidarity and generosity of seven men whom hardship
compacted like the coal they dug.
</P>
<P>
   The portrait of Kirill, the unit leader, is the most memorable.
After months of brutal preliminary detention Bayliss had arrived at
the seeming lower depths of the mine pit. It is a suggestive
reversal: These outcasts find themselves oddly out of the system
that cast them out. And oddly free. Kirill initiates Bayliss into a
place where, devoid of all vestiges of humanity, it is possible to
rebuild the condition of being human. Addressing the new arrivals,
all with sentences of 20 years or more, Kirill tells them:
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to the rest of your lives. And take a word of advice.
Do not dream of the day of your release....Men go mad thinking
about the past, the future. Here, there is no then and no next.
There is only now.''
</P>
<P>
   The scenes in the mine and Bayliss' walk through the village are
intercut. The contrast seems vast; Bayliss, whose hard-won wisdom
illuminates the story even as it overworks him as a character,
finds the connection.
</P>
<P>
   Mortally injured when their pit collapsed, Kirill had extracted
Bayliss' promise that if he was ever released he would make his way
out of Siberia and find his daughter: ``Go to Frosya. One day, a
million years from now. Even if you are a ghost.''
</P>
<P>
   It is more than a paternal plea. The courage, the humanity, the
steadfastness of the men in the mine stand for hope of a future
beyond the national nightmare. (At one point someone notes the
irony that here, a mile and a half underground, is Russia's only
true communism, and that only here does ``comrade'' have meaning.)
</P>
<P>
   To the villagers of Myshkino, Bayliss is an icon of that hope;
partly for what he has been through _ as it were, on their behalf _
and partly from his refusal to be defeated by it. This foreigner,
staying with them and teaching their children, is a sign that
history can be redeemed.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day one question hangs over both Bayliss and the
villagers. A cousin in England has traced him; he will be arriving
that evening with a member of the British embassy to invite him to
go home. It is the thread of suspense that pulls the day taut.
Suspense of a kind, that is. The village doesn't know what he will
decide. Bayliss knows but isn't saying. For the readers he doesn't
need to; his answer has been annealed in the 20-year crucible of
Work Unit 8, Sosnogorsklag.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE INDUSTRY OF SOULS'
</P>
<P>
   By Martin Booth
</P>
<P>
   250 pages. St. Martin's Press. $22.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
