<SLUG> BC-DIGICOM-COLUMN-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIGITAL COMMERCE: TAKING TECHNOLOGY TO AFRICA 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DENISE CARUSO    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The technology sector's financial success in the last three
years has been largely a North American phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   But some forward-thinking investors have been moving offshore
toward untapped markets and investments, often pushing
communication technologies into underdeveloped countries in Latin
America and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   On foreign soil, U.S. investment often looks _ and acts _
remarkably like invasion. And it is sometimes treated accordingly,
as cellular-telephone providers discovered last year when the
Chinese government abruptly terminated a number of successful joint
ventures with vendors like Motorola and Ericsson in favor of its
own technologies.
</P>
<P>
   So how will U.S. investors, particularly those drunk on their
recent good fortune and feeling perhaps a little invincible,
henceforth enter these raw new markets? The answer to that question
may determine which nations are pulled into the global market and
which are left behind.
</P>
<P>
   Some areas, notably much of Africa, might even welcome an
invasion of foreign technology investment.
</P>
<P>
   With nearly 800 million people in nearly 50 countries speaking
hundreds of dialects and often in conflict with one another, Africa
has attracted almost no technology investment. Add to those
problems the continent's relatively high levels of poverty and
illiteracy, and the risk-reward ratio is not exactly compelling.
</P>
<P>
   Yet people like Noah Samara are willing, and even eager, to take
the risk.
</P>
<P>
   After 10 years of planning and development, Samara, the
Ethiopian-born founder and chairman of Worldspace Corp. in
Washington, began broadcasting digital radio programming from his
company's Afristar satellite on Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Afristar, the first of three Worldspace satellites (two more
serving Asia and Latin America are to be launched in 2000), is the
first satellite to deliver simultaneous programming to the entire
African continent.
</P>
<P>
   If all three satellites are in orbit by the end of next year,
Worldspace's potential audience will be more than 4.8 billion
people.
</P>
<P>
   Worldspace was conceived when, while practicing law in
Washington, Samara saw the AIDS epidemic ravaging Africa. People
desperately needed information to stem the spread of the virus, he
realized, but distributing printed materials was expensive and
impractical in a continent with so many remote areas and such
illiteracy, and television sets were rare and were too expensive
for most Africans.
</P>
<P>
   Samara's answer was the world's first portable satellite media
receiver: a digital radio that connects with various power sources,
including solar panels for poor, rural areas, as well as to PCs and
printers.
</P>
<P>
   The receivers, manufactured by Matsushita's Panasonic and JVC
subsidiaries, Hitachi and Sanyo, cost about $250 today, Samara
said. That seems prohibitively expensive, but he said that ``once
you start introducing new products and services, people start
working harder to make sure they can benefit from the
conveniences.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've calculated the number of families in our coverage area
that can afford receivers at these prices,'' he added. ``We
designed the African satellite's footprint to cover the more
affluent Middle East, as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Why radios and not the Internet? Digital radio was the only
solution that made sense, he insisted, because it was the cheapest,
most efficient way to reach the widest population, from poor,
illiterate rural villages to more affluent urban areas.
</P>
<P>
   It was also the most adaptable, he said, because the digital
radios could also receive data, like documents and static Web
pages.
</P>
<P>
   Worldspace, with $1.2 billion of investments, primarily from
Saudi backers, hopes to make money by selling time on the
satellites to various broadcasters, and by offering pay services of
its own.
</P>
<P>
   Today, these include Time Warner's CNN International and
Bloomberg Financial News as well as national and indigenous
broadcasts from countries like Egypt, Ghana, Senegal and South
Africa. But more interesting than its commercial services is its
goal of creating markets by fighting poverty.
</P>
<P>
   A central part of Samara's strategy was setting aside 5 percent
of his satellites' capacity for a nonprofit organization called
Equal Access, which Worldspace started with Solaria, a solar-energy
equipment provider and the State of the World Forum
(www.worldforum.org), a nonprofit global leadership and education
organization formed by Mikhail Gorbachev in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Equal Access aspires to provide free digital radios and a rich
flow of basic information, including educational and health
programming, to the poorest African villages, at a net cost of $10
a user.
</P>
<P>
   Its strategy is to get money directly from organizations like
UNESCO and the World Bank, which have millions of dollars earmarked
for poverty-eradication programs.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   An early project will be a Pan-African, noncommercial news
program, in the tradition of National Public Radio. Samara calls it
``the voice of Africa talking to the people of Africa.''
</P>
<P>
   And because the Worldspace radio receiver can also connect with
a PC and a printer, even remote villages would be able to receive
multimedia data for distance learning and health programs as well
as school curriculums in multiple languages.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most l project for Equal Access, says Tom
Rautenberg, director of strategy and program development for State
of the World Forum, is a broadcasting service for women and
families.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've learned from World Bank studies that the education of
women and girls is probably the most critical variable in
sustainable development,'' Rautenberg says. ``Their status and
economic potential is a leading indicator of how that community is
doing and its potential for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Samara is dedicated to changing the lives of Africans
and others in developing countries, he argues that the strategy
makes business sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought a lot about how to subsidize the development of the
poorest part of the market,'' he said. ``People need so many things
in these areas _ information on hygiene, how to be better
entrepreneurs, a whole range of issues. If we can do that, we will
help them break through some of the hardest barriers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
