<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-10 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2497 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-UNIVERSAL-FILMS-ART-1     10-10 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNIVERSAL-FILMS-ART-1075(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS RUMORS PERSIST, UNIVERSAL EXCEEDS EXPECTATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ A year ago, Universal Pictures was a forlorn little
puppy. The studio's entire roster of summer movies had grossed just
$62 million. And to cap it all, Universal finished a lackluster
year by watching its two most expensive and important films of late
1998, ``Meet Joe Black'' and ``Babe: Pig in the City,'' tank at the
box office.
</P>
<P>
   It was a debacle. Casey Silver, the chairman of Universal's
movie division, was dismissed in November. And rumors permeated
Hollywood that Seagram, which owns Universal Studios, would sell
off the movie division or at least chop off a few more executive
heads.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, it was as if somebody had flipped a switch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patch Adams,'' the Robin Williams comedy about an
unconventional doctor, was released last Christmas Day and went on
to earn $135 million at the domestic box office and $200 million
worldwide. In May, Universal released ``The Mummy,'' a
special-effects-laden spin on the old horror staple; it made $155
million domestically and more than $400 million worldwide,
exceeding all expectations and creating a new movie franchise for
the studio.
</P>
<P>
   These were followed by ``Notting Hill,'' a romantic comedy with
Julia Roberts that earned $116 million domestically; ``American
Pie,'' a teen-age sex comedy, that earned $101 million
domestically, and ``Bowfinger,'' the Steve Martin and Eddie Murphy
comedy, which has taken in $65 million.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on Oct. 2, something remarkable occurred, said Ron Meyer,
Universal Studios' president and chief operating officer. Someone
in America bought a ticket to a Universal movie that day, breaking
the 87-year-old studio's single-year domestic box-office record of
$709,652,731 _ a record that had stood since 1982, the year of
Steven Spielberg's ``E.T.: The Extra-Terrestrial.'' A month
earlier, the studio had also broken its three-year-old
international record of almost $910 million, Meyer said.
</P>
<P>
   It is not unusual for studios to break box-office records;
ticket prices keep going up and such records can be affected by
luck and timing. And of course, a record year at the box office
does not automatically translate to record profits. As Meyer points
out, it is possible to buy a record year simply by releasing more
films than usual _ although Universal did not do so this year. And,
of course, profitability depends not only on how much the films
take in but how much they cost to make.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's ``Meet Joe Black,'' for instance, cost more than $90
million but grossed only $45 million at the domestic box office. By
comparison, this year's ``Mummy'' has long since recouped its $78
million cost.
</P>
<P>
   It is tricky to gauge from a single year's box office whether a
studio will be profitable for that year because it generally takes
three years for the bulk of a film's revenues to go through the
cycle of worldwide distribution, video and cable. But Meyer is
optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a devastating year last year,'' he said, ``and we will
pay the price for that for the next several quarters. But we're on
our way to profitability.''
</P>
<P>
   The studio still has seven films to release this year, including
``End of Days,'' with Arnold Schwarzenegger; ``Man on the Moon,''
with Jim Carrey, and ``The Hurricane,'' with Denzel Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most intriguing about this year's performance for
Universal is that it comes so quickly on the heels of such a dismal
year _ and that it comes amid so many persistent whispers in
Hollywood that the studio lacks a defining vision; that its
corporate parent is less interested in movies than in its newly
expanded music division; that it might be sold or merged at any
moment, or that its top executives were about to depart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard those rumors and it's just ridiculous,'' said
Meyer, a founder of the Creative Artists Agency who came to run
Universal in 1995 after Seagram purchased the company from
Matsushita for $5.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The rumors that Seagram and its chairman, Edgar Bronfman Jr.,
were more interested in music than film were sparked by Seagram's
deal in May 1998 to pay $10.4 billion to purchase Polygram, the
world's largest music company, which is now merging with
Universal's existing music division.
</P>
<P>
   But Seagram is not losing interest in movies, Meyer said. ``If
they felt that way, frankly, they would get out of the business.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the notion that he would depart, Meyer expressed
exasperation. ``The rumors keep coming, every day it's a new name
who's coming to replace me,'' said Meyer, who added that he had no
intention of leaving or of changing the current top management
team, including Brian Mulligan and Stacey Snider, who replaced
Silver.
</P>
<P>
   Another persistent rumor is that Dreamworks SKG _ the studio
formed by Spielberg, Jeffrey Katzenberg and David Geffen that has
most of its offices on Universal's lot, and whose films Universal
distributes abroad _ will merge with Universal. Not so, Meyer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are personally close friends of mine,'' he said. ``And
there is no talk of anything like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Another way to measure box-office performance for a studio _ a
way that takes into account both the films that succeed and those
that fail _ is to measure the studio's average revenues from each
film. In 1998, Universal's per-film revenue was $4.5 million; thus
far this year, it is $23 million, an increase of more than 400
percent. And the studio's market share has grown _ to 12.5 percent
this year, up from 2.4 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But is there any way to determine whether this indicates a
fundamental turnaround or simply a blip caused by the vicissitudes
of the movie business?
</P>
<P>
   ``You can never tell,'' said Jessica Reif Cohen, a media and
entertainment analyst for Merrill Lynch. ``For some reason, these
studios tend to go in cycles. It's a hit-or-miss business and very
difficult to predict.''
</P>
<P>
   Universal executives fully expect that some people will find
irony in the fact that Universal is having its record year with a
roster of films that was developed while Silver was chairman of the
studio _ and that the hot streak began just a month after Silver
was dismissed. But Meyer has a ready response.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are clearly working better as a team this year,'' Meyer
said. ``Which is not to say that Casey Silver didn't make a
significant contribution to this year.'' But a lot of the other
executives who were developing films along with Silver, including
Ms. Snider, are still at the studio, he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Michael Shamberg, president of Jersey Films, one of 31
production companies that has deals with Universal, said: ``Give
Casey credit for some of the films. But this management team has
made some good strategic decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Shamberg mentioned the decision to open two
movies _ ``The Mummy'' and ``Notting Hill'' _ just before and just
after the release of the hotly anticipated ``Star Wars: Episode
1,'' when many studios were moving their films as far as possible
from that George Lucas juggernaut. It worked.
</P>
<P>
   Silver, who is still negotiating his final release from
Universal and has not yet announced his plans for the future, said
the performance of Universal's films ``reflects the hard work of a
lot of people, all of whom deserve to take bows. I feel
satisfaction that the studio is very successful and I'm pleased for
the filmmakers, the executives and the rank and file.''
</P>
<P>
   Those interested in understanding the future of Universal
Pictures, and the current executives' vision for the studio, need
only look at the films that resulted in the record-breaking
performance this year, Meyer said.
</P>
<P>
   The year was built on a diverse roster of successful films
rather than one or two blockbusters, and on the fruits of deals
with a long list of production companies, not just one or two.
Indeed, Amblin Entertainment, which once, along with Imagine Films
Entertainment, constituted the bulk of Universal's film roster, did
not have a single Universal film this year, though there are
several in development.
</P>
<P>
   Among the films Universal has in the works for 2000 and beyond
are several high-profile sequels, including ``Jurassic Park 3,''
``Mad Max IV'' and ``Hannibal,'' the sequel to ``Silence of the
Lambs.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Snider said the deal had finally been made last week for the
screenwriter for ``Hannibal,'' who will be Steve Zallian,
screenwriter for ``Schindler's List.'' Ridley Scott will direct.
The original film's stars, Anthony Hopkins and Jodie Foster, are
waiting for a finished script to decide whether to take part in the
sequel, she said.
</P>
<P>
   What made this record year possible, Ms. Snider said, was that
``all of our groups _ production, marketing and distribution _ kept
their eyes on the ball during some really tough times.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Davis, an entertainment industry analyst for Schroder and
Co., said the Universal team deserves credit. ``I think things are
working at Universal at the moment and some of the griping people
have had will go away,'' Davis said. ``Does that mean Universal is
the prime integrated machine that Disney is? No. But they're making
progress.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
