<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-CONSERVATIVE _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Seven months into his
presidential campaign, George W. Bush is discovering the bumps in
the middle of the political road. While Bush is getting traction
with his effort to show that his self-styled ``compassionate
conservative'' label is not oxymoronic, the strategy also invites
attacks from the party's right lane. (Herman, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   REFORM-PARTY _ For a political party all but declared dead 10
months ago, the Reform Party is garnering its share of attention
this month. Jack Gargan, the Floridian who heads the party, is
courting the likes of Jesse Ventura and Donald Trump. The party
``old liners'' are courting the likes of Pat Bucahan. Mike Murphy,
the GOP strategist, wonders why a party that isn't expected to
carry a single state next November is getting all this attention.
The answer: it's like covering a circus and the media love it.
(Crowley, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   HEPATITISC-PRISON _ Out of 42,000 people in Georgia prisons, 54
have hepatitis C. While that might seem a low count, Department of
Corrections health officials expect the number to increase almost
sixfold _ to about 300 _ by the end of next June. After that, their
numbers will continue to rise exponentially; how high is anybody's
guess because inmate lifestyles, such as intravenous drug use, make
them vunerable. (Cook, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   METRIC _ So the guys at Lockheed speak English measure, the
people
</P>
<P>
   talking to their spacecraft speak metric and as a result the
multibillion dollar thing goes up like a fireball. Didn't their
teachers ever tell them, ``If you don't learn metric now, you're
going to be in a load of trouble when the whole world uses nothing
but.'' Do teachers still say that? On paper, the U.S. government is
still on a course towards complete conversion, but is anyone in the
classroom, or anywhere else taking that seriously? We'll talk to
some teachers, look at the law, etc. And all in time for next week
... National Metric Week. (Isger, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
