<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIMON-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIMON DANCE CO.: THE BOXER AS ANTIHERO IN AND OUT OF THE RING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jose Limon was identified with epic themes in his
choreography. But many of his contemporaries in the modern dance of
the 1940s favored the equivalent of the urban short story,
especially if it had a social-protest subtext.
</P>
<P>
   Human insight links the separate genres, and the Limon Dance
Company has come up with a winner in its company premiere and
revival of Sophie Maslow's 1948 ``Champion,'' a terse tale about an
antihero, a man of the people who exploits the people.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Maslow, who began her distinguished career in Martha
Graham's company in the 1930s, has often drawn inspiration from
life around her. One of her celebrated works is ``Dust Bowl
Ballads'' (1941), set to songs by Woody Guthrie.
</P>
<P>
   The springboard for ``Champion'' was a story by Ring
Lardner &UR;  &LR; about a boxer, a public hero who is a heel in private
life. An outright period piece, ``Champion'' nonetheless came
across with exciting pungency when the Limon company performed it
last Friday night at the Joyce Theater.
</P>
<P>
   The work is more than a historical curiosity, and no one will
find the theme unfamiliar. How many pop stars lead a less than
exemplary life today, even if, unlike the Champion, they don't
steal from a crippled kid brother or beat up a hard-working mother?
To make Ms. Maslow's story complete, the protagonist here also
seduces a groupie (there is a shotgun wedding) and steals his
manager's wife.
</P>
<P>
   Stylistically, Ms. Maslow has something to teach us, mainly the
art of emotional distillation through movement. ``Champion'' has
not been performed since 1950, and because there was no dance
notation or film of the work, Ms. Maslow and Donald McKayle have
reconstructed the original through memory and made some changes.
More dancers have been added, and the original jazz-tinctured score
by Samuel Matlowsky has been ``adapted and arranged,'' as the
program puts it, by David LaMarche, the company's music director
and conductor. Matlowsky asked that his name be omitted from this
production.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever changes were made, ``Champion'' remains true to a
mainstream modern-dance esthetic of the 1940s that knew how to
telegraph psychological states through significant gesture. The
point is that the gesture is the movement; gesture is not imposed
on top of dance movement.
</P>
<P>
   This is a method that choreographers who seek to express
narrative content today fail to understand after years of working
with formal plotless dances. The Limon company has ventured
successfully into the style of psychological portraits in the past
by reviving Daniel Nagrin's bad-boy solos of the 1940's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Champion'' is the kind of piece no young choreographer today
could do. It is both stylized and realistic at the same time, and
its moral lessons, although mordant, are lessons. In short,
didactic.
</P>
<P>
   The witty conceit of the piece is to suggest a blow-by-blow
account of the champion's life by a sports announcer. Charley
Hayward, an actor, spits out his ringside narration brilliantly and
gutsily from a balcony while on stage the danced images offer a
negative contrast to the fighter's public adulation.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Vollet Kingston's costumes are a contemporary version of
originals that once suggested different walks of life for a crowd
that opens and closes the piece.
</P>
<P>
   The dancers have caught the spirit of the work, but Jonathan
Reidel stands out in the title role. In his shoulder-rotating
swagger and powerful stride he has the gait of a born bully and
manages to make his eyes burn like embers. Bradon McDonald as the
brother and Nina Watt as the mother do well with stock roles.
</P>
<P>
   Each round in the fight gushily described by the announcer is
equated with an episode in the hero's life. ``The Gym,'' a lively
segment, has McDonald, Robert Regala, Zhen Jun Zhang and the
impressive and intense Raphael Boumaila do some stylized feisty
shadow boxing around Carlos Orta, the manager. A group of women
fans leans forward.
</P>
<P>
   Reidel's seduction of Kimiye Corwin, who is instantly
transformed into his bride, takes place to a sardonic waltz and is
followed by the hero's further womanizing. Natalie Desch, excellent
as always in her clarity, is the slinky sophisticated girlfriend
who loses out to Carla Maxwell, as the manager's wife. Miss Maxwell
and Reidel depict an adult passion within a stylized tango. Ted
Sullivan's lighting adds the right drama to a suite of vignettes
that have the power of truth.
</P>
<P>
   The program included repeats of two Limon pieces, ``The Winged''
and ``The Moor's Pavane,'' with Orta as the Othello figure
surrounded by a new cast: Ms. Watt, Reidel and Ms. Ford. All did
well, although more projection could help. On the other hand the
company was outstanding in its communal fervor last Saturday
afternoon in Limon's ``There Is A Time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
