<P>
   The Wall forms part of the retaining base of the temple built by
Herod the Great and destroyed in 70 A.D. It is one of the holiest
sites in Judaism. It is regularly visited by tourists of all
religions.
</P>
<P>
   At the Wall, Morning was lead in a short Hebrew prayer by an
elderly rabbi known for his unsolicited blessings of foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   He joined his teammates and other worshipers in placing
handwritten prayers between the stones. The players declined to say
what they had written, but said they were thinking of family and
good health, not hoops, in their notes to God.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what happens in the game. this is truly amazing,''
said the Heat's Jamal Mashburn, looking at the worshippers at the
Wall.
</P>
<P>
   Still, pressure for a Heat championship followed the team on its
travels.
</P>
<P>
   Though most of those gathered at the Wall _ many religious
immigrants from western countries _ did not know of the Heat,
Israelis in general are avid basketball fans.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli reporters in a press conference Saturday night asked
Heat coach Pat Riley the questions he might expect back home: Will
this finally be the Heat's year? What happened in their play-off
loss last season? Why didn't they make more moves in the
off-season?
</P>
<P>
   The game is expected to sell out the 10,000-seat arena in Tel
Aviv. Though a soccer game took top billing, Israeli sports reports
Sunday night offered a feature on ``legendary coach Pat Riley'' and
commercials hyped the match up.
</P>
<P>
   The Heat agreed to play the exhibition in 1996 as part of a deal
to win rights from the Tel Aviv team for draft pick Martin
Muursepp. It was also looked forward to by Heat founder Ted Arison,
a billionaire American-Israeli who died on Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Tel Aviv has a few players who have flirted with NBA teams or
played major college basketball in the United States. The two teams
played 10 years ago in Miami, with the Heat winning by just six
points. Tel Aviv beat the Washington Bullets in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not for fun,'' said the Heat's Dan Majerle. ``We
definitely want to play well. We don't want to lose. All the
pressure is on us to perform well.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
