<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-10 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2519 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-JETS-KEYSHAWN-NYT     10-10 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-KEYSHAWN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS' JOHNSON EXPECTS A PRIME-TIME PERFORMANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   So, you think Monday Night Football is pressure? Keyshawn
Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pressure is having my NFL draft party at the House of Blues on
Sunset Boulevard, inviting 3,000 people _ and then taking my
midterm the next day.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Johnson is grinning, flashing what looks like three rows of
white teeth. He does that often when he contemplates the actions of
ordinary football players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear guys talk about overcoming adversity,'' he said. ``I
sit there and laugh and say, `You don't know about pressure until
you've lived in South Central L.A.'''
</P>
<P>
   If prime time were a 16-game season, Johnson would be averaging
98 catches and more than 1,100 yards.
</P>
<P>
   But he probably could have told you that himself. And he would
be right. He knows his stats.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night is his moment, and he expects to be at his best.
The Jets are playing their first Monday night game at home in seven
years, in the glow of the bright lights of the big city, the
opponent is the highly regarded Jacksonville Jaguars, and Johnson
understands how important a victory is for his 1-3 club.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, he expects his ``A'' game Monday night. He will go against
the Jaguars' cornerback Aaron Beasley, who leads the American
Football Conference with three interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I go against the `A' players I go with my `A' game,''
Johnson said. ``When I play against lesser players, I go down to
their level.''
</P>
<P>
   It is in prime-time that Johnson pushes the envelope _ and
defensive backs _ with his 6-foot-3-inch frame.
</P>
<P>
   Going back to his rookie season of 1996, Johnson has played in
eight of these ``spotlight games:'' five on Sunday or Monday nights
in prime time, a network Saturday game and two playoff games. He
averages six catches and 71 yards in those network appearances _
compared to 4.5 receptions and 65 yards for all the other games he
has played.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm relaxed in pressure games,'' Johnson said. ``When I relax,
my concentration is higher. I've been like that pretty much all the
time in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   In Johnson's final performance at Southern California in 1996,
he established a Rose Bowl record of 216 receiving yards against
Northwestern. It was part of a 12-catch, one-touchdown day.
</P>
<P>
   As a Jets' rookie eight months later, he was the lightning rod
on a woeful team that was invited to play in only one prime-time
game. It was against Washington on a Sunday night. With the Jets
trailing by 8 points, Johnson outleaped a defender in the end zone
and hauled in an alley-oop pass from Neil O'Donnell.
</P>
<P>
   The officials conferred. There was no replay then. They spent 10
minutes discussing it, and then ruled he had interfered with the
defender _ no touchdown. But the next day, in a rare event, the
league apologized to the Jets. Johnson had indeed made a legitimate
touchdown catch.
</P>
<P>
   That was the start of his network appearances.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Jets faced the Jaguars, Johnson couldn't wait.
He knew he would make things happen. He spoke during the week of
how he would be the most important person in that game, how he
wanted to be, and how, if anyone was logical about it, he should be
expected to star. It was his first playoff game in the pros, and it
came last January.
</P>
<P>
   He produced not only an extraordinary game, he turned it into an
event. By then Johnson had tired of comparisons to Jerry Rice or
Michael Irvin. Johnson explainecontinues to explain _ that
he uses skills beyond those plThat he blocks. That he runs.
He even plays defense.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Jaguars he ran for a touchdown on a 10-yard reverse,
he scored a touchdown on a 21-yard pass from Vinny Testaverde, he
produced an interception when he was used as a defender against a
desperation pass and also made a fumble recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Chrebet has been lauded as the Jets' clutch third-down
receiver, and with good reason. Chrebet has led the league in that
category and has always been among the best. But last season
Johnson tied for the league lead on third-down catches with seven
touchdowns. And with Testaverde, Johnson finally went to the Pro
Bowl last season.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, Johnson led AFC receivers with 10 touchdowns, was
third with 83 receptions and fourth with 1,131 yards. This season
he is ahead of that pace in catches (22) and yards (366) and has
the best average of his career at 16.6 yards a catch.
</P>
<P>
   In only three-plus seasons, Johnson has caught passes from seven
Jets' quarterbacks: O'Donnell, Frank Reich, Glenn Foley, Ray Lucas,
Testaverde, Tom Tupa and now Rick Mirer.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Johnson about having to catch passes from all those
quarterbacks, and he knows there have been seven. He waited for
Mirer to catch up to him, to realize what could happen with their
collaboration. Johnson also points out that since he became a Jet,
he has drawn more penalties by defenders than any of his teammates.
He knows that he has been flagged only twice for holding the last
two years, while being asked to block for other teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Why such prime-time excellence?
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe my focus changes,'' he said. ``I make mistakes in
regular games, but maybe they don't show. Maybe my mind doesn't
stray in front of a national audience out there rooting for me, and
most of the time in prime time I'm going against the top guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Bill Parcells understands what Johnson is saying.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are relaxed in big games,'' Parcells said. ``I
know I am. ``You know they're sharp. I told my team, you're
prepared for this week. They know it's a big game. What separates
people in football is their ability to do it. They don't always get
it done, but the mind and will are there. Some people's will is
diminished by adversity. You've got to get those guys off your team
pretty quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   When Mirer was looking for Johnson last Sunday in the fourth
quarter at Denver, with the Jets trailing, the quarterback tossed
four passes to him. Johnson caught two, but two more resulted in
penalties on cornerback Dale Carter. A total of 76 yards on the
80-yard scoring march involved Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to know,'' Mirer said later, ``that when you throw
the ball up, something good is going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   By the way, just how did Johnson do in that midterm exam after
his big draft party (he was the No. 1 pick over all) in Los Angeles
the night before?
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a B-minus,'' he said. ``Passed sociology.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-10-99 1844EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
