u e BC-TV-DATELINE-REVIEW-NY     10-10 0432
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-DATELINE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (Attn: N.Y.)  
 `DATELINE': ONE WOMAN'S PUSH TO UNDO JUSTICE THAT WAS TOO
QUICK  (Eds.: Viewing date is for New York area. Check local
listings.) 
(jw) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When it comes to eyewitness testimony, you can't always believe
your eyes. Such is the lesson of Monday night's ``Dateline'' report
on a Greenwich Village murder in November 1990 that brought a quick
arrest and second-degree murder conviction for an 18-year-old man,
whom seven witnesses told a jury they had seen at the crime scene.
</P>
<P>
   By the program's cautionary account, the only offense committed
by the teen-ager, Luis Rojas, was to fit the description of the
murderer's accomplice as a young Hispanic male wearing a bright
orange jacket. Rojas, in a jacket with an orange lining, was picked
up on the subway and, largely owing to the eyewitnesses, was found
guilty and sentenced to 15 years to life.
</P>
<P>
   Those who knew him as a student with no record of violence came
to his defense, and a teacher's pleas moved Priscilla Read
Chenoweth, a 69-year-old legal editor, to act. Most of Monday's
hour is given to the evidence she gathered with the help of a
couple of former New York detectives: evidence suggesting that the
police, prosecutors and Rojas' lawyer failed in their professional
duties.
</P>
<P>
   The harshest criticism is of the arresting officers, who took
Rojas back to the crime scene within minutes of the murder. Several
bystanders, still shaken by the shooting, had an opportunity to see
him in his orange-lined jacket and handcuffs and would testify
against him. He was further identified in a carelessly arranged
line-up. Such procedures ran squarely contrary to police department
guidelines on gathering reliable eyewitness testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The young man who first implicated Rojas as the killer's
accomplice tells Stone Phillips, the program's reporter, that he is
still sure of his identification. ``I remember the face,'' the
witness says. But when another of his identifications had proved
faulty, he changed his story to say that Rojas was the one who
fired the murder gun. The program's strong suggestion is that the
air of certainty of this witness influenced others to join him.
</P>
<P>
   Given the evidence gathered by Ms. Chenoweth's investigators, an
appeals court came down hard on the police for their handling of
the case and on Rojas' lawyer for a sorry defense. In a retrial, a
jury acquitted. By then Rojas had spent 4{ years in a
maximum-security prison, and Ms. Chenoweth had spent $50,000 of her
retirement savings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-10-99 1849EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
