<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SING IT WITH ME: STAND BY YOUR HASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is only one thing wrong with country songs or bluegrass
music: they're fattening.
</P>
<P>
   Arlo Guthrie told the tale of ``Alice's Restaurant.'' Bob Dylan
rhapsodized about ``Country Pie.'' ``Home Grown Tomatoes'' was
written by Guy Clark, and Dave Akeman asked the musical question,
``How Many Biscuits Can You Eat?'' You wouldn't believe how many
biscuits I can eat, but that's another song.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Rodgers wrote about ``Peach-Picking Time in Georgia'';
Hank Williams recalled eating endless bowls of ``Jambalaya,'' with
side dishes of crawfish pie and file gumbo. Even songs about
starvation like, ``Take a Cold Tater and Wait'' make you hungry.
</P>
<P>
   John Prine is famous for his musical ode to ``Fish and
Whistle,'' but he is really a roast-beef hash kind of guy.
</P>
<P>
   Ronnie Lundy, a former country music critic from Louisville,
wrote a cookbook containing ``memories and melodies from country
music stars.'' She called it ``Shuck Beans, Stack Cakes and Honest
Fried Chicken.'' She also shares Prine's lust for roast-beef hash.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever Prine left his family home to return to Nashville, his
mother did more than pack him a lunch. She furnished him with ``big
Tupperware things of hash,'' Prine recalls in the book. ``She asks
me what I want for birthdays and Christmas: I say `10 pounds of
hash.'''
</P>
<P>
   I am unable to carry a tune in a wheelbarrow. But I share
Prine's passion for hash, whether it is constructed out of beef,
roast turkey, sockeye salmon or Puget Sound clams. You might call
this recipe of mine ...
</P>
<P>
   Nashville Hash
</P>
<P>
   3 cups diced cooked beef
</P>
<P>
   2 cups diced raw potatoes
</P>
<P>
   1 and one-half cups chopped onions
</P>
<P>
   Three-quarters cup chopped green peppers
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoon minced parsley
</P>
<P>
   1 and one-half teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter teaspoon thyme
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 and one-half cups homemade beef gravy or 1 10-ounce can
</P>
<P>
   Lundy's mother insists the onions must be sauteed in the hash
pan before the meat and potatoes are added. But this version cooks
so long in the oven that you get the same result.
</P>
<P>
   All you do is moosh all the ingredients together in a greased
oven dish and shove it into a 375-degree oven. Cook 45 minutes
covered, remove cover and return hash to the oven for another 15
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   This is supposed to serve four modest appetites. Two is more
like it.
</P>
<P>
   Terminal Turkey
</P>
<P>
   3 cups diced leftover turkey
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup soft bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup chopped green pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup cream or milk
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon sage
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Good grinding of fresh pepper
</P>
<P>
   Toss the turkey, crumbs, green pepper, onion, parsley and
seasonings into a big bowl.
</P>
<P>
   In a saucepan melt 2 tablespoons butter and blend in the flour.
Stirring, pour in the cream. When this mess has thickened, gloop it
into the bowl and run your fingers through everything for a while.
</P>
<P>
   Melt the remaining 2 tablespoons of butter in a large frying
pan. When it is bubbling, spread the turkey mixture over the bottom
of the skillet and cook, uncovered, for 25 minutes, running a
spatula under the bottom crust a few times to keep the hash from
burning.
</P>
<P>
   Again, this will serve two although Prine could probably polish
off the beef and turkey hash by himself.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, but how many biscuits can he eat? An even better question
is this: How many hush puppies can he pop?
</P>
<P>
   Baked Hush Puppies
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup yellow cornmeal
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup flour
</P>
<P>
   One and one-half teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of ground red pepper
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup finely chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   1 egg, beaten
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup milk
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons canola oil
</P>
<P>
   Grease six cups of a small muffin pan. Blend together the
cornmeal, flour, baking powder, salt, sugar and ground red pepper.
Stir in the onion.
</P>
<P>
   In another bowl, beat the egg, milk and oil. Add the cornmeal
mixture and stir until just blended.
</P>
<P>
   Spoon batter into muffin cups, filling one-half to two-thirds
full. Bake until golden, about 15 to 20 minutes, in a preheated,
425-degree oven.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-10-99 1850EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991010.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-10 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2528 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-DISNEY-MUSIC-REVIEW-N     10-10 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLENNIUM SYMPHONIES: COMPOSED FOR WALT DISNEY CO. 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By PAUL GRIFFITHS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Think big. Be happy. Probably these words were not in
the contracts Aaron Jay Kernis and Michael Torke signed with the
Walt Disney Co. to write ``millennium symphonies,'' but they might
as well have been. Both composers took the opportunity to write for
a large orchestra with choir, boys' choir and soloists, and both
were encouraged also to be affirmative in ways that only the common
chord knows: their works both, curiously enough, ended in D major.
</P>
<P>
   But they took very different routes to get there. Kernis gave
himself the heavier task in planning immense structures _ a
10-minute first movement and a half-hour second _ and aiming for
seriousness. Such grand optimism has come rarely from composers in
the last half-century outside the works of Messiaen, who had not
only an unwavering faith to support him but also a vast imagination
for sound and a harmonic language that embraced major chords from a
new angle.
</P>
<P>
   Kernis, in his ``Garden of Light,'' tried to get there with
harmonies and colors and exultant rhythms that, however rich and
sometimes dazzling, related to other music, from Scriabin through
Bernstein, rather than to millennial regeneration, and he was not
helped by a text full of bromides. The hoped-for variety of the
second movement (Mahler's Eighth Symphony seems to have been a
model) was stymied by bland words and by the composer's
determination to be simple, to hold a tight rein on his melodic
invention and eliminate the unruly counterpoints that often give
his music character and interest.
</P>
<P>
   Torke's ``Four Seasons'' offered shorter segments _ vignettes of
recent American life for each of the 12 months, running roughly
five minutes each _ and a considerable dose of humor, helped by the
quick, strong images of Philip Littell's text, although the wit was
as much musical as verbal. In one section, for example, a comic new
meaning for Minimalism was found in the slight terrors of life in
the new postwar suburbs: ``I can't find my house,'' sang the tenor,
to a little phrase that was being repeated over and over by the
orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four Seasons'' also included a controlled riot of electric
guitar sounds from orchestral ensembles, a touching ``Letter to
God'' set against a melody whose relaxed character was energized by
some typical Torkean torsions and a sweet scene of teen-age
romantic fantasies. It all ended with an unashamedly infantile
finale, after the boys had come rushing back into the hall to lead
everyone on the platform in variations on the playground chant
``nah nah nahnah nah.'' It was like those sheets of stamps for the
decades you can get from the Post Office: fun, varied, smartly
designed, made not for the millennium but to be used now.
</P>
<P>
   Kurt Masur conducted the New York Philharmonic at Avery Fisher
Hall over the weekend, with the New York Choral Artists and the
American Boychoir, in resounding and remarkably assured
performances of both works. The soloists included Margaret Lloyd,
Mary Phillips, Anthony Dean Griffey, Dean Ely, Jubilant Sykes and
Lili Thomas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
