<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAUTY-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE BEAUTY PART': PERELMAN AIMS A SHOTGUN AT SOCIETY'S VARIED
FOIBLES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes appear at the end of the review.) 
(ms) 
 By WILBORN HAMPTON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As a humorist writing for The New Yorker, S.J.
Perelman always had a reserved seat at the Algonquin round table;
as a screenwriter he wrote zany Marx brothers classics like ``Horse
Feathers'' and the film adaptation of ``Around the World in 80
Days;'' as a playwright he was a bomb.
</P>
<P>
   The closest thing to a real hit on Broadway was a collaboration
with Ogden Nash on the book for ``One Touch of Venus.'' His last
play, a 1962 comedy called ``The Beauty Part,'' featured Bert Lahr
playing five different roles. It opened during a newspaper strike
and a blizzard and survived neither. In hopes of rediscovering a
long-neglected classic, the Peccadillo Theater Company is staging a
revival. The striking critics and bad weather may have been a
blessing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Beauty Part'' is little more than a series of skits strung
together in which Perelman skewers Hollywood, modern artists, the
judiciary, television, book publishing and faddish magazines. The
story line _ plot would be too strong a word _ that holds these
spoofs together is a quest by young Lance Weatherwax to discover
his artistic talent. He drops out of his Ivy League college,
renounces the wealth of his Park Avenue parents and tries
everything _ painting, writing, the movies, even advertising _ in
an effort to become an ``artist'' and win the girl of his dreams, a
Greenwich Village gold digger named April Monkhood. What he finds,
of course, is a world of hypocrisy and greed.
</P>
<P>
   The writing is in the faux hip that Perelman employed elsewhere
with success. But what reads funny on the page does not always play
funny on the stage, and the dialogue often sounds more like
captions for Thurber cartoons than anything one might actually say.
``The Beauty Part'' at times resembles a sort of low-rent ``Thurber
Carnival,'' only angrier.
</P>
<P>
   It is that bitterness that runs through the play that tends to
undermine the comedy. It takes a real clown to find the sympathy in
such broadly drawn characters and turn the ire into humor, and Dan
Wackerman, the Peccadillo director, does not have a Bert Lahr among
his cast of 13 actors who tackle the more than 40 different roles.
There are a couple of bright spots. Nicole Ravenna delivers a
vivacious and energetic performance as April, the material girl who
fires Lance's artistic impulses, and Philip Levy finds a way to
make the unscrupulous Hollywood huckster Harry Hubris a genuinely
comic figure. Jeff Patterson is an acceptably naive boy next door
as Lance.
</P>
<P>
   A group of eight jazz dancers not only provide entertainment
during the 11 scene changes but also become the sets themselves by
holding up doors, cabinets, tables and chairs for the actors to
use. As scenery it is clumsy, but the dancing is diverting.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE BEAUTY PART'
</P>
<P>
   By S.J. Perelman; directed by Dan Wackerman; choreography/dance
director, Cathleen Sweeney; sets by Mark Verzosa and Will Sharp;
costumes by Linda Ross; lighting by Doug Filomena. Presented by the
Peccadillo Theater Company. At the Bank Street Theater, 155 Bank
St., West Village.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Lisa Altomare, Dale Carman, Nicole S. Eaton, Ruth Jaffe,
Philip Levy, Jeff Patterson and Nicole Ravenna.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
