<HEADER>
A2530 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BRIDGE-OPERA-REVIEW-A     10-10 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRIDGE-OPERA-REVIEW-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`VIEW FROM THE BRIDGE': AN ADMIRABLE AND AFFECTING WORK
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ill., N.Y.)   (See also BRIDGE-OPERA-OPENING) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(jw) 
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Composers searching for opera subjects have to be wary
about turning automatically to stage plays, especially great plays
by well-respected authors. There are some obvious questions to ask
first: Why tamper with something that already works? What will
music add to it?
</P>
<P>
   Andre Previn grappled with this in composing his opera based on
Tennessee Williams' ``Streetcar Named Desire.'' The language of
this iconic masterpiece is so richly poetic and allusive, and the
escapist, anguished and brutal resonances of the characters are so
palpable and close the surface, that there is little any composer
could add, let alone someone of Previn's modest gifts.
</P>
<P>
   William Bolcom faced these questions also when he first
considered making an opera of Arthur Miller's 1955 play, ``A View
From the Bridge.'' But he was emboldened to do so by the playwright
himself, who wound up collaborating on a text for the opera with
Bolcom's longtime lyricist and librettist, Arnold Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
   That opera, more than four years in the making, was given its
premiere on Saturday night by the Lyric Opera of Chicago in a
strikingly designed, musically accomplished production with an
excellent cast. At its conclusion the audience responded with a
prolonged, cheering ovation, and Miller _ no opera buff, he admits
_ seemed especially awed. Although it does not break new ground in
the genre, or even attempt to, ``A View From the Bridge'' is an
admirable and often affecting work that convincingly solves the
problem of translating this play into an opera.
</P>
<P>
   Miller always said that ``A View From the Bridge'' was his most
operatic play. The story could be a modern-day Verdi tragedy. Eddie
Carbone, a workaday, hotheaded but decent-hearted longshoreman in
Red Hook, Brooklyn, and his steadfast wife, Beatrice, have raised
her sister's orphaned niece, Catherine, a spirited and blooming
woman of 17. Like some overprotective Rigoletto in a Brooklyn
tenement, Eddie has kept Catherine close to home and away from
young men. Not so deeply buried in his fatherly love is longing for
Catherine.
</P>
<P>
   The precarious balance of the small family is toppled when
Beatrice's cousins, illegal immigrants from Sicily, arrive one day.
The brawny Marco wants to earn money for his wife and sickly
children back home, and his winsome, charming younger brother,
Rodolpho, soon becomes enamored of Catherine, sending Eddie into
fits of twisted jealousy.
</P>
<P>
   Like an ill-fated character in ``La Forza del Destino,'' Eddie
brings about his own demise. Breaking a sacred code of the
neighborhood by reporting the men to the immigration service, he is
shunned by his neighbors and cursed by Mho provokes a fight.
Eddie pulls a knife. Marco plunges it into the crazed man's gut as
the neighbors watch helplessly.
</P>
<P>
   Miller says the play is filled with ``big block emotions.'' The
complexities of the characters are never fully explained, which is
why some critics consider the play an involving but lesser work.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
