<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-LONGHORNS-SOONERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOWN 17-0, LONGHORNS MARCH PAST SOONERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ There is, Texas coach Mack Brown said, a defining
moment for every team in every season.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, in a game that frequently lives on in legend long
after the final gun, the Longhorns might have found theirs in a
38-28 come-from-behind victory over Oklahoma before the 54th
consecutive sellout crowd in the Cotton Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game was critical for us because we're trying to
establish a personality,'' Brown said. ``To go two games down in
the Big 12 South with a week off and Nebraska coming in would be
really tough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt the thing our football team did today was play as a
team. Coach \RDarrell\S Royal always said you play as one heartbeat
and that's how you win. We didn't do that last week. We didn't do
that in the fourth quarter against North Carolina State. Today, we
played as a team. This game can help this young team win other
games.''
</P>
<P>
   A Texas team has not come from 17 points down to victory in 34
years, since a 21-17 victory over Texas A&AMP;M in 1965.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game does everything for team confidence,'' said senior
wide receiver Ryan Nunez, who caught passes for two touchdowns and
a two-point conversion among his five receptions for 51 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``The electricity in that stadium today was unreal. To bounce
back after a loss \Rlast week to Kansas State\S and after being
down 17 points today _ I just can't give us enough credit for the
way we played as a whole.''
</P>
<P>
   The teams combined for a series-record 883 yards total offense
and Texas posted a series-high 553. But the 23rd-ranked Longhorns
(5-2, 2-1 Big 12) were stunned by the Sooners' 17-point,
first-quarter scoring burst highlighted by long touchdown runs
after the catch by receivers Antwone Savage and Jarrail Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   But as Texas' defense finally corralled OU's offense _ holding
OU to 38 yards in the second quarter _ the Longhorns chipped into
the deficit with Kris Stockton field goals of 46, 41 and 37 yards.
Then just before the half, they struck quickly on a 61-yard,
two-play scoring drive that changed the game's momentum and tied
the after receiving the second-half kickoff to take its first lead
at 24-17 on a 21-yard run by halfback Hodges Mitchell, who had a
career game with 204 yards on 30 workhorse carries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our offensive players and coaches did a tremendous job of
taking the ball down and scoring with very little time left,''
Brown said. ``I thought that was a tremendous key to the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas struck again on an Applewhite-to-Kwame Cavil pass for 48
yards and a 31-20 lead, and OU answered with a 4-yard pass from
Patrick Fletcher to kicker Tim Duncan on a fake field-goal attempt.
</P>
<P>
   And Texas' crowning moment came when the Longhorns broke the
bonds of the worst-possible field position _ in the OU end of the
bowl _ to march 99 yards to the clinching touchdown on an 18-yard
pass from Applewhite to Nunez with 8:16 to play. The drive consumed
5:29.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably the difference in the game,'' Brown said. ``We've got
the ball on about our 6-inch line. And to take a 99-yard drive and
use that much of the clock showed so much character for an
offensive team that has not been able to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell popped the first play from the 1 for 35 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they put us at the 1-yard line they were thinking, `We
stop them here, we're going to win.''' Mitchell said, ``We knew if
we went 99 yards, Oklahoma's will would be broken.''
</P>
<P>
   OU held faint hope when cornerback Mike Woods recovered
Mitchell's fumble at the Sooner 39 with 2:50 to play. But Texas
cornerback Ahmad Brooks killed it when he picked off a Heupel pass
at the UT 15 with 1:20 left and Texas ran the table.
</P>
<P>
   The Sooners (3-2, 1-1) now contemplate a season stalled by
consecutive losses to Notre Dame and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to point the blame at the players or the
coaches,'' OU rookie coach Bob Stoops said. ``We need to get
better, to where we can make the plays that make the difference in
games like this.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think it's obvious we can play with anyone in this
league.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
