<HEADLINE>
SAFETY BLITZ HELPS TAKE AIR OUT OF OU
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ After watching Oklahoma roll to 17 points on its first
three possessions, Texas defensive coordinator Carl Reese began a
regular series of safety blitzes. The Longhorns' pass rushers,
during the final three quartrers, included three defensive linemen,
a linebacker and a safety from Texas' 3-2-6 alignment.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first quarter, we never touched the quarterback,''
Reese said. ``Once we started bringing the safety, we got to him.
We had to. They'd been picking us like a chicken until that
point.'' \Nname:_ Jimmy Burch \Nsubheds:Offensive showcase Texas
and Oklahoma combined for 883 yards of total offense yesterday,
including 553 by the Longhorns _ their highest output against
Oklahoma in the series' 94-game history.
</P>
<P>
   Texas' 38 points is the most it has scored against OU since the
Longhorns routed the Sooners, 41-9, in 1970. Meanwhile, first-year
Oklahoma quarterback Josh Heupel now has 1,669 passing yards in
five games, good for fourth on the school's career list. \Nname:_
Nathan Sanders \Nsubheds:Pass and run shows Some teams win with the
running game, some with the passing game. Fans of the Texas-OU
rivalry have seen both in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Oklahoma's DeMond Parker rushed for 291 yards and
Texas' Ricky Williams had 223 yards, making it only the third time
in NCAA history that two backs from opposing teams rushed for more
than 200 yards in the same game.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday showed what a difference two years makes, as the game
featured two 300-yard passers in OU's Josh Heupel (311 yards) and
Texas' Major Applewhite (328 yards). Texas running back Hodges
Mitchell also rushed for 204 yards. \Nname: _ Nathan Sanders
\Nsubheds:New-look Sooners Oklahoma rushed the ball 18 times in the
game for a total of 15 yards. It was the fewest rushes Oklahoma has
ever had in a ganst Texas. The previous low was 30 rushing
attempts in 1992 when Oklahoma fell behind early in a 34-24 loss to
the Longhorns.
</P>
<P>
   The Sooners were credited with two rushes in the first quarter
when they built up a 17-3 lead. One of the rushes was a 19-yard
quarterbac
</P>
<P>
   The Sooners threw the ball 49 times in the game, completing 32
for 315 yards. \Nname:_ John Miller \Nsubheds:Back-breaking drives
In each of the past two weeks, the Sooners have given up long
drives that changed the momentum of the game in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Last week against Notre Dame, the Sooners led 30-14, but allowed
the Fighting Irish to mount a comeback. Notre Dame scored the
go-ahead touchdown after putting together a 98-yard drive.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 31-28 yesterday to Texas, the Sooners pinned the
Longhorns back to their own 1-yard line after a 43-yard Jeff
Ferguson punt with 13:45 left in the game. Hodges Mitchell gave the
Longhorns breathing room with a 35-yard run first play of
the drive. That sparked a 12-9-yard drive that ended with an
18-yard touchdown pass from Major Applewhite to Ryan Nunez with
8:16 left to play, giving Texas a 38-28 lead. \Nname:_ John Miller
\Nsubheds:Briefly Texas played much of the game with six defensive
backs, giving freshman Roderick Babers his first career start and
cornerback Joe Walker his first start in four games. Walker had a
second-quarter interception, his first of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma was the first team in 15 games to score a touchdown on
its opening drive against the Texas defense.
</P>
<P>
   The two teams combined for 883 yards total offense, most in
series history. The previous mark was 850 in 1992. Texas' 553 yards
were the most the Longhorns have ever amassed against the Sooners.
</P>
<P>
   The two teams combined to throw 95 passes. In a four-year
stretch from 1973-76, the teams combined for 56 passes. \Nname:_
Jimmy Burch
