<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-LOAIZA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOAIZA MADE ONE MISTAKE THAT HURT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ One hundred pitches. One devastating mistake.ink about that. Think long and hard about that.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Esteban Loaiza will.
</P>
<P>
   ``One pitch cost us the game,'' Loaiza said. ``It's going to be
hard for me to forget about it.''
</P>
<P>
   New York's Darryl Strawberry unleashed the fury of his
left-handed swing and launched Loaiza's sinking, two-seam fastball
into The Ballpark in Arlington's sea of red.
</P>
<P>
   The three-run, first-inning home run stood the test of nine
innings and will be remembered as the decisive and only blow landed
during the Yankees' 3-0 victory in Game 3 of the Division Series on
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just got his arms extended and went to the opposite field
with it,'' Loaiza said of the 1-0, two-out pitch. ``He took a good
hack at it. I wish I could have that one inning back, and maybe
we'd still be playing right now. We're going to be thinking about
this all winter.''
</P>
<P>
   Few, though, will remember how well the Rangers pitched during
this Division Series despite being swept in three games by the
Yankees for the second time in as many Octobers.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' potent lineup will be scorned for scoring only one
run and hitting .152 during this series. Forgotten will be the
rotation's 3.93 earned-run average after being ridiculed most of
the regular season for posting the American League's second-worst
mark (5.49).
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys rose to occasion again,'' pitching coach Dick Bosman
said. ``I couldn't be prouder of those guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, their maligned rotation pitches best when it matters most.
</P>
<P>
   It delivered during the Rangers' make-or-break, September series
with the Anaheim Angels in 1998 and again the next month during the
Division Series against the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   The rotation rallied again this season during the Rangers'
all-important September series against the Oakland Athletics before
its effort this October.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know we can pitch,'' said right-hander Rick Helling,
who lost Game 2 despite allowing only two runs during a 61/3-inning
appearance. ``We believe in ourselves. I don't think you can
underestimate that.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, you have to be arrogant to a certain degree to be a
professional athlete. There are going to be times when no one
believes in you except yourself. We read all the time about how bad
we are, about our ERA's and the fact that we don't have an ace.
Well, we've done a pretty decent job the past two years.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't matter, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say much,'' Loaiza said. ``I pitched the game I wanted
to pitch.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-10-99 1857EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991010.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-10 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2534 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BRIDGE-OPERA-REVIEW-A     10-10 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRIDGE-OPERA-REVIEW-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 CHICAGO: lesser work.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Yet that very lack of specificity is what made the play
adaptable to operatic treatment. Music can fill in those big block
emotions. Miller urged his collaborators to cut and change lines
and reconfigure scenes as necessary to make the play an opera. He
specifically encouraged Bolcom to turn the neighbors of Red Hook,
who in most productions observe the family drama from the outskirts
of the stage, into a fully engaged operatic chorus. The play's
narrator, the lawyer Alfieri, here becomes the leader of that
chorus. It works very well in Weinstein's and Miller's deft
libretto.
</P>
<P>
   But operas are remembered, or not, for their music. Bolcom has
said that his goal in this score is to create ``grand opera
Brooklynized,'' and this he achieves. Although there are rootless
atonal passages and thickly layered orchestral sonorities that
recall Messiaen, the musical language is essentially tonal and the
melodic writing, for all the darting intervalic zigs and zags, is
essentially lyrical, as befits a contemporary work that evokes the
sensibility of Italian opera.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Bolcom's ear for harmony is acute and interesting. His
chords are often thick with notes and pungent with dissonance,
especially when played on the piano from the piano-vocal score.
That biting quality is softened by the orchestration, not always
for the better. Dissonant notes are tucked neatly into rich
sonorities. I often found myself wishing that Bolcom had preserved
the astringency of his harmony.
</P>
<P>
   The most pronounced characteristic of the score is its bold mix
of styles. Bolcom's penchant for incorporating vernacular American
song and dance forms into his concert works and operas has divided
critics. Some find it vibrant and authentic. (Few composers today
have his direct experience as a pianist and arranger of that
vernacular music.) Others think it self-consciously clever and
superficial. In his last full-length opera, ``McTeague,'' a grim
tale of an avaricious couple, a work also commissioned and given
its premiere, in 1992, by the Lyric Opera, the mix of ragtime,
blues, waltzes, barbershop quartet, Italianate arias and aggressive
modernist angst put off some critics.
</P>
<P>
   In ``A View From the Bridge'' the musical styles that collide
are less wide ranging and overall more subtly rendered than in
``McTeague.'' The excitable Rodolpho sings a clackety sort of
hyper-aria about his dream of one day owning a motorcycle,
concluding with a tenorial high C, a cue for the audience to
applaud in the grand tradition. A group of dock workers, drinking
on the job at Christmastime, break into doo-wop.
</P>
<P>
   The pop standard ``Paper Doll'' is heard on the phonograph in
Eddie's house as Rodolpho and Catherine dance, and also, during a
comic moment, in an emotive, soggy, soaring version that Rodolpho
sings in his idea of American jazz style. Touches like these flesh
out characters and bring variety to the score.
</P>
<P>
   The most compelling music comes when anxious, ominous orchestral
writing provides a subtext for sung dialogue between characters, as
in the passage when Eddie tries to convince Beatrice that the
blond, flamboyant Rodolpho is not only a ``hit and run guy'' just
interested in gaining American citizenship by marrying Catherine,
but also not ``right,'' meaning sexually. (Eddie's evidence is that
Rodolpho is a good cook, mends dresses and sings in a high tenor
voice.) Here Eddie's punchy vocal lines are buttressed by
insinuating orchestral music with softly piercing chords and
asymmetrical (or ``off'') measures of seven beats.
</P>
<P>
   That said, dramatically and musically Bolcom is almost too fixed
on his goal of creating Brooklynized grand opera. Often it sounds
like Bolcomized Italian verismo. There are mellifluous arias for
the lovesick Rodolpho and the aflutter Catherine and an impassioned
sort of Mama Lucia monologue for Beatrice. The most overtly Verdian
moment is a basso aria of aggrievement and retribution for Marco
(with new words by Miller) that actually explains this pivotal
character more convincingly than in the play. But I wish Bolcom had
taken more chances.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the chorus of neighbors could have been used more
pervasively. There are moments when the chorus members line up,
ominously intone some lines like ``Eddie never knew he had a
destiny,'' then leave. It can get melodramatic, like something out
of the musical ``Titanic.''
</P>
<P>
   And Brooklynized grand opera is not entirely new. Gian-Carlo
Menotti tried it in his under-appreciated opera ``The Saint of
Bleecker Street'' (well, same city, different borough, but pretty
close). Even ``West Wide Story'' is in the general esthetic
vicinity. ``A View From the Bridge'' is maybe too quick to please,
too willing to give away its musical secrets.
</P>
<P>
   But such quibbling comes close to criticizing the opera for what
it is not rather that acknowledging it for the serious, skillful
and often captivating work it is.
</P>
<P>
   The production could not have been better. The set by Santo
Loquasto places the Carbone family in the shadow of the Brooklyn
Bridge; black-and-white images of the neighborhood, the docks and
far-off Italy are projected on large, intersecting background
screens.
</P>
<P>
   The director, Frank Galati, has drawn memorable performances
from the fine cast, headed by the robust baritone Kim Josephson as
Eddie, whose bluster is a pitiable cover for his weakness, and the
intense soprano Catherine Malfitano as Beatrice, whose compliance
in the face of her husband's domestic rule does not mask her steely
willpower. The radiant soprano Juliana Rambaldi was the vulnerable
Catherine, who learns too late that Eddie will baby her as long as
she acts like a baby. The impressive young tenor Gregory Turay was
an ardent, endearing Rodolpho and the strong bass-baritone Mark
McCrory was all smoldering righteousness as Marco. The baritone
Timothy Nolen was a stentorian Alfieri.
</P>
<P>
   Bolcom set words felicitously, but this cast deserves much
praise for making them clear. Dennis Russell Davies conducted a
richly colored and supplely paced account of the score.
</P>
<P>
   Where ``A View From the Bridge'' ranks in the pantheon of opera
is a boring question. Let history decide. For now we have a new
work of integrity and skill that reached people and much deserves a
hearing beyond the eight additional performances it will receive
here through Nov. 5.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
