<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHANGE IS SOUGHT IN DIGITAL TV
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 300 of the nation's 1,600 television stations have filed
a petition with the Federal Communications Commission reque
revision in the nation's digital TV standard. The stations contend
that the standard is flawed because the digital receivers on the
market cannot easily receive a viewable picture in anything short
of ideal circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   BRITISH PAPERS TAKE BRAWL TO WEB
</P>
<P>
   The no-holds-barred competition among Britain's broadsheet
newspapers has taken a new turn, and the fabled wars of what used
to be known as Fleet Street have spilled into cyberspace. The
Financial Times, for example, is creating an integrated newsroom
where journalists will work to feed the Web site, FT.com, as well
as the newspaper. The Web site itself will be reinvented as a fully
fledged Internet portal. Indeed, Britain's online broadsheet
newspapers are promoting a range of interconnected offerings
designed to lure just about everyone from job seekers to movie
buffs to high-flying executives.
</P>
<P>
   HELPING TO SET UP SHOP ON THE WEB
</P>
<P>
   As more companies develop a full-scale Internet presence,
e-commerce software and service providers are competing more
furiously for market share. One increasingly popular approach is to
offer an ``all-in-one'' package, in which merchants pay a nominal
monthly fee for software that enables them to build a site that is
then run by a third party. Bob Tedeschi: E-Commerce Report.
</P>
<P>
   EASING OF EXPORT RULES HAS LIMITS
</P>
<P>
   Under plans to relax restrictions on exports of data-scrambling
software, a key issue that escaped notice was that the new policies
affect only shrink-wrapped software, not the original source code _
the lines of instructions that programmers actually write.
</P>
<P>
   NOTES SUBPOENAED IN MURDER CASE
</P>
<P>
   A reporter for a magazine published by a civil rights group hn subpoenaed to provide tape recordings and notes of an
interview with a murder defendant. The reporter is said to have
told a federal investigator that the defendant acknowledged killing
someone.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY INVESTORS LOOK TO AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   With nearly 800 million people in nearly 50 countries speaking
hundreds of dialects and often in conflict with one another, Africa
has attracted almost no technology investment. But that is
beginning to change as Worldspace, a Washington company, broadcasts
digital radio programming from a satellite to the African
continent.
</P>
<P>
   COLUMBUS DAY CLOSINGS
</P>
<P>
   Though stock markets are open Monday, the Treasury bond market,
commodity trading in some financial contracts, government offices
and many banks are closed in observance of Columbus Day. They will
reopen Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
