</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVES' JORDAN PLANS TO KEEP HIS BAT HOT AGAINST THE METS
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Brian Jordan left the St. Louis Cardinals and signed with
the Atlanta Braves before this season, he envisioned winning a
championship in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Jordan is determined to reach his goal. He hit .474
during the National League Division Series, carrying Atlanta's
offense, and is a major reason the Braves will be facing the New
York Mets in the league championship series beginning Tuesday night
at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is why I signed to come here,'' said Jordan, who was 8
for 17 with a home run and 8 runs batted in as Atlanta eliminated
the Houston Astros, 3 games to 1, in the division series. ``This
team, year after year, is in the postseason. They have a great
organization, and I'm happy to be back in the postseason. This is
it, either you are going to win, or you're going home. The way I
see it, I'm going to lay it on the line. I'm going to put my body
out there and may the best man win. Hopefully, we'll come out on
top.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be difficult for the Mets to win unless they figure out
how to contain Jordan. Batting cleanup behind Chipper Jones, Jordan
made the Astros regret their decision to pitch around Jones. While
Jones drew a team-high five walks during the series, which ended
with Atlanta's 7-5 victory on Saturday, Jordan kept getting clutch
hits and driving in runs.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have seen that before. The Braves beat the Mets 9 out
of 12 times during the regular season, and the hitting of Jones and
Jordan was a major reason why Atlanta dominated. Jordan hit .359
against New York during the regular season, with 3 triples, 3 home
runs and 13 RBIs, while Jones was even more devastating against the
Mets, hitting .400 with 7 home runs and 16 RBIs
</P>
<P>
   In a crucial three-game sweep of the Mets in September, Jones
almost single-handedly won the series, hitting four home runs.
Another performance like that will send the Mets packing, but if
the Mets pitch around Jones, Jordan has served notice that he will
be ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm at my best when I've got runners in scoring position,''
said Jordan, who drove in a career-high 115 runs during the regular
season despite a wrist injury that limited his power in the second
half of the season. ``If you get some guys out there for me, I'm
going to come through for you.''
</P>
<P>
   While Jones and Jordan are a formidable one-two offensive punch,
pitching is the constant in Atlanta's success. Every starter the
Mets will face during the NLCS will be capable of a dominant
performance. Greg Maddux, John Smoltz and Tom Glavine are all Cy
Young Award winners, but Atlanta's best pitcher at the moment may
be 24-year-old Kevin Millwood, who was 18-7 this season and threw a
one-hitter against Houston in Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``After about the first four or five starts this year, Kevin
really got on a roll where he was just dominating every game,''
said Bobby Cox, Atlanta's manager. ``I don't know how many games
Kevin went into this year with no-hitters in the fourth inning, the
fifth inning, or the sixth inning. It was almost a routine deal
that you'd look up on the scoreboard and the other team didn't have
any hits. That's a good indication of how he was throwing.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter how Cox sets up his rotation against the Mets, he will
feel confident. Glavine was 3-0 against the Mets this year, Maddux
was 3-1 and Millwood was 1-0. Smoltz was the only starter in
Atlanta's four-man playoff rotation who lost to the Mets all
season.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, John Rocker has emerged as a dominant relief pitcher
for the Braves. Against Houston, Rocker escaped a base-loaded,
nobody-out jam in the 10th inning of Game 3, which proved to be the
turning point of the series. Then in the clinching victory, Rocker
shut down another Astros rally and recorded the final four outs of
the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a lot of heroes this year, but if I had to pick one,
I'd say John Rocker,'' said Smoltz. ``I've never seen a guy
dominate in crucial situations like he has.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Braves will feel more pressure in the championship
series than the Mets will. This is Atlanta's eighth appearance in
the NLCS this decade, but Atlanta has won only one World Series in
that time, beating the Cleveland Indians in 1995. The Braves have
grown accustomed to lofty expectations, and they will take a
business-like approach into the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just a belief from spring training that we are going
to do whatever it takes to win a World Series,'' said Smoltz.
``There's very few organizations that year in and year out have the
mindset to do whatever it takes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't make the playoffs, it's easy to forget. But if
you keep going to the playoffs like we have, it's more of a sore
thumb if you don't win it all.''
</P>
<P>
   But once again, the Braves find themselves one series away from
a potential World Series berth. This time, the Mets are standing in
Atlanta's way. But the Braves appear ready for the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mets are a good club and so are the Braves,'' said Cox.
``It should be a great series.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
