A2546 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKEES-WILLIAMS-     10-10 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-WILLIAMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES' WILLIAMS AND HIS DEFENSE REST FOR A FEW DAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Bernie Williams was among the last to depart
the sweet-smelling visitors' clubhouse here, a room soggy from the
champagne and beer sprayed and spilt in celebration following the
Yankees' mastery of the Texas Rangers in the Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   Williams had avoided the most tempestuous portion of the
post-game party last Saturday night, and that is his way. He mostly
keeps to himself in words and thought, and what he believed when
the series began was that defense would be the difference between
winning or losing. Williams then turned this into a self-fulfilling
prophecy with three spectacular games in center field.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees returned home Sunday, and there were no formal
workouts planned for Monday. They will practice Tuesday, in
preparation for the four-of-seven American League Championship
Series that is scheduled to begin Wednesday, at Yankee Stadium; the
Yankees will play the winner of the Division Series between the
Cleveland Indians and the Boston Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Torre, the Yankees' manager, said Sunday that he is not sure
what his pitching rotation will be for the next round of playoffs.
David Cone had been scheduled to work Game 4 against Texas _ a game
that became unnecessary when the Yankees swept the Rangers in three
games, limiting Texas to one run and a .152 batting average _ and
is available to open the ALCS.
</P>
<P>
   If Torre employs the same strategy he did last year, when the
Yankees swept Texas in the first round, then he will revert back to
the rotation he used to start the playoffs. Orlando Hernandez would
be scheduled to pitch Games 1 and 5, Andy Pettitte Games 2 and 6,
Roger Clemens Games 3 and 7, and Cone Game 4. ``I don't know why
you'd change anything,'' Cone said. ``Whatever Joe decides is fine.
All of his decisions have worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees probably will not know until Tuesday or Wednesday
whether right fielder Paul O'Neill will be available to play in the
first games of the next round. They do not even know if he will be
able to play for the rest of the postseason, because of the bruised
ribs that forced him to the bench for Game 3 of the Division
Series. O'Neill said Saturday that unless he improves quickly, he
is not sure if he will be able to play.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was far more than able against the Rangers. To Johnny
Oates, the Texas manager, the Yankees' center fielder was
difference between losing and winning. After the Rangers' Game 3
loss, Oates referred to the sliding catch Williams made in Game 1
of the series. If Juan Gonzalez's liner had fallen in, Oates said,
``It would have been a whole different series. That play set the
tone, I thought.''
</P>
<P>
   But Williams provided a wide range of choices for his best
defensive play in the series. Jorge Posada, the Yankees' catcher,
believes that Williams' sliding stop of Ivan Rodriguez's bounding
ball and quick throw to second in the sixth inning of Game 2 _
which prevented Rodriguez from stretching a lead-off single into a
double _ was the pivotal moment of the playoff. The score was tied
1-1 at the time and Juan Gonzalez followed Rodriguez by bouncing
into a double play. ``If they get a run there,'' said Posada, ``who
knows what happens after that.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, in Game 3, the Yankees established a 3-0 lead in the first
inning, on Darryl Strawberry's home run, and Roger Clemens fought
to protect this advantage. Royce Clayton, the Rangers' No. 8
batter, opened the bottom of the fifth with a long drive that some
of the Texas players thought would clear the center-field fence
easily.
</P>
<P>
   But in his sprinter's stride, Williams dashed toward the wall,
made the catch about two steps from the fence and slammed into the
padding, chest first. ``He was so quick getting to it that he was
able to catch it and still sort of brace himself to hit the wall,''
Torre marveled afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the idea in my mind that the series was going to be won
on the defensive side, rather than the offensive side,'' Williams
said. ``I knew these guys could hit, and I had to be on my toes and
catch everything that I could out there. It worked out well,
because I was able to get a lot of good jumps on balls in really
crucial situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams made another running catch to take away a hit from
Clayton in the seventh inning. All of the Yankees seemed to play
well defensively in the series. Posada and Joe Girardi, the
catchers, were lauded by some of the club's staff for studying the
scouting reports on the Rangers, formulating a plan of attack with
the pitchers and then exploiting the Texas weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch, whose throwing problems had been a concern when
the series began, played well defensively with the exception of a
fumbled grounder in Game 2. He threw with confidence, particularly
as he finished double plays. First baseman Tino Martinez made a
leaping catch to start a double play in Game 1 and the left side of
the Yankees' infield played flawlessly. One of the Yankees'
greatest weaknesses, their inability to prevent opposing base
runners from stealing, ne a factor, because the Rangers
mustered just 14 hits in three games.
</P>
<P>
   But the challenges to the Yankees' defense could be much greater
in the ALCS, especially if Cleveland advances. Kenny Lofton, Omar
Vizquel and Roberto Alomar are all capable of creating havoc on the
bases, and most of the Indians do not hit with the reckless abandon
that the Rangers have.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox are not graced with great base-stealers, but they
are aggressive, and Fenway Park's outfield is difficult to
navigate, with its odd angles and dimensions. If O'Neill is out of
the lineup, Ricky Ledee could be playing Fenway's right field,
perhaps the most difficult outfield spot in the majors because of
its huge space and curling fence line. Williams knows this: Defense
could decide the Yankees' next series as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
