u s BC-BBN-METS-NOTEBOOK-NYT     10-10 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
 
METS NOTEBOOK  (ms) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   YOSHII MAY OPEN AGAINST MADDOX
</P>
<P>
   Mets Manager Bobby Valentine still has not officially announced
his pitching rotation for the National League Championship Series,
but Masato Yoshii will almost certainly start Game 1 Tuesday night
against Greg Maddux. Al Leiter would be available for Games 3 and 7
on his regular rest, meaning that Valentine would have to juggle
the order in which Kenny Rogers and Rick Reed pitch. The rotation
for the division series was Yoshii, Rogers, Reed, Leiter.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine said that he was planning to discuss the rotation with
the pitching coach Dave Wallace, but a few things are certain: Orel
Hershiser and Octavio Dotel will remain in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Millwood, Tom Glavine and John Smoltz will also face the
Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we're going to be doing anything radical,''
Valentine said. ``It will probably be a little bit of change
somewhere in the rotation.''
</P>
<P>
   GAME-TIME DECISION ON PIAZZA
</P>
<P>
   Mike Piazza continued to receive treatment on his inflamed left
thumb Sunday and hoped to swing a bat during Monday night's workout
in Atlanta to help determine his availability for Tuesday night's
game.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets, who have to submit their 25-man roster for this round
by Tuesday morning, may add Mike Kinkade, an infielder who spent
most of the minor league season catching. General Manager Steve
Phillips said the team would stick with 11 pitchers on the roster,
meaning an extra position player would be dropped but he would not
specify who it might be.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Mets hope Piazza can return, they would add the
extra catcher if for some reason he could not return for
consecutive games.
</P>
<P>
   TARDY BENITEZ IS FINED
</P>
<P>
   Armando Benitez, who arrived about a half-hour before last
Saturday's game, will be fined for his tardiness. The team
stretched at 11:45 a.m. and Valentine was told that Benitez had at
to arrive by 12:30 p.m. for the 1:10 game. Benitez, who lives about
40 minutes from Shea Stadium, said he was stuck in traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you time it late, you're going to be late,'' Valentine
said. ``I'm sure he left late and I'm sure he was not there on time
because he left the house late. It wasn't the greatest news before
a game. I was on pins and needles making the decision to have him
go out there, not because they hit two balls solid but because I
was unsure of his condition. The explanation could be as simple as
bad planning and hopefully it won't be anything worse than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Benitez gave up a two-run double to the first batter he faced,
Jay Bell, but pitched one and one-third innings.
</P>
<P>
   SUSPENSION LIKELY FOR ROJAS
</P>
<P>
   The third-base coach Cookie Rojas is likely to receive a two- or
three-game suspension in the wake of his furious argument with the
left-field umpire Charlie Williams, after which Rojas said Williams
had cursed him.
</P>
<P>
   Mets General Manager Steve Phillips said he had not heard
anything from the National League President Leonard Coleman, but
the league is expected to announce the punishment Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the replays during the game,'' Phillips said. ``It
seemed to me the contact was from the umpire to Cookie first. It's
hard to predict how the president will rule on this.''
</P>
<P>
   TICKETS GO ON SALE
</P>
<P>
   Tickets for National League Championship Series games to be
played at Shea Stadium next weekend will go on sale Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Numbered wristbands will be distributed to fans at Shea Stadium
at 7 a.m. Tuesday, and the Mets will randomly select the starting
number and announce it at 9:15 a.m. Only cash will be accepted at
the ball park.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone sales start at 10 a.m., and only American Express,
Discover, MasterCard and Visa will be accepted. There is a service
charge of $6 per ticket for phone orders.
</P>
<P>
   Most tickets are priced at $50 to $70. Each fan may purchase a
maximum of eight tickets a game.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets are home for Games 3 Friday at 8:12 p.m., Game 4
Saturday at 7:42 p.m. and Game 5, if necessary, Sunday at 4:09
p.m. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
