<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    One-day rain delay no sweat for Burton
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ Jeff Burton's specialty this season has been
winning races in the rain.
</P>
<P>
   Burton won both of the rain-shortened events at Darlington. And
he may find himself looking through a wet windshield again today at
Lowe's Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Light showers are expected for the UAW-GM Quality 500, which has
been rescheduled for 11 a.m. today. The race was postponed on
Sunday because of inclement weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rain affects your strategy for a race,'' Burton said.
``You can win big with your decisions, or you can lose big.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's postponement was the first of the season for NASCAR
officials. It was also the first time since 1960 the Charlotte
track has had to reschedule a Winston Cup race.
</P>
<P>
   With many drivers already complaining about Charlotte's
traditional Wednesday qualifying _ two days earlier than normal for
a Sunday race _ the postponement has made a long week even longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ridiculous that we're at Charlotte as long as we are
anyway,'' Burton said. ``To have to be at a race track for six days
with one of those being a rain day is ridiculous, and that's just
part of a whole deal about being here so long. These guys are away
from home enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton, who is fifth in the Winston Cup points standings, has
won five races, second best on the circuit behind Jeff Gordon
(six). The Ford No. 99 driver was successful twice at Darlington
with his team's rain strategies.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can win races in the rain by using certain strategies,''
Burton said. ``However, if it doesn't rain or it stops and you've
used that strategy, then you're in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rain changes really everything because if it starts sprinkling
halfway through a race and you need to pit for fuel, you are like,
`I can't pit for fuel. I've got to sit out here and wait and hope
my car doesn't run out of fuel because the race could be called at
any moment.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It changes things 100 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
