<HEADER>
A2553 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKEES-COLUMN-NY     10-10 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE CHAMPAGNE IS NOT STALE FOR THE YANKEES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JACK CURRY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Yankees sipped, sprayed and splashed champagne on another
methodical sort of night in Arlington, Texas, a scene that was so
familiar to them it was eerie. Once again, the Yankees ejected the
Rangers from the Division Series in three games. Once again, Darryl
Strawberry was the focus of a wet celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-three weeks ago, Tim Raines stood on a folding table in
the middle of the clubhouse, requested silence and then hoisted a
bottle of bubbly to toast Strawberry, who was in the hospital
preparing for colon cancer surgery the next day. The Yankees had
Strawberry's No. 39 on their caps and they had bulges in their
throats as they chanted his name.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday night, the Yankees toasted Strawberry in person by
showering the Prodigal Yankee with some non-alcoholic champagne
after his three-run homer had helped guide them past the powerless
Rangers, 3-0. Strawberry has amazingly evolved into a critical
component on a team that looks real special again. Does this
slightly updated script seem like a repeat from last October?
</P>
<P>
   ``For some reason, these Yankee uniforms bring out unbelievable
stories,'' said Chuck Knoblauch. ``It's almost spooky sometimes how
things work out here. It's that Yankee mystique, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a different team, but the Yankees accomplished the same
expected result. This is a different season, but the Yankees have
the same lofty goals. This is not 1998 and no season will ever
duplicate that magical march, but do not underestimate these
Yankees. Do not doubt that they can defend their World Series
championship and probably will over the Braves. A Subway Series
would be phenomenal for New York, but the Braves have halted the
Mets in almost the same manner as the Yankees humbled the Rangers
so realism needs to be exhibited, too.
</P>
<P>
   The ease in which the Yankees dispatched the Rangers, a team
that won 95 games yet looks like a scared Class AAA club against
them, is incredible. With Orlando Hernandez, Andy Pettitte and
Roger Clemens mesmerizing the Rangers and stifling them on one run,
the Yankees emphatically reminded everyone that they should be
considered the premier team in baseball until proven otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people are always putting the word vulnerable in front of
the team,'' said Derek Jeter. ``It's still the same team we had
last year. We didn't win the same number of games, but we know
we're capable of doing a lot of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though players sometimes create their own motivation by
selectively remembering critical comments, some Yankees felt they
have not received proper respect this year. Texas Manager Johnny
Oates, who cannot push his disappearing team past the first round,
called the Yankees ``human'' before El Duque tossed a pitch in Game
1. Oates might have been trying to spark his players, but he would
have been better off waiting until Texas won a game before he
tweaked the Yankees for not being among the best teams of all-time
for a second straight season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we didn't win 114 games in the regular season and
people say we lost our swagger and lost this and lost that,'' said
Tino Martinez. ``But we never had a cockiness. We always had a
business-like approach and found ways to win. We haven't changed
that. People wrote us off a little, but we have just as much
confidence as we ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   And they should. The Yankees have better pitching than the
Indians or the Red Sox and Joe Torre should not tinker with the
rotation for the ALCS. While Torre has said David Cone could start
Game 1 in what seems like a verbal bouquet to a proud pitcher, Cone
should remain behind Hernandez, Pettitte and Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   If Paul O'Neill's bruised ribs prevent him from playing, that
would be a serious loss. But the Yankees looked formidable as they
played terrific defense, received enough offense from Bernie
Williams and Strawberry and watched Mariano Rivera, who may be the
best pitcher in the major leagues behind Pedro Martinez, powerfully
finish two games in the Division Series. The Yankees' body language
seemingly snapped, ``OK, who's next?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I almost felt like everyone was writing us off by saying we
could be beat this year,'' said Knoblauch. ``Any team can be beat,
but I still don't understand why I heard it so much. Because we
didn't win 114 games? We got almost the same pitchers and the same
lineup. It's strange. It motivates us.''
</P>
<P>
   The motivation for the 1999 Yankees, who had 16 fewer victories
during the regular season than in 1998, is to duplicate the final
result of 1998, imitating the 1961 (109 victories) and 1962 (96)
Yankees and the 1927 (110) and 1928 (101) Yankees. Even if the
Yankees might not be as dominating as in 1998, a World Series title
is all that matters. That is why Jeter should have choked on
champagne when he was asked if another exhilarating October felt
stale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does it look like it's getting old?'' asked Jeter, his shirt
soaked and his eyes darting around the clubhouse in self-defense.
``It's not getting old. I hope it lasts forever.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
