<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-RESERVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NETS' SCRIMMAGE REVEALS ENCOURAGING BENCH STRENGTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. _ More than 200 people filed into the
bleachers at the Atlantic City Convention Center on Sunday, eagerly
awaiting a demonstration of basketball prowess by Stephon Marbury
and Keith Van Horn of the New Jersey Nets.
</P>
<P>
   But as the Nets' intrasquad scrimmage materialized, the crowd oly youngsters found themselves cheering for three other Nets
whose play was both surprising and encouraging in its
effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Newman, who will turn 36 next month; Gheorghe Muresan,
who has played less than two minutes the last two seasons, and
Elliot Perry, who the Nets have attempted to trade on numerous
occasions, were the surprise stars of an exhibition in which
Marbury and Van Horn were relegated to the periphery.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets' reserves blasted the starters, 56-33, in a 24-minute
scrimmage that served as the official close of training camp.
</P>
<P>
   And while no one put much stock in the embarrassing result _
except perhaps a custodian attendant who insisted that ``the Nets
should start their bench'' _ everyone was thrilled with the
performance of a second unit that appears to give the Nets great
depth.
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn, who scored only 4 points on 2-of-7 shooting, said the
reserves were due for a victory because the starters had been
pounding them all week.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it was great that they beat us and showed what they can
do,'' he said. ``The two most encouraging players were Johnny
Newman and Gheorghe Muresan. It's nice to know that we'll have guys
like that coming off the bench, so when the first five comes out,
there won't be any slippage.''
</P>
<P>
   Newman, the journeyman small forward playing for the sixth team
of his 14-year National Basketball Association career, was
dazzling, scoring a game-high 18 points on nearly flawless offense.
He hit a 3-pointer, finished strong on the fast break, lofted a
nifty finger roll over Jim McIlvaine and was active on defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been more than what we anticipated,'' General Manager
John Nash said of Newman. ``We wanted him for his leadership
qualities and his character, but as a player we would not have
predicted that he had as much as he's shown. He was fresh as a
daisy at the end while some of our younger guys were wheezing.''
</P>
<P>
   With his streaky scoring ability, Newman would seem to be a
great player off the bench, but he has been so productive
throughout camp that he could wind up nudging Scott Burrell for the
starter's job.
</P>
<P>
   ``My intention is always to be a starter,'' said Newman, who
insists that his age is not a factor. ``I take care of myself. I
don't let my body go down in the off season. There's nothing bad or
illegal in my extracurricular activities and my night life is very
conservative. So I'm able to come out and compete.''
</P>
<P>
   While Newman and Perry (10 points and 3 assists) dominated the
perimeter, Muresan _ who is listed as 7 feet 7 inches and 303
pounds _ ruled play inside.
</P>
<P>
   After missing two days with a strained left groin, he returned
to exhibit many of the qualities that enabled him to average 14.5
points, 9.6 rebounds and 2.2 blocks for the Washington Bullets four
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Though Newman did most of the scoring, Muresan was arguably the
game's most valuable player. His soft shooting touch was missing,
but he was still able to score 10 points on 5-of-10 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Muresan also led all rebounders and moved relatively smoothly
while changing the trajectory of several shots to help hold the
Nets' starters scoreless from the post.
</P>
<P>
   Few players can keep Muresan from establishing post position on
the low block, and his size and shooting accuracy make him nearly
unstoppable.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, his presence in the lane limits almost all
penetration by the opponent. If Muresan can maintain his health and
improve his conditioning, he could be the find of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how he impacts games when he's on the floor,'' said
Nash, who signed Mure the final two games last season. ``He
immy improves a team defensively because players won't
contest him. He's not quite where he was in Washington but he's
getting there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
