<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-AVALANCHE-ISLANDERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
18-YEAR-OLD ROOKIE CENTER LIFTS ISLANDERS TO VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ Sometimes, it is hard to believe that Tim
Connolly, the Islanders' rookie center, is just 18. He seems so
much older when he is faking a veteran defenseman or making a
snappy pass or shooting the puck past one of the league's top
goaltenders.
</P>
<P>
   This year's first-round draft pick did all of that and more
Sunday afternoon. But perhaps most importantly, he gave the 14,523
fans at the home opener a reason to come back to Nassau Coliseum
this season. Connolly scored a dazzling goal, his first in the
National Hockey League, and he also recorded his first assist to
help the Islanders beat the Colorado Avalanche, 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   After putting his team ahead by 2-1 early in the second period,
Connolly, who was selected by the Islanders with the fifth pick
over all in June, set up the game-winning goal. The goal, scored on
the power play by Mariusz Czerkawski later in the same period, gave
the Islanders (1-1-0) a commanding 3-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The pass was pretty, but it was Connolly's spectacular goal that
will be remembered by Islanders fans, who gave Connolly a warm
welcome when he was introduced before the game. Islanders fans, it
seems, have found their new favorite player.
</P>
<P>
   On the play, Connolly, a center, was fed the puck in the corner
by Mark Lawrence. Connolly then faked defenseman Aaron Miller,
before skating between the circles, where he faked Chris Drury to
his knees. But the most impressive part of the play was Connolly's
patience, the way he waited for the clean shot, which he eventually
got.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up watching Patrick Roy,'' said Connolly, who after the
game was presented with the puck by his linemate Gino Odjick, ``and
to score my first goal against him was unbelievable. It's also
relieving getting that first goal out of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Islanders forward Claude Lapointe, who scored the Islanders'
fourth goal on a breakaway late in the game, said: ``He's
impressing a lot of people. He's only 18, but it seems like he's
been playing in the league for a few years, at least.''
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders were coming off of a long layoff between games,
and they had fresher legs than the Avalanche, who is without Peter
Forsberg (shoulder surgery) indefinitely. The visiting team looked
tired and disorganized at times. But the Islanders played above and
beyond their expectations for 60 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was extremely impressed,'' Islanders Coach Butch Goring
said. ``I was worried about how we were going to perform after the
eight days off. But to my surprise, we had some good jump. We
played aphysical, good forechecking game.''
</P>
<P>
   Roy, the Colorado goalie, made 27 saves; Felix Potvin made 14
stops for the Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   The customary opening day pre-game ceremony was classy and
sentimental, from the player introductions to Mike Bossy, the
former Islander great, coming out to a standing ovation before
dropping the puck in a ceremonial face-off. Later, Bob Nystrom,
Mike Bossy, Wayne Merrick and Al Arbour, all of whom were a part of
the Stanley Cup teams of the 1980's, welcomed home their old
friend, Goring, the Islanders' first year coach, in a video
tribute.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, the pre-game activities were not the game's only
fireworks. The Islanders blew away the Avalanche early in the game,
out-shooting the visitors by 12-2. Although the score was 1-1 at
the end of the first period, it seemed like a victory for the
Islanders, who have struggled in recent seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado defenseman Sandis Ozolinsh scored on the power play on
Colorado's first shot of the game at 3 minutes 37 seconds. The
Avalanche did not get off another shot until 13:14. During the
Colorado cold streak, Mats Lindgren scored the Islanders' first
goal on the power play at 12:22 to tie the game at 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders took a 3-2 lead in the second period and had
out-shot the Avalanche by 24-8. The Islanders got the goals from
Connolly at 1:28 of the second period and Czerkwski on the power
play at 3:25 to take a 3-1 lead. Colorado's Alex Tanguay pulled the
Avalanche within 3-2, scoring on the power play at 16:59 of the
second period.
</P>
<P>
   Lapointe added an insurance goal on a breakaway with 54 seconds
remaining in the game to make the score 4-2. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
