<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-10 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2573 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-HKN-THRASHERS11-COX     10-10 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-THRASHERS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Forwards get boost from more ice time
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It wasn't what Curt Fraser expected would be the cure
to his team's struggling offense _ and it may not be the long-term
solution.
</P>
<P>
   But after scoring five goals against an improbable opponent
(Stanley Cup finalist Buffalo), including four against a
sometimes-impossible goaltender (Dominik Hasek), the Thrashers on
Saturday night came to the realization that less might be more.
</P>
<P>
   Fraser suited up only 11 forwards and carried an extra
defenseman (seven total) for the first time, which gave more ice to
the primary three forward lines. That hardly was the only reason
the Thrashers _ after scoring only two goals in the previous four
outings, including two exhibitions _ managed a 5-5 tie with
Buffalo, but Fraser is convinced it was a significant contributor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Running four lines is very important for us because we need to
get everybody involved in the offense,'' Fraser said. ``But right
now we need to find ways to win. With the (television) timeouts and
all the stoppages in play, guys like (Patrik) Stefan and (Ray)
Ferraro aren't getting enough ice time. This gives them a chance to
generate a little more offense for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro struggled for the third consecutive game, going
pointless and picking up two minor penalties, one of which led to a
Sabres power-play goal. Fraser's abbreviated analysis: ``He's
getting frustrated. We can't have that.'' Andrew Brunette, one of
Ferraro's linemates, scored his first goal of the year, which
Fraser hopes jumpstarts the center.
</P>
<P>
   But the Thrashers were aided by strong play from two other
trios: The Stefan-Kelly Buchberger-Nelson Emerson line accounted
for three goals and four assists. The new combination of Per
Svartvadet-Johan Garpenlov-Denny Lambert started the game and
produced a goal and three assists and several scoring chances.
</P>
<P>
   Fraser alternated wingers with fourth-line center Mike
Stapleton, even using defenseman Yannick Tremblay twice. Tremblay
responded with his best game of the year, assisting on two goals.
``He's really the only defenseman we have with the ability to jump
into (an offensive rush),'' Fraser said. ``Dressing seven
defensemen gives us a lot more flexibility.''
</P>
<P>
   What Fraser hasn't solved yet are the problems with his team's
play in its own end. Facing New Jersey, Detroit and Buffalo is not
a friendly way to open a season, but 16 goals allowed in three
games is not acceptable to the coach. Goaltending by Damian Rhodes
and Norm Maracle has been inconsistent. Rhodes made some key saves
to preserve the tie down the stretch but allowed a bad goal by
Curtis Brown early in the third period to start a Sabres rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's early, and we started against three of the best teams in
the league,'' Fraser said. ``Everybody makes mistakes, including
goaltenders. We have to let them grow this year, just like the rest
of us.''
</P>
<P>
   The team's hope is its next growth spurt comes on Long Island.
The team opens a three-game trip Thursday against the New York
Islanders, who appear to be the most beatable opponent thus far.
The trip continues with games against Tampa Bay and the New York
Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be good for us to get on the road,'' Fraser said. ``We
can relax a little. We won't be playing in front of everybody who
we're worried about trying to impress.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
