<SLUG> BC-OCEAN-ROCKET-LAUNCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEA LAUNCHING OF A SATELLITE IS SUCCESSFUL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   (rk) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Ushering in a new era in rocketry, a multinational
company has launched a communications satellite into space from a
platform floating in the Pacific Ocean, the first such launching
from sea rather than from land.
</P>
<P>
   The 200 foot-tall rocket lifted off from the launch pad _ a
converted offshore oil drilling platform _ at 11:28 p.m. Eastern
time Saturday from a location on the equator about 1,400 miles
southeast of Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   The achievement is significant because the use of the offshore
platform allows launchings to be conducted at the equator, where
the rotation of the earth's surface is the fastest. The rotation
gives the rocket a boost, allowing it to use less fuel or to carry
a heavier payload than a similar rocket launched from a higher
latitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything came off exactly the way we planned it,'' Allen B.
Ashby, president of the Sea Launch Co., the multinational launching
venture, said late Saturday from the company's home port in Long
Beach, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Sea Launch is led by the Boeing Co. The other partners are
Kvaerner Maritime, a Norwegian ship builder, and rocket builders
from Russia and the Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   The launching is a welcome event for the satellite industry,
which has found it more difficult recently to get satellites into
space.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year or so, there have been six big failures of
American rockets. At the same time, it has become more cumbersome
for American satellite companies to use foreign rockets because of
tighter national security restrictions that took effect after
reports that two American satellite companies might have helped
China improve its rocket and missile technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always good to get a new reliable source of launch
vehicle services,'' said Eddy W. Hartenstein, president of DirecTV,
the owner of the satellite launched Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Telecommunications companies are planning to launch hundreds of
communications satellites over the next decade to provide
telephone, television, Internet and other services.
</P>
<P>
   The achievement is also a bright spot for Boeing. It comes after
the company's new Delta III rocket failed in its first two
launchings.
</P>
<P>
   To convince a nervous satellite industry that its concept would
work, Sea Launch hoisted a dummy satellite into orbit in March. But
Saturday's launching was the first of a real commercial satellite.
</P>
<P>
   Sea Launch already has 18 launchings planned over the next five
years. Thirteen of them are for Hughes Electronics, the nation's
largest satellite company and the parent of DirecTV, and five are
for Loral Space and Communications.
</P>
<P>
   Sea Launch has worked five years on its project, and has
invested more than $500 million.
</P>
<P>
   The initial launching took place almost a year behind schedule,
partly because the project was suspended last year by the State
Department while it investigated whether Boeing had transferred
sensitive data to its Russian and Ukrainian partners in violation
of arms export laws.
</P>
<P>
   The Ukraine's Yuzhnoye design bureau and Yuzhmash production
plant, which developed the first two stages of Sea Launch's Zenit
rocket, once made the Soviet Union's most deadly missile. The
Russian partner in Sea Launch, RSC Energia, built the third stage
of the rocket.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing agreed to pay a $10 million fine in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Ashby, the Sea Launch president, said Boeing did not endanger
national security but that it had not always gotten the proper
clearances before exchanging data with the foreign partners.
</P>
<P>
   The launch pad, built by Kvaerner, is nearly the size of two
football fields and stands 20 stories tall. It traveled to the
launch site from Long Beach, a journey that took about 10 days. A
crew of 300 people managed the launching.
</P>
<P>
   The 7,600-pound satellite will replace an older DirecTV
satellite that beams dozens of channels of television to dish
antennas at customers' homes. The new satellite will have extra
capacity, allowing DirecTV to also transmit local broadcast
channels and better compete with cable television.
</P>
<P>
   The DirecTV satellite will be in geosynchronous orbit 22,300
miles over the equator.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
