<SLUG> BC-U.S.-YUGO-AID-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. AND ALLIES DIVIDED OVER HARDSHIP AID TO YUGOSLAVIA
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With winter fast approaching, the United States and
its allies are deeply divided over whether to increase the
isolation of Yugoslavia and its leader, Slobodan Milosevic, or to
offer some aid to ease the hardship of the people in the hope of
encouraging a more vital opposition.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of a meeting Monday of the European Union's 15
foreign ministers in Luxembourg, the Clinton administration has
outlined its strong opposition to plans by the group to provide
heating oil and other aid to certain Yugoslav cites controlled by
opposition parties, American and European officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the program, the European Union would initially supply two
cities with about $5 million in heating oil to help cope with
shortages caused by destruction of Yugoslavia's petroleum
refineries during NATO's air war over Kosovo. That aid would be the
first part of a broader package that would eventually include food,
medicine and even small-scale public works projects, European
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But American officials have said they fear that the assistance
could shore up Milosevic by alleviating public discontent, which
they hope could lead to protests in Yugoslavia, early elections, or
even Milosevic's ouster or resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright has laid out the Clinton
administration's objections in a series of discussions with her
European counterparts, including Foreign Secretary Robin Cook of
Britain and Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer of Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're concerned about proposals that may have appropriate
humanitarian goals but may lead to developments that directly or
indirectly support the regime,'' State Department spokesman James
Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute over providing aid highlights the difficult
situation facing the United States in the wake of NATO's air war
over Kosovo last spring, which left Milosevic politically battered
but still clinging to power. The quarrel also underscores
Washington's philosophical differences with the Europeans over how
to isolate and weaken Milosevic's government further.
</P>
<P>
   While the United States has said it supports aid to relieve the
suffering of ordinary people in Yugoslavia, it has ruled out any
aid for reconstruction in the nation as long as Milosevic remains
in power.
</P>
<P>
   Many American allies in Europe, however, view things
differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Europeans don't necessarily see isolation as the only way
to do away with Milosevic,'' said Ivo Daalder, a former National
Security Council aide who now studies the Balkans for the Brookings
Institution.
</P>
<P>
   ``The administration wants to keep the pressure on,'' he added.
``They're afraid, one, that if you divide the allies from us,
Milosevic will exploit these divisions and, secondly, that the
allies are weaker than we are, as on Iraq and Iran, and will
undermine the sanctions.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the war ended, Yugoslavia has remained under strict
sanctions that prohibit trade, even as millions of dollars of aid
has poured into Kosovo, which is technically still a province of
Serbia, but increasingly is being administered by the United
Nations as a separate entity.
</P>
<P>
   The sanctions against Yugoslavia, coupled with NATO's
destruction of bridges, refineries and factories, have caused the
country's already feeble economy to collapse. There are shortages
of foods, and spiraling inflation is making even basic items
unaffordable for many.
</P>
<P>
   In a report on Sept. 20, the U.N. Office for the Coordination of
Humanitarian Affairs says that as winter sets in, Serbia faces
severe shortages of electricity, heating oil and coal. Electricity
supplies, it warned, could fall 40 percent to 50 percent below its
requirements as winter progresses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overall impact of such shortages is expected to be
increased morbidity and mortality, particularly in urban areas,''
the report said. ``The most vulnerable will be the elderly, the
very young, the sick and the urban poor.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said the United States, based on its own analysis, did not
believe that the energy shortage would be substantial, but the
Europeans have shown more willingness to consider ways to respond
to the warnings.
</P>
<P>
   The European Union has been trying to tailor a relief program
that would not directly support Milosevic, who has been charged
with war crimes by the international tribunal in The Hague. During
a meeting last month, the group's humanitarian office pledged
roughly $40 million in aid.
</P>
<P>
   European officials said they planned to provide aid only if they
could guarantee that it would not end up in the hands of
Milosevic's government. The $5 million worth of heating oil being
considered under the initial plan would, for example, go to two
cities in southeastern Serbia _ Nis and Pirot, which are governed
by opponents of Milosevic's ruling Socialist Party.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Daalder said such plans had potential downsides, especially
since energy, like money, could easily be diverted to the central
government. ``These localities don't have real power other than
political power,'' he said. ``They don't have police or security
power. How do you assure it doesn't get stolen or simply taken
away?''
</P>
<P>
   At their meeting in Luxembourg, the foreign ministers are
expected to discuss ways to ensure that Milosevic's central
government could not redirect the assistance _ something that Dr.
Albright demanded in her discussions with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to prove they are democratic forces,'' one European
diplomat said of potential aid recipients, ``and we have to be sure
these funds are not siphoned off to the government of Slobodan
Milosevic.''
</P>
<P>
   The diplomat said that directing aid to cities, rather than
denying it, could shore up the opposition leaders by showing the
people of Serbia that the international community was prepared to
help those committed to democracy. Otherwise, European officials
have argued, the democratic opposition is left looking as if it is
in partnership only with Western countries that first bombed
Yugoslavia and now want to make Serbs suffer still more.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you give them some glimmer of hope if they chose another
path, they might chose the other,'' the official said. ``It is a
carrot-and-a-stick question. The EU sees more profit in the carrot
than the stick.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
