<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-VOTE-725(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE-DISCREDITED COMMUNISTS PLACE THIRD IN BERLIN VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ Ten years after the fall of the Berlin Wall, the
successor to East Germany's Communist Party drew on a groundswell
of disillusionment about the transition to capitalism to surge
Sunday night to its best showing yet in city elections.
</P>
<P>
   Just a month after Berlin became the official capital of
reunified Germany, the center of Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder's
self-proclaimed ``Berlin Republic,'' the Party of Democratic
Socialism won about 40 percent of all votes in the formerly
Communist eastern half of Berlin, and some 18 percent citywide.
</P>
<P>
   The once-discredited former Communists are still third behind
the center-right Christian Democrats, who retained the mayor's
office and won almost half the votes, and the center-left Social
Democrats, who won barely 22 percent _ a far cry from their
domination of West Berlin's politics under Willy Brandt in the
1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's election seemed emblematic of the polarization of
Berlin, and perhaps of Germany itself. West of the line where the
wall once ran, the Christian Democrats appeared to have generated
their best result since World War II by capturing about 48.9
percent of the vote. East of the wall, the buoyant and
reinvigorated former Communists increased their share from 36.3
percent to 39.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The retooled Communists even advanced their hold in the western
part of the city, where they remain bit players but doubled their
vote share from 2.4 to 4.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The results mark another setback for Schroeder and his Social
Democrats, whose support slipped to its lowest ebb ever in a city
that after 1945 became known for blending a tough, proletarian edge
with a vibrant intellectual liberalism.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few weeks, Schroeder's party has had stinging
defeats in state elections around the country. Criticized for its
confusion and more recently for its advocacy of unpopular cuts in
social spending, the Social Democrats were ousted from power in the
industrial region of Saarland, long a stronghold, lost substantial
ground in the eastern states of Brandenburg, Thuringia and Saxony,
and even saw support decline sharply in local elections in its
traditional industrial stronghold of North-Rhine Westphalia.
</P>
<P>
   For practical purposes, Sunday's election will leave Berlin's
local Parliament essentially unchanged. The Christian Democrats
will continue in a ``grand coalition'' with Social Democrats
because neither will gain a majority of seats in the city
Parliament. Eberhard Diepgen, a Christian Democrat who has held the
job for eight years, will continue as mayor.
</P>
<P>
   In massive apartment blocks in the eastern district of Marzahn,
however, the rising support for the former Communists was on full
display.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have people at the top who have attracted a great deal of
sympathy and convinced people that they can make government work
for them,'' said Bernd Wodicka, a 48-year-old civil engineer who
voted for the Party of Democratic Socialism for the second time in
his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Immediately after the wall, I had no interest in voting for
them,'' said Wodicka, referring to the Nov. 9, 1989, fall of the
Berlin wall. But he said he had become convinced that both of
Germany's two mainstream parties were steering the country toward
nothing less than ``bankruptcy, misfortune and breakdown.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Berlin has long since lost all but a few remnants of
the wall, the infamous ``wall in the mind'' remains intact, if not
in some ways reinforced. The eastern side of the city remains
populated by people who were either part of the old government or
built their careers in the very specific ways of the old East
German Communist system.
</P>
<P>
   The homes and buildings of eastern Berlin may have undergone
extensive outward renovation _ most of the drab old concrete
apartment towers now sport bright colors and fancy new facades _
but unemployment continually hovers around 14 percent, and the chic
and glitz surrounding the new German Parliament and the shopping
complexes at Potsdamer Platz are still miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Under the leadership of Gregor Gysi, the former Communist Party
has managed to retain much of its original base and reinvent itself
as a smart, even fashionable party that speaks to the genuine
interests of easterners.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very good result,'' Gysi exulted Sunday evening.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Noting that Communist parties now play a significant role in the
politics of many west European nations _ as indeed the reform
Communists do in other former Soviet-bloc countries _ Gysi said
Germany's mainstream parties have no choice but to heed his group
as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Social Democrats are only used to reacting to pressure
from the right,'' he said. ``But now they have to react to pressure
from the left as well. It is normal in many other countries, and
they have to get used to the idea of it being normal here too.''
</P>
<P>
   Walter Momper, the Social Democratic candidate for Mayor,
acknowledged his party's setback but expressed relief that the
party had avoided the much steeper declines recorded in the earlier
state elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a defeat and we absolutely cannot gloss over that,''
Momper said shortly after the first projections were announced.
``But the second point is that we have stopped the national
trend.''
</P>
<P>
   That remains far from clear. The Social Democrats' loss was not
as bad as many experts had predicted in recent days, but they still
appeared to have slipped slightly from what had already been their
worst-ever result in Berlin city elections four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The results also seemed to reinforce a more chronic weakness of
Schroeder's party in the former eastern states. It did not help
that Momper, who was the mayor of Berlin from 1989 , was
strongly against a formal reunification of the city.
</P>
<P>
   While the votes of residents of the former East Germany
apparently helped Schroeder to his victory last year over
Chancellor Helmut Kohl, the same East Germans seem now to be
disillusioned that Schroeder has not made good on promises of
reducing unemployment. In eastern states like Thuringia and Saxony,
voters are increasingly choosing between the conservatives of the
Christian Democratic Union and the more authentically ``eastern''
Party of Democratic Socialism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
