<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-10 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2605 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BRAZILE-PROFILE-ART-N     10-10 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZILE-PROFILE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENANCE COMPLETE, A CONFIDENT BRAZILE STEPS IN FOR GORE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: D.C., La., Tenn., Mo.)   (ART ADV: Photo NYT8 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By MELINDA HENNEBERGER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Donna Brazile, who was just named Al Gore's new
campaign manager, did not supply a terse, ``that was a long time
ago, in another country'' response when asked about the night she
stepped down from another presidential campaign, Michael Dukakis',
in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   She had agreed to resign after it had hit the news wires that
she had prodded reporters, with some way-out-of-school comments, to
check out rumors about Vice President George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   That evening, she called her mother in Louisiana and told her
that it looked like the two of them would be spending lots of time
together, making gumbo and sitting on the porch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Jean,' _ I called my mom Jean _ `I got fired.' I
said, `I called the vice president a racist, a liar and a
philanderer.' '' (In fact, her comments had been limited to that
third thing she mentioned.) ``And she said, `Is that all?' But I
thought I'd failed my mother,'' Ms. Brazile said, looking for a
split second as though she might cry. ``I've tried never to bring
dishonor to my family and that was hard.''
</P>
<P>
   When her mother, a domestic worker with no health insurance,
died several weeks later in the same New Orleans charity hospital
where Ms. Brazile and her eight siblings were born, Ms. Brazile
said she used her last paycheck from the Dukakis campaign to bury
her. Grieving and ashamed, she lost 40 pounds and, as a Roman
Catholic, she said, ``I did penance. That's what I called it and
that's what it was.''
</P>
<P>
   e months, she lived in a Washington homeless shelter
while working for Mitch Snyder, an advocate for the homeless.
</P>
<P>
   She recovered, though, became chief of staff for Eleanor Holmes
Norton, the District of Columbia delegate, and today suffers no
obvious lack of confidence in her abilities.
</P>
<P>
   At 39, Ms. Brazile is not the sort of person you might meet at a
party and then not remember when you run into her again in an
airport nine years later. When Matt Drudge, publisher of The Drudge
Report, the gossipy Web site, recently referred to her as a ``smear
queen,'' she remarked, ``Well, he got the queen part right. I am a
diva.''
</P>
<P>
   All of which might explain why Ms. Brazile seemed so genuinely
unfazed by the problems facing Al Gore's presidential campaign. She
knows about coming back.
</P>
<P>
   And if her candidate's bio was perhaps a little thin in the
overcoming adversity department, hers was full to bursting. Her
father, she noted, was wounded in the Korean War, run over by an
18-wheeler, had his back broken when he was hit by a crane, and
after suffering a heart attack on a bus, got off and checked
himself into a hospital. Yet he was still around to remark of her
recent promotion: ``Gift from God, Donna, but also another job.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Kenner, La., outside New Orleans and ``across two train
tracks, that's how poor we were,'' just a block from the
Mississippi River, Ms. Brazile said she grew up praying hurricanes
away, because her family didn't have the money for a new roof.
</P>
<P>
   Her father, Lionel, worked mostly as a janitor, usually holding
more than one job, and her mother was up every morning early enough
to straighten her six daughters' hair before she had to leave to go
clean house.
</P>
<P>
   As a child, Ms. Brazile herself rose at 5:30 a.m. to read the
newspaper to her grandmother, who she said ``gave me a thirst for
knowledge.'' While she was at it, she clipped coupons.
</P>
<P>
   And at a young age, got interested in politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom used to call me Nosy Nancy, always sticking my nose
into grown folks' business.'' When she was 9, she heard that a City
Coandidate had promised to pave their roads, improve their
schools and _ this is important _ get a playground built in their
neighborhood, so she became a junior volunteer in his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I organized all the kids, and told them that if he won, we'd
get a playground. Which we did. So that was my first job in
politics.''
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from Louisiana State University, she was hired
by Coretta Scott King to help organize a 20th-anniversary
reenactment of Martin Luther King Jr.'s March on Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Later, she worked for the Rev. Jesse Jackson, who she said
taught her to make a proper entrance by arriving late, and Rep.
Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., to whom she pledged eternal gratitude
because ``he asked me what I thought.''
</P>
<P>
   As she prepares to turn 40, this was supposed to be the year
that Ms. Brazile also got a personal life. ``I was going to buy
myself a Jeep, have a relationship that lasted more than two weeks
_ usually it's two weeks and you bore the hell out of me _ and lose
weight. I had it all in my diary.''
</P>
<P>
   Then last week, she heard that the vice president would be
dropping by headquarters to address the troops, and Ms. Brazile
decided to make one of her patented entrances by arriving late.
Stepping off the elevator, the first thing she heard was a gaggle
of colleagues yelling, ``Donna! Donna! And I'm like, `Oooooh,
drama!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Gore wanted to see her privately, and assuming she was about to
be fired, Ms. Brazile was already planning a vacation. ``When
you've already been fired once, the thrill is gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Gore elevated her to campaign manager from political
director and announced a shake-up that included relocating his
entire campaign to Nashville from Washington. She called a
subsequent briefing on the state of the campaign ``a tour of
Goreworld that made me lose my appetite; my lunch is in the trash
over there.''
</P>
<P>
   But she said she was taking the job because she believed that Al
Gore was the only candidate who really cared about making life
better for Americans left behind by the bull market, uninsured
domestic workers like her mother. Having grown up poor and on a
budget, Ms. Brazile said, will make cutting campaign spending no
big thing.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Coelho, Gore's campaign chairman, called her the best
grass-roots organizer around and if it was a shake-up that Gore
wanted, then Ms. Brazile seemed wildly qualified.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
