<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A date with a Valentine
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's only right that it came down to this.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets and Braves have duked it out in the National League
East all season long, so perhaps they should determine who will
represent the league in the World Series. This passionate rivalry
commanded baseball's imagination in the last two weeks of the
season. It's only fitting that it will do the same in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the way it should be,'' Braves pitching coach Leo Mazzone
said. ``The Big Apple and the South. We've all felt all along
they're a great team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets are back from near extinction, a tough road they hold
the Braves responsible for after they lost five of six to Atlanta
in the last 10 days of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets won the wildcard by winning their last three games of
the regular season and a one-game playoff against the Reds for
their first trip to the postseason since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Outspoken Mets manager Bobby Valentine said after his team's
Division Series victory against Arizona that he thinks the Braves
counted them out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see what it's all about in the championship
series,'' Valentine said. ``I'm the guy with the big mouth, but
they're the ones playing the ghosts.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Braves are not surprised to see the Mets in the NLCS.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a great team,'' John Smoltz said. ``I couldn't believe
the flak they were getting.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have won nine of 12 games against New York and all
four series this season. But that doesn't make the Braves feel
secure, especially given the way the Mets are playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they made it as a wild-card team, I knew their momentum
would carry over,'' Brian Jordan said. ``It's going to be
exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   If the last two series of the regular season were any
indication, that's an understatement. The Braves will host the Mets
at Turner Field for Games 1 and 2 Tuesday and Wednesday and then
head back to Shea Stadium for Games 3, 4 and 5 during the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to get the worst reception you can think of,''
Smoltz said. ``We've played the Yankees. We're going to get the
same treatment at Shea. They're going to try to dominate us.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Braves are feeling a little tingle of destiny
themselves, after bouncing back from a Game 1 loss to take three
from the Astros in the Division Series, including the exciting Game
3 in 12 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year we're not ready for it to end,'' Smoltz said.
``We're not ready for the magic to end.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
