<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-FLOODS-ART-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN POLITICIANS CRITICIZE FLOOD RELIEF EFFORTS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By SAM DILLON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ With eastern Mexico awash in brackish waters from
the region's worst flooding in decades, opposition politicians have
charged in to fan citizen anger. They said that the disaster had
been caused by government negligence and that relief efforts had
been sluggish.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of soldiers, sailors and civilian relief crews pulled
more bodies from lagoons, canals and swamps of Gulf Coast mud
Sunday after dozens of rivers, swelled by 10 days of heavy tropical
rains, overwhelmed hundreds of villages.
</P>
<P>
   The flooding washed out scores of highways and bridges, and
several communities were reported to remain cut off from outside
help.
</P>
<P>
   A statement issued by the government Sunday put the official
death toll at 314. Unofficial tallies compiled by Mexican news
agencies put the dead at more than 400, with some estimates
reaching 600.
</P>
<P>
   The Interior Ministry reported death and destruction in a
coastal strip extending 500 miles along the southeastward curve of
the Gulf Coast, from northern Veracruz and Hidalgo into Puebla and
south to Tabasco. About 200,000 people are homeless, the ministry
reported.
</P>
<P>
   Governor Miguel Aleman of Veracruz said he doubted that there
had been a more sweeping disaster in his state in the last 400
years.
</P>
<P>
   The flood waters, which began to overflow a few causeways early
last week but swelled suddenly into a regional calamity as rains
from a tropical depression continued, appeared to have caught the
federal authorities by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   But by the weekend, 10,000 soldiers and sailors and hundreds of
other officials from nine Cabinet ministries were cranking up an
ambitious relief effort.
</P>
<P>
   The rising death toll made the calamity the worst that President
Ernesto Zedillo has experienced since he took office in 1994,
surpassing the hundreds killed in the states of Oaxaca and Guerrero
by Hurricane Pauline in 1997 and during devastating floods last
year in southern Chiapas.
</P>
<P>
   The presidential candidates of the two main opposition parties
and even one candidate from the president's own party accused the
government of contributing to the disaster.
</P>
<P>
   During helicopter and walking tours through communities in
Veracruz on Friday and Saturday, Zedillo heard calls from flood
victims for shipments of food, fresh water and other aid. On
Saturday in the town of Poza Rica in Veracruz, he encountered
crowds grumbling over the tardiness of government relief, said
David Najera, an aide to the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were some hard exchanges,'' Najera said. ``The people
were angry and they were looking for help. And they wanted the
president to ignore the mud and walk through their neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo waded knee-deep into the riverside muck that had poured
through dozens of homes so he could hear one woman's story at first
hand. Many in the bedraggled throng applauded that, Najera said.
``The people weren't angry at the president but at the government
in general, because they needed drinking water and none had
arrived,'' Najera said.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents accused government officials of opening the
sluice gates of regional dams to protect government-owned equipment
from being damaged by the the waters, greatly increasing the
destruction to private homes and businesses downriver.
</P>
<P>
   But Zedillo and the director of the National Water Commission
denied those reports. Many of the dams in question do not even have
sluice gates, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo flew back to the capital on Saturday night, his clothes
splattered with mud, in a presidential plane reeking of slime. He
rested Sunday but has tentatively scheduled a new tour of the
disaster zone for Monday, Najera said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One vivid incident on Friday, when Zedillo toured a devastated
neighborhood in the coastal town of Gutierrez Zamora in Veracruz,
received widespread news coverage and provoked criticism from
opposition politicians.
</P>
<P>
   During the visit, a crowd of citizens surrounded the president,
demanding that the government quicken the flow of water, food and
clothing.
</P>
<P>
   One primary school teacher, Leonardo de Luna Martinez,
questioned Zedillo so loudly and insistently about how the
government would deal with local merchants who speculated with food
prices during the disaster that the president finally shouted back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shut up and let me talk!'' said Zedillo. ``I'm the president
of the republic!''
</P>
<P>
   Abashed at the presidential tongue-lashing, de Luna moved to the
rear of the crowd, witnesses said. He later apologized to the
president for appearing to heckle him and received a presidential
apology in return, Najera said.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper Reforma reported Sunday that de Luna later said he
considered Zedillo ``an authority who respects freedom of
expression.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel proud that the president scolded me,'' the paper quoted
de Luna as saying.
</P>
<P>
   But Vicente Fox Quesada, the presidential candidate of the
center-right National Action Party, called Zedillo's outburst of
irritation with de Luna ``a lamentable attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm president, I'm not going to be like Zedillo and get
mad at the people,'' Fox said. Zedillo ``should have kept the dams,
waterways and reservoirs better maintained, and he should have
established a national disaster fund. Now when the disasters come,
he walks around very remorseful and paternalistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox, who did not visit the disaster zone, made his comments to
reporters in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, the presidential candidate of the
center-left Party of the Democratic Revolution, lashed out at
Zedillo and his predecessors from the long-governing Institutional
Revolutionary Party for cutting money for social programs,
including the maintenance of riverside dikes and drainage systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``In cases like these, they should have carried out engineering
projects to help prevent this kind of flooding,'' Cardenas told
local reporters during a campaign tour in Oaxaca.
</P>
<P>
   Several other politicians, including Roberto Madrazo Pintado, a
presidential candidate from Zedillo's party, weighed in with
similar criticism of the government's handling of the floods.
</P>
<P>
   But Najera said, ``The president is just doing his best to
attend to the situation, and he's not going to get into a political
debate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
