<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A SUBWAY SERIES HAS BEEN ON TRACK SINCE 1921 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If it's not too early to dream about a Subway Series,
as every Noo Yawker worth a MetroCard is doing, it's not too early
to remember what a Subway Series was really like _ all 13.
</P>
<P>
   Old-timers attended the last one in 1956 when Don Larsen pitched
a perfect game against the Brooklyn Dodgers at Yankee Stadium, but
hardly a man is now alive who saw the first one in 1921 when the
Giants were the Yankees' landlord at the Polo Grounds in upper
Manhattan where an apartment complex now rises.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, the Yankees won 10, the Giants two, the Dodgers one as
Subway Series names defined much of New York baseball, for better
or for worse:
</P>
<P>
   Babe Ruth, Lou Gehrig, Joe DiMaggio, Mickey Mantle, Tommy
Henrich, Joe Page, Billy Martin, Don Larsen for the Yankees; Frank
Frisch, Carl Hubbell and Eddie Stanky for the Giants; Mickey Owen,
Hugh Casey, Jackie Robinson, Harry (Cookie) Lavagetto, Al
Gionfriddo, Johnny Podres and Sandy Amoros for the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   And as both a Giants center fielder and a Yankee manager, Casey
Stengel.
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning, the term Subway Series would have been a
misnomer. In 1921 there wasn't a subway stop, as such, beneath the
Polo Grounds, but an elevated line extended to Eighth Avenue at
West 157th Street ouhe center-field bleachers and Giants'
offices.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants had played on that site since 1891, and in 1913 the
Yankees moved there. After the Yankees acquired Babe Ruth from the
Boston Red Sox in 1920 and soon were outdrawing the Giants, John
McGraw, the Giants' manager, evicted the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Needing their own ball park, the Yankees built Yankee Stadium,
which opened in 1923 after they had lost the first two Subway
Series to the Giants with all of the games at the Polo Grounds.
</P>
<P>
   In 1921, the Yankees had a 3-2 lead after Game 5, but with the
Babe suddenly out with a bad knee and an infected arm, the Giants
won three straight in the last five-of-nine Series.
</P>
<P>
   In 1922, the Giants, sparked by Frisch, swept as the Babe batted
.118 with no homers. In 1923, with the opener at the new Yankee
Stadium in the Bronx across the Harlem River, he hit three homers
as the Yankees won their first of 24 World Series championships.
</P>
<P>
   Stengel, then the Giants' center fielder, hit two memorable
homers in that 1923 duel _ hobbling on a loose shoe on an
inside-the-park drive to left center at the Stadium, and later
thumbing his nose at the Yankee dugout as he trotted around third
base.
</P>
<P>
   From 1936 through 1956, the Yankees would win 9 of 10 Subway
Series, losing only to the Dodgers in 1955.
</P>
<P>
   In 1936, DiMaggio's rookie season, the Yankees pummeled the
Giants, 18-4 in Game 2 and 13-5 in the Game 6 finale, both at the
Polo Grounds. In 1937, they routed Hubbell, then baseball's best
left-hander, with a 7-run sixth inning in the 8-1 opener at the
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   In 1941, the Dodgers momentarily appeared to have squared the
Series at 2-2 when Henrich swung and missed a third strike, but
Casey's curveball skidded past Owen. Henrich ran to first before
the Dodger catcher's throw got there. The game wasn't over.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio singled. Charlie Keller doubled. Bill Dickey walked.
Joe Gordon doubled. The Yankees won, 7-4, and according to Flatbush
lore, a man with a dog on his lap tossed the dog out a nearby open
window.
</P>
<P>
   In 1947, Yankee right-hander Floyd (Bill) Bevens had a no-hitter
with two out in the ninth at Ebbets Field in Game 4, but with
Gionfriddo and Eddie Miksis, pinch-running for teammates who had
walked, on base, Lavagetto doubled for a stunning 2-1 victory.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 6, Gionfriddo raced to the left-field bullpen at the
Stadium to snatch a home run away from DiMaggio, who in a rare
display of emotion kicked the dirt near second base. In Game 7,
five shutout relief innings by Page preserved another tray of
Yankee rings.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1949 opener, Stengel's first as Yankee manager, Henrich
led off the ninth with a homer off Don Newcombe for a 1-0 victory.
Preacher Roe blanked the Yankees, 1-0, the next day for the only
Dodger victory.
</P>
<P>
   In 1951, the Giants were in a Subway Series for the last time.
Stanky kicked the ball out Phil Rizzuto's glove, but the Yankees
won in six. DiMaggio hit his last home run (at the Polo Grounds)
and Mantle, then a rookie, twisted a knee in a Stadium outfield
drain.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees frustrated the Dodgers again in 1952 when Martin
sprinted to catch Robinson's bases-loaded pop fly that first
baseman Joe Collins had lost in the sun, and in 1953 when Martin
batted .500 on 12 hits for manager Stengel's record fifth
consecutive title.
</P>
<P>
   In 1955 Amoros made the catch near the left-field foul line at
the Stadium for the double play that preserved Podres' 2-0 shutout
in Game 7 for the Dodgers' only Series triumph representing
Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   The next year Larsen's perfect game in Game 5 upstaged Yogi
Berra's two homers off Newcombe that ignited a 9-0 rout in Game 7
at Ebbets Field. Two years later the Dodgers and Giants were ifornia; six years later the expansion Mets had adopted a blend
of ancestral colors _ Dodgers' blue and Giants' orange.
</P>
<P>
   And now, together in the post-season for the first time, the
Mets and Yankees eawithin four championship series victories
of a Subway Series. Get your MetroCard here!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-10-99 2037EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991010.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-10 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2618 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-METRIC11-COX     10-10 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-METRIC11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Conversion to metric system still inching along
 &HT;    By Sonja Isger
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A bunch of space engineers sent the Mars
Climate Orbiter to a fiery demise earlier this month because they
gave the $125 million contraption bad directions. The engineers
plotting its path used kilometers, meters and the like. Another
group of scientists fed them information about how fast the craft
should go using miles, yards and inches ... and someone failed to
convert.
</P>
<P>
   Can you hear their third-grade teachers now, clucking their
tongues in a collective I-told-you-so loud enough to rattle
launchpads across the country?
</P>
<P>
   ``Learn metric or else.'' That was their mantra, particularly in
the 1970s when the metric push was most visible. ``Learn it now,
because when you grow up, they won't use pounds and inches.''
</P>
<P>
   They had the U.S. government's word on it. More than once, but
most recently in 1988, the government has declared the metric
system ``the preferred system of measure in the U.S.'' It is the
system we are supposed to use in commerce and trade and the one our
scientists use. (It was NASA's engineers who used metric during the
Mars debacle; the contractor used English measure.)
</P>
<P>
   But today, the rush toward metric has slowed to a creep. We buy
cola by the liter but rain still falls in inches. We measure the
size of a car's engine in liters, but fill the gas tank by the
gallon. Our athletes race by the meter, but a long jumper's mark is
counted off in feet and inches.
</P>
<P>
   Industry has probably come the farthest toward conversion, said
Lorelle Young, president of the nonprofit U.S. Metric Association.
Prompted by a more global economy, businesses have retooled their
factories so that the widgets they make here can work with widgets
made in other countries.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the classroom, teachers have dropped the doomsday speech.
But Florida's standards and statewide exams such as the FCAT
continue to strap teachers with teaching two systems _ a method
that one researcher says wastes hundreds of days in math class.
</P>
<P>
   The students at Poinciana Elementary, a science, math and
technology magnet in Boynton Beach, don't begin with inches or
centimeters, they begin with paper clips.
</P>
<P>
   ``They might use them to measure their desk tops,'' said math
resource teacher Nancy Higgins. They'll talk about how whatever
units you want to use, the unit has to be the same size for
everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Which then brings them to the book ``How big is a foot?,'' a
clever tale of a king who wants to have a bed made for his queen
and must find a way to describe the dimensions to an apprentice
carpenter. The king chooses his big foot, but when the apprentice
uses his much smaller foot ... voila, the bed is too small. To
resolve the disparity, the king has a cast of his foot made and it
becomes the standard measure of the kingdom. (Indeed, body parts
are the base of what became the English system of measure.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we explain it was pretty arbitrary to have a foot as a
standard of measure,'' Higgins said. From there they learn about
the less arbitrary metric system, that unlike its English
counterpart is neatly broken into units of 10.
</P>
<P>
   Across the district, similar lessons abound. District elementary
and middle school teachers say they set aside between three and six
weeks to cover both systems and let kids work in each.
</P>
<P>
   Carver Middle in Delray Beach is one of several schools to host
a metric Olympics where students fling a paper-plate discus or lob
a cotton ball shot put, each time estimating and then measuring
their efforts metrically.
</P>
<P>
   And most students embrace metric.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so much easier,'' said Middle School of the Arts math
department Chair Cheryl Gobel.
</P>
<P>
   ``You ask people how many cups are in a quart, see how many
answers you get,'' said the metric association's Young.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, a researcher with the Americanutes for Research
in Washington concluded that if teachers had to teach only one
system _ metric _ between 75 and 201 days of math would be cleared
for something else. First, because teachers wouldn't have to
duplicate lessons and second because metric is mathematically less
complicated.
</P>
<P>
   By high school, most text books and teachers do just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We use nothing but metric in high school science,'' said
Atlantic High biology teacher Fred Hock. ``If they do something in
inches, we make them do it again, because in science, metric is
basically universal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Students grasp the concept very well, but like any other
concept, if they don't use it, they lose it,'' said Theresa
Newkirk, math resource teacher at Belvedere Elementary in West Palm
Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts outside the classroom haven't exactly made metric
inroads. It seems every time there's a national step to move toward
conversion, a step backward is soon to follow.
</P>
<P>
   In 1982, the U.S. Metric Board, which was supposed to oversee a
conversion called for in 1975, was disbanded to save money.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, Florida legislators thought they'd move ahead of the
curve, erecting dual speed limit signs that announced 55 mph and 80
km. But they came down a year later, and the national push to
convert every sign by 1996 died in 1994 after more than 2,200
people wrote the highway administration opposing the plan. The
biggest gripe: the estimated $200 million price tag nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as educators prepare for National Metric Week this week,
the students in Claire Greene's fourth-grade class at Poinciana
Elementary wonder what's wrong with all the grown-ups.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were all astounded when the Mars thing blew up because of
the mix-up between the different units. They couldn't believe it. I
said, `You kids could've done a better job.'''
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach Post researcher Lynne Palombo contributed to this
report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
