<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-RANGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROUBLE COMES IN DIFFERENT SIZES FOR COYOTES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JASON DIAMOS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If Theo Fleury's style is that of a gnat, buzzing
through traffic in a general attempt to annoy, it is only natural
that Todd Harvey's approach has a little more sting. After all, the
6-foot, 200-pound Harvey is six inches taller and 20 pounds heavier
than his diminutive Rangers teammate.
</P>
<P>
   But Fleury sees similarities between his game and Harvey's: Both
are pests.
</P>
<P>
   And the Phoenix Coyotes seemed to be more concerned with Fleury
and Harvey than with anything else on the Madison Square Garden ice
Sunday afternoon, as the Rangers rallied for a 4-2 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're similar guys,'' Fleury said. ``We have to try to
play with emotion, play on the edge a little bit. When you play
like that, you walk a kind of tightrope. They want you to play that
way, but you can't take penalties. You have to play smart. And
that's something we both bring to the team.''
</P>
<P>
   hough he didn't score a point, Fleury _ who was stopped on
breakaways _ was his usual pesky self. And Harvey twice made plays
that changed the complexion of the game for the the Rangers
(2-2-1).
</P>
<P>
   As much as the Rangers will need production from Fleury, who has
one goal this season (despite putting 23 shots on goal thus far,
including seven in Sunday), they will also need Harvey to continue
to perform the way he did Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey outhustled Phoenix defenseman Todd Gill to a puck in the
corner, delivered an energizing hit on the Coyote and earned an
assist on Mike Knuble's goal at 12 minutes 33 seconds of the second
period. The goal tied the score at 1-1. It could also be argued
that Harvey deserved an assist on the game's deciding goal, even
though he was not directly involved in the play.
</P>
<P>
   The rookie Mike York scored at 7:04 of the final period to give
the Rangers a 3-1 lead. Skating on an odd-man rush, York took a
drop pass from Brian Leetch and drilled a slap shot from the top of
the left-wing circle that beat Phoenix goaltender Mikhail
Shtalenkov.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey set up the odd-man rush by engaging not one, but two
Coyotes in front of the Phoenix bench. While York was scoring,
Harvey could be seen arguing with the Coyotes' captain Keith
Tkachuk. The two were joined by Rick Tocchet, creating a situation
that interrupted a Phoenix line change.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sort of ran into each other and a few words were
exchanged,'' Harvey said of his initial encounter with Tkachuk.
``And then Tocchet came in. I guess we had a man advantage, because
there were two of them and only one of me. I didn't see how the
goal scored. I knew the play was going on, but I didn't know what
was going on. I was concentrating on keeping my teeth in my
mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix Coach Bobby Francis said: ``Harvey floated the bait and
we chomped down on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleury admired the play of his teammates. ``On York's goal, Todd
was out on the edge,'' he said. ``But he pulls back, we score a
goal, and that's the difference in the hockey game.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangers Coach John Muckler boiled the difference down to one
word: emotion. And it was Fleury and Harvey who sparked it Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike his teammates, Fleury had a productive first period.
</P>
<P>
   One moment he was yapping at Tkachuk and Tocchet, like a Jack
Russell terrier standing up to a pair of Great Danes. Another
moment Tkachuk was stuffing him into the Phoenix net.
</P>
<P>
   But Fleury's finest moment came midway through the period, when
he absorbed a crushing hit into the glass by Travis Green. Fleury
and Green came down together. When both got back on their skates,
Green was missing his helmet and his stick.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Graves who scored a third-period power-play goal to give
the Rangers a 2-1 lead _ skated in and pounced on Green in
retaliation. Shane Doan hurried over to join the scrum. Fleury
faked like he was going to hit Doan high, then, in a move out of
the Three Stooges, he stooped down and applied a low bridge. Doan
went flying and the Garden went wild. ``It was either that or get
cross-checked in the face,'' Fleury said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the referees are going to let him get away with theatrics
like that, he's going to be very successful here,'' Francis said,
fuming.
</P>
<P>
   And if other teams are going to let Fleury and Harvey get under
their skin, the Rangers could be very successful, too. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
