<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-10 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2620 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-2TAKE     10-10 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-2TAKES(935)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN RUSSIAN POLITICS, MONOPOLY POWER-PLAYS SEEN AS PART OF THE GAME
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Even by Russian standards, last month's power play at
the top of Transneft, the country's fourth largest monopoly, was
unusually nasty. In the highly charged atmosphere of Russia's
yearlong election season, however, the battle was perhaps just the
most public example of the fight between political clans over
sources of power and money.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 14, the day after he was crudely and maybe illegally
ousted as the general director of Transneft, Russia's
state-controlled oil pipeline monopoly, Dmitri Savelyev was called
to an unusual meeting with Roman Abramovich, a young Russian oil
baron and close friend of President Boris N. Yeltsin's family.
</P>
<P>
   At their meeting in the coffee shop of the ritzy Baltschug
hotel, according to Savelyev, Abramovich gave the ousted executive
some blunt advice: give up and keep quiet.
</P>
<P>
   ``He suggested that I leave voluntarily; he said I was trying to
fight the system,'' Savelyev recalled in a recent interview. ``When
he understood I wouldn't agree, he said that there was no sense in
putting up a struggle. The result will be the same, but you will
harm yourself. Because there are lots of ways to force a person to
keep silence.''
</P>
<P>
   The next day, as a phalanx of armed police officers surrounded
Transneft's Moscow headquarters, Savelyev's successor,
Vainshtok, assumed management of the state-controlled company,
which controls some 29,000 miles of pipeline linking Russia's oil
industry with domestic and foreign customers, and had a turnover in
1998 of $2.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   For Yuliya Latynina, a Russian economic journalist who closely
tracks the intertwining of the country's business and politics, the
Transneft case is a harbinger of abrupt management changes pending
at several other government-controlled oil and gas companies _ the
country's real moneymaking concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is quite evident that certain groups are looking for
sources of cash for the campaign,'' she said, referring to the
December parliamentary and June presidential elections. ``There are
many guys who would like to have a nontransparent company in their
pocket.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Ms. Latynina and others, the Kremlin's aggressive
political team already has set its sights on Rosneft and Slavneft,
two government-controlled oil companies. Some say that a fight over
control at Gazprom, Russia's giant gas company, may not be over.
</P>
<P>
   The goal, the experts say, is not only to gain access to cash,
but to use critically placed state companies to reward and punish
private companies and regional governors who have moved closer to
the Kremlin's opponents.
</P>
<P>
   As the tussle for power intensifies, such assumptions become
harder to prove. All sides engage in disinformation and
mudslinging, using newspapers and television stations, which _ with
rare exceptions _ serve the interests of competing media barons.
</P>
<P>
   Add to this endless arcane intrigues and a random sprinkling of
``kompromat,'' or compromising material, and you have a country in
the throes of ``fin de regime'' fever, where a struggle for power
is being waged without ideology, rules or scruples.
</P>
<P>
   ``The different clans are really fighting, but they are fighting
not for elections, but for more money,'' said Andrei Piontkovsky, a
political analyst. ``They understand that Yeltsin's time is ending,
and they are trying to get as much money as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Quoting a recent interview with Mikhail Khodorkovsky, another
Russian oil baron, Piontkovsky said, ``The only real business in
Russia is politics, and by that, he meant closeness to the
presidential family.''
</P>
<P>
   To some Western analysts, the pattern suggests that the fight
over state assets has not been checked by a wave of business
scandals that spread beyond Russia's borders, tarnishing the
reputations of its businessmen and politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people hoped that with elections coming up, this was a
great chance to change the situation,'' said James Fenker, an
analyst at Troika Dialogue, a Moscow-based investment group. ``But
instead, it looks as though all those people who are fingered by
corruption haven't booked their tickets out.''
</P>
<P>
   The hostile takeover at Transneft, in which the government holds
75 percent of the shares, became notable mainly because it happened
in the open.
</P>
<P>
   Ignoring Abramovich, Savelyev did not remain silent. Not only
has he taken his case to court, he has held a news conference and
gone on television, accusing those who fired him of flouting a law
that requires 45 days' notice for management changes at joint stock
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Various political figures came to Savelyev's defense, notably
Anatoly B. Chubais, the architect of Russia's privatization schemes
and now head of the country's electricity monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   Savelyev, 31, was himself a political appointee, becoming head
of Transneft in the spring of 1998 at the behest of Sergei V.
Kiriyenko, a former business partner who was then prime minister.
He replaced a longtime director who is still under investigation
concerning the distribution of Transneft preferred shares to the
company's top management.
</P>
<P>
   Savelyev survived the eight-month government of Prime Minister
Yevgeny M. Primakov, but his fate became uncertain with the
appointment last spring of Deputy Prime Minister Nikolai Y.
Aksyonenko, who is widely believed to have the support of Yeltsin's
inner circle _ a tiny group made up of Yeltsin, his daughter,
Tatyana Dyachenko, the business mogul Boris A. Berezovsky and his
associate, Abramovich, who owns a major share in Sibneft, an oil
company that is one of Transneft's main customers.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   After an attempt to oust Savelyev backfired in June, Aksyonenko
and an ally, Viktor Kalyuzhny, the fuel and energy minister, moved
swiftly last month, acting when Prime Minister Vladimir V. Putin
was out of the country. They simply summoned a smattering of
government representatives who sit on Transneft's board to vote
Savelyev out.
</P>
<P>
   Savelyev was informed of the decision on Sept. 13, and told
Aksyonenko he would leave only if proper legal procedures were
followed. The meeting with Abramovich, who holds no formal position
at Transneft, followed the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Upon his return to Moscow, Putin made no attempt to reverse the
changeover at Transneft.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   According to Savelyev, Aksyonenko ``did not even try to invent a
reason'' for his dismissal. After the fact, Kalyuzhny was quoted as
saying that the government was dissatisfied with the dividends from
and the lack of openness at Transneft.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Vainshtok, a former executive of a wholly owned
subsidiary of Lukoil, Russia's largest oil company, declined to
speculate on why his predecessor had been removed. ``I have not
asked these questions,'' he said. ``I am a completely apolitical
person.''
</P>
<P>
   Vainshtok refuses to criticize the previous management. But in
the last week, several documents were leaked to newspapers and
television stations, indicating that on the day he was fired,
Savelyev transferred $700,000 from a Transneft account to a
personal account, purportedly to buy an apartment in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Savelyev responded that money for the purchase of an apartment
had been promised in his original contract, and that he did not
recall when the transfer was actually made. Now, he said, he has
already written a letter asking that the money be donated to an
orphanage.
</P>
<P>
   In Savelyev's view, the takeover at Transneft was not only
political but also commercial. He said certain oil companies,
including Lukoil and Sibneft, were trying to take control of a
company that is one of Russia's most vital public utilities.
</P>
<P>
   Savelyev agreed that scandal has surrounded the privatization of
Russia's oil industry, which began in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Then, he said, at least certain rules were obeyed, ``people
talked about privatization, about investment projects and so on.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Today they simply discharge managers or heads of ministries
and appoint their own people,'' he said. ``The redistribution of
property is being carried out quietly. But in my case it was not so
quiet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
