<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-10 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2623 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBC-HEISMAN-COLUMN-NY     10-10 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HEISMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: WARRICK LEAVES RACE FOR THE HEISMAN WIDE OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JOE DRAPE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are a host of ways for players to get knocked out of the
running for the Heisman Trophy: season-ending injuries, the poor
record of a candidate's team, statistics that do not quite meet
standards set by opinion-makers, or a poor performance in a big
game.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State's Peter Warrick may have introduced a new way last
week: felony arrest. Last Thursday, the all-American wide receiver
was arrested on a single charge of grand theft for his role in a
scheme to underpay for clothes at a Tallahassee, Fla., department
store.
</P>
<P>
   In the span of five days, he verbally dismissed a police
investigation on how he and a teammate allegedly bought $412.38 of
designer label clothing for $21.40 with this memorable defense:
``It's not like I killed the nt.''
</P>
<P>
   He admitted he knew the transaction with a 19-year-old store
clerk was wrong, and Florida State suspended him indefinitely from
the football team. Last Saturday, he apologized on national
television and watched from the sideline as his teammates outlasted
rival Miami, 31-21.
</P>
<P>
   In all, it was a rather eventful week for the dazzling pass
catcher who had been the Heisman Trophy front runner. Now what?
</P>
<P>
   Well, Warrick's immediate football fate is in the hands of the
Florida justice system, his university and his coach, Bobby Bowden.
Warrick's lawyer, John Kenny, said he would try to expedite the
legal process _ normally it would take at least six weeks to go to
trial.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State's athletic director, Dave Hart, said, ``The door
certainly is open for Peter to return.'' Under the athletic
department's code of conduct, however, Warrick's status cannot be
decided until the legal issues are resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden, however, made it clear where he stood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found myself pleading for a misdemeanor, and I'm not used to
pleading for misdemeanors,'' Bowden said after beating Miami,
running their record to 6-0 and climbing to No. 2 in The New York
Times' computer rankings. ``I just didn't want to lose the talent.
It shook me. It shook our team.''
</P>
<P>
   The legal and moral arguments of how the State of Florida and
the university handle Warrick's college future are already a hot
button for print and broadcast pundits and talk-radio devotees. Let
them have at it.
</P>
<P>
   Here, let's address the Heisman Trophy race, which before
Warrick's troubles was muddled and barely interesting. Even if he
returns, his coach doesn't think he has much of a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would tell him to take a very back seat, a very back seat,''
Bowden said Sunday. ``You go out there and play the very best you
can play and don't even think about the Heisman.''
</P>
<P>
   So who is left? Until last weekend, Wisconsin running back Ron
Dayne and Purdue quarterback Drew Brees were hanging in there, and
Georgia Tech quarterback Joe Hamilton seemed to be gaining ground.
</P>
<P>
   But Dayne managed just 80 yards on 25 carries in Wisconsin's
20-15 overtime victory over Minnesota. Dayne has had a productive
college career at running back, but the Badgers are 4-2 and he has
had too many duds this season _for example, zero yards in the
second half against Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   For the second week in a row, Brees was also just ordinary. He
was 24 of 39 for 205 yards and no touchdowns as the Boilermakers
lost their second straight, this time to Ohio State, 25-22.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton fared better and is probably now the favorite, though a
lukewarm one. He led the Yellow Jackets to a 31-24 overtime victory
over North Carolina, but he also struggled, fumbling twice and
throwing two interceptions. He is exciting and usually efficient,
but Georgia Tech (4-1, No. 12 in the Times ranking) already lost to
Florida State and does not have a true showcase game left on its
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   So throw the race open _ at least that's what the Virginia Tech
all-American defensive end Corey Moore wants to do. He watched the
Hokies' freshman quarterback, Mike Vick, throw four touchdowns and
run for another in a single half of a 58-20 pasting of Rutgers and
declared: ``Mike right now is good enough to be considered for the
Heisman.''
</P>
<P>
   Any other year, Moore's statement could be dismissed. But maybe
now is a good time for Heisman voters and the public to remember
the criteria employed by the late Southern Methodist great, Doak
Walker. He won it in 1948 and, 38 years later, talked about how he
cast his vote in an article for The New York Times. ``First, I look
at the record of the team. I believe that's a fair standard borne
out by the years,'' Walker wrote. ``I also look at how much that
individual has produced for that team. I try to find out if he has
been a good leader. If he kept his nose clean. If he is a good
citizen.''
</P>
<P>
   He also fretted that the public may have become confused because
of the preeminence of professional football.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of people have been misled into thinking that
the award should go to the collegiate player who is the best pro
prospect. And that's simply not the way it should be. A good number
of Heisman winners have never played pro ball, or have not played
well in the pros for very long. Many have, but that is not why any
of us received the award,'' he concluded.
</P>
<P>
   So why not Vick? The national title aspirations of Virginia Tech
(5-0, No. 10 in the Times ranking) rest on the strong left arm and
sure feet of their freshman quarterback. Or what about Marshall
quarterback Chad Pennington? No one has penciled the Thundering
Herd into the Bowl Championship Series championship game, but they
are 5-0 and ranked No. 16 by the Times because of his 1,569 passing
yards and 14 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Michigan State quarterback Bill Burke. He threw
for 400 yards and 2 touchdowns to upset Michigan, 34-31. The
Spartans are 6-0 and ranked No. 5 by The Times computer because he
has thrown for more than 1,300 yards and 13 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   In short, maybe it's time for a good player from a good team to
win the most coveted award in college football. And when he does,
it is not fair if he is overshadowed by the great player from the
great team who took himself out of the race. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-10-99 2044EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
