<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-10 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2626 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-REFORM-PARTY11-COX     10-10 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFORM-PARTY11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reform Party struggles with fresh attention, internal conflicts
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ On the edge of irrelevance just a few
months ago, the Reform Party is back with a cast of characters that
is grabbing headlines and bringing new attention to a party that
seemed close to extinction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were not getting much attention and now suddenly we're
everywhere,'' says Jack Gargan, the Cedar Key retiree who will
become the party's national chairman in January. ``You can't turn
on the television or pick up a newspaper without seeing something
about the Reform Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting attention had been a problem for the party because it
was disintegrating. Ross Perot, the quixotic founder, had so
alienated some leading members of the party that they formed a
splinter group called the American Reform Party. Meanwhile,
membership was plummeting, the party was unfocused and the 20
percent vote it got nationwide in the 1992 presidential election
dwindled to less than 9 percent four years later.
</P>
<P>
   Even the election of Jesse Ventura as governor of Minnesota last
year failed to unite the party. Instead, factions developed around
Ventura and Perot. Gargan became national chairman with the help of
Ventura in a power struggle with Perot for control of the party.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest problem we have as a party right now is Jack
Gargan,'' says David Goldman, a Sarasota attorney and chairman of
the Florida Reform Party. ``He has attempted to undermine the
presidential process and that's not the job of a chairman.''
</P>
<P>
   Gargan says Goldman is complaining because he is aligned with
Perot, who opposed Gargan's selection as national chairman. Goldman
says that's not true, he just wants the party to abide by its
rules.
</P>
<P>
   And so it goes.
</P>
<P>
   While the party is basking in the attention it is getting from
the possibility of having Pat Buchanan, Donald Trump and even
Ventura and Perot as presidential candidates, it is a party rife
with internal bickering.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not going to win a single state and if it wasn't for
the circus that is going on now, no one would pay any attention to
them,'' said Mike Murphy, a Republican political strategist who
worked for Bob Dole in 1996. ``Look at those people who want to run
as Reform Party candidates. It's like something you would see in
the waiting room of a psychiatrist's office.''
</P>
<P>
   On this point, Gargan and Goldman can set aside their
differences.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Reform Party is the only party where independent people
who want to see change can come and have the potential of being a
successful candidate,'' says Goldman. ``We're a grass-roots party,
not a party of elitists.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a party where people can tell it like it is,'' says
Gargan. ``We don't have candidates who only want to say what they
think people want to hear. We have candidates who speak the
truth.''
</P>
<P>
   A change to the Florida Constitution means that the Reform Party
will get a spot on the ballot next year without having to get
signatures on a statewide petition. Florida voters gave Perot 20
percent of the vote in 1992. But Perot's support began to fade in
Florida just as it did in the rest of the nation. By 1996, he got
only about 9 percent of the Florida vote.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, interest in the Reform Party began to wane.
Loyal supporters who gave countless hours of volunteer time
organizing congressional districts complained that Perot was trying
to control too much from his Dallas, Texas, headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   By 1998, the Florida Reform Party, as in most states, had become
largely an Internet party. But even state Web pages are often
woefully out of date. With support crumbling, it appeared that the
Reform Party would have little influence on the 2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   That started to change with Ventura's surprise victory in the
Minnesota governor's race. As the party's top elected official,
Ventura attempted to ease Perot out of the way, suggesting that the
Texas billionaire was doing more harm than good. A sign of
Ventura's growing power was his success in making Gargan the
national chairman over Perot's objections.
</P>
<P>
   Then along came Buchanan. Frustrated with his failing campaign
for the GOP nomination, Buchanan and Perot began courting each
other. Ventura countered with Trump.
</P>
<P>
   Gargan and Goldman both say that their party jobs require them
to remain neutral. But Gargan speaks fondly of Ventura, who has
hinted he might enter the race next summer. And Goldman thinks
highly of Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a party that is going to be lucky if it gets 3 or 4
percent in the next election,'' says Murphy. ``They probably would
not be a factor at all next year if it wasn't for the fact that you
suddenly have some huge egos out there who couldn't make it in any
other party.''
</P>
<P>
   That assessment is way off the mark, says Gargan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, there are a lot of people out there very frustrated with
the other parties. People are seething and they want change.''
</P>
<P>
   Gargan wants all of the Reform Party's factions to work out
their differences. He sees Perot as the party's elder statesman and
Ventura as ``the man who saved the party.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can win the election next year,'' Gargan says. ``I
really do. That's not something I could have said a year ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
