<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO HORSE-OF-THE-YEAR CANDIDATES ARE UPSET ON SLOPPY TRACK
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JOE DURSO    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the mud and the mist of Belmont Park, two of the
top candidates for Horse of the Year tumbled from the pinnacle
Sunday: Behrens ran second to River Keen in the $1 million Jockey
Club Gold Cup and the great filly Silverbulletday ran second to
Beautiful Pleasure in the $500,000 Beldame.
</P>
<P>
   The upsets scrambled the standings just four weeks before the
same horses meet again in the Breeders' Cup championships at
Gulfstream Park. And a third stakes race at Belmont Sunday produced
a hot new contender among 2-year-old fillies, Surfside, who won the
Frizette by a nose over Darling My Darling.
</P>
<P>
   But for stunning effect, this will be remembered as the day when
Behrens and Silverbulletday were outrun on a sloppy track.
</P>
<P>
   Behrens, widely considered the best race horse in the country
and the favorite for the $4 million Breeders' Cup Classic, had won
four straight races and probably gave his best performance in the
Whitney at Saratoga in August when he was nosed out in a classic
duel by Victory Gallop.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday he was forced to make a late rush to salvage second place
by a head in the Gold Cup, but still crossed three-and-a-quarter
lengths behind River Keen.
</P>
<P>
   And there is some melodrama there, too. River Keen is a
7-year-old bred in Ireland who was claimed last December for
$100,000 by Hugo Reynolds. He is on a roll, finishing second in the
Pacific Classic in August and first in the Woodward in September.
And in his first workout after the Woodward he developed a cracked
hoof.
</P>
<P>
   ``We almost scratched this horse because he was dead lame last
night,'' Bob Baffert, River Keen's trainer, said by telephone from
California. ``It looked like he got a bit of an infection in there.
But we worked on it.''
</P>
<P>
   River Keen responded so well that he ran the mile and a quarter
in 2:01 2/5 under Chris Antley, taking the lead after
three-quarters of a mile and widening it to the finish. He paid $26
for a $2 bet, and earned a cool $600,000. Lemon Drop Kid, who won
the Belmont Stakes and the Travers, never fired on the wet track
and finished fifth behind Almuwatakel and Stephen Got Even.
</P>
<P>
   ``Behrens showed me that he is courageous,'' James Bond, his
trainer, said. ``He didn't like that surface at all, and he still
got second. They won't beat him in the Breeders' Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   Ieldame, only five fillies were entered, probably because
of the forbidding presence of Silverbulletday. The 3-year-old star
had won 14 of her 16 starts and 11 straight against other fillies.
But this was the first time she raced against older fillies, and
one of them, the 4-year-old Beautiful Pleasure, took the lead at
the start and kept it.
</P>
<P>
   Beautiful Pleasure won more than a race; she also won a share of
the lead among fillies and mares, a contest that will be decided in
the Breeders' Cup. But in her last two starts, she has outrun
Banshee Breeze on a sloppy Saratoga track and Silverbulletday on a
sloppy Belmont track.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made Silverbulletday commit to our style rather than us
committing to her style,'' John Ward Jr., who trains Beautiful
Pleasure for John C. Oxley, said. ``Beautiful Pleasure has earned
herself a spot in the Breeders' Cup Distaff.''
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Chavez, the jockey on Beautiful Pleasure, put it
succinctly. ``When a horse runs in the slop and has speed,'' he
said, ``it's very tough to beat. And I had a lot of speed today.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Bailey, the rider on Silverbulletday, said: ``She got
outrun. Beautiful Pleasure loves to be on the lead, and she loves
the slop.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the mud, Beautiful Pleasure flashed the mile and
one-eighth in 1:47 3/5. She returned $6.80 for a $2 bet to win, and
went home with $300,000.
</P>
<P>
   In the Frizette, another wire-to-wire performance was given by
Surfside, who fought a duel down the stretch with Darling My
Darling. She seemed to surrender the lead in the final furlong, but
regained it with a second effort directed by Pat Day, and won by a
head.
</P>
<P>
   It was the third victory in four starts for Surfside, and the
sixth in the Frizette for her trainer, D. Wayne Lukas. She is a
daughter of Seattle Slew and Flanders, and she promptly set her
sights on Chilukki, the undefeated West Coast filly who won her
fifth straight on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was concerned about the weather,'' Lukas said. ``But I think
she won on class and breeding. Unless something comes up in the
next 30 days, I have no excuses.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
