<SLUG> BC-FBN-BILLS-STEELERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLUTIE'S TRICKS FOOL THE STEELERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORCHARD PARK, N.Y. _ Buffalo quarterback Doug Flutie's bag of
tricks is large. As they say in basketball, he creates. He
frustrates a defense with a run, bobbing and weaving his way
through linebackers and safeties who always seem to be surprised by
his speed. His passes are like good fastballs. His decisions are
rarely bad ones.
</P>
<P>
   When the Pittsburgh Steelers' coaches and players look at the
film of their game Sunday against Flutie and the Bills, it will
resemble a horror show. The Steelers will not see masks or axes or
people lost in the woods, just a little man wearing No. 7, slowly
draining them of life. Buffalo won its fourth straight game by
beating Pittsburgh, 24-21, before 71,038 at Ralph Wilson Stadium,
behind what Flutie called his best passing effort of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was my best day throwing the ball this year,'' said
Flutie. ``I was seeing everything. I was being patient with my
throws.''
</P>
<P>
   But the afternoon was actually much more than that for Flutie.
He played a critical part, in one way or another, in each of
Buffalo's four scoring drives. Flutie's day was one of the most
impressive performances by a quarterback in the National Football
League this season.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half, Flutie was 8 of 8 passing for 127 yards and
one touchdown on first down. Overall, he finished the game 21 of 32
for 261 yards, 3 touchdowns and no interceptions. Pittsburgh
quarterback Kordell Stewart, who has struggled all season, also
played well, completing 21 of 29 passes for 216 yards and two
touchdowns. But unlike Flutie, Stewart threw a critical
interception that led to a Buffalo touchdown and a 24-14 Bills'
lead late in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Flutie finished with 39 yards rushing, which included a 21-yard
scramble on third-and-20, a crucial play that kept a Bills drive
alive. Later, kicker Steve Christie connected on a 29-yard field
goal for a 17-7 second-quarter lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Doug played a great game today,'' said Bills wide
receiver Eric Moulds, who had 6 catches for 122 yards and 1
touchdown. ``Last week against Miami he was in a slump until the
fourth quarter. Today we just spread them out, and that is when
Doug is at his best, because he can see a little bit clearer and he
made the plays when it counted.''
</P>
<P>
   It is time to start taking this Buffalo team seriously as a
contender in the American Football Conference East Division, thanks
to Flutie and to the Bills' defense, which is probably the best in
the AFC. How Buffalo got to this point _ tied with New England for
the division lead with a 4-1 record, after the Patriots lost to
Kansas City Sunday _ is contrary to the way it got to four Super
Bowls earlier this decade. Then they used a big, tough quarterback
in Jim Kelly to lead an explosive offense. Now, while the
5-foot-10-inch Flutie and the talented Moulds are among the top
offensive combinations in the conference, Buffalo's defense,
composed of young players and gritty veterans like Bruce Smith,
carries the team.
</P>
<P>
   The differences between the Bills and Steelers coming into this
game were immeasurable. The Bills were riding an emotional high
from a victory Monday night at Miami. Then there were the 2-3
Steelers, who own a losing record after five games for the first
time in the 1990s. While their defense is formidable, offensively
Pih is confused. Stewart has played in a haze; running back
Jerome Bettis, nicknamed the Bus, has spent much of this season in
the repair shop with various injuries, and the team, because of
free agency, has lost a number of other offensive weapons.
</P>
<P>
   What truly hurts Pittsburgh _ and especially hurts Stewart _ is
the lack of a running game. Bettis, once one of the most feared
runners in football, had just 24 yards on 13 carries. The Steelers
had only 48 rushing yards overall.
</P>
<P>
   Flutie, on the other hand, now scares defenses, and a series
late in the second half demonstrated just how much. The Bills were
at the Pittsburgh 8-yard line, and Flutie started a first-down play
by rolling right and faking as if he were going to run. The
Steelers, scared silly after Flutie had burned them on runs all
day, overreacted, running to stop him as if he were stealing their
paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, tight end Jay Riemersma, who had thrown a block
low on a Steelers lineman, lay on the ground as if he were done for
the play. Then Riemersma bounced up and began running the opposite
way. Flutie stopped in his tracks and threw across his body to the
tight end for the touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   It was trickery designed to take advantage of Flutie's
play-faking ability and of the way he terrifies defenses. Flutie
and smart play calling _ a deadly combination.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
