<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHOOLKIDS-COMMUTE-ART-535(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG STUDENTS COMMUTE FOR BETTER SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT19 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By LYNETTE HOLLOWAY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Akshay Ganesh, a 12-year-old seventh-grader who lives
on Staten Island, rolls out of bed every weekday about 6 a.m. He
has 20 minutes to eat breakfast and get dressed before heading out
the door to catch the S66 bus to catch the 7 a.m. ferry to
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Swimming in a sea of suits, briefcases and crumpled newspapers,
he tries to avoid dozing off as he rides the ferry to Battery Park,
where he then dashes east across Whitehall Street to jump on an
uptown subway. At 14th Street, he switches to an eastbound train to
get to First Avenue. Two hours after waking up, he arrives at
school, the Institute for Collaborative Education in Gramercy Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commute's really a hassle,'' he said one day last week,
trying to stave off a yawn. ``But education is really important,
and I like the school.''
</P>
<P>
   Akshay's morning adventure, an act of educational ambition and
preadolescent bravery, is hardly unique these days for middle
school students. Throughout New York City, children as young as 10
are setting off at daybreak, climbing aboard buses and squeezing
onto the subway to travel long distances to get to class.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Francis, 12, stands on a gritty street corner in
Brooklyn, at 6:45 a.m. to catch the bus that will take her to the
subway that will get her to the Clinton School for Artists and
Writers on the West Side of Manhattan. Maria Theresa Alonzo, 12,
who lives in Queens, commutes four hours a day to attend the New
York City Lab School in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the sagas of high school students making near-epic
trips across the boroughs to get to the city's finest public high
schools have played out for decades. But now, driven by an
explosion in the number of higher-quality junior high schools
created by individual public school districts, younger and younger
children are taking up the often risky project in commuter gumption
to reap the educational rewards.
</P>
<P>
   For parents, the decision to allow their 11- and 12-year-olds to
travel on the subway for an hour or more to school requires them to
balance concerns about safety with desires for educational
benefits. For those who opt to hire private buses to pick up their
children, the decision can also be one of finances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that crime is down, but I am still a little worried
about Akshay's safety in the afternoons,'' said Kala Ganesh, a
domestic-violence social worker who works in Manhattan. ``But what
do you do when you are looking for a great education and
opportunities?''
</P>
<P>
   About 30 new middle schools have cropped up in New York City
since 1991 _ increasing the number to 197 _ largely in response to
a public outcry over deplorable academic conditions. For years, the
city's middle schools have been described as the weakest link in
the system, one that pushed many families into private education.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the new schools are trumpeting specialized programs in
such areas as science, mathematics and dance to compete with other
districts for the best students. Last year, Brooklyn's District 15
created eight new middle schools, including The Manuel de Dios
Unanue Journalism School and the New School for Research in the
Natural and Social Sciences.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Manhattan's District 2, which began middle school choice in the
late 1980s, has long drawn students from around the city to the
Clinton School for Artists and Writers, the New York City Lab
School and others.
</P>
<P>
   But officials stepped up the effort when middle school choice
became citywide policy in 1993. The district _ which covers parts
of the Upper East and West Sides, the Lower East Side and Greenwich
Village _ went on to create the Salk School for Science and the New
York City Museum School.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember `Field of Dreams,' build a ball field and they will
come?'' said Burton Sacks, chief executive director of community
school district affairs for the city's Board of Education,
recalling the movie. ``Build a program, and if parents feel
comfortable that their youngsters are going to get a quality
education, they will let them travel. We think that's great.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennyson Lyttle, a big teen-ager with a soft voice, does not
mind getting up at 5:30 a.m. every weekday for a trip that would
make any adult cringe. He lives in Queens, near Kennedy
International Airport, and attends the Institute for Collaborative
Education in Manhattan. The 16-year-old 10th-grade student has been
making the trip since middle school.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard waking up, and the trip is long, but it's worth it
because I like the school,'' he said, arriving at the front door a
few minutes after 8 a.m. last Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Francis, 12, a seventh-grader at the Clinton School in
Manhattan, has a hard time most days waking up at 6 a.m. Her
mother, Marie Rose Bowman, has to call her at least a half-dozen
times, she said. But once she gets out of bed in the family's tiny
one-bedroom apartment in Brooklyn, she gets dressed in 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mind getting up,'' Mrs. Bowman, dressed in a
nightshirt, said one morning as she pulled Michelle's hair into a
ponytail while her daughter ate breakfast. ``I just go back to bed
after she leaves. You know, a child's education is important, and I
don't want her to go to school around here.''
</P>
<P>
   Michelle, hovering over a toasted bagel with butter at the
kitchen table, was coming to life at about 6:30 a.m. ``There is a
school up the block,'' she said between bites of the bagel. ``It's
not that good. That's where my cousin goes. My cousin's mean. I
don't want to be like her.''
</P>
<P>
   When Michelle began attending the Clinton School last year, she
had to choose a different route after the first month because she
arrived late every day. ``I had to take two buses and three
trains,'' she said, rolling her eyes. ``Now, I take a bus and two
subways. It's much better, and I run into friends from school on
the subway all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Concerns over safety have prompted some parents to arrange their
own transportation. Susan Weine, who lives in Park Slope, and five
other parents jointly chartered a small yellow school bus so that
their children would not have to ride the subway before daybreak.
The parents each pay about $2,300 a year for the door-to-door
service, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Weine's 10-year-old daughter, Sarah Ransom, is in the sixth
grade at the Institute for Collaborative Education.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's costly, but convenient,'' Ms. Weine said of the bus
service. ``But the jury's still out on whether all of this is worth
it. Now that we're in it and I see how stressful the long hours are
for everyone in the family, I wonder.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason she picked Collaborative was that it runs
through the 12th grade. ``The search ran my life,'' Ms. Weine said
of her three-month effort to find the perfect school. ``I saw 11
schools and took a lot of time off work to see them.''
</P>
<P>
   When Ellen Driesen of Brooklyn, helped her daughter, Rebecca,
12, choose a middle school last year, it reminded her of searching
for a college. The two scoured dozens of schools in Brooklyn's
District 15 and Manhattan's District 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were all of these choices,'' Mrs. Driesen said one
morning while waiting for Rebecca to finish dressing. They settled
on the Clinton School for Artists and Writers, which means that
Rebecca must take a bus and two subway trains. Mrs. Driesen goes
with her on the first stage of the trip.
</P>
<P>
   One day recently, they managed to get two seats on the packed
B61 bus, parting ways at the Jay Street-Borough Hall stop. Before
moving on, Mrs. Driesen watched her lanky daughter disappear
through the turnstile to the train.
</P>
<P>
   Once alone, Rebecca's soft features transformed from carefree
adolescent into don't-mess-with-me-I'm-from-Brooklyn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-10-99 2100EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
