<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEE-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES' NOTEBOOK 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AFTER YANKEES CELEBRATE, A RASH OF PROBLEMS
</P>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The Yankees were supposed to be celebrating
after they completed a sweep of Texas in the division series, but
Derek Jeter and some of his teammates were not smiling. They were
comparing rashes.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared as if some of the players reacted to the champagne
or beer being poured during the post-game celebration. Jeter, Luis
Sojo and at least a half-dozen other players suddenly were covered
with deep red rashes on their chests and shoulders. ``It's because
of that cheap stuff,'' one player said, referring to the quality of
the champagne.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees will presumably have medical concerns far greater
than skin rashes this week as they prepare for the start of the
American League Championship Series on Wednesday. Paul O'Neill has
bruised ribs and will go to Yankee Stadium on Monday for treatment.
Brian Cashman, the Yankees' general manager, said Sunday that if
O'Neill does not feel any relief _ he is extremely sore and has had
shortness of breath _ then he will go for more extensive tests in
the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a question about whether O'Neill will be able to
play, then the Yankees are likely to add outfielder Shane Spencer
to their postseason roster by Wednesday. The natural switch would
seem to be swapping Spencer for Clay Bellinger, the utility
infielder.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees also have the option of inserting Spencer in place
of the veteran Jim Leyritz, who has played sparingly and generally
struggled since joining the team in a trade before the July 31
deadline. But Joe Torre, the Yankees' manager, usually sticks with
players who have helped him win, and Leyritz's home run in Game 4
of the 1996 World Series was the Yankees' most important hit in the
last 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Cashman said he and Torre had spoken of the possibility of
adding Spencer, ``but not in detail.'' The Yankees now have only
three healthy, full-time outfielders on the roster.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Clemens hobbled around the Yankees' clubhouse after Game 3
Saturday with a large ice pack wrapped around the lower part of his
right knee, but that was treatment for the calf injury that came
when Tom Goodwin laced a ground ball against the side of Clemens'
leg; the pain worsened as the game progressed and stiffness set
in. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A GAME OF NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   With Roger Clemens and Darryl Strawberry dominating the news of
Game 3, other factors were overlooked:
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Rangers were stunned by their offensive failures. In
the last two years, they have scored two runs in six playoff games
against the Yankees. After batting .141 in 1998, they hit .152 in
this year's playoff. ``It's very hard to take _ very hard to
take,'' said Mark McLemore, the Rangers' second baseman. ``We came
into this year with a better ball club and the same thing happened
again. It's tough to deal with.'' The Rangers went 0 for 12 with
runners in scoring position in the series.
</P>
<P>
   Mariano Rivera, the Yankees' closer, entered Game 3 in the
eighth inning and got the last six outs. He has surrendered just
two earned runs in 38 innings in the post-season in his career, for
an 0.47 earned run average _ the lowest of any pitcher in major
league history with 30 or more innings. ``There's always hope until
the last out,'' said Rusty Greer, the Texas left fielder. ``Rivera
didn't allow us any more, though. He's a great closer.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeter had two hits in four at-bats in Game 3 and finished with a
.455 average for the series, leading the Yankees in hits (five) and
runs scored (three).
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' pitchers allowed 23 base runners in 27 innings,
giving up 14 hits and nine walks, and Torre used only five of his
10 pitchers. The right-hander Hideki Irabu has been on the
post-season roster for the Yankees' last four series and has not
pitched an inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankee hitters had a generally punchless series against
Texas in 1998, and did so again this year, batting .235 as a team,
with 10 walks and 14 runs scored. But nine of their 23 hits were
for extra bases; Texas had just three extra-base hits. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
