<SLUG> BC-WYO-GAYMURDER-TRIAL-540(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LARAMIE BRACES FOR TRIAL IN MATTHEW SHEPARD'S SLAYING
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Wyo.)   (jw) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LARAMIE, Wyo. _ The rail fence remains, a lonely span of timber
at the end of a rutted limestone trail, separating only one side of
prairie from the other.
</P>
<P>
   It was here a year ago that Matthew Shepard, a 21-year-old
political science student at the University of Wyoming, was beaten
by two men, tied to the fence and left to die, perhaps because he
was gay. He was found unconscious 18 hours later by a bicyclist and
taken to a hospital, where he lived four more days.
</P>
<P>
   The brutality of the crime turned it into a national rallying
cry for hate-crime laws to recognize a victim's sexual orientation,
along with race, religion annal origin, as a basis for
prosecution. Fewer than half the states have passed such expanded
measures, and eight, including Wyoming, have no hate-crime laws at
all. A federal bill that would include sexual orientation is under
consideration by a House-Senate conference.
</P>
<P>
   But criminal justice in this old cowboy town gallops ahead.
Russell Henderson, 22, one of the men charged with kidnapping,
aggravated robbery and murder in the death of Shepard pleaded
guilty in April and received consecutive life sentences in a deal
that spared him a death sentence.
</P>
<P>
   And on Monday, here in the county district court building, jury
selection begins in the trial of the second man, Aaron James
McKinney, 22, who is facing the same charges and a death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   While testimony is expected to provide a detailed account of
events leading to Shepard's death, it might never explain with
certainty why, as prosecutors charge, Henderson and McKinney preyed
on Shepard the night of Oct. 6, 1998, luring him out of the
Fireside Lounge on the pretense that they were gay, driving him out
of town, binding him in ropes, robbing him of $20 and his wallet,
beating him with the butt of a gun and leaving him tied to the
fence.
</P>
<P>
   The conventional theory is that Shepard's sexual orientation
offended the two in some way, and they felt a need to punish him.
In presiding over the plea bargain of Henderson, District Judge
Jeffrey Donnell said Shepard died in ``part because of his
lifestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   But the judge also suggested that the crime might have been
committed for other reasons, because Henderson's statement to the
court included no mention of Shepard's homosexuality or how he and
McKinney convinced Shepard to leave the Fireside with them.
</P>
<P>
   Some explanation might emerge in the trial of McKinney, which
could include testimony by Henderson.
</P>
<P>
   But Calvin Rerucha, the prosecutor, declined to discuss any
aspect of the McKinney case, citing an order by the judge, Barton
Voigt. And neither of McKinney's lawyers returned a telephone call
seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   For gay and lesbian organizations, the motive was unequivocal:
Shepard was killed because he was gay. ``The evidence is crystal
clear,'' said David M. Smith, senior strategist for the Human
Rights Campaign, a national advocacy group for gay and lesbian
rights.
</P>
<P>
   But questions linger in the minds of others. The victim's
mother, Judy Shepard, said in an interview that there are elements
of her son's death she may never understand. ``I don't think there
will ever be answers to all my questions,'' Ms. Shepard said.  &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Smith said his greatest fear was that McKinney's lawyers would
wage a successful ``panic defense,'' a tactic designed to build
sympathy with the jury and lessen the penalty by portraying the
defendant as someone so offended by homosexuality that, when
approached by a gay man, he panicked and responded with violence.
</P>
<P>
   Many in this town of 27,000, where Henderson and McKinney
repaired roofs for a living, worry that it is now viewed by the
rest of the country as an outpost of intolerance and bigotry, an
image testimony could cement.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think if you live in Laramie you come from a broken
home filled with hatred,'' said Joseph Bushnell, a retired
restaurant manager who now works as a computer consultant. ``Like
everybody here's from the other side of the tracks.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Glaser, Bushnell's colleague at the computer company, said,
`'It's unfortunate the way we've been cast.''
</P>
<P>
   There is little to suggest that the Shepard killing was anything
more than a brutal but isolated event. Once a railroad town,
Laramie now exists pretty much like any other working-class city of
its size in the Rocky Mountain West, with a mix of shops, bars and
restaurants in the downtown area and strip malls beyond. The
university adds a touch of diversity to a town that is
overwhelmingly white and heterosexual.
</P>
<P>
   Crime appears to be no worse than anywhere else. Police here say
they respond to garden-variety offenses, many of them the
byproducts of too much alcohol. Murders are rare, maybe one a year,
and murders of a minority member or gay person are rarer still.
</P>
<P>
   Yet nothing in Laramie's recent past has resonated so widely as
the killing of Shepard, and that could say as much about the macho
nature of Western culture in Wyoming, the least populated state in
the country, as Shepard's sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   Here, the cowboy is king. At least the cowboy image is king. The
silhouetted bucking-bronco rider that serves as Wyoming's official
state symbol adorns almost everything, from neon lights over bars
to restaurant logos to license plates. Even if the number of real
cowboys is declining as farm prices fall, the image endures.
</P>
<P>
   Shepard, a slightly built man at 5-foot-2, would not have been
mistaken for a cowboy. He was born in Casper, Wyo., where his
father worked as an oil rig safety inspector, but he studied in
Switzerland before returning to the United States to attend the
university here. He spoke several languages and wanted to become a
diplomat.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson and McKinney were high school dropouts. McKinney was
known around town as something of a bully, and the Laramie police
say that after the two left Shepard on the fence, McKinney
assaulted a Hispanic man back in town with the same gun he used to
beat Shepard.
</P>
<P>
   Bushnell, the computer consultant, said he had lived in the West
all his life, the last 10 years in Laramie. He said he knew Shepard
informally; they attended the same church now and again, St.
Matthew's Episcopal.
</P>
<P>
   He said most people in Laramie really did not know what drove
the two men to kill Shepard. ``Maybe he hit on them or maybe it was
a different type of thing and it wasn't sex,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it really doesn't matter why. He could have been a
homosexual, Jewish, black, whatever. He was a human being, and the
biggest percentage of people here have a great deal of sympathy for
human life. No matter what his preference was, to take a human
being's life is wrong.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-10-99 2114EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991010.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-10 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2655 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-REPUBS-BUDGET-CUTS-(T     10-10 1210
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-BUDGET-CUTS-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS WEIGH RISKS OF ACROSS-THE-BOARD SPENDING CUT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Okla., S.C., Fla., Miss., Texas)  (EDS: This story, which was eliminated earlier, has been
restored.) 
(mk) 
 By TIM WEINER and RICHARD W. STEVENSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Running out of weapons in their politically charged
fight to finance the government without using Social Security
money, Republicans in Congress are turning to the crudest of fiscal
tools, an across-the-board cut in spending.
</P>
<P>
   That blunt instrument would be a last-ditch choice for
Republican leaders. The political risks are such that analysts are
skeptical Congress will use it. But party leaders say they support
the idea, and 54 Republican senators passed a nonbinding resolution
in favor of it last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are drawing the line,'' said Sen. Don Nickles, R- Okla.,
the majority whip. ``If necessary, and hopefully it will not be
necessary, we will implement across-the-board reductions.''
</P>
<P>
   That would avoid the difficulty of cutting specific programs by
spreading the pain. And Republicans say they will do whatever is
necessary not to reach the point at which government spending for
the fiscal year that began Oct. 1 dips into excess Social Security
revenues.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans are well aware that the cuts could generate
widespread public opposition and draw intense attacks from
President Clinton and Democrats in Congress. And because
Republicans are talking about exempting the military and veterans'
programs from the cuts, the reductions could fall even harder on
domestic and social programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This approach is a sign of desperation,'' said Rep. John
Spratt, D-S.C., the senior Democrat on the House Budget Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The cuts would be so painful that many Republican lawmakers have
no stomach for them. But they say they have few alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican spending bills increase money for the Pentagon,
while freezing or cutting some domestic programs. So an
across-the-board cut would mean some real reductions in social
spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who wants to cut 6 percent out of education, health care,
medical research?'' asked Rep. C.W. ``Bill'' Young, R-Fla., the
chairman of the House Appropriations Committee. ``But if the
leadership directs us to do it, we'll do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The House speaker, Dennis Hastert, and the Senate majority
leader, Trent Lott, R-Miss., say the cuts must be made if the
alternative is tapping Social Security money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an indication of how desperate they are up on Capitol
Hill for a way out of their appropriations problem,'' said Stanley
Collender, head of the federal budget consulting group at
Fleischman Hillard, a public relations firm.
</P>
<P>
   The cuts could also aid the Democrats' argument that the
Republican majority in Congress cannot meet its most basic
responsibility of setting priorities and passing spending bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``An across-the-board cut is the ultimate confession of policy
failure,'' said Robert Bixby, policy director of the Concord
Coalition, a nonpartisan fiscal watchdog group. ``It's the meat
cleaver approach.''
</P>
<P>
   One difficulty would be the pressure to exempt the military,
veterans and other favorites. ``As soon as you talk about
across-the-board cuts, everybody jumps up and salutes it, and then
their second point is, `But I have this very special program,'''
said the House majority leader, Dick Armey, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives outside of Congress said the approach is not
ideal, but better than raising tobacco taxes, as Clinton has
proposed, or breaking the Republicans' pledge not to use Social
Security revenues for general government operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like the least bad of several bad choices,'' said
Peter Sperry, a budget analyst at the Heritage Foundation, a
conservative research organization.
</P>
<P>
   Spending some Social Security money would have no direct effect
on the retirement system's long-term financial condition and little
or no economic impact. But it has immense political significance
for Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has still not finished work on six of the 13 spending
bills needed to finance the government, now operating under
temporary spending authority that expires Oct. 21.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans are trying to limit overall spending outlays for
government agencies to $592 billion for fiscal 2000 _ roughly the
same as fiscal 1999 _ and they are using every accounting device
available.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Pentagon spending bill delays payments to
military contractors from late September 2000 to early October
2000, shifting $1.25 billion of spending into fiscal 2001,
congressional aides said.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Republicans are weighing whether to delay federal
workers' paychecks for late September until early October 2000,
shifting about $3.6 billion in spending into the next year, those
aides said.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans' only alternatives to this kind of creative
bookkeeping are cutting their spending bills or tapping the Social
Security money.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   It is possible that the Republicans will achieve their goal on
time and on budget. But it will be hard. Congress is on track to
use at least $8 billion of the Social Security surplus, House
Republican estimates show.
</P>
<P>
   To bring outlays down by $8 billion in fiscal 2000, Congress
would have to pass and Clinton would have to sign into law
across-the-board cuts of 2.7 percent, or $15.2 billion in budget
authority, the Republicans estimate.
</P>
<P>
   Budget authority, which pays for one or more years of spending,
must be cut deeper to yield savings in outlays, which cover only
one year.
</P>
<P>
   Under a 2.7 percent cut, the military would have to furlough
close to 100,000 personnel, disband an Army division and a Navy
carrier battle group and deny health care to many veterans, House
Democrats say. If military and veterans programs were exempted, the
cuts on all other programs would be 6.3 percent, Republicans and
Democrats say.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But the cuts might have to be even deeper. The Congressional
Budget Office and the White House have both judged the Republicans
to be on track to spend at least $19.2 billion of the Social
Security surplus.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid that, the cuts would have to be 6.9 percent if the
military and veterans are included and 16.1 percent if not,
Democrats on the House Budget Committee say.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The precise effect across-the-board cuts would have on specific
programs is hard to predict. But the cuts would almost certainly
shake every branch of the government, from national parks to
national security, and force thousands of layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   They would cut off money for food and education to hundreds of
thousands of poor children, cancel millions of home-delivered meals
for the elderly and hobble federal law enforcement, the White House
says.
</P>
<P>
   The White House budget director, Jacob Lew, said in an interview
that in many ways a 2.7 percent cut would be the worst of both
worlds, failing to protect the Social Security surplus while
hurting the needy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This idea hasn't been floated lightly, and we're taking it
seriously,'' he said. ``But it's a silly way to make policy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-10-99 2118EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
