<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: CHEATING THE SCHOOLS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By BOB HERBERT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The numbers are stark. The system is unfair. New York City kids
account for 38 percent of the state's public school enrollment but
get only 34 percent of the state's school aid.
</P>
<P>
   The annual per-pupil expenditure on behalf of children in the
city is roughly $8,100. The statewide average is about $9,200. This
translates into hundreds of millions of lost education dollars each
year.
</P>
<P>
   With so much less money to spend, it's no wonder city schools
are hurting. In the city there are fewer than eight computers per
100 students, and most are antiquated. Head out to the suburbs and
you will find twice as many computers, most of them up to date.
</P>
<P>
   City schools have about 90 library books per 100 students.
Downstate suburban districts have about 235 per 100.
</P>
<P>
   Only a nitwit would think this steady shortfall of money makes
no difference. Teacher salaries in New York City are among the
lowest in the state. The number of uncertified teachers in the city
is among the highest. And the teacher turnover rate is the highest.
</P>
<P>
   The blunt truth is that the state is quick to smile on the
children of the suburbs, particularly the wealthy downstate suburbs
of Westchester, Nassau and Suffolk counties. The motley million or
so kids in the New York City school system, most of them black or
Hispanic and many of them poor, are another matter entirely. They
are shamelessly ripped off by the state, year after year after
year. In the eyes of the power brokers, they are not as worthy of
state aid as their suburban counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been living with this for a very long period of
time,'' said Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew, who noted that the
annual per-pupil allocations in Nassau and Suffolk were,
respectively, about $12,000 and $11,700 _ far higher than the
city's $8,100.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kind of inequitable distribution begs for a challenge,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't gotten a lot of attention, but that challenge is under
way. An advocacy group that calls itself the Campaign for Fiscal
Equity has sued the state in an effort to force changes in the
funding formulas. A trial of that suit is to begin Tuesday in state
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone looking for an insight into how the New York City kids
are viewed by the state need look no further than the outside law
firm hired to fight the lawsuit. It's a firm from down South _
Sutherland, Asbill &AMP; Brennan of Atlanta, Ga. _ that has built a
national reputation for fighting orders to desegregate public
schools.
</P>
<P>
   What a great idea to bring that outfit into New York and pay it
millions of taxpayer dollars (some $5 million to date) to undermine
the interests of the ethnic minorities and newly arrived immigrants
in the city's public schools. If you want to keep some poor kids
down, this is the way to do it. Call in the experts.
</P>
<P>
   The Court of Appeals has ruled that the state is not required to
provide the same level of education funding for students throughout
the state. But under the state Constitution all students have a
right to a sound basic education. In its lawsuit, the Campaign for
Fiscal Equity charges that the state, by relentlessly underfunding
the city's school system, is failing to meet its obligation to
provide a sound basic education for the city's kids. The suit also
argues that because such a preponderance of the city's students are
from ethnic minority groups, the inequities may be racially
discriminatory.
</P>
<P>
   The Court of Appeals has allowed those claims to go to trial,
and has indicated that it will impose remedies if the Campaign for
Fiscal Equity proves its case.
</P>
<P>
   Randi Weingarten, president of the United Federation of
Teachers, which is supporting the lawsuit, noted that the state is
raising its educational standards and demanding a higher level of
performance from all students.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they expect the same level of performance, which is a good
thing,'' she said, ``then we have to have the wherewithal to do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to public school funding, said Ms. Weingarten,
``what tends to happen in this society is that the kids who are
wealthy get more and the kids who are poor get less.''
</P>
<P>
   That fundamental inequity is compounded by the fact that
youngsters who come from disadvantaged backgrounds and immigrants
struggling to learn a new language often need more in the way of
educational resources, not less. To provide less money for such
youngsters is not just unfair, it's perverse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-10-99 2125EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
