<HEADLINE>
ON BASEBALL: METS MIGHT BE ON THEIR WAY TO EQUAL RESPECT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Mets obviously are the stepchild of these
playoffs, the Yankees the preferred progeny. But the Mets' day is
coming. When the World Series begins in 12 days, the Mets will be
the Yankees' equal in the eyes of baseball and television
officials, who will have no choice but to show the Mets playing at
the same time and on the same network as the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   All right, so the Mets and Yankees have to get there first, and
the Mets will have a far more difficult task in getting there than
the Yankees. The way the Yankees have played postseason series in
recent years, they seem to have a pass to the World Series. Holding
the Texas Rangers, the American League's most potent slugging
machine, to one run a series in successive seasons is either a sign
of a great pitching staff working with a great scouting report or a
crying need for an immediate investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have to work for their success. Led by a manager who
seems to have a compulsive urge to induce other managers and even
some of his own players to despise him, they create obstacles for
themselves that they then have to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets recovered from a late-season losing streak just in time
to reach the postseason for the first time in 11 years. Though they
did not match their phenomenal 1998 achievement of 114 victories,
the Yankees cruised into their fifth successive postseason
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the television schedule for the four division series,
the Mets played two games that began after 11 p.m. New York time
and one game, the one in which they won the series against Arizona,
that was carried on ESPN's baby. Mets fans without cable or unable
to get New York's Channel 11 had to revert to practices of another
time, reading newspapers, to learn that their team had won their
first postseason series since the 1986 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, meanwhile, played a prime-time schedule that was so
desirable it had to be shared by two networks. If any Yankees fans
missed the final scores, it was only because the Yankees had so
much fun beating up on the Rangers, their favorite practice
dummies, that they took an inordinate amount of time doing it.
</P>
<P>
   As with the division series, the league championship series
stands to be a far more perilous road for the Mets to navigate than
for the Yankees. The Mets, after all, have to beat the Atlanta
Braves, the team that shoved them onto the precipice last month by
beating them five of six times in a 10-day span. How are the Mets
going to be able to beat the Braves four times in seven games?
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't do too well this season against Atlanta,'' Todd
Pratt said in the immediate aftermath of his electrifying
series-ending home run Saturday. ``We said we wanted one more
chance. Now it's time to put up or shut up.''
</P>
<P>
   For inspiration, the Mets can look to the fate suffered by their
1988 predecessors, who beat the Los Angeles 10 times in 11 games
during the season, then lost the league playoff series to the
Dodgers. Actually, they don't have to go back that far. This season
the Mets lost seven of their nine games with Arizona but then
dispatched the Diamondbacks in the playoffs. So it can be done.
</P>
<P>
   But Greg Maddux, Kevin Millwood, Tom Glavine and John Smoltz
present a formidable array of pitchers for the Mets to overcome.
Sure, they beat Randy Johnson in the first game of the division
series, but they didn't have to face him every day. Maybe Chipper
Jones won't be so devastating with his bat this time, but ask the
Houston Astros about Brian Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   But the Braves have had outstanding teams and formidable
pitchers every time they reached the league championship series,
which they have now done eight consecutive times, and they have
lost the series three times, including the last two. In other
words, there is a way to beat the Braves; the Mets just have to
find it. Again, if they seek inspiration, think of the Florida
Marlins only two years ago. They were a wild-card team, and they
beat the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees should be as formidable an opponent for whichever
team they face as the Braves will be for the Mets. Last year the
Cleveland Indians tossed a momentary fright into the Yankees by
winning two of the first three games with two more games to play in
Cleveland. But the Indians didn't win another game.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have no guarantee that they will make it through to
the World Series this time, but like the Braves, they will enter
the American League series with the better pitching staff. Pitching
often dominates a post-season series. The Rangers keep finding that
out.
</P>
<P>
   There is no question that the Mets and the Yankees want to see
each other win so that they can revive what was once an annual
event _ the Subway Series. New York hasn't seen one since 1956,
when the Yankees defeated the Dodgers. This is the first time since
that year that two New York teams are in the post-season at the
same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have both teams playing in the next 10 days, battling to
try and play each other is going to be exciting,'' Tino Martinez,
the Yankees' first baseman, said. ``Hopefully, we can do it and
hopefully they can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Recalling his first World Series experience last year, Chuck
Knoblauch said: ``It was crazy enough last year with just us being
in the World Series. With two of us in there, it would be scary. It
almost looks like it's heading that way. It would be crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Strawberry has played for both teams, the Mets the last
time they were in the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got to think how crazy would it be in New York more than
anything,'' he said of the possibility of a Yankees-Mets World
Series. ``We know we would have to play, but as far as the fans and
the rivalry between Mets fans and Yankee fans, you might not be
able to control that.''
</P>
<P>
   Derek Jeter wasn't sure if the entire city wouldn't get out of
control. ``The city would be kind of hectic,'' he said. ``It gets
crazy when one team is in it. I don't know if they'd be able to
handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
