<SLUG> BC-R-WYO-GAYMURDER-TRIAL-ART-540(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LARAMIE BRACES FOR TRIAL IN MATTHEW SHEPARD'S SLAYING
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to add photo note) 
(Attn: Wyo.)   (ART ADV: Photo NYT 24 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jw) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LARAMIE, Wyo. _ The rail fence remains, a lonely span of timber
at the end of a rutted limestone trail, separating only one side of
prairie from the other.
</P>
<P>
   It was here a year ago that Matthew Shepard, a 21-year-old
political science student at the University of Wyoming, was beaten
by two men, tied to the fence and left to die, perhaps because he
was gay. He was found unconscious 18 hours later by a bicyclist and
taken to a hospital, where he lived four more days.
</P>
<P>
   The brutality of the crime turned it into a national rallying
cry for hate-crime laws to recognize a victim's sexual orientation,
along with race, religion and national origin, as a basis for
prosecution. Fewer than half the states have passed such expanded
measures, and eight, including Wyoming, have no hate-crime laws at
all. A federal bill that would include sexual orientation is under
consideration by a House-Senate conference.
</P>
<P>
   But criminal justice in this old cowboy town gallops ahead.
Russell Henderson, 22, one of the men charged with kidnapping,
aggravated robbery and murder in the death of Shepard pleaded
guilty in April and received consecutive life sentences in a deal
that spared him a death sentence.
</P>
<P>
   And on Monday, here in the county district court building, jury
selection begins in the trial of the second man, Aaron James
McKinney, 22, who is facing the same charges and a death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   While testimony is expected to provide a detailed account of
events leading to Shepard's death, it might never explain with
certainty why, as prosecutors charge, Henderson and McKinney preyed
on Shepard the night of Oct. 6, 1998, luring him out of the
Fireside Lounge on the pretense that they were gay, driving him out
of town, binding him in ropes, robbing him of $20 and his wallet,
beating him with the butt of a gun and leaving him tied to the
fence.
</P>
<P>
   The conventional theory is that Shepard's sexual orientation
offended the two in some way, and they felt a need to punish him.
In presiding over the plea bargain of Henderson, District Judge
Jeffrey Donnell said Shepard died in ``part because of his
lifestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   But the judge also suggested that the crime might have been
committed for other reasons, because Henderson's statement to the
court included no mention of Shepard's homosexuality or how he and
McKinney convinced Shepard to leave the Fireside with them.
</P>
<P>
   Some explanation might emerge in the trial of McKinney, which
could include testimony by Henderson.
</P>
<P>
   But Calvin Rerucha, the prosecutor, declined to discuss any
aspect of the McKinney case, citing an order by the judge, Barton
Voigt. And neither of McKinney's lawyers returned a telephone call
seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   For gay and lesbian organizations, the motive was unequivocal:
Shepard was killed because he was gay. ``The evidence is crystal
clear,'' said David M. Smith, senior strategist for the Human
Rights Campaign, a national advocacy group for gay and lesbian
rights.
</P>
<P>
   But questions linger in the minds of others. The victim's
mother, Judy Shepard, said in an interview that there are elements
of her son's death she may never understand. ``I don't think there
will ever be answers to all my questions,'' Ms. Shepard said.  &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Smith said his greatest fear was that McKinney's lawyers would
wage a successful ``panic defense,'' a tactic designed to build
sympathy with the jury and lessen the penalty by portraying the
defendant as someone so offended by homosexuality that, when
approached by a gay man, he panicked and responded with violence.
</P>
<P>
   Many in this town of 27,000, where Henderson and McKinney
repaired roofs for a living, worry that it is now viewed by the
rest of the country as an outpost of intolerance and bigotry, an
image testimony could cement.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think if you live in Laramie you come from a broken
home filled with hatred,'' said Joseph Bushnell, a retired
restaurant manager who now works as a computer consultant. ``Like
everybody here's from the other side of the tracks.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Glaser, Bushnell's colleague at the computer company, said,
`'It's unfortunate the way we've been cast.''
</P>
<P>
   There is little to suggest that the Shepard killing was anything
more than a brutal but isolated event. Once a railroad town,
Laramie now exists pretty much like any other working-class city of
its size in the Rocky Mountain West, with a mix of shops, bars and
restaurants in the downtown area and strip malls beyond. The
university adds a touch of diversity to a town that is
overwhelmingly white and heterosexual.
</P>
<P>
   Crime appears to be no worse than anywhere else. Police here say
they respond to garden-variety offenses, many of them the
byproducts of too much alcohol. Murders are rare, maybe one a year,
and murders of a minority member or gay person are rarer still.
</P>
<P>
   Yet nothing in Laramie's recent past has resonated so widely as
the killing of Shepard, and that could say as much about the macho
nature of Western culture in Wyoming, the least populated state in
the country, as Shepard's sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   Here, the cowboy is king. At least the cowboy image is king. The
silhouetted bucking-bronco rider that serves as Wyoming's official
state symbol adorns almost everything, from neon lights over bars
to restaurant logos to license plates. Even if the number of real
cowboys is declining as farm prices fall, the image endures.
</P>
<P>
   Shepard, a slightly built man at 5-foot-2, would not have been
mistaken for a cowboy. He was born in Casper, Wyo., where his
father worked as an oil rig safety inspector, but he studied in
Switzerland before returning to the United States to attend the
university here. He spoke several languages and wanted to become a
diplomat.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson and McKinney were high school dropouts. McKinney was
known around town as something of a bully, and the Laramie police
say that after the two left Shepard on the fence, McKinney
assaulted a Hispanic man back in town with the same gun he used to
beat Shepard.
</P>
<P>
   Bushnell, the computer consultant, said he had lived in the West
all his life, the last 10 years in Laramie. He said he knew Shepard
informally; they attended the same church now and again, St.
Matthew's Episcopal.
</P>
<P>
   He said most people in Laramie really did not know what drove
the two men to kill Shepard. ``Maybe he hit on them or maybe it was
a different type of thing and it wasn't sex,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it really doesn't matter why. He could have been a
homosexual, Jewish, black, whatever. He was a human being, and the
biggest percentage of people here have a great deal of sympathy for
human life. No matter what his preference was, to take a human
being's life is wrong.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-10-99 2158EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
