u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-SPREWELL-N     10-10 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-SPREWELL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER A 45-HOUR DRIVE, SPREWELL SHRUGS OFF HIS DETOUR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PURCHASE, N.Y._ A black Mercedes crawled through a half-full lot
until the driver behind the tinted windows rolled to a stop in a
no-parking zone.
</P>
<P>
   Out popped Latrell Sprewell, 20 minutes late. Inside the Knicks'
practice facility Sunday morning, Coach Jeff Van Gundy and General
Manager Scott Layden were waiting for him to arrive and provide an
explanation for dropping off the radar and missing all of training
camp. About 45 minutes later, Sprewell emerged and shrugged his
shoulders, as if to say, ``Why all the fuss?''
</P>
<P>
   While Sprewell understood the reason the team had to fine him
for his unexcused absences at camp _ a penalty that could reach
$40,000 _ he was not remorseful about his behavior. For one thing,
he did not find his actions so strange _ not his failure to tell
anyone of his plans to drive across the country after closing
arguments last Monday in a civil suit he faced in California, or
his refusal to return three days' worth of messages left by the
Knicks?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what agents are for,'' Sprewell said, referring to
Robert Gist. ``There was no particular reason. I really didn't call
anybody. I'm not denying I didn't call them back; I just didn't. I
thought my agent knew. But it's not like I told him, `I'm leaving
at this time, and I'm going to do this.' I'm not blaming him; it's
on me. I didn't really communicate to anybody. It's like, I'll get
there; I'll be there. It was not like I'm ditching camp. I had to
do the thing in court, and that was exhausting enough. Then, to
have to drive.''
</P>
<P>
   And drive and drive. With music as his only traveling companion,
Sprewell drove 32 hours from Oakland, Calif., to his hometown of
Milwaukee, where he pulled into the driveway at 3 a.m. last
Wednesday. On Thursday night, with his brother and a friend, he
loaded up his belongings and drove 13 more hours to New York.
</P>
<P>
   The effort could have been avoided. He was asked whether he
could have called a shipping company to move his belongings, but
made it clear that that he does things on his terms. That is how
Sprewell plays, how he drives, how he lives his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is me,'' said Sprewell, who has a $9.1 million annual
salary. ``Me, I like doing stuff myself. It can take two weeks to
ship stuff. If I can do it in a day, why wait?''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't just a day, though. Sprewell missed all of the team's
training camp in Charleston, S.C., last week, and stood as a symbol
of insubordination. Although he plans to explain his actions to his
teammates, his conduct only intensifies the image of a player who
lacks respect for authority.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Sprewell choked Golden State Coach P.J. Carlesimo
and was suspended. Upon his return to the league as a Knick last
season, he grumbled about his role and often glared at Van Gundy
for playing him as sixth man. But Van Gundy and Layden made it
clear that the Knicks are not worried about Sprewell's pattern of
behavior as long as it doesn't effect his performance and the team
keeps finding a path to the National Basketball Association finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're committed to winning; we want him here,'' Layden said.
</P>
<P>
   That means the Knicks still intend to sign Sprewell to a
contract extension that could top $70 million. Instead of scolding
Sprewell more publicly Sunday, Layden and Van Gundy kept quiet
about the mood of the meeting and stepped around their enigmatic
guard's sensitivities. So far, Sprewell hasn't been offended. He
still wants to be a Knick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that way right now,'' Sprewell said. ``Things change,
but hopefully they won't.''
</P>
<P>
   If Sprewell has his way, he will be a starter this season. But
he also said his contract situation isn't solely contingent on his
role.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends on what the numbers look like,'' Sprewell said.
``Obviously, I want to do what's best for me.''
</P>
<P>
   With his absence last week, Sprewell set the team back in its
preparation and became a distraction as the subject of a scavenger
hunt. Privately, some members of the organization questioned the
message Sprewell was sending to his teammates about his commitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't trying to send a message,'' Sprewell said. ``People
are going to think what they want to think. I don't see any reason
why we can't hit the ground running. I'm a big part of what we do,
but I wasn't the sole reason why we got so far last year. Those
guys were a much bigger part of why we were there. We still have
time. It's not like the first game is tomorrow or in a week.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks' first exhibition game is Tuesday. Although Sprewell
will play in Monday's open scrimmage at Madison Square Garden, Van
Gundy and Layden don't feel comfortable enough with his physical
conditioning to play him against Philadelphia one day after his
first practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to sit here and say I'm in great shape,'' said
Sprewell, who seemed fit at first glance today. ``But one thing
about me, it won't take long to get in shape.''
</P>
<P>
   In no time, Sprewell is likely to be embraced by his teammates
and the public. Last season, Sprewell proved he could counter a
negative image with a few menacing dunks to drive the crowds wild.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say, like I've always said, everyone will have their
own opinion,'' Sprewell said. ``I don't get upset about it. It
doesn't affect me.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he emerges from each scrape typically nonchalant.
Besides, if you ask him, he was never missing at all. He is just a
man who chooses his own route.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like I was away,'' he said. ``I was on my way here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
