<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-10 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2677 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-GIANTS-CARDINALS-     10-10 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-CARDINALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS TURN TO COLLINS, AND THE PROBLEMS GROW 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ They changed quarterbacks Sunday, but the Giants
could not change themselves.
</P>
<P>
   In the mind-numbing reality of Giants football after Phil Simms,
another quarterback failed to jolt the offense from its slumber, a
trance-like sleepwalk that has made the Giants one of the National
Football League's worst offenses for five years running.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry Collins made his Giants debut Sunday against the Arizona
Cardinals, but he inherited the same unimaginative attack that
produced the same predictable results.
</P>
<P>
   Ill-timed penalties, clumsy execution, a lack of poise and
questionable play-calling, it was all there in the Giants' 14-3
dreadful loss to the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' defense once again dominated a game that was lost
when the Cardinals went ahead by two touchdowns in the first half.
But neither Collins nor coach Jim Fassel had any answers for
rousing the offense.
</P>
<P>
   The increasingly embattled Fassel did not even have any answers
after the game, which is hardly a good sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm befuddled,'' said Fassel, whose Giants are 2-3 for a third
successive year. ``On offense, I don't know what's in their minds.
Right now, we're playing terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a refrain Fassel has issued after nearly every game this
year. Asked what was left for him to do, Fassel answered: ``I don't
know.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins completed 24 of 38 passes for 202 passing yards,
although he fumbled while scrambling, which set up the first
touchdown by the Cardinals (2-3). And he was intercepted in the
first half.
</P>
<P>
   Collins also spent much of the day avoiding or overcoming
pressure as the Giants' offensive line played perhaps its worst
game of the season. Collins was sacked three times.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel said he would not announce whether Collins or Kent Graham
would be his quarterback for next week's game with Dallas until at
least Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' offense noticeably stumbled twice Sunday in short
yardage situations that could have turned the game. On a
third-and-2 in the first quarter when the game was still scoreless,
Fassel sent fullback Charles Way _perhaps his slowest running back
_ on a pitch play around left end. Way did not gain any yardage.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the third quarter, on a third-and-1 when the Giants
were desperately trying to get back into a game they trailed by
14-0, Fassel tried Gary Brown, another ball carrier best known for
his bull rushes up the middle, on the same play. It lost a yard.
Both drives ended in punts.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the calls, Fassel and Collins said it was a play
that had worked successfully for the Giants in past meetings with
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, it may be indicative of a Giants' offense that is
getting worse rather than better.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants also did not throw the ball downfield until late in
the game, when they were in a no-huddle offense and racked up most
of the 285 yards they produced for the game, as well as their lone
field goal.
</P>
<P>
   But Fassel dismissed the suggestion that play-calling had a
significant impact on the game, saying the Giants' lack of
execution doomed most plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter, you can call whatever you want,'' Fassel
said. ``If you're getting sacked or there's a penalty called, it
doesn't matter what you call.''
</P>
<P>
   A case in point may have been the Giants' last serious
opportunity to get back in the game. Down by 11 points, the Giants
drove to the Cardinals' 3-yard line with six minutes to play.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants could have gotten there sooner, and perhaps scored a
touchdown earlier, except for three penalties in the drive: one
each on tackles Scott Gragg and Romen Oben and a delay-of-game
penalty when Collins didn't call for the snap in time.
</P>
<P>
   On fourth down at the 3, Collins again lost track of the play
clock and the Giants were penalized five yards. On fourth-and-goal,
Collins and his receivers got mixed up when the Cardinals blitzed a
safety.
</P>
<P>
   Collins threw it one way, Ike Hilliard and Amani Toomer ran
opposite patterns away from Collins' throw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't do anything close to spectacular,'' Collins said. Of
the delay-of-game penalties, he said: ``That's nobody's fault but
mine. It's inexcusable.''
</P>
<P>
   Lost in the Giants' offensive blundering was another brilliant
effort by the team's defense. It knocked Cardinals quarterback Jake
Plummer from the game with a hip pointer and bruised ribs. He was
limited to just 156 yards passing with a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona, which had just 31 yards rushing, converted 2 of 13
third-down chances.
</P>
<P>
   But Arizona did take advantage of Collins' first-quarter fumble.
Collins lost the ball when he was scrambling to his left; Arizona's
Andre Wadsworth knocked the ball free. With the Cardinals taking
over on the Giants' 30-yard line, Plummer was sacked on first down
but recovered to bring the Cardinals to the 1 with a 37-yard pass
to David Boston. He split Giants cornerback Jason Sehorn and Percy
Ellsworth on the play and turned each defender the wrong way.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer's quarterback sneak gave Arizona a 7-0 lead early in the
second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona extended its lead just before the half ended when it
called a stop-and-go route for Boston. Giants cornerback Phillippi
Sparks fell on Boston's fake at the play's start, with Sparks also
losing his shoe.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks recovered and was with Boston in the end zone. But Boston
is three inches taller than Sparks and was in position to jump
sooner. He wrestled away Plummer's pass from Sparks for the 11-yard
touchdown play in the corner of the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' lone scoring opportunity of the first half was a
42-yard field-goal attempt, which Brad Daluiso missed wide right.
</P>
<P>
   The third quarter was more of the same for the Giants' offense,
with the ground game mildly successful _ Brown had 67 yards on 18
carries. Collins often had little time to throw as the defensive
ends Simeon Rice and Wadsworth frequently overran Oben and Gragg.
</P>
<P>
   Daluiso's 31-yard, fourth-quarter field goal was the only play
that kept the Giants from being shut out for the first time in
three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know who is going to be the quarterback and I'll
support any decision,'' said Collins, who quickly summed up the
doleful situation. ``We've got problems. I know that.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
