<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-10 22:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2678 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX     10-10 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The Cowboys gave Philadelphia Eagles fans
something to cheer about yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Twice, actually.
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit A: Cheering erupted for an injured Michael Irvin,
diagnosed with trauma to the head and neck, and who lay motionless
on the turf of Veterans Stadium for more than 15 minutes. Irvin was
taken on a stretcher by ambulance to a local hospital and retained
overnight for observation.
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit B: The final 1:07. This outbreak of cheering was purely
for the previously winless Eagles, producers of no offensive
touchdowns in 18 quarters, who came back from a 10-point,
fourth-quarter deficit to win, 13-10.
</P>
<P>
   Let the record show that the Cowboys no longer are undefeated.
They're 3-1 and tied with Washington for the NFC East lead.
</P>
<P>
   Let the record show that yesterday's game-winner for the Eagles
came on a 28-yard touchdown pass from Doug Pederson to Charles
Johnson, who split the Cowboys' safeties in zone coverage, then
dived across the goal line.
</P>
<P>
   Also let the record show that a sporadic Cowboys offense, with
more turnovers (3) than scoring drives (2) in this game, allowed
the Eagles to hang around just long enough for them to steal their
first victory since Dec. 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you give a team that's hungry a chance to win in the
fourth quarter, you see a change in them,'' Cowboys coach Chan
Gailey said. ``That's exactly what happened to them.''
</P>
<P>
   The door of opportunity flung wide open with just over 31/2
minutes left in the game when Emmitt Smith was stuffed on
successive running plays, as the Cowboys twice failed to pick up
two yards from the Dallas 36. On fourth-and-four, the usually
reliable Toby Gowin shanked a 28-yard punt out of bounds at the
Eagles' 36.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed and upset that we couldn't make two yards
there,'' Gailey said. ``I thought we could make a first down,'' and
protect a 10-3 lead if not add to it.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Smith spoke of the obvious frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good team would close the deal,'' said Smith, who accounted
for 145 yards of offense (114 rushing, 31 receiving) but had only
14 rushing yards in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a ways to go as a ball club,'' Smith added. ``We have
to learn how to win when we have had success, and we have to close
the deal when we're up on somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   This Cowboys team reverted back to the form of last season when
the Cowboys lost games that they shouldn't have: 13-12 vs. Oakland,
13-12 at Chicago, 22-3 at New Orleans. These teams finished a
combined 18-30.
</P>
<P>
   With this victory, the Eagles become the first NFC East team to
defeat the Gailey-coached Cowboys in two seasons. Gailey brought a
10-0 divisional record into yesterday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the Cowboys' three turnovers came inside the Philadelphia
25, including Smith's first-quarter fumble at the Eagles' 1. Aikman
had two interceptions, including a 24-yard pass intended for Rocket
Ismail that was picked off by cornerback Troy Vincent in the end
zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had our chances with good field position,'' said Aikman,
who finished 21-of-39 for 177 yards. He was sacked once, breaking a
string of nine quarters without a sack. ``We just weren't able to
establish anything as far as getting some momentum going.''
</P>
<P>
   But the low point came on third-and-two, with 31/2 minutes left,
when Smith never made it out the Cowboys' backfield. Linebackers
William Thomas and Jeremiah Trotter poured through the left side of
the Cowboys' offensive line, which added another patch in the
second quarter when center Mark Stepnoski (back contusion) had to
be replaced by first-year free agent Ben Fricke.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles went 62 yards the other way for only their fourth
offensive touchdown in five games this season. Pederson, 2-for-3
passing for 48 yards on the drive, finished the game a paltry
11-for-29 for 145 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Eagles running back Duce Staley, who broke off a 19-yard run on
the game-winning drive, became the first 100-yard rusher (110 on 22
carries) against the Cowboys' defense since Stephen Davis (109 on
24 carries) in the season-opener at Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Only when the Eagles cut into the Cowboys' 10-0 lead with a
48-yard Norm Johnson field goal early in the fourth quarter, making
it 10-3 with 11:48 left, did Gailey stray from playing it close to
the vest. He ordered up a 50-yard field-goal attempt, on which
Richie Cunningham was wide left.
</P>
<P>
   With a short-field drive, as a result of the missed kick,
Johnson added a 28-yard field goal with 5:42 left, and gave the
Eagles a chance to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this league, it's a fight every week,'' Gailey said. ``I
would hope we're hurt. I would hope we're upset.''
</P>
<P>
   Good chance they are.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
