<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-10 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2680 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-LeBRETON-TEX     10-10 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LeBRETON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAGLES HANDED VICTORY WITH COWBOYS IN STUPOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Among the many manifestations of emotion
yesterday was a banner in the Veterans Stadium end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Embarrassed To Be A Fan,'' it read, simply.
</P>
<P>
   Must have been a Cowboys fan.
</P>
<P>
   For this was embarrassing. As well as humiliating. And
preposterous. And every other shameful adjective that a good fan
could muster after the Cowboys turned a leisurely Sunday stroll
into a 13-10 one-car collision.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Philadelphia defense seized the day. Yes, a nobody
named Doug Pederson, the league's second-lowest-ranked quarterback,
huffed and puffed and finally blew down the Cowboys' house of
straw.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it was first-year Philly coach Andy Reid's first NFL win.
</P>
<P>
   But let's not quibble over the semantics. With coach Chan Gailey
leading the parade of lost sheep, the Cowboys kissed this game
away.
</P>
<P>
   They took a team that was almost willing to be beaten and handed
it a gift with all the trimmings. They took a no-class crowd, one
that cheered when a stretcher was wheeled out for Michael Irvin,
and sent them home happy.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Reid's first win may have been black magic. But he
outcoached Gailey, now, didn't he?
</P>
<P>
   ``To determine how good a team really is you have to go out
there when you're 3-0 and the Eagles are struggling,'' running back
Emmitt Smith said, standing outside of a Cowboys locker room that
seemed more resigned than angry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good teams go out there and do what they have to do. They
close a team out early. We've got to learn how to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys are good, but their ambitions have always been
loftier than that. And a team with Super Bowl ambitions cannot let
a mongrel like the Eagles bite it in the leg.
</P>
<P>
   A team with that kind of ambitions must take care of business.
It can't sit back and be satisfied with watching the punch-drunk,
punchless Eagles beat themselves. It can't think 10 points is
enough. It can't let a good, but not great, Philly defense dictate
its day.
</P>
<P>
   But that's exactly what Gailey did. The Cowboys never went for
the Philly jugular _ because, in large part, the play-calling never
went for the jugular.
</P>
<P>
   Once Irvin left the game, moreover, a pall seemed cast over the
Cowboys' bench. Which was understandable, to a degree. But the head
coach, of all people, has to bring his team's head back into focus.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey never did. In fact, he admitted, ``I don't even know what
happened the rest of that drive.''
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Gailey grumbled about his offense failing to
convert a third-and-two run up the middle in the game's final four
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's bad when you can't make two yards,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But what Gailey neglected to say was that he had also tried to
run it down the Eagles' throats on second-and-two _ with the same
result.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would not let us throw the ball deep,'' Gailey said,
explaining the day's other uninspired play-calling. ``We tried two
or three times.''
</P>
<P>
   A few moments later, quarterback Troy Aikman observed, ``They
did a nice job of getting under our intermediate stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   So what was it _ the deep stuff or the intermediate stuff? Or
was the problem the running stuff, considering the patch-quilt
offensive line and Smith's resultant modest second half?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have to look at the film,'' Aikman said.
</P>
<P>
   Say what? Week in and week out, without fail for eight seasons,
Aikman has stood in front of the cameras and notepads. And he has
never answered a question, to my recollection, with ``We're going
to have to look at the film.''
</P>
<P>
   The point is yesterday so discombobulated the Cowboys _ and
their head coach _ that they forgot what they came to do.
</P>
<P>
   They heard the crowd's cheers _ a new low, even for Philadelphia
_ as Irvin lay motionless on the turf, and, while it made the
Cowboys angry, they didn't respond. They heard the Philly fans boo
whenever Pederson took the field. They saw the banners, like the
one in the end zone that read, ``We want a refund.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Cowboys never could script an appropriate response.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they seemed to watch the clock like nervous schoolboyting for the 3 o'clock bell to ring. Maybe they hadn't done
their homework. Maybe the dog ate it.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the dog was named Philadelphia.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
