<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LYONS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRANGE THINGS HAPPEN IN PHILADELPHIA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ After he got over the disgusting sight of 66,000
fans cheering as his best friend lay motionless waiting for a
stretcher to carry him out of Veterans Stadium; and after he
learned that his best friend would be able to walk _ and most
likely play again _ Emmitt Smith could finally put a spin on a day
in which the bad news wasn't a 13-10 Cowboys loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have written the script to this,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   The moon and the stars always align so surreal for
Cowboys-Eagles games. There was Barry Switzer and the
fourth-and-one game here on a frozen December day in 1995. There
was Troy Aikman's end-zone pass intercepted and returned 104 yards
for an Eagles score on the last play of a game in 1996. And there
was Tommy Hutton bobbling the snap to what would have been a
chip-shot, game-winning field goal for the Eagles on a Monday night
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was yesterday, albeit a yesterday that was
overshadowed by frightening circumstances. As Irvin said he was
having problems moving after catching a pass and landing on his
head in the first quarter, you couldn't help but think of the Daryl
Stingleys and the Mike Utleys who suffered head and neck injuries
while playing and never walked again.
</P>
<P>
   Almost as sickening a sight were the fans here in the City of
Brotherly Shove, who hoorayed Irvin's predicament, and booed the
sight of Deion Sanders praying over his fallen friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disgusted me to death,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   That was ``ignorant and stupid,'' Sanders said.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin's scary moment wasn't the only ominous sign of things to
come here yesterday. The game was played in a steady drizzle and
you know what they say about Troy Aikman and the wet ball. Aikman
threw two interceptions and was incomplete on 18 of 39 pass
attempts. (Aikman, who has suffered at least two concussions on
this field, managed to avoid a third while playing behind an
offensive line that ended the game without two starters).
</P>
<P>
   On the same drive immediately following Irvin's injury, Smith,
who admitted that he was still ``filled with anger'' toward booing
Philadelphians, lost some of his focus and fumbled the ball away on
the Eagles' 1-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the game, center Mark Stepnoski and cornerback Kevin
Smith went down with back injuries. The sequence of events
compromised the Cowboys' ability to throw, run, and play pass
defense.
</P>
<P>
   But if you know how bad the Eagles are, then you know the
Cowboys still should have walked away with a 40-0 victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles have the worst offense in football. Before yesterday,
they hadn't scored an offensive touchdown since the first quarter
of the first game of the season, a span of 15 quarters. Starting
quarterback Doug Pederson was so unsure of himself after the club's
loss at New York last week that he suggested benching himself for
rookie Donovan McNabb might not be a bad idea.
</P>
<P>
   For three quarters yesterday, Pederson looked like the man who
should be benched. He wildly overthrew and underthrew his
receivers. The passes that did get to the target were dropped. By
the end of the third quarter, the Eagles had more punts (8) than
points (0) or first downs (4).
</P>
<P>
   But then a funny thing happened on the way to the Cowboys' first
4-0 start in four years. Chan Gailey shut down the Cowboys
playbook, calling conservative plays instead of stretching the
Eagles defense. Then Eagles halfback Duce Staley started running
like Wilbert Montgomery and Pederson started completing passes
longer than an eyelash.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles finally put together three consecutive scoring drives
that netted 13 fourth-quarter points against a Cowboys defense that
couldn't make a play in the clutch. The winning score came on a
Pederson pass to Charles Johnson, who beat zone coverage on the
side vacated by Kevin Smith's injury.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Emmitt Smith emerged from the losing locker room with
a prayer for Irvin and a smile for the media. He wasn't willing to
make any excuses, and he definitely didn't believe that ghosts
float around during Cowboys-Eagles games.
</P>
<P>
   Or did he?
</P>
<P>
   ``...something weird always happens,'' he said, ``though you
don't have to necessarily believe in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Believe what?
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
