<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BATTERIES-POWER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BATTERY-MAKERS SCRAMBLING TO SATE THE GROWING HUNGER FOR  MORE
POWER &HT;       By HENRY NORR
 &HT;    c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When IBM's mobile computing division tallied the
results of a recent customer-satisfaction survey, one message came
through loud and clear: Users of the company's ThinkPad notebooks
want longer _ much longer _ battery life. In fact, they raised the
issue more than twice as often as any other in the survey.
</P>
<P>
   That's a source of some frustration for Fran O'Sullivan, vice
president for development at the IBM mobile group in Raleigh, N.C.
As laptop computers go, the ThinkPad has a reputation for pretty
good battery life, and O'Sullivan said the battery's capacity has
increased 15 to 20 percent during the past year alone.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, as fast as the company improves its batteries,
the extra energy is eaten up by larger screens, more power-hungry
processors, and new features like DVD drives and wireless modems.
</P>
<P>
   Technically, it would be easy enough to satisfy the unrelentingdemand for more power _ by building in bigger, heavier batteries.
But IBM's research also shows that customers aren't willing to make
that trade-off.
</P>
<P>
   The result: a growing ``satisfaction gap.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What customers demand in terms of battery life is increasing,
and we're not reaching their expectations,'' O'Sullivan told
executives and engineers at Power '99, an annual battery-industry
conference held last week in Santa Clara, Calif. And the problem
isn't going away anytime soon: IBM expects nearly to double the
capacity of its batteries during the next two years, yet it reckons
that power demand will grow at roughly the same rate.
</P>
<P>
   Notebook computer-makers are hardly alone: Manufacturers of
cellular phones, digital cameras, personal digital assistants and
every other portable electronic gizmo are in the same boat.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it's a painful paradox: High-tech manufacturers boast
that they move at warp speed, yet the battery industry still lives,
to a remarkable extent, on discoveries made decades ago. While
high-tech building blocks like microprocessors and hard drives
double in capability every year or two, battery-makers count
improvements of 10 or 15 percent per year as good &LR;   &LR; progress.
</P>
<P>
   The norm is still a 20-year lag between battery-related
scientific advances and mainstream products based on them,
according to Christina Lampe-Onerrud, associate director of
battery-industry studies at Arthur D. Little Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Some high-tech gadgets, such as most Palm organizers and Diamond
Multimedia's Rio line of MP3 digital music players, rely on
alkaline batteries, the current standard in consumer electronics.
</P>
<P>
   But for more complex devices, alkalines are rarely a good
solution despite their low per-unit cost, universal availability
and relatively benign impact on the environment. The main problem
is that devices like notebook computers, digital cameras and cell
phones devour power so quickly that users would need to replace
alkaline batteries every few days, if not hours.
</P>
<P>
   For such devices, there's an obvious need for rechargeable
batteries. While rechargeable alkalines have become common in
recent years, they're usually good for only 10 to 20 recharges, and
as they're charged and drained, their energy density _ power per
unit of weight _ declines rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, they, too, would end up being an expensive
hassle in most high-tech products.
</P>
<P>
   That's forced tech manufacturers into a sometimes frantic search
for alternatives. Four solutions have come to the fore over the
past decade. &UR;  &LR; Today, lithium-ion is most popular in most high-tech
applications, but the other technologies still are in wide use.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the battery industry and its high-tech
customers eagerly have been looking ahead to a fifth rechargeable
technology, generally known as lithium polymer. Technically, it
should be called lithium  &LR; ion  &LR; polymer because it's really just a
variant of existing lithium ion technology; the main difference is
that it replaces the liquid electrolyte used in lithium ion
batteries with a gel.
</P>
<P>
   Because the gel is less flammable, the change will let
manufacturers create batteries with thinner walls and less
expensive safety circuitry than current lithium ion cells require.
The new material also will make it possible to design
custom-contoured and ultra-thin batteries _ Sharp Electronics
recently announced a laptop with a flat lithium polymer battery so
thin that it fits behind the computer screen.
</P>
<P>
   Not too far into the 21st century, ``we might even see lithium
polymer batteries so thin and flexible, they could be used as
wallpaper or printed on,'' said Lampe-Onerrud. It's not clear who
needs wallpaper batteries, but another futuristic possibility
sounds more promising: ``We could even have batteries built into
clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   Some other experts are more skeptical, though. ``Whatever
chemicals you use, whether it's polymer or anything else, how much
power you can get out of a battery depends on how much active
material there is,'' said Barry Huret, a longtime consultant to the
battery industry. ``If you make it thinner, you lose active
material. Or you have to make it wider or longer, but is that
really something people want?''
</P>
<P>
   Even in standard shapes, lithium polymer batteries have turned
out to be more difficult to manufacture than expected, and the
technology is just starting to reach the consumer market. But in
recent months, the major manufacturers have declared that they're
ready to begin volume production. The technology is especially
appealing in the cell phone industry, where thin is always in, and
in recent weeks, a slew of companies have announced new high-end
phones with lithium polymer batteries.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, at last week's Power '99 conference, several speakers
proclaimed the year 2000 as ``the Year of Lithium Polymer.''
</P>
<P>
   But no one pretends that lithium polymer, at least in its
current form, will deliver what high-tech developers like IBM's
O'Sullivan want most: batteries that deliver significantly more
power without requiring extra space, weight and expense. Lab tests
of new polymer variants do show ``very high capacity,''
Lampe-Onerrud said. But since the chemistry on which the initial
polymer products are based is the sameas that in current lithium
ion cells, the transition won't produce any dramatic increase in
energy density.
</P>
<P>
   In Sharp's new lithium polymer laptop, for example, the company
had to make an important compromise to make the new battery viable:
It adopted a passive-matrix display, which saves power compared
with the active-matrix used in most quality notebooks today, but
doesn't match the latter in image quality.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, most observers agree, no magic bullet that would
satisfy the ever-growing power demands of high-tech devices is even
on the horizon. That doesn't discourage Lampe-Onerrud, who expects
an accelerating series of incremental improvements in rechargeable
technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot will happen in the next five to 10 years, more than in
the last five or 10,'' she said. More companies and countries will
enter the market, bringing new insights and innovations. Instead of
four or five chemical combinations for rechargeable batteries,
there could be 20, each appropriate for different types of
products.
</P>
<P>
   Again, however, other experts are not as sanguine. ``There's no
new electrolytic couple (combination of materials) that I've heard
of that will replace lithium ion in the foreseeable future,'' said
Huret. ``What I heard people saying (at the Power '99 conference)
is, `We're going to have to learn to live with what we have.'''
</P>
<P>
   O'Sullivan agrees: IBM projects that progress in battery-energy
density will level off after 2001. That's a scary prospect because
there's no sign that customers suddenly will lose their hunger for
new features, better performance and longer battery life in the new
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of that prognosis, researchers are looking far and
wide for new approaches. Scientists at MIT have been studying the
possibility of using body heat or the motion of users' fingers as
they type to generate electricity. Seiko last week announced a
watch powered by body heat, but so far, no one's claiming to be
able to power a computer or phone that way.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, the most likely scenario for the next decade seems
to be more of the same: Manufacturers of portable high-tech
products, whipsawed by demands for more features and longer battery
life, will continue to engage in a difficult balancing act. And
just like today, users who insist on taking the latest bells and
whistles on the road will be well advised to keep an eye on the
power gauge and a backup battery close at hand.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
