<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-10 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2689 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s BC-NY-YANKS-METS-1STLD-W     10-10 1123
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-YANKS-METS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES FANS AND METS FANS: MUTUAL DENIGRATION SOCIETY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (CORRECTS ``taken'' to ``take'' in 11th graf)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT22 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic
is being sent to NYT graphics clients. Nonsubscribers may make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By DAVID M. HALBFINGER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This is the time when grown-ups in blue plastic
helmets look perfectly normal on crowded city streets. When
friends, lovers, family members and co-workers find themselves
discovering ugly things about one another. When perfect strangers
launch into passionate debates at the sight of the letters N and Y.
</P>
<P>
   New York hasn't experienced this in a long, long, long time.
</P>
<P>
   It's still too early to count on a Subway Series. (You don't
want to jinx it, do you?) There are details to take care of in
Atlanta and Cleveland _ or better still, in Boston. But the buzz is
building with every lopsided Yankees and heart-stopping Mets win.
</P>
<P>
   And so is the anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Valentino, 24, was passing through midtown Manhattan on
his way from Glen Ridge, N.J., to Shea Stadium on Friday afternoon,
when he ran into Karrien Bell, 22, a student from Newark. At any
other time, these two would have hardly noticed each other. But
Valentino was wearing an old Mets helmet he had dug out of his
closet and worn every game day for the last two weeks. Bell was in
a new, bright blue Yankees jacket and a turned-around Yankees cap.
And neither man was in a rush.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, this tiny piece of West 40th Street and Broadway might
as well have been a corner tavern and these two friendly old
antagonists. ``The most popular ride is the bandwagon,'' Valentino
was saying, sneering through his smile.
</P>
<P>
   Bell denied being a front-runner, saying he simply preferred the
better team. Then, candidly, he voiced his deepest fear: ``If the
Mets face the Yankees in the Series, they're going to win,'' he
said. ``They're more hungry.''
</P>
<P>
   That didn't make Valentino feel much better. ``If they don't,''
he said, ``I'll probably dig a hole and bury myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing would be better for New York, the saying goes, than a
New York-New York championship matchup. But nothing would be worse
for the egos of more New Yorkers. Because one team would have to
lose.
</P>
<P>
   Just listen to anybody wearing a blue hat.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't deny the Yankees are a fantastic team,'' said
Christine Bracco, 27, a lifelong Mets fan from Bensonhurst,
Brooklyn, who cheered herself hoarse in the mezzanine at Shea after
Todd Pratt's home run Saturday that won the Mets a trip to Atlanta.
``But the fans they have take that for granted. They just are so
arrogant. You've got all your Wall Street boys with cigars and
suits, bragging like they've been fans for life. And they don't
even acknowledge that other teams exist.''
</P>
<P>
   If Ms. Bracco sounds hurt, her wounds are fresh. Her
ex-boyfriend, Michael Farkas, is just as avid a Yankees fan. The
two parted company amicably last week, but neither denied that
their escalating baseball rivalry had been a factor in their
breakup.
</P>
<P>
   Farkas, a Brooklyn homicide prosecutor who so despises the Mets
that he rooted for the Boston Red Sox in the 1986 World Series,
says he cannot decide who are worse, the Mets or their fans. ``I
can't get over their pretty-boy attitude of the '80s,'' he said.
``I have nothing to hate about them now, except for their decrepit
stadium and ugly pastel colors. But if you grow up with hate, it's
hard to let it go. I really saw the Mets bandwagon take off in the
1980s, and that flew in the face of the history and tradition of
the Yankees. It was demeaning to baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   As any fan will explain, there are serious differences between
the followers of New York's two contenders _ beyond the fact that
Shea Stadium remains a nice place to take the kids, while the
loudest louts in the loges at Yankee Stadium have lowered the
overall tone nearly to the level of the Bleacher Creatures.
</P>
<P>
   Mets fans, in the unanimous, unbiased opinion of tens of Yankees
fans interviewed this week, are a pathetic bunch of loser punks who
will never get over their insecurities, just as their forebears
never got over their misplaced loyalty to the Brooklyn Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to put them in their place, sweep them and get them out
of my hair, once and for all,'' said Vinnie Minichello, 39, an
accountant from Brooklyn who wore full-dress Yankees regalia to
Shea Stadium on Friday night, taunted everyone around him in the
upper deck, yet somehow made it out alive. (``He's adopted,'' his
father, Frank, kept telling people apologetically, and
untruthfully.)
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Yankees fans, according to a similarly exhaustive
informal survey of Mets fans, are a big-headed blight on the Bronx
who lack the constitution, heart and humanity to root for an
underdog, the common sense to be repulsed by the designated hitter
rule, and the adventurousness to value the unexpected over the
routine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too easy to be a Yankee fan,'' said Peter Badini, 53, of
Bedford Hills, N.Y., who lingered at Shea with his son after the
last game of the regular season. ``Five-nothing, 6-0, 7-0 _ it's
boring. With the Mets, it's always an uh-oh.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the fans' self-images are rich with fantasy: Mets fans see
themselves as monks, willing to endure lasting deprivation for the
sake of a future reward _ ``It makes the victories that much
sweeter,'' Badini said _ while Yankees fans like to think they are
priests guarding the flame of an ancient tradition, that they are
winners just as much as their team. It's enough to make you wonder
who's hiding what.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, people read into their chosen teams exactly what they
want, or need. So David Rosenthal, whose older brother was a
Yankees fan, needed no other reason as a boy to root for the
fledgling Mets. Coming of age in the 1960s, he began to see the
youthful Mets as the counterculture's answer to the conservative,
corporate Yankees, who at the time were owned by CBS. The Mets had
heart, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Yankees hurt the ones they loved,'' said Rosenthal, now
the publisher of Simon &AMP; Schuster's trade division. ``They fired
Casey, they fired Yogi after they won the pennant in '64, then they
traded Roger Maris to the Cardinals, they traded Moose Skowron to
the Dodgers. The Yankees treated the ones we loved with an air of
disrespect, and that was hideous. And the Mets continued to employ
losers past their prime, which was endearing. They hired Yogi, Duke
Snider and Willie Mays in their senescence. So those of us who grew
up in the '60s got to live in the '50s all over again.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Richard Wessler, 63, a Yankees fan who grew up in
the Midwest, suggests that people who root for the Mets because
they prefer an underdog are more likely underachievers themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of this comes from the immigrant experience, where the
immigrants are the underdogs initially, and then in a generation or
two, they make it and become winners,'' he said. ``But some people
make it better than others. The Yankees have got it made, year
after year. It's easier to identify with them if you've got it
made, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Wessler, the chairman of the psychology department at Pace
University, favors the blue-collar/white-collar analogy. Suggest
that watching the Yankees win all the time is boring, for example,
and he says: ``Like being a millionaire's boring. We're like
spoiled children. We're used to getting what we want: victory.''
</P>
<P>
   He adds: ``Like a good working man, the Mets are sometimes fully
employed, but sometimes they're completely out of work. If you've
made it to a full lunch pail most of the time, but you're still a
lunch pail kind of guy, you're probably still identifying with the
underdog, and maybe feeling a little sorry for yourself that you
haven't made it to the upper echelons, to the elite. Met fans are
dealing with more uncertainty in life.''
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, there are some hoary cliches, and some red herrings,
at work here. It may be convenient right now to deride the Yankees
as machinelike and invincible and lionize the Mets as thrilling
underdogs. But to do so overlooks the Yankees' long absences from
postseason play, from 1965 to 1975 and from 1982 to 1994 _ absences
during which the Mets played in three World Series and won two, the
second as the dominant power in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The supposedly deep-rooted personalities of the two teams have
changed significantly every few years, as well. What resemblance
did the hapless Mets of the early 1960s bear to the swaggering men
about town of the late 1980s, or the dysfunctional firecracker
throwers of the early 1990s? How do today's Yankees, admired for
their sublimated egos, in any way look like the creatures that
inhabited the Bronx Zoo of the 1970's?
</P>
<P>
   What was convenient about those asynchronous swings was that
whichever team did well had the New York stage all to itself. And
fans of the other team could lick their wounds in the shadows, the
Mets' by invoking the wait-till-next-year motto of the old Dodgers,
the Yankees' by reminding themselves and everyone around them of
their team's past glories.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, there is nowhere to hide.
</P>
<P>
   So we have every self-loving Yankees fan idolizing and
identifying with Joe Torre, that supremely confident Buddha of the
bench, conqueror of cancer, tamer of Steinbrenner, owner of two
World Series rings, coolly and methodically and all but inexorably
leading his men toward a third.
</P>
<P>
   And we have every self-loathing Mets fan simultaneously hating
and loving Bobby Valentine, that headline-grabbing,
costume-wearing, bubble-blowing manager with exactly nothing to his
credit thus far but longevity, the only man jumpier than Turk
Wendell, outpacing and outthinking and outblundering his opponents
but somehow still inspiring his men to survive.
</P>
<P>
   If all this keeps up, the ultimate New York psychodrama could
start at Shea Stadium on Saturday, Oct. 23.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
