<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-10 22:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2691 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-AIRLINE-CHECKIN-SFCHR     10-10 1099
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINE-CHECKIN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
AIRLINE'S HIGH-TECH CHECK-IN &HT;       By BENNY EVANGELISTA
 &HT;    c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Before flying from San Jose to Portland, Ore.,
last month, Kathy Bloom got a taste of what airline passengers may
see in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   Bloom, a training manager for Santa Clara (Calif.) semiconductor
company IDT Inc., was in Salinas, Calif., visiting a plant on the
afternoon of her Alaska Airlines flight from San Jose International
Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving Salinas, Bloom hopped on to a company computer,
logged on to the Internet, checked herself in for the flight and
printed out her own boarding pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I just took that with me to the airport, and I didn't
have to wait in line,'' Bloom said. ``I just walked up to the gate.
I thought it was slick.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, passengers like Bloom also might be able to print
out their own baggage tags from a PC, send the luggage through a
sophisticated bomb-detection scanner at the airport and board the
plane without having to stand in line or talk to an airline ticket
agent.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's the vision of Alaska Airlines executives, who
are dreaming up and testing a wide variety of high-tech gadgets to
help speed passengers on and off planes.
</P>
<P>
   Using technology to automate processing passengers might be how
the airline industry deals with an increasing volume of traffic and
long lines. The number of passengers carried by U.S. airlines is
expected to grow from 614.2 million in 1998 to about 1 billion by
2010.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't just expand ticket counters and add more space for
the queue,'' said Ed White, vice president of customer service for
Alaska Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Alaska, a pioneer in electronic ticketing, is testing the first
online check-in system on a select group of employees of IDT Inc.,
which racks up frequent-flier miles by sending people between its
headquarters and a chip-fabrication plant in the Portland suburb of
Hillsboro.
</P>
<P>
   Alaska says the test has proven to be successful. It hopes to
make the service available to all customers as soon as next week
(week of October 17).
</P>
<P>
   Alaska's online check-in program works like this: A passenger
who already has purchased an electronic ticket online, through a
ticket agent or over the phone logs on to Alaska's Web site from a
home or office computer.
</P>
<P>
   The passenger types in an e-ticket confirmation number and
answers the standard questions required by the FAA about whether he
received something from a stranger to carry on board or left any of
his own luggage unattended. Online check-in can be done only on the
day of the flight.
</P>
<P>
   The passenger then prints out a boarding pass and brings it to
the gate. The customer still must produce a picture identification
card, but the boarding pass has a bar code that verifies the seat
assignment in Alaska's computers.
</P>
<P>
   Alaska uses the same system for 250 self-service check-in kiosks
installed at airport terminals the carrier serves, including San
Francisco, Oakland (Calif.) and San Jose. Other airlines like
American, Delta and Continental also employ automatic check-in
machines.
</P>
<P>
   Online or kiosk check-in works if the passenger only has
carry-on baggage, but Alaska also is testing a new self-service
baggage check system in Anchorage. There, passengers also print out
their own bar-coded baggage tags and place their luggage in a
bomb-detection machine, which is monitored by an attendant.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the Federal Aviation Administration has given Alaska the
green light. FAA spokeswoman Kirsti Dunn said safety inspectors who
have reviewed Alaska's plans say the carrier meets all FAA
requirements because its agents still look at passengers' photo
IDs. And luggage still must be scanned and matched to the
passengers boarding the plane.
</P>
<P>
   Alaska also is testing a system to keep photos or fingerprints
of frequent fliers in a company database, so those passengers
wouldn't need to fumble with a driver's license at the gate.
</P>
<P>
   One longtime airline consumer advocate questioned the benefit of
using high-tech systems, which essentially shift the work of
airline employees to the passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Perkins, consumer affairs advocate for the American Society
of Travel Agents, said, ``The idea of cutting down the amount of
time you spend in line is a worthwhile one.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, ``The idea of improving the passengers' lot by
having the passenger do more of the work is not necessarily a step
in the right direction. Sure, it'd be even better if you flew the
plane yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   A better low-tech solution might be to have more efficient
curbside baggage service, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But not every airline believes that customers want more
self-service gadgets, and so far, no other carrier has plans to
start online or self-service baggage check-in.
</P>
<P>
   United Airlines, in fact, has done away with its automated
check-in terminals because customers just were not using them.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the airline is trying more ``low-tech'' choices, like
an extra line at the ticket counter for frequent fliers, said
United spokesman Matt Triaca. ``We've found that's what our
customers have preferred.''
</P>
<P>
   United did test a high-tech mobile check-in cart, about the size
of a hot-dog cart but ``sleeker,'' which helped ticket agents
reduce long lines at San Francisco International.
</P>
<P>
   ``It worked so well, we're putting them in at all of our hub
airports,'' Triaca said.
</P>
<P>
   Perkins also said some airports were wary of the security
problems raised by allowing people to check in their own baggage or
print their own boarding passes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's a loophole, someone's going to try to exploit that
loophole,'' Perkins said.
</P>
<P>
   And, Perkins asked, will airlines try to shift the blame for
lost self-tagged baggage onto the passenger?
</P>
<P>
   White, who said the bar codes help Alaska Airlines keep better
track of baggage, said not all the new gadgets the airline has
tried have worked, such as a key-chain device that stored passenger
data and a wrist-mounted bar-code scanner for baggage handlers.
</P>
<P>
   But passengers could, in the future, be using wireless palm-top
devices to beam their ticket information into the airline
reservation systems.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, new airline technology is inevitable, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not about trying to automate the airport and eliminate
people,'' White said. ``This will take care of the simple and
routine transactions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are still going to be people who need interaction with
our folks,'' he said. ``This is giving our people more time'' to
deal with those transactions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
