<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOMASH-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
MORNINGSTAR OFFERS STOCK RATINGS
<TEXT>
<P>
   By HARRY DOMASH
</P>
<P>
   C. &LR; dk,1,18  &LR; Free service analyzes &QL; 
financial statements &QL; 
of public companies
</P>
<P>
   &LR; rt wrapper i  &LR; I n our heart of hearts, we know we should
examine a company's financial statements before making an
investment decision. Nevertheless, I'm sure most of us would rather
go to the dentist than dig into balance sheets and income
statements.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; x  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  Now Morningstar is making us an offer we can't refuse. They will
do the green eyeshade work for us, for free.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; uncx  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  Although Morningstar of Chicago ( &LR; www.morningstar.com &LR; ) is best
known for its mutual fund ratings, I doubt many investors realize
that the ratings are computer generated. There is no human
intervention in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Morningstar is applying that same principle to rating individual
stocks. Its computer analyzes just about every publicly traded
company's financial statements and gives the results in a format we
all understand: grades A through F.
</P>
<P>
   I'll use Tommy Hilfiger as an example, and compare Morningstar's
grades to what you would have seen if you actually had dug into the
financial statements. Then we'll compare Morningstar's grades for
Tommy Hilfiger with the grades for Sears.
</P>
<P>
   I used Market Guide ( &LR; www.marketguide.com &LR; ) as my source for
financial statements and related information.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; x  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  Tommy Hilfiger is a well-known producer of casual clothing, shoes
and related merchandise. Its stock has suffered in recent months
(down 32 percent from its high on May 13) as market analysts have
forecast a slowdown in the retail sector.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; uncx  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  Start by entering the ticker symbol or the first few letters of
the company name into the Quotes and Reports box on Morningstar's
home page. (If you entered the company name, click on the ticker
symbol.)
</P>
<P>
   Then click Snapshot on the menu on the left to display
Morningstar's analysis of Tommy Hilfiger. Company Basics describes
Hilfiger's business in considerable detail and is more interesting
than the usual cryptic outline.
</P>
<P>
   Before we get into Hilfiger's grades, look at the listing for
Stock Type, just below Industry and Sector on the right. Analysts
say companies go through stages as they progress from speculative
startup to maturity. Morningstar places each company in one of
eight parts of the cycle: speculative growth, aggressive growth,
classic growth, slow growth, cyclicals, hard asset or distressed.
You can use this stock-type rating to evaluate how a stock meets
your overall investment needs. For instance, you might find that
your portfolio is overweighted with speculative stocks.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of DOMASH11 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Morningstar classifies Tommy Hilfiger as an aggressive growth
company, meaning it has rapidly growing sales and earnings. The
rating makes sense because Hilfiger's sales and earnings rose, on
average, 51 percent, and 31 percent annually during the past three
years.
</P>
<P>
   Morningstar's Style Box is another aid for evaluating the
suitability of a stock. It gives you company size (small, medium or
large) and valuation (value, blend or growth) based on
price/earnings and price/book ratios. Morningstar classifies
Hilfiger as ``medium value,'' meaning it is a value-priced,
medium-size company.
</P>
<P>
   The Morningstar grades are just below the Style Box. Morningstar
grades each company in four categories: growth, profitability,
financial health and valuation.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how Morningstar graded Hilfiger in these categories:
</P>
<P>
   &LR; x  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; rh1  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; _ &UR; Growth: &LR;  A+. Morningstar looks at historical sales growth over
the past five years. Higher is better, and companies with
consistent, increasing growth rates score highest. Morningstar gave
Hilfiger the highest possible grade, an A+.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; uncx  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  When I looked at Hilfiger's growth using Market Guide, however, I
noticed that sales growth had slowed in the June quarter.
</P>
<P>
   When I asked about this, Morningstar said ``the bulk of the
grade is focused on the longer-term, just because there's so much
quarter-to-quarter fluctuation.''
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I think ignoring the latest quarter is a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; x  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; rh1  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; _ &UR; Profitability: &LR;  A. Morningstar uses Return on Equity, a measure
of earnings compared with shareholder's equity, to measure
profitability. As in sales growth, higher is better, and a
consistent rising trend of ROE adds to the rating. Again,
Morningstar appears to give most weight to long-term results
because Hilfiger's latest reported ROE, according to Market Guide,
is 19.3 percent _ well below its 23.4 percent five-year average.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; rh1  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; _ &UR; Financial Health &LR; : A_. Morningstar uses current levels and
trends of financial leverage (assets/equity), cash in the bank and
cash flows to rate financial health. It's not clear how these
factors are used to come up with a grade, so we can't tell if the
June quarter is included.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of DOMASH11 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  However, Market Guide says Hilfiger has $235 million in the bank,
$180 million of free cash flow in the last fiscal year, and
reasonable debt, so it's easy to see how the company earned a high
grade for financial health.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; rh1  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; _ &UR; Valuation: &LR;  A_. Morningstar calculates fair value by adding the
current value of estimated future earnings to the book value and
then adjusting the result downward, based on how likely the company
is to achieve the predicted earnings. The valuation grade compares
the current stock price with the calculated fair value. Undervalued
stocks get the best grades.
</P>
<P>
   Using data as of October 1, Morningstar said Hilfiger was about
20 percent undervalued because the then-current $28.19 stock price
was about 20 percent below its $35.09 calculated fair value.
</P>
<P>
   For comparison, Stock Selector ( &LR; www.stockselector.com &LR; ) came up
with a fair value for Hilfiger of $63.73 using the PEG method
described in our August 30 column.
</P>
<P>
   Now let's see how Morningstar grades Sears, a company beset by
problems. Sales are running below last year's, earnings growth
averaged less than 3 percent annually for the past three years, and
the company is shaking up management. The stock is down more than
45 percent from its July 1998 high. Morningstar's grades for Sears
are: Growth D+, Profitability C+, Financial Health C and Valuation
B.
</P>
<P>
   Morningstar's grades make it easy to see that, based on
fundamental factors, Tommy Hilfiger is in much better shape than
Sears.
</P>
<P>
   Morningstar's Honor Roll lists companies with A grades in each
of the four categories. To see the list, click Stocks on the top
menu bar, select Stock Selector, then click Preset Screens and
finally, select the Honor Roll from the drop-down menu.
</P>
<P>
   I may quibble with Morningstar's underweighting of the most
recent results, but it's giving us an analysis _ at no charge _
that most investors don't have either the time or the experience to
perform.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; pu,domash &LR;  &QL; 
Harry Domash lives in Aptos and publishes the Winning Investing
newsletter. You can read his columns at  &LR; www.winninginvesting &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; .com &LR;  or contact him at  &LR; hdomash &LR; winninginvesting.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COL. 3 of DOMASH11 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  uncx &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
COL. 4 of DOMASH11 () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-10-99 2237EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991010.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-10 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2695 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-DOMASH-COLUMN-SFCHRON     10-10 1137
