u p BC-LA-GOV-RACE-NYT &LR;      10-10 1287
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-GOV-RACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MYSTERY IN LOUISIANA GOVERNOR'S RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Ever since he began running for a second term,
Gov. Mike Foster of Louisiana has been dogged by one political
embarrassment and mix-up after another.
</P>
<P>
   At times, he says, he wonders whether running for office is
worth all the grief, especially when he could be down on some bayou
in Cajun country, where he grew up, hunting birds instead of votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people want me out of office,'' he said this week
while campaigning in New Orleans. ``A lot of them enjoy all this
grief I'm taking.''
</P>
<P>
   It is no exaggeration to say that the governor is taking some
political grief. What is perhaps more interesting is that despite
it, he remains a heavy favorite to win on Election Day, Oct. 23.
</P>
<P>
   That probably says as much about how the political game is
played in Louisiana as anything.
</P>
<P>
   The more curious and outlandish twists a contest takes here, the
more voters seem to like it, especially if there is a whiff of
corruption or dark dealing, real or imagined. As they say in
southern Louisiana, that's lagniappe, a little something extra
added to the recipe or moment at hand.
</P>
<P>
   Foster's grief began with an incident in which the governor, a
Republican, ended up acknowledging that in his first run for
office, in 1995, he secretly bought the former Ku Klux Klan leader
David Duke's list of contributors and supporters for a whopping
$150,000.
</P>
<P>
   Then, just as the furor seemed to be dying down, along came a
federal grand jury and the state Ethics Board, asking a lot of
questions about the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The Ethics Board ordered the governor to pay a $20,000 fine for
not reporting the purchase as a campaign expenditure, but chose to
ignore accusations, denied by the governor, that what the $150,000
really bought was not access to supporters of a racist who is still
politically powerful but a promise by that racist not to jump into
the governor's race.
</P>
<P>
   The grand jury wanted to know, and apparently still is
pondering, whether Duke ducked paying taxes on the $150,000.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with Election Day just two weeks off, comes the strangest
and most curious campaign incident yet.
</P>
<P>
   A few days ago, several news organizations in Louisiana received
copies of an audio tape of a conversation the governor recently
held with a private investigator from New Orleans, Dwayne
Alexander. Who recorded the conversation and who distributed copies
of it remain a mystery, but neither the governor nor Alexander
questions the tape's authenticity.
</P>
<P>
   In the conversation, the governor, who has summoned Alexander to
his office, says he has learned that the investigator is ``spying''
on him. He demands to know who hired Alexander and why.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hired to do a job,'' the investigator replies
elliptically.
</P>
<P>
   Foster tells Alexander that spying on a governor is unwise and
warns, ``If you're doing it, I don't think it's to either one of
our best interests.'' He says he will turn the tables on anyone who
tries to ``mess'' with him and will have ``a lot of fun messing
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the governor suggests that Alexander become a ``double
agent.''
</P>
<P>
   The tape ends there. But Alexander has since said he refused to
become a double agent, considers the incident over and has gone
about other work.
</P>
<P>
   Federal, state and local investigators have said they see no
reason to become involved in the dispute, that it is strictly an
issue between the governor and Alexander.
</P>
<P>
   As the governor tells it, he was ``just talking with Alexander,
no threats, just fooling around with him, feeling him out, trying
to figure out what he was up to.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You always have to keep in mind that I've got a lot of
political enemies out there,'' Foster said on Wednesday while
talking to reporters on a visit to The Gambit Weekly, a local
tabloid.
</P>
<P>
   But probably he has nowhere near enough enemies to turn him out
of office on Oct. 23.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all his problems, the governor has a lot going for him
besides the forgiving nature of Louisiana voters. As a result, his
challengers _ there are 11 in all _ are having big trouble finding
political traction, including the strongest of the candidates, Rep.
William J. Jefferson, a five-term Democrat from Louisiana's 2nd
Congressional District, which includes most of New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Like the rest of the country, Louisiana, long beset by economic
difficulties, is now booming, and Foster is riding that boom. The
state's schools, among the nation's worst for many years, are now
beginning to improve, thanks in part to overhauls pushed by the
Foster administration. And the state's business and property
owners, once among the easiest targets in the land for personal
injury lawsuits, now enjoy extra safeguards, thanks to changes
pushed through by the governor.
</P>
<P>
   Also, this being Louisiana, the race is not being run like most
races for governor.
</P>
<P>
   There are no primaries, only an initial contest in which all
Democrats, Republicans and independents run together. If no
candidate emerges from that with a clear majority, there will be a
runoff on Nov. 20 between the top two finishers.
</P>
<P>
   Few polls have been taken and those that have carry the usual
caveat that they were conducted for candidates. But, significantly,
not one released thus far shows the governor with less than 50
percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Foster says he has ``high hopes'' he can win it all the first
time around.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson is banking on a runoff.
</P>
<P>
   A black candidate in a state whose population is 30 percent
black, Jefferson expects to get all of the black vote in the first
contest. He also predicts that he will pull enough white votes to
end up with 45 percent of the ballots cast, and he says he is
confident that the 10 other candidates together, even though little
known and short of money, will take 10 percent to 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The math on that leaves the governor with only 45 percent of
the vote at best, and that means a runoff,'' Jefferson said this
week after a campaign swing through the city. ``Come that runoff,
if I can hold my original vote and pick up roughly half of the
white vote that went to the 10 other guys, who will then be out of
the running, then I've got a real shot at being governor.''
</P>
<P>
   If Jefferson pulls it off, he will be the first black to win
statewide office in Louisiana since Reconstruction. If he falls
short, he can run again for Congress in 2000 or for mayor of New
Orleans _ his ultimate goal, many of his friends suggest.
</P>
<P>
   The big issues in the governor's race, as Jefferson sees them,
are the ``fiction'' that the governor has significantly improved
the state's schools and economy. Jefferson says that he has much of
the labor and teacher vote sewed up and that that would not be the
case if the governor had achieved all he said he had.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson says he expects to spend almost $1.5 million on his
campaign, about $1 million of it raised two weeks ago when
President Clinton came to town for a fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   The governor says he will spend about $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the state's political professionals and political
scientists foresee an easy Foster victory, maybe not a clean-cut
win on Oct. 23, but a victory eventually, and probably a big one.
</P>
<P>
   Edward F. Renwick, who follows state political developments as
director of the Loyola University Institute of Politics in New
Orleans, says that while a reasonable mathematical case can be made
that the governor will fall short of winning 50 percent of the vote
in a crowded field on Oct. 23, he is as certain to win a runoff as
anything can be certain in Louisiana politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bet on it,'' Renwick says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
