<DOCNO> NYT19991010.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-10 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2697 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CALIF-LIGHTHOUSE-DARK     10-10 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-LIGHTHOUSE-DARK-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THRIFT DIMS A WELL-LOVED LIGHTHOUSE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn:   Calif.)   (ART ADV: Photo NYT25 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By   PAUL ZIEBAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIA, Calif. _ All is peaceful and dark along this swath of
central California coastline nowadays. For some folks here,
especially those with bay-window views of the Pacific Ocean, that
just isn't right.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is not the quietude. What has dismayed some of the
residents in this small colony of antique shops, three hours south
of San Francisco, is the unpunctuated darkness that has swallowed
their shoreline each night since that sad day in April when the
rays from the Piedras Blancas lighthouse went dark.
</P>
<P>
   Until that day, the rhythmic implosions of Pacific surf in these
parts had been accompanied, every eight seconds for the past 124
years, by a churning arm of light broadcast from the top of the old
lighthouse, towering over a craggy outcropping 13 miles to the
north.
</P>
<P>
   But strong April winds this year wobbled the gears that gave
life to the 50-year-old beacon and its 25 nautical mile beam.
Instead of repairing it, the U.S. Coast Guard station in Alameda
chose to save $20,000 and simply replace the light's 20-foot
housing with a weaker light, a simple dome roughly the size of a
police siren, that engineers bolted to a four-foot pole atop the
90-foot lighthouse.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the change was inevitable. In this age of satellites and
geo-positioning software, when a mate can calculate his ship's
exact location by pushing a few numbers into a hand-held computer,
the lighthouses, like sextants, are now more essential to seafaring
nostalgia than navigation.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, to the dismay of some old souls around here, the new light
atop the whitewashed Piedras Blancas tower now blips every 10
seconds, instead of grinding around the dial, as it historically
has, every eight. Worse, the blip burrows through only 10 nautical
miles of Pacific darkness, three miles short of Cambria.
</P>
<P>
   Ask once whether they miss their light's nightly sweep, and
people in this unincorporated slice of San Luis Obispo County
shrug. Ask again, and deeper sentiments bubble up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The light is really beautiful _ was beautiful,'' recalled Hope
Fawl, a hotel receptionist who is a twilight regular on Cambria's
shoreline. ``It was a comforting feeling, something you looked for
when you went down to the beach.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Ms. Fawl, most people who live beyond the range of the
retooled lighthouse understand the Coast Guard's need to cut fiscal
corners, and they do not complain. But they seem to know that to
the government, lighthouses are like soda fountains, features from
another era that don't fit into American life anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's more to a lighthouse than just shining out to sea,''
said LaVerne McDonnell, 71, who has lived in Cambria, a retirement
community of 6,100 residents just off Highway 1, since 1988. ``It's
a beautiful thing, it's something that you feel, it's not just
visual. The light gives you an emotional connection with the
land,'' she added. ``It's there, it's solid, its always flashing.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite their regrets, Cambrians haven't registered any official
complaints about the new light, which during the day barely
registers with the naked eye of a driver along Highway 1 or Route
46. There's good reason, it seems, for the dearth of protests.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who lived up there in the '40s and '50s, they've
all died,'' said Shirley Bianchi, the county supervisor, referring
to the steep golden hills north of William Randolph Hearst's famous
castle, where the bovine community outnumbers the human one. ``If
it had been in the middle of Cambria, I'm sure there would have
been a huge uproar.''
</P>
<P>
   This brings up an interesting point. The original light and lens
atop Piedras Blancas - the name means ``white rocks'' in Spanish,
an apt tribute by early explorers to the avian residue that still
cakes the huge stone escarpments that rise from the water a few
yards off shore near San Simeon _ now rests inside a towering glass
carapace in downtown Cambria.
</P>
<P>
   The story of the French-made Fresnel lens, one of only three of
its kind in the United States, illuminates the widely held belief
that American lighthouses have always meant more to the community
they served than the bureaucrats that built them.
</P>
<P>
   When the Pacific Lighthouse Board installed the light in 1874,
the 8,400-pound cast-iron casing, with its eight panes of crystal
and glass refractors and kerosene wick was an engineering marvel
that could produce the light of 1.4 million candles, according to
the Cambria Historical Society.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kept in working order for decades by real live lighthouse
keepers, the light, which was switched to electricity in the 1930s,
performed more or less flawlessly until 1949, when either a storm
flooded it or something inside it cracked - the Historical Society
isn't sure which is accurate. Instead of repairing that lens, the
Coast Guard installed a new one and left the original for junk a
few yards from shore.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, the Cambria Lions Club rescued the rusted and
chipped lens and, with the Coast Guard's permission, mounted it on
a cement dais in town. Soon enough, Coast Guard officials in
Alameda, near Oakland, asked for the lens back. Giving away
government property, they explained, was not legal.
</P>
<P>
   ``While it was up there, they said, `We think we're not going to
give it back to you,' '' said Jerry McKinnon, 70, Cambria's
unofficial keeper of the lens, recalling local lore. ``We said,
`Why not? It's ours now.' They said it had an intrinsic value that
they wanted protected.''
</P>
<P>
   The two sides eventually struck a deal: the government would
permanently lend the lens to Cambria if someone would insure it for
$2 million. ``What was worthless in 1949 became priceless in
1951,'' McKinnon, a former Navy engineer's mate who fought in the
Korean War, noted with a hint of irony.
</P>
<P>
   So even if the Piedras Blancas light is no longer a daily
feature in Cambria, the old Fresnel lens, resting under its glass
dome on Main Street, will be.
</P>
<P>
   ``We turn it on if there's somebody around,'' said McKinnon,
``like anybody who says, `I'd like to see it turned on.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
