u a BC-NY-GOVERNOR-ETHICS-61     10-10 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GOVERNOR-ETHICS-615&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 FREE OFFICE FOR GROUP THAT PAID GOVERNOR'S FARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When the Hungarian-American Chamber of Commerce of
New York and New Jersey paid for two trips by New York Gov. George
Pataki to Hungary a few years ago, the group was based in suburban
New Jersey and listed its address as its president's home.
</P>
<P>
   These days, it has more distinctive quarters: a small office on
the 63rd floor of 1 World Trade Center.
</P>
<P>
   The chamber pays no rent to the building's owner, the Port
Authority of New York and New Jersey. The authority's executive
director, Robert E. Boyle, who was appointed by Pataki and is his
longtime friend, gave the furnished office to the chamber at no
charge. A similar space elsewhere in the trade center complex would
rent for roughly $6,000 a year without furniture.
</P>
<P>
   The authority also contributed $2,500 to help sponsor a trade
conference held by the chamber at the World Trade Center in 1997.
And it was not the only government agency connected to Pataki that
lent its name. The state's economic development arm also was a
sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   When the governor accepted the trips in 1995 and 1996, his aides
said, the chamber was a nonprofit outfit that promoted trade with
Hungary and had nothing to gain from the Pataki administration in
return.
</P>
<P>
   Michael McKeon, a spokesman for the governor, said Friday that
the governor had played no role in Boyle's decision to give the
chamber the office and the help with the conference. Asked whether
this assistance was linked to the trips, McKeon said, ``We are
pleased that we and the Port Authority have a good working
relationship with the chamber.''
</P>
<P>
   Monika Szarka-Elling, the chamber's president, did not respond
to two messages on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, the World Trade Center address was listed on the
chamber's World Wide Web site (www.haccusa.org) as its primary
office. After The New York Times reported last month that three
large corporations with interests before the governor had made
sizable donations to the chamber and had been involved with the
Hungary trips, the address was removed from the Web site. The only
address that now appears is a post office box in Far Hills, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Allen Morrison, a spokesman for the Port Authority, said the
authority had not offered free office space to other nonprofit
trade groups. He said Boyle gave the chamber the office _ which is
about 200 square feet _ because the chamber did valuable work, not
because it had paid for the governor's trips.
</P>
<P>
   He said Ms. Szarka-Elling approached Boyle in February 1998 and
asked for an office, and Boyle agreed. Morrison noted that the
office, which has no window, was in an area occupied by the Port
Authority staff, so even if the chamber did not use it, the
authority would not customarily rent it out. As such, the authority
did not lose money on the office, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would entertain similar requests from other nonprofit development groups,'' Morrison said, ``as long as the request is in
keeping with the Port Authority's mission to promote trade in the
Port of New York.''
</P>
<P>
   The state Ethics Commission, which permitted the chamber to pay
for Pataki's trips to Hungary after determining that the chamber
had no business before the governor, is now considering whether to
investigate the financing of the trips.
</P>
<P>
   Of the three corporations that contributed to the chamber, the
tobacco giant Philip Morris gave the most _ $10,000 shortly before
the first trip, $10,000 a few weeks before the second and another
$10,000 a year later. The other two corporations are Bristol-Myers
Squibb, the pharmaceuticals conglomerate, and Pepsico.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's aides have said that he and others in the
administration were not aware of the donations.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   If it can be determined that the corporate donations were
intended to pay for the trips, that could be a violation of state
ethics rules barring the governor and other administration
officials from accepting gifts of $75 or more from companies doing
business with the state, even through a third party.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear whether the chamber's use of the World Trade
Center office and the support for the trade conference would fall
under the ethics rules.
</P>
<P>
   The Port Authority is not technically part of the Pataki
administration and the state government. It is a bi-state agency
that Pataki controls jointly with Gov. Christie Whitman of New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The authority would not allow photographs of the office, which
has a desk, a circular table with four chairs, and a bookcase
adorned with a large photograph of Pataki.
</P>
</TEXT>
