<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CARDINAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATIGUED BY TREATMENTS, O'CONNOR MISSES A CATHEDRAL MASS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By   PAUL ZIELBAUER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Conceding the physical toll of radiation treatments,
Cardinal John O'Connor did not say Mass Sunday at St. Patrick's
Cathedral, but said in a message that he hoped to be back next
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been riding very high since my recent surgery, and
almost beginning to believe the nice things people have been saying
about me,'' the cardinal began a wry, five-paragraph missive read
to parishioners by Monsignor Jeremiah Monahan, the chancellor of
the archdiocese, at the 10:15 a.m. Mass.
</P>
<P>
   After entering Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center on Aug.
23, O'Connor underwent surgery to remove a small tumor on the
surface of his brain. After his release on Sept. 4, he began a
schedule of five weekly radiation treatments at the hospital to
minimize the possibility of the tumor recurring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly, but not without warning from the doctors, comes the
crash,'' he wrote. ``I used to think that I knew what it was to be
tired. After having received all but the final radiation treatment,
I now realize that at my most exhausted I could have run a marathon
compared with the tiredness that can come with radiation
treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   The cardinal is scheduled to undergo his final treatment Monday,
said Joseph Zwilling, a spokesman for the archdiocese.
</P>
<P>
   The cardinal ended his note to parishioners with a dash of
characteristic humor. ``Although my pride does not accept delays in
getting back to work fully, God always has the last word,'' he
wrote. ``I hope to see you next Sunday, when I feel as though I
will have reached my 300th birthday.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his fatigue, the cardinal has not completely put aside
his public schedule, Zwilling said.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 4, O'Connor spoke at a dedication ceremony for St.
Vincent's Comprehensive Cancer Center in Manhattan. On Oct. 5, he
met with Gov. George W. Bush of Texas at his archdiocese residence.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is working every day at his residence,'' Zwilling said.
``He is celebrating Mass every day at his residence. He is still
very much in control of the archdiocese.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
