series on Sunday. Pedro Martinez will not be available to pitch for
the Red Sox in a possible Game 5 of the Division Series on Monday
night against the Indians. (Jim Davis/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) CAMBRIA, Calif. -- Oct. 10, 1999 --
CALIF-LIGHTHOUSE-DARK, 10-10 -- Jerry McKinnon, keeper of a
traditional, cut-crystal lens no longer used at the lighthouse near
Cambria. Strong April winds this year wobbled the gears that gave
life to the 50-year-old beacon and its 25 nautical mile beam. What
has dismayed some of the residents in this small colony of antique
shops, is the unpunctuated darkness that has swallowed their
shoreline each night since that sad day in April when the rays from
the Piedras Blancas lighthouse went dark. (Paul Ziebauer/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) LARAMIE, Wyo. -- Oct. 10, 1999 -- WYO-GAYMURDER-TRIAL,
10-10 -- A visitor at the site where Matthew Shepard, a 21-year-old
political science student at the University of Wyoming, was left to
die after a brutal beating by two men a year ago. The brutality of
the crime turned it into a national rallying cry for hate-crime
laws to recognize a victim's sexual orientation, along with race,
religion and national origin, as a basis for prosecution. A federal
bill that would include sexual orientation is under consideration
by a House-Senate conference. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NABLUS, West Bank -- Oct. 10, 1999 --
PALESTINIANS-GUNS-2, 10-10 -- Bashar Abu Salhieh, a Palestinian
butcher, at home after a recent shootout at a wedding. The incident
has propelled Palestinian officials into a crackdown on thousands,
if not tens of thousands, of illegal weapons, as required by every
peace accord since 1995. (Rina Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- Oct. 10, 1999 -- BBO-YANKS-METS, 10-10 --
Patricia Moran, a New York Yankees fan, left, and Maribel Diaz, a
Mets fan, both from North Bergen, N.J., with posters supporting
their respective teams during a game between the two ball clubs at
Yankee Stadium in June. Nothing would be better for New York, the
saying goes, than a New York-New York championship matchup. But
nothing would be worse for the egos of more New Yorkers. Because
one team would have to lose. (Chang W. Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) WEST HARTFORD, Conn. -- Oct. 10, 1999 -- COLT-HANDGUNS,
10-10 --Steven Sliwa, Colt Manufacturing's chief executive, holds a
special edition of Colt's new Cowboy single action revolver in
March, 1999. More than 160 years after Sam Colt invented the
revolver, the company that bears his name is getting out of the
consumer handgun business. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) AL AMARI, West Bank. -- Oct. 10, 1999 --
PALESTINIANS-GUNS, 10-10 -- A Palestinian raises his weapon during
a part last week in the Al Amari refugee camp on the West Bank. A
recent shootout at a wedding has propelled Palestinian officials
into a crackdown on thousands, if not tens of thousands, of illegal
weapons, as required by every peace accord since 1995. (Rina
Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- Oct. 10, 1999 -- NY-SCHOOLKIDS-COMMUTE 10-10
-- Akshay Ganesh, 12, waits to board his bus for a ride to the
Staten Island ferry just after dawn as he begins his school day.
Throughout New York City, children as young as 10 are setting off
at daybreak, climbing aboard buses and squeezing onto the subway to
travel long distances to get to class. (Angel Franco/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) LONDON -- Oct. 10, 1999 -- BRITAIN-ONLINE-MEDIA, 10-10
-- Peter Martin, an editor at the Financial Times, on Southwark
bridge near his office. Martin aims to transform the paper's Web
site into a full-fledged Internet portal. (Carlos
Lopez-Barillas/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) BOSTON -- Oct. 10, 1999 -- WRITERS-ON-WRITING, 10-10 --
Saul Bellow in his Boston University office in April, 1997. Bellows
says that from the first years of being a fiction writer, he was
aware that his was a questionable occupation. (Ed Quinn/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) CHICAGO -- Oct. 10, 1999 -- BRIDGE-OPERA-REVIEW, 10-10
-- Juliana Rambaldi, left, Catherine Malfitano and Kim Josephson in
``A View From the Bridge.'' The opera, adapted by the Lyric Opera
of Chicago from the 1955 play by Arthur Miller, is an admirable and
often affecting work that convincingly solves the problem of
translating this play into an opera. (Todd Buchanan/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) CHICAGO -- Oct. 10, 1999 -- BRIDGE-OPERA-OPENING-2,
10-10 -- Arthur Miller, Arnold Weinstein and William Bolcom bow at
the opening of ``A View From the Bridge,'' an operatic adapatatino
from Miller's 1955 play. More than four years after it was
commissioned from the composer William Bolcom and the librettist
Arnold Weinstein, the creators and performers of the opera were
overjoyed at its debut. (Todd Buchanan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) CHICAGO -- Oct. 10, 1999 -- BRIDGE-OPERA-OPENING, 10-10
-- From left, Arthur Miller, Sidney Port, a donor, Catherine
Malfitano, William Mason, and Frank Galati after the premiere of
the Lyric Opera of Chicago's adaptation of Miller's 1955 play ``A
View From the Bridge.'' More than four years after it was
commissioned from the composer William Bolcom and the librettist
Arnold Weinstein, the creators and performers of the opera were
ebullient. (Todd Buchanan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) BOSTON -- Oct. 10, 1999 -- COLUMBUS-DAY-FLOATER, 10-10
-- Maureen Gordon Geary watches the Columbus Day parade from her
horse-drawn coach as she waited to go in to King's Chapel for her
wedding on Sunday. A little rain did not prevent marchers from
celebrating the discovery of America or Ms. Geary's march into her
nuptial. (Evan Richman/Boston Globe Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) ROTFRONT, Kyrgyzstan -- Oct. 10, 1999 --
KYRGYZSTAN-GERMANS-21, 10-10 -- Ethnic German parishioners of the
House of God Church walk down a road after services earlier this
month. The 300 ethnic Germans who live in this well-kept town are
part of one of the world's most rapidly disappearing ethnic
minorities: Germans in the former Soviet Union. (Staton Winter/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) ROTFRONT, Kyrgyzstan -- Oct. 10, 1999 --
KYRGYZSTAN-GERMANS-1, 10-10 -- Parishioners leave church after
services earlier this month. The 300 ethnic Germans who live in
this well-kept town are part of one of the world's most rapidly
disappearing ethnic minorities: Germans in the former Soviet Union.
(Staton Winter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) MASSAWA, Eritrea -- Oct. 10, 1999 -- ERITREA-ECON-2,
10-10 -- A group of men pass the time drinking tea outside a tea
house in the port city now idle because of the continuing war with
Ethiopia. The war has undermined the Eritrean economy, once a
bright spot on the continent. (James Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) KEREN, Eritrea -- Oct. 10, 1999 -- ERITREA-ECON-1, 10-10
-- A barber with a client at a shop inland from Asmara in late
August. War with neighboring Ethiopia has already begun undermining
the Eritrean economy, once a bright spot on the continent, and the
longer it drags out, the harder it will be for the nation to
recover. (James Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 10, 1999 -- BRAZILE-PROFILE, 10-10 --
Donna Brazile, who was just named Vice President Al Gore's new
campaign manager, during an interview last week. At 39, Ms. Brazile
is not the sort of person you might meet once at a party and then
not remember when you ran into her again in an airport nine years
later. When Matt Drudge recently referred to her as a ``smear
queen,'' she remarked, ``Well, he got the queen part right. I am a
diva.'' (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) GALLUP, N.M. -- Oct. 10, 1999 -- NAVAJO-CODE-WARRIORS-3,
10-10 --Sam Billison, right, president of the Navajo Code Talkers
Association, shows photographs to fellow members which were
presented by a Marine veteran from Minnesota following a parade.
During World War II, hundreds of Navajos were sent to the South
Pacific to use their language in creating secret codes the Japanese
could not break. Their mission has been a secret for years. However
this weekend, some of the Navajo veterans reunited to tell their
stories at a reservation in Gallup, N.M. (Monica Almeida/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) GALLUP, N.M. -- Oct. 10, 1999 -- NAVAJO-CODE-WARRIORS-2,
10-10 --Young ROTC recruits salute members of the Navajo Code
Talkers Association during a parade. During World War II, hundreds
of Navajos were sent to the South Pacific to use their language in
creating secret codes the Japanese could not break. Their mission
has been a secret for years. However this weekend, some of the
Navajo veterans reunited to tell their stories at a reservation in
Gallup, N.M. (Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) UNDATED -- Oct. 10, 1999 -- NAVAJO-CODE-WARRIORS-1-B&AMP;W,
10-10 -- Pfc. Preston Toledo, left, and Pfc. Frank Toledo, cousins
attached to a Marine artillery regiment in the South Pacific, relay
orders using a Navajo code over a field radio in July 1943. During
World War II, hundreds of Navajos were sent to the South Pacific to
use their language in creating secret codes the Japanese could not
break. Their mission has been a secret for years. However this
weekend, some of the Navajo veterans reunited to tell their stories
at a reservation in Gallup, N.M. (Courtesy of the Navajo Code
Talkers Association/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) UNDATED -- Oct. 10, 1999 -- MEDIA-TALK-B&AMP;W, 10-10 -- Lou
Cannon in an undated photo. Cannon, a Reagan biographer, is no fan
of Edmond Morris' ``Dutch: A Memoir of Ronald Reagan.'' In the
spring, ``Public Affairs'' will publish an updated trade paperback
version of Cannon's 1991 biography, ``President Reagan: The Role of
a Lifetime,'' said Peter Osnos, the publisher of Public Affairs, a
two- year-old company. (Steve Malone/Santa Barbara News Press)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) HUNTINGTON BEACH, Calif. -- Oct. 10, 1999 --
E-COMMERCE-COLUMN, 10-10 -- Rosa Simon runs her Blindsdepot.com
Internet company from her home. Despite some initial difficulties,
she says that her business has grown sharply. Within the E-commerce
sphere, the segment that ``solutions providers'' seem to think
needs the most help is the small business category. (Ed Carreon/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 10, 1999 -- INTERNET-PRIVACY, 10-10 --
Christine Varney at the law firm of Hogan &AMP; Hartson. Varney was the
Federal Trade Commission's Internet activist until she left to join
an alliance dedicated to staving off government privacy rules.
(Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) CUPERTINO, Calif. -- Oct. 10, 1999 -- APPLE-SOFTWARE,
10-10 -- Shortly after his return to Apple Computer, Steve Jobs,
left, recruited Avidis Tevanian Jr. to help improve its software.
Much has been said and written about the turnaround at Apple
Computer Inc. in recent years. But the seeds of Apple's remarkable
renaissance were sown in a contentious meeting that took place here
in January 1997 and that involved the unsung part of Apple's
business: software. (Dan Krauss/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
