<HEADLINE>
GORE AND BRADLEY IN CAMPAIGN ROLE REVERSAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also GORE-CAMPAIGN, GORE-AFL-CIO)  
(mk) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE and KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ In an unlikely role reversal, the
front-runner for the Democratic presidential nomination, Al Gore,
is behaving less like a front-runner, or a vice president, and more
like a brawling insurgent. And Bill Bradley, who is the true
insurgent, is behaving more like the man to beat.
</P>
<P>
   The contrary approaches, which were on display _ in stark relief
_ on Saturday night here before 3,000 Democrats at the
Jefferson-Jackson Day Dinner, reflected the extraordinary turn in
the Democratic contest. With Bradley creeping up on him, or even
outpacing him, in important states like New Hampshire and New York,
Gore is determined to do whatever he can to upend the dynamic.
Bradley, happy with his surging campaign, does not dare make any
move that could tamper with a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   So at the dinner, Gore repeatedly taunted Bradley, imploring him
to debate, while Bradley refused to engage, portraying himself as a
graybeard of Democratic politics who would travel only the high
road.
</P>
<P>
   While the strategies seem sensible, they also carry potential
perils.
</P>
<P>
   By refusing to engage, Bradley opens himself up to being
portrayed as a risk-averse, aloof politician who does not have the
mettle _ or the hunger _ to fight emphatically for the nomination.
And if he succeeds in persuading voters that he is the strongest
candidate, Bradley will have to contend with a pressure most
challengers never worry about: heightened expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, in discarding his front-runner's reserve, risks appearing
desperate _ and could even be accused of besmirching the dignity of
the White House. When President Bush, alarmed by Bill Clinton's
climb in the polls in 1992, reacted by deriding Clinton's running
mate, Al Gore, as ``Ozone Man,'' many Republicans said he only hurt
his cause.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by his performance on Saturday, Gore apparently had few
qualms _ or perhaps few alternatives _ about trying a new strategy.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president descended from his perch of incumbency,
stepped out from behind the lectern and looked down at his
competitor in the audience and tried a new stunt. He issued a
challenge for weekly debates. ``How about it, Bill?'' Gore needled
his rival. ``If the answer is yes, stand up and wave your hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, needless to say, did not stand _ or even wave.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president, as part of his new offensive, unleashed a
call to arms: ``Stay and fight!'' he cried repeatedly as hundreds
of blue and white signs bearing those words bobbed up and down at
the Polk County Convention Complex.
</P>
<P>
   The slogan, which seemed to win over this audience, pulled
together, in a simple expression, the threads that Gore has been
struggling to meld into an overarching theme: It suggested a
passion that his critics say he has lacked. It enlivened the
audience. It suggested focus and purpose _ a rationale to his
candidacy that he has not so far expressed.
</P>
<P>
   The slogan also helps Gore deal with a troubling subject: his
loyalty to President Clinton. He has tried in other unsubtle ways
to distance himself from the president's scandals, only to find
that he draws more attention to his own inconsistencies than to
Clinton's behavior. But the slogan was intended to underscore his
loyalty _ and answer critics who said he should have cut and run
during impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a year, Gore had tried blander themes that seemed
suited for a cautious incumbent. First he trotted out, then
discarded, an abstract slogan of ``Practical Idealism.'' He then
tried ``New Horizons.'' More recently, he has been trying to utter
the mouthful that his staff stitched together after talks with
focus groups: ``Change that works for working families.''
</P>
<P>
   In another attempt to slow Bradley's surge, Gore on Saturday
portrayed him as a disloyal Democrat. He said Bradley failed the
party in its two most defining moments of the last 20 years:
Bradley voted for the 1981 Reagan budget cuts and, in 1995, he
announced he was quitting the Senate and would ``not rule out'' an
independent candidacy for president.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1981, when the Reagan budget cuts in education, housing and
health care threatened decency and social justice, even some
Democrats said we have to support them to survive politically,''
Gore told the crowd in an unstated but unmistakable reference to
Bradley. ``But I didn't walk away. I decided to stay and fight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When Newt Gingrich took over Congress and tried to reinforce
Reaganomics to try to force deep cuts in Medicare and Medicaid, I
didn't walk away,'' Gore said. ``I decided to stay and fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the words, Gore has tried to shed the White House
trappings. He has dumped the vice presidential seal that usually
hangs on the lectern; in fact, he has abandoned the lectern
altogether, edging close to the audience.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   When he spoke before Gore, Bradley stayed safely behind the
lectern _and delivered the sort of safe speech preferred by
front-runners. He refused to respond to Gore's attacks. He has
resisted Gore's request for several debates. And he did not say one
negative word about the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Bradley spoke loftily of his ``big ideas,'' asserting,
for instance, that ``the moral imperative for health care shouldn't
scare us.'' And he extolled the virtues of a positive campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why can't American politics be like McGuire and Sosa?''
Bradley asked, referring to the friendly competition for baseball's
home run championship between Mark McGuire and Sammy Sosa. ``Why
can't it be Vice President Al Gore pushing Bill Bradley and Bill
Bradley pushing Al Gore to be the best we can be so that the
national interest will benefit?'' He added, ``It takes discipline
to be positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when pressed, Bradley refused to be drawn into responding
directly to Gore, though he defended his loyalty to the Democratic
Party. ``I've always been a Democrat since I cast my first vote in
1964,'' he said. ``I am simply not going to deal with the darts
that are being thrown.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gore's barbs seemed to make the Bradley camp a bit more
defensive. When Anita Dunn, Bradley's communications director, was
asked whether he had considered running for president as an
independent, she repeatedly sidestepped the question. The closest
she came to a reply was: ``It was not a serious consideration.''
And rather than take up Gore's request for repeated debates,
something most challengers would relish, Ms. Dunn offered a
non-answer: ``There are going to be plenty of debates.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Gore's advisers, after weeks of discouraging
publicity, sounded excited about the new rollout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something just clicked,'' Michael Whouley, Gore's top
strategist in Iowa and New Hampshire, said of his candidate's
performance. ``This is the `Al Gore on Fire Tour.'''
</P>
<P>
   Whether that was wishful thinking or not, the question now is
whether either Bradley or Gore can sustain the images they are
trying to project to voters. It will not be easy.
</P>
<P>
   As part of his insurgent message, Gore has tried to distance
himself from the world of politics. His retooled campaign speeches
have included passages about his being disillusioned with politics.
After Vietnam and Watergate, he has said, the last thing in the
world he wanted to do was become a politician.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Gore also seeks to claim the birthright of a natural-born
Democrat, delivering passionate appeals to labor, minorities,
homosexuals and other party constituencies.
</P>
<P>
   But once Gore picks up the prized endorsement of the AFL-CIO
this week, as is now expected, it might be harder for him to paint
himself as an anti-establishment outsider _ and easier for Bradley
to paint him as an entrenched insider.
</P>
<P>
   Just the same, if Gore's new style appears to be catching on,
Bradley may no longer have the luxury of trying to be above
politics _ and repeated debates.
</P>
<P>
   Pam Hinton, a librarian from Fort Dodge who attended the dinner
Saturday night, said she was taken aback by Gore's debate
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was rather strange, actually,'' said Ms. Hinton,
51, who is torn between the candidates. ``That's not the way a
front-runner usually conducts himself.''
</P>
<P>
   But Tom Salvatore, a postal worker from Fort Dodge who backs
Bradley, said the vice president was in rare form. ``I was
impressed with Al Gore's speech,'' he said, ``because it was so
unlike him. He's usually so stiff.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
