<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-WYNN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LARRY WYNN, 89, LYRICIST FOR `FIVE GUYS' 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 &HT;     
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Larry Wynn, a lyricist who wrote the words for the 1941 novelty
hit ``Five Guys Named Moe,'' died on Sept. 28 at Englewood Hospital
in New Jersey. He was 89 and lived in Cliffside Park, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Wynn's lyrics for ``Five Guys'' were combined with music by
Jerry Bresler, and the song was recorded for Decca by Louis Jordan
and his Tympany Five.
</P>
<P>
   Wynn, a performer and songwriter who later became a salesman in
radio and television, once said that six decades ago he had
listened to a group of musicians whose names he could not recall,
so he referred to them as ``five guys named Moe.'' In a 1992
interview with The Record of Hackensack, N.J., he recalled that he
thought at the time: ``Man! That's a title begging for a song.''
</P>
<P>
   He wrote the song's words quickly. They include these lines:
``There's a brand new band sensation/That is sweeping all the
nation/Every hepcat knows them by their name.'' The lyrics also
identify the five Moes as Big Moe, Little Moe, Four-Eyed Moe, No
Mo' and Eat Mo'. The song's title later became the name for a
Broadway revue based on Jordan's song hits.
</P>
<P>
   Wynn, originally named Lester Litwin, was reared in Queens and
graduated from Washington and Lee University.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Evelyn, died in 1990.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
