<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REAL-LIFE-COMEDY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METROPOLITAN DIARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ENID NEMY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A weekly column featuring readers' reports on life in the Big
Apple.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   When I arrived for my regular hair appointment at the Joseph
Martin salon on Madison and 63rd Street recently, I was informed
there was a leak and no water. That meant the colorist couldn't
start work, but then finally word came that the water was back on
and he went ahead and applied the color.
</P>
<P>
   After 30 minutes, the timer went off, but once again the water
had stopped. With the color still on my hair and no time to spare,
the salon arranged for me and the man who was to shampoo me to go
to another salon two blocks away.
</P>
<P>
   We went off, me with my ill-fitting brown gown, a blue towel
covering my hair, sunglasses and a look of a creature from
somewhere else. I walked with my head down, hoping no one would
recognize me.
</P>
<P>
   We arrived at our destination, my hair was washed and we began
walking back to my original salon. We passed a man in a wheelchair
whose habit for years has been to sit in front of a coffee shop. My
friends and I have always tried to help him out. Despite my
disguise, he spotted me. ``Hi, sweetheart,'' he said, ``How are you
doing today?''
</P>
<P>
   There was not another soul who even glanced my way. Apparently
no one even thought I looked unusual. That made me wonder about
being a New Yorker and a woman over 50. Are we so invisible?
</P>
<P>
   _ ROBERTA ABRAMS
</P>
<P>
   Christine Hoffman saw this scrawled in an empty advertising
space over the back-door exit of an uptown M101 bus:
</P>
<P>
   ``Wait for green light
</P>
<P>
   Take a deep breath
</P>
<P>
   With all your strength push door
</P>
<P>
   Let go of door
</P>
<P>
   Door will automatically smash next person in face.''
</P>
<P>
   FROM JERSEY WITH ANGST
</P>
<P>
   I love New York when all's said and done,
</P>
<P>
   but getting there is certainly not half the fun.
</P>
<P>
   Commuting's a chore and too expensive by far.
</P>
<P>
   And after dining and wining I could lose my car.
</P>
<P>
   The high-rise hotels are way over my head.
</P>
<P>
   It's a great place to visit.
</P>
<P>
   Or is it?
</P>
<P>
   I'd rather live there instead.
</P>
<P>
   _ GENE NEWMAN
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   I am a frequent shopper on the Lower East Side and have a
special appreciation of good pickles.
</P>
<P>
   As my order was being packed on a recent expedition, I noticed a
woman with a very confused look perusing the assorted barrels. When
her turn came, she asked the pickle man, in a very British accent,
what was the difference among the pickles? He, in fast New Yorkese,
replied ``Quarter sour, half sour, three-quarter sour and full
sour.'' Looking even more perplexed, the woman asked, ``What would
you recommend for beginners?''
</P>
<P>
   He told her she could buy three for $1 and suggested she try
three different ones. Sounding very relieved, she happily went off
with her assortment. Now I wonder if after tasting them, she will
be able to tell which is which and if she'll return as an
intermediate pickle purchaser?
</P>
<P>
   _ ANONYMOUS
</P>
<P>
   Morris J. Bloomstein, a lawyer, called another law firm and
tried to find out from the switchboard operator which lawyer was
handling a certain case. He finally became frustrated at his
inability to get the necessary information.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's your name anyway?'' the operator finally asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bond, James Bond,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   There was a moment of silence. ``How do you spell that last
name?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, Hildegarde M. Hennington and a friend accepted
the invitation of another friend to spend a vacation with her at
her rented apartment in Spain on the Mediterranean coast.
</P>
<P>
   When they arrived, Ms. Hennington went to a car rental agency,
and an English-speaking employee completed the paperwork after
looking over her license and passport. When she returned to her
hostess's apartment, she studied the contents of the packet she had
been given and discovered that the car had been leased to ``Mrs.
Organ Donor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no compunction about traveling under that name, and the
three of us took off for a glorious trip,'' she recalled. Mrs.
Organ Donor then returned the car without incident.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   It was noon on a Saturday, and over Roosevelt Island five little
skywriting planes flew around in a circle several times, spelling
out: ``Diana, I need you. I love you. Joey.''
</P>
<P>
   It did not sound like a proposal. I began to wonder: Are they
married and he's in trouble? If so, what did he do? Are they just
friends and he can't make the big commitment? If so, why go to the
expense of hiring skywriters? Did he pound at her door and she
didn't let him in? What if she never looked up?
</P>
<P>
   All the mysteries of a big city. Good luck, Joey. Be wary,
Diana.
</P>
<P>
   _ THOMAS LUBART
</P>
<P>
   SPIDER WEB
</P>
<P>
   A spider out seeking his prey
</P>
<P>
   Encountered a fly on the way
</P>
<P>
   With no wish to provoke
</P>
<P>
   He cordially spoke
</P>
<P>
   ``Please visit my web site today.''
</P>
<P>
   _ PAUL PICKREL
</P>
<P>
   A recent story about a waiter who used the expression ``menu
schmenu'' reminded Samuel I. Joseph of another waiter of the same
era. Joseph and his friends were enjoying one particular variety of
the selection of rolls in their basket and asked the waiter for a
refill. When the waiter returned with the refill, it was suggested
that he remove the rolls they weren't going to eat. He was
indignant. ``I don't take away; I only bring,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Avrum Hyman was returning to Manhattan from a visit to his
sister in New Jersey when he noticed a sermon announcement sign in
front of a church in downtown Newark. The message read: ``This is a
C H _ _ C H. What's missing?''
</P>
</TEXT>
