<SLUG> BC-EDIT-A-BETTER-WAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A BETTER WAY TO TREAT THE OLD
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, Oct. 11:
</P>
<P>
   At a Roman Catholic nursing home in Albany, N.Y. a year ago, the
order of Carmelite nuns that runs it broke from tradition by asking
the aged applicants who were about to become residents: ``What time
do you like to get up in the morning? When do you like to have
breakfast? What do you like to eat?'' The Teresian Home had decided
to end the tyranny of structure and schedule that herds old people
through the day in nursing homes across the country: up at 6:30
a.m., dressed for breakfast at 7:30 to 9, lunch at noon in a dining
room with scores of others, showers at a certain time, naps at a
certain time, dinner at 5 to 5:30 p.m. and back in bed by 8, two to
a room, on long hallways.
</P>
<P>
   In Fairport, N.Y., on the Erie Canal, the Fairport Baptist Home
decided about four years ago to break that same rigid pattern. At
meals where 42 Alzheimer's patients were fed all at once, in chaos
and din, the staff was tying some down to keep them at the table,
giving appetite stimulants to others who did not want to eat and
sedatives to the agitated. The impulse to try something different
came from nurses on the staff, but the administrator, the Rev.
Garth Brokaw, found what he wanted to copy at a United Methodist
home in Oshkosh, Wis., the Evergreen Retirement Community, and at
the Roman Catholic Mount Saint Vincent's in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Jewish Home in Rochester, N.Y., has begun making
changes, too. The point is to try to shape daily life around the
needs and preferences of the residents, rather than the
institution's. In an industry where 1.6 million old people,
two-thirds of them impoverished and 70 percent suffering from
dementia, live mostly in hospital-style buildings, it is a
revolutionary idea. It is also not surprising, in an industry
increasingly dominated by corporate chain ownership, that the
changes are occurring in nonprofit, church-sponsored homes.
</P>
<P>
   After $23 million was spent on the gradual reconstruction of its
buildings, the Fairport Baptist Home had a grand opening in August
of its new architecture, in which 9, 10 or 12 residents live in
single rooms clustered around big open kitchens, living rooms and
dining areas, with the Alzheimer's patients mixed in. The residents
are allowed to eat and sleep and dress according to their habits,
and each cluster of rooms has a staff to nurse, feed, launder and
care for those in need. Dogs and children are brought to visit.
Plants grow everywhere. The noise level, the drug level, the
wandering and the number of patients in restraints are all down.
</P>
<P>
   The effect on operating costs has yet to be seen. For such
humane changes to be copied by for-profit homes, the finances would
have to work. But the chains are showing interest, sending
representatives to visit church homes and attend conferences.
Rightly or wrongly, nursing homes have come to have a terrible
reputation among the old. No one wants to end up there. The homes
with the worst financial troubles at the moment _ and the most
consistent patterns of resident abuse _ are the for-profit homes.
Some real, caring changes could do them a world of good.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-10-99 2345EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
