u k BC-EDIT-CRACKDOWN-IN-IRA     10-10 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CRACKDOWN-IN-IRAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CRACKDOWN IN IRAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, Oct. 11:
</P>
<P>
   The student protests that convulsed Iran in July were the
largest public outpouring of emotion there since the 1979
revolution. The demonstrations _ for cultural freedoms and greater
democracy _ were peaceful until paramilitary groups and security
forces attacked the students. Now, in a terrifying illustration of
the kind of strictures the protesters challenged, four people have
been sentenced to death on charges of organizing the
demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   The sentences, a clear attempt to discourage further protests,
are a sign of the panic that Iran's restlessness is causing among
the mullahs. Since Mohammad Khatami was elected president on a
reform platform two years ago, he has been battling the
conservative Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, the country's spiritual and
political leader. and his fundamentalist followers. President
Khatami's election encouraged writers, journalists, students and
politicians to emerge from silence and fight for more liberties.
But his popularity has not been able to keep the fundamentalists
from cracking down on these newly visible targets.
</P>
<P>
   The identity of the four sentenced to death is still not known,
and their trial was held in complete secrecy. The chief judge of
Tehran's Revolutionary Court said the Supreme Court had already
approved two of the sentences and two were being reviewed. He
hinted that others could get a death sentence as well. Hundreds of
students are believed to be in detention.
</P>
<P>
   This has been a dangerous year for reformers. In January, a
death squad inside the intelligence service was found responsible
for the murders of several prominent reformist writers and
political activists. Repression of the pro-Khatami press has also
increased. Four proreform dailies have been closed this year, and
one publisher recently received a 30-month suspended sentence. Iran
is also preparing to try 13 Iranian Jews on dubious charges of
spying for Israel. Clerics have called for their hanging even
though no evidence has yet been made public. The most recent
obsession of the fundamentalists is a play that makes fun of one of
Islam's most holy events. It was published in a student newsletter
(circulation 150) at one of Tehran's scientific universities. Some
have demanded that the authors be hanged.
</P>
<P>
   There are some new signs, however, that the fundamentalists are
wary of losing support. On Oct. 1, Khamenei gave a speech _ at the
shrine of the revolution's Ayatollah Khomeini no less _ admonishing
the radicalism of some of his supporters. Khamenei also praised the
president as a pious man working for the rebirth of Islam. The
astonishing speech offers some hope that recent extremist decisions
could be softened or reversed.
</P>
<P>
   Although Khamenei's speech included his usual criticisms of the
reformist media, his apparent desire for conciliation charts a
wiser course. But the speech must now be followed by the release of
those jailed and an end to punishment for those who believe, as the
president does, in a more accountable, democratic and freer Iran. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-10-99 2347EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991010.0228 </DOCNO>
