<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-10 23:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2848 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-SOFT-MONEY-NYT &LR;      10-10 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SOFT-MONEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE SENATE CONFRONTS SOFT MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, Oct. 11:
</P>
<P>
   When campaign finance reform comes before the Senate this week,
Trent Lott and other enemies of cleaning up the system will make
the usual predictions that reform cannot win. In fact, the
Republican leadership's barricade against change is crumbling.
Under pressure from a growing number of business leaders, and
rising outrage over a projected $3 billion to be spent in the
current campaign, some important Republicans are thinking about
supporting the McCain-Feingold ``soft money'' ban. Sen. Chuck Hagel
of Nebraska is planning to offer amendments, a welcome sign that he
and others might be showing up to help pass the bill, not block it.
</P>
<P>
   A solid bipartisan majority passed campaign reform in the House
last month. In the Senate it is backed by a majority consisting of
all 45 Democrats and seven Republicans. But eight more Republicans
are needed to break the filibuster to be engineered by Lott and
Mitch McConnell of Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   McConnell, an energetic fund-raiser and ardent proponent of the
present system, is telling colleagues that changing the campaign
laws is a liberal plot to destroy the Republican Party. In fact,
Democratic Party professionals also fear that banning soft money _
the unlimited money that corporations, unions and rich individuals
give to the parties _ would cripple the Democrats. What the bill
will really do is curb each party's ability to haul in vast
corrupting sums from special interests looking for favors.
</P>
<P>
   The core bill to be introduced by Sens. John McCain of Arizona
and Russell Feingold of Wisconsin is a simple ban on soft money,
without an earlier provision regulating contributions to
independent groups for their campaign ads. Their aim in pushing
this stripped-down version was to lure Republicans genuinely
worried about regulating the rights of such groups. We support the
restrictions on these groups' fund-raising but also accept the
tactic of dropping that part of the bill. Democrats pushing to
re-attach the regulation of independent groups should realize that
they are probably reducing the chances of winning enough votes to
get the entire bill passed in the Senate. One alternative might be
to widen disclosure requirements for money donated to independent
groups that run campaign ads before an election.
</P>
<P>
   Amendments to be offered by Hagel or other Republicans should be
aimed at attracting more supporters without opening loopholes to
corrupt money. The Senate can consider raising ceilings on
donations to candidates, but only if the soft-money ban for the
parties remains intact. Among the senators whose constituents
should press them to join this process are Spencer Abraham of
Michigan and William Roth of Delaware. Both are in tough
re-election fights in states where voters care about campaign
reform. They must know that they would receive tremendous credit at
home for standing up for principle, not campaign money.
</P>
<P>
   This is a signal moment for McCain, whose poll numbers in New
Hampshire are starting to move upward in his drive for the
Republican presidential nomination. But other Republicans, notably
Susan Collins of Maine, have been working hard to corral support
within their party. McConnell's bullying tactics have not worked.
After his threatening letter to the Committee for Economic
Development, telling it to stop recruiting among businesses for
support for the soft-money ban, the committee doubled its
membership to more than 200 leaders.
</P>
<P>
   McConnell likes to define campaign donations as free speech. But
everyone knows that money does more than talk in Washington. It
buys influence. The only way to stop that practice is to limit the
money that sloshes through the system. Most Americans, most House
members and most senators agree. The only question now is whether
the majority or cash will rule. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-10-99 2349EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
