A2850 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS &LR;      10-10 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O'DONOVAN PLANS BIG CHANGE FOR REVOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The Revolution should benefit from having
been eliminated from playoff contention in the last game of the MLS
season in Washington. This was an unsuccessful season, only
slightly masked by the team's 1-1 regulation-time tie against D.C.
United Saturday night, and had New England inched into the playoffs
it would have been a deceptive measure of success.
</P>
<P>
   Miami's 2-0 victory over Colorado allowed the Fusion to finish
with 29 points, three ahead of New England in the race for the
final playoff berth. But the Revolution, propped up only by the
failures of Miami and the even more disastrous New York-New Jersey
MetroStars, were less than a playoff team for much of the season
</P>
<P>
   This was the worst regular-season record in the Revolution's
four years of existence. The atmosphere surrounding the team
improved slightly over the 1998 season, but the record did not. The
Revolution continue to be pursued by demons of the past, weighed
down by losing and pessimism.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Zenga's ultra-pragmatic approach might have been a
lifeline for the Revolution, who really never have had a
discernible identity in their playing style. Zenga reasoned that
the Revolution needed only to band together and stay in contention
in every game, and they could finish in the top four in the Eastern
Conference. But even this simple philosophy could not be carried
out, only partially because of Zenga's shortcomings as a coach.
</P>
<P>
   Too many Revolution players are accustomed to losing _ the team
has 36 regulation-time wins in four years _ and they are carrying
the weight of failure. At least Zenga brought a winning attitude _
the Revolution have only 19 regulation-time victories without Zenga
in goal _ and he made it obvious he could not accept losing.
</P>
<P>
   Nor are the fans likely to continue to accept losing, at least
not in the same numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We owe it to the fans to look at this project and correct,
once and for all, what we are doing wrong,'' general manager Brian
O'Donovan said. ``Because whatever we have been doing has not been
working. We are talking about significant change, but whatever that
is has not been decided yet. We have created something really
special here _ a franchise with awareness, passion, interest in
what the club is all about, a fan base. We've probably sold more
tickets for soccer than any other city in the country this year,
and we've sold more sponsorships than probably any other MLS team.
But on the field we are doing something fundamentally wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Donovan has made bold moves at the start of each season,
hiring former English League star Frank Stapleton as coach in 1996,
signing MLS coach of the year Thomas Rongen from Tampa Bay in 1997,
following Rongen's extensive makeover plans last year, then
bringing in Zenga as player-coach, followed by Steve Nicol this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would be a whole change in the organizational
structure,'' O'Donovan said. ``It's safe to say we need somebody in
here who thinks, eats, and breathes soccer, and who also knows
international soccer, a sort of director of winning. He could be
the director of soccer operations, or he could be the coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicol is a candidate for the job, but O'Donovan would not reveal
other names. The Revolution likely are considering collegiate
coaches, but they also would consider someone such as Steve
Heighway, a former Liverpool star who played in the North American
Soccer League, holds a US coaching license, and is now director of
Liverpool's player development program.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-10-99 2358EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
